text: aroma is the best part . lots of grapefruit and citrus . tons of hop aroma . taste is great . tons of hops . reminds me of hop slam a bit . mouthfeel is good . overall an awesome beer that i 'm going to want another growler of .  tingly in the nose which is common with sour ales but this is n't sour at all t. sweet with dried fruit , malty m. has a biting quality , a bit to carbonated .
aroma is wow coffee , rich robust , you want it , it 's here , with a nice dark malt sweetness underneath .  very astringent .

a - pours what appears to be black with some amber/red when held up to the light . has an incredibly creamy tan 1-finger head that lasts for an incredibly long time . very heavy lacing .  the mouth feel was hindered a bit , as the bottle had n't been sitting in my refrigerator long enough , the ale could have been a little more carbonated .

it has a gold cloudy body with a beautiful head and just the right amount of carbonation from an aesthetic point of view . it is a simply picture perfect beer .  taste is light and airy , a tad sweetness is overpowered by barley and water . this stuff does n't dry out the mouth , which is good . then again , that 's because there is nothing in here except water and barley . i will take a soda anyday , but i guess i can see why people trying to quit alcohol but still like a cold `` beer '' here and there will spend money on it .

dark mahogany to black with a two finger beige head . great lace and retention for a porter .  its sucks to know that in a different format this could be so much more . body and carb is okay , but by this point i 'm already at the meh stage .

the aroma is particularly good on this stout ; there is a lot of fresh blueberry aroma , along with nutty , chocolaty , and yeasty aromas to compliment . the beer pours with a very deep black color and a head that stays around the rim of the glass leaving a swirl on top of the beer . from the smell i expected this to be very fruity , which in it 's own right it is , however not in an alcipop sort of way . flavors that hit the tongue right off the bat are a little overwhelming but very nice to pick through .  this is an excellent pilsner . number three on my list , only behind konig and pilsner urquell . just as crisp and refreshing as both of those , but a little lighter in taste and body . very clean , top quality .

well , the label says brewed with peaches and pecans and you get tons of peach on the nose . and it 's a real peach smell too , not the kind in gummy candy .  a surprisingly great beer from a brewing giant . it could have been a little less punishing when guzzled , but hey it 's a dark beer and we are not dealing with coors light here . i think the beer is buitiful to look at , and is rather smooth . but the lable and beer fit perfectly ph
honestly one of the most impressive looking ipa 's i 've encountered .  mouthfeel is a little too carbonated and light but i still enjoyed the beer in-spite of those tow minor complaints .
a tall , tan , thick head that lasts .  m/d : the mouthfeel is a tad low on this for my liking of an oud brune .

complex , unique , and very intriguing . lots of vanilla , caramel , and pumpkin with cinnamon , nutmeg , and allspice . big and flavorful , intriguing , and easy to drink in a non-session beer kind of way .  the feel in my mouth was medium and it was a bit syrupy .

really beautiful beer , pours a hazy golden color with a huge frothy white head that retains impressively and leaves nice lacing .  a watery texture and lighter body than i expected from the nose , with a moderate amount of carbonation .

oh , man ... the aroma on this is , perhaps as the name implies , heavenly . almost a perfect balance in the nose -- fruity , pine needles , grapefruit . and this one goes through three `` hoppings , '' kettle , hop back , and dry hopping ... awesome . the flavor is just about perfect . a fine balance of hop flavors , including a nice grapefruit bitterness and a light bready undertone . but , as a whole , this is a very drinkable beer ... and quite delicious .  the palate is thin but ok .

pours a beautiful clear copper with a tight beige colored head of foam . the head sticks around , with good lacing on the glass .  this beer has a lot of flavor for a light . too bad its not a good flavor ! nothing impressive at all here . i 'm not sure what they are putting in this beer but its not worth the 7.99 they are charging for a six pack . i would recommend pabst blue ribbion over this any day !
pours a nice amber color with a white head and excellent lacing .  under carbonated .

appearance : cloudy golden yellow with an amazing , big , billowy head that last all the way through the beer , incredible lacing too which sticks all over the glass . the best looking tripel i 've ever seen .  the mouthfeel is a bit harsh with the 8.0 % alcohol , but i have found very few tripels that can hide the alcohol content .
smell : chocolate , lots of malt , good !  it it a bit on the carbonated side , so the mouthfeel is a bit more bland than i had expected .

s- wow , loads of scents starting with a spiced apple and spiced pear followed by great light sweet malt scents and of course the belgian bready yeast ... this reminded me of my trips i used to take to julian with my parents and brothers as a child , we would always go up there for some fresh apple pie and hot cider ... t- not as much as the smell , but still great . you pick up on the apple/pear , spices , light sweet malt and loads of bready yeast with a nice crisp finish .  m - the mouth feel is spritzy and aggressive with a dry finish .
s : sweet dark frut nose come out followed by a chocolate toasted malt . on second whiff i am reminded of chocolate covered cheries .  the mouth fell was a little thin for stout .

its smell is its best characteristic -- floral hops , malty , a hint of wheat -- really beautiful . the taste is sweety & malty , as well as bitter .  the mouthfeel is thinner when compared with other stouts , merely decent .
very nice aroma of christmas spices , oak , raisins , old sherry , toffee and treacle .  the mouthfeel is quite thin , verging on watery .
a - black with a 1 '' tan head . nice lacing .  m - medium body , fair carb , etc .

the beer is an oil black , with no foreseeable brown hue when held to the light . the head is impressive , huge , sea-foam that stays around for a long , long time .  smooth , medium body with a palate almost entirely made up of bitter , herbal hops ; perhaps trace notes of biscuity malt can be detected , but they are virtually non-existent . finish is long , dry , and bitter , and leaves you wanting more , which leads to a great level of drinkability , especially for a hophead .
great chocolate smell as soon as the cap came off , smelled just like a candy bar .  the only complaint i have is that the texture left much to be offered . overall i great beer .

s. pears on the nose once i open the bottle . i 'm excited to take a sip . not a great representation of the style , but a surprisingly champagne-like beer : they hit the bottle 's stated target on the mark , but i 'm still disappointed that all of the wonderful scents did n't fully transition into the taste .  on my first stop on my michigan beer tour . the grand cru on tap was a very nice start to my tour . the first taste was wonderful , but , the flavor of the beer left my mouth looking for just alittle more .

smell : by far the most enjoyable aspect of this beer . the smell is incredibly complex with a strong prune backbone and hints of everything from lemon to chocolate . i like smelling it more than drinking it .  mouthfeel : low carbonation , light-medium body , slick texture . a bit flat all in all .

i had this beer poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : the beer pours a darker color than golden , with a small white head and okay lacing ... s : the smell is very strongly grapefruited ... t : wow , a very potent hop flavor . the bitterness is actually quite light ... m : crisp , pretty light , and slightly dryish ... d : a really nice beer .  feel is kinda harsh .
looks the part . `` glugged '' into my tulip glass and created a nice tight brown head that leaves lots of lace as i drink .  it had a light feel on the palate with mild carbonation .
smell is great . coffee beans and some roasted aromas , a touch of chocolate .  mouthfeel - rather bubbly , fairly thin .

s- nice nutty aromas , butterscotch , caramel , high end rum notes . this makes me smile . t- starts out a nice light dry chocolate , some nutty notes , light caramel , and some light dry hoppiness on the clean finish .  the feel is smooth , suprisingly light for a beer that seems so heavy . while i feel that this is one of north coast 's better efforts ... though none are really bad , i do wish that it had a bit more body .

tons of chocolate malt , coffee , anise , plums , raisons a fruit blender of aromas . it really needed more hops to balance this bad boy out .  taste is more of the same ... some wild floral flavors , hints of citrus ... seems like the dominant flavors have switched from the citrus to the floral characteristics . i like it , for sure , but could use some balance . i 'm not a big fan of the bitter taste left in the mouth ... but it 's still plenty drinkable . a definitely above-average ale , but not the best .
great retention and lacing . looks fantastic .  carbonation is a little much in my opinion and cuts down on the smooth/velvety texture .

mainly coffee and bittersweet cocoa come through on the nose . minimal hop characteristic if any at all .  m- the weakness of the beer - moderately light body feels a little weak to me . light carbonation does n't add much .

the aroma is pretty complex like any respectable barleywine , but definitely more on the malt side . brown sugar is obvious and is of pleasant company to figs , peaches , alcohol and an all-around complex fruitiness .  had one warm just to see what the flavors were really like , and blllaaahhhh corn up the ying yang ! honestly , if youre going for the light beer on a budget , i 'd go with bud light just because it has no flavor , this is like a bad , adjunct-y lager that 's been in storage for a year . i 'm just wonder if miller has some weird process that makes their beer taste stale , because i notice the exact same thing in mgd , yet not high life , maybe its just the filterization . anyways , about twice as yellow , piss looking as a heineken , yet actually produces a decent mouthful . and the smell seems to get better when there is less of it , so the finish is actually pretty satisfying . overall , decent for why people drink it , but for a light beer , i 'd go with amstel , even for its price .
a : gentle pour creates a 3 finger powdery white head with incredible retention . a beautiful beer to behold .  palate : medium body and higher end carbonation .

can holiday wine cellar escondido , ca a ( surprisingly ) better than average pour ! clear light goldenrod yellow with a large , persistent white head , and lots and lots of spiderweb lacing down the glass .  the mouthfeel is just average . also , carbonation is lacking enough to make this feel sticky .

wow ... what a head !  i picked this lager over the ale 's offered , due to the miserable heat wave here in no . cal . it was an appropriate choice . saaz hops seemed to be prominent with good malt base . a nice refreshing beer . nothing spectacular but very acceptable when in the mood for this style .

the smell is strong with brandy ( and seemingly bourbon ) and dark fruity sweet malts , caramel , and vanilla . very pleasant . holy shit , what this beer would be if it were carbonated ! dark fruit sweetness complimented by a smooth and invigorating alcohol presence ( 12.5 % ) , much like an imperial stout ... its damn decent right now , but so much greater in my carbonated imagination .  m-its a little undercarbonated but the balance of the sweetness with the malt and subtle hops make for a relitivly complex october beer . d-easy to drink and very nice to have this time of year , easy to session .

the aromas were inviting and very exciting . t : dark and sweet fruits at the beginning of the sip , hints of alcohol in the middle , ending in a pretty strong bitter kick .  i did notice after a while that it has been pulled from tap that it acquires a lack of a better word , a buttery taste that really dos n't go good with anything . i do like this beer and i 'm not bashing it . the buttery taste in my opinion did not take effect until thirty or so minutes after pour . i do keep some in my fridge . i have shiner before to make burgers with , which turned out great . good beer for beer lovers .

great nose on this altbier . very mild fragrance , overall , but perfectly to style . perfect for the cool austin weather this time of year .  the body becomes thin on the mid palate and that 's my primary complaint .

$ 5.00 / 750ml bottle county market grocery store stevens point , wisconsin appearance - a haze of golden yellow to a pale orange with a lasting frothy white head . very much carbonated as a constant flow of tiny bubbles speed to the top if the beer from the side and bottom of the pint glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit too watery and perhaps a bit chalky .

porterhouse in dublin pours black with thick , dense and creamy head that does not dissipate till the end of the glass , leaving dense lacing .  i wish the carbonation was a little more noticeable in the mouth .

the aroma is honeysuckle and dark fruit , complex , tropic , and soothing . mouthfeel is brighter than i would have expected , but leaves a slightly gritty film on the teeth . the taste is not nearly as complex or abundant as the smell and alcohol does not feature much part in it .  m - light body , with a carbonation level that is probably too sharp for the style .
very fresh and clean smell , hardly any yeast aroma .  the carbonation is heavy and it adds harshness to the palate . medium-full body .

slightly billowy , about 1/2 '' and slowly drops . looks sticky . very natural . not bright orange . i think this is as good looking as an ipa gets .  way too thin in the mouthfeel category , however .
big chocolate smell . sweet malts and molasses lend to a chocolate bar wrapper aroma .  mouthfeel was moderate , not super heavy or light .
consumed 2 days later a : poured a deep maroon color with good carbonation and a dirty white head s : caramel .  the body is pretty light though and clean .
pours clear copper , with a two finger off white head . the head sticks around a long time and laces good .  mouthfeel is thin for a stout imo , but not bad .

not much there in the way of lace ... s - i could smell the hops when i was pouring this ... beautiful floral aroma with a little citrus ... like putting your nose in a bag of fresh hops t - good balance for how much hop aroma there is ... more on the sweet malty side rather than bitter ... definitely a sweet aftertaste .  nice chewy mouthfeel , but significantly under-carbonated . the only thing it lacks is carbonation and a decent head .

pours a luscious peach/dark gold color with a substantial , fluffy , two-finger head that exhibits excellent retention and lacing .  a rather thin aqueous body with less carbonation than expected , but otherwise nothing wrong with this brew .

clear copper colored beer with a large , cream colored head . head retention is good , with nice lacing .  as for the go-down : thin & lightly carbonated , not aggressive but not annoying either & no aftertaste .
the bottle popped furiously , and poured with a full head and glowing color .  m : surprisingly on the more carbonated side with a slight fizzy mouthfeel .

that settles into a nice thick lace covering most of the glass yes it 's a chocolate stout and the aromas defiantly back it up lots of sweet chocolate aromas some earthiness to it along with some hint of roasted malts flavor 's of dark chocolate are dominate not overly sweet with a coffee backbone it 's got this mocha thing going on the mouthfeel is medium to thin would have liked it a little thicker this is really one of the great chocolate stout 's especially for under $ 5 a bomber well worth the experience  m : sharp carbonation is pretty overpowering , and any refreshing aspects of the smell and taste are lost .

overall , the aroma is wonderful , the flavor is almost there , but the harsh bitter finish leaves you afraid to take another sip .  out of all of the blueberry beers i have had i would have to say this is probably my favorite . very fruity with a somewhat dry finish to it . the blueberries are definitely the star of the show . overall this is a very drinkable beer and makes a great summer brew .

overly sweet at times , but still nice . if it was n't for the mild astringent smell i 'd give it a 5 .  bought this over a month to two months a go and decided to give it a go . it is an ipa so it does have a nice bright orange to copper color . the taste and the smell are sweet and fruity , the only bad thing i have to to say about it , is the taste of tea is very lacking . i cant pick it up but , other than that i wish that stone , ishii and baird made this more as a yearly offering , cause its really good

this big california ipa packs a heavy alcoholic punch at 8.5 % abv , but for such a great smell , i was let down with the taste . do n't get me wrong , its good , but it is not the best for this style .  as readily available as bud , and a whole lot better . a great fall-back session brew , which is good with a meal , or having several at a baseball game .
appearance : dark red-burnt orange body , medium head . the head is creamy and tan , leaves full lace .  mouthfeel : the body is oddly thin , and crisp .

this beer poured a cloudy deep gold that bordered on light amber . it 's pure white head was thick and rich , solid lacing adorned the glass .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and somewhat tannic , but the overall effect is quite interesting .

poured into a chimay goblet and it looks beautiful . nice size head with a nice golden clear look to it .  went down smooth with no after taste . not bad , but could include a few more hops to round out the beer . i would recommend even without . it was very good between 45 and 55 degrees .
has a really nice fluffy one finger tan head that sticks around . lacing covers a huge portion of the glass .  mouthfeel : a little watery , but not terrible .

the smell was slightly chocolate . 2007 bottle 02/23/2008 beautiful smell like gourmet chocolates , an amazing improvement over the last year . this beer is a really good example of a cellar-worthy beer . 2006 vintage 01/10/09 smells malty grains , some chocolate , tastes good and probably ca n't get much better .  medium thin body manages a bit of creaminess .
big bulky beige head 1 1/2 inches . a thin head remains throughout no matter how long it sits ( very nice ) .  mouthfeel , i would like it have been a bit more carbonated , but it did fine .
smell was amazing , coffee , toffee , bitter chocolate , sugar , fruit .  the mouthfeel is fairly overcarbonated and dry .

very nice . t : initial attack is pleasant , pure coffee , but then it turns quite bitter , but not in a hoppy way , more of an unpleasant burnt coffee way .  i 've always liked this beer , and if they beefed up the abv and gave it a little more body , it would be the perfect porter . why grant 's beers share these characteristics i do n't know , but if they ever did beef 'em up a little , they could truly be a contender .

tasted in mid-may 2009. nearly opaque , black/brown , with reddish brown on the edges under the light . great lacing , forming curtains in the latter half of the glass .  it was creamy with an average carbonation level and also average alcoholic strength ( 6.0 % abv ) . overall : awful .

this is where this beer truly shines . sweet brown sugar and candied fruits - i thought of cherries and apricot - are met head-on by the alcohol . the result is a rich , warm , somewhat medicinal elixir that was just wonderful to inhale . do n't get me wrong - it 's very nice . it just did n't quite live up to the advance billing . very nice .  a bit thin , but a very good stout flavor develops in the mouth . i 'd have preferred a bit fuller body .
appearance : clear gold with a mammoth head , slow fading , lightly hazed body . looks good .  nicely carbonated .
aromas are awesome . i can smell this for a couple of feet away .  the carbonation is nice throughout . thinner than expected also .

classic pride look - inviting transparent brown body with a reasonably large head , albeit casked up suds . leaves superb lace on the glass . awesome .  initial taste of a sparkling mouthfeel with a puckering sour cherries that coat the mouth incredabily . the palate duration is average . medium body .

the best thing about magic hats roxy rolles is the appearance , a dark ruby brown color with a creamy burnt tan head .  tart and dry feel , but not overly so . lower carbonation detracts a little , really the only flaw in my mind .

from the nitro-can , started as a full glass of thick , creamy foam . slowly the foam turned over from bottom to top revealing a deep yellow beer with a steady half-inch foamy white cap .  mouthfeel : surprisingly thin body , full carbonation , fairly thick coat after the swallow .

s : bright fruit , almonds , yeast , nutmeg , and delicate toast round out this great smelling saison . t : begins with off-dry fruit -- apricots , grapes , and lemons -- slightly acidic .  too much carbonation for this style ( -1.0 ) .

see-thru orange with a massive frothy head that does n't leave crazy amounts of lacing , but is to be commended for its excellent retention .  if i had to log a complaint , it would be that this stout is too thin and less of a cream offering . however , it is full of flavor and easy to drink despite being 6.5 % abv .

very very unique beer , the nose right off the bat informs you of it . rich aroma of the carmel malts used , very heavy scent , but goes along nicely with the character of the porter . really good on a cold day in warm house kind of beer .  m : flat , slick , and that 's it . not quite watery , but pretty close .

three floyds beers have a unique aroma . the hops come across , thick and flowery . ive heard they use amarillo and columbus hops for aroma . many brewers could learn from these folks . milk chocolate , coffee , a little toasted malt with just a mild flowery hop flavor on the finish . slick , smooth and rich mouth feel , very nice , very drinkable .  it went down smooth with a little bite in the after taste .

smell is immensely yeasty with hints of clove , orange , and vanilla . decent nose if you ask me .  this is very malty at the opening with a twinge of caramel . upon downing it , the taste resembles a very dark beer . very malty with heavy caramel presence that makes it a bit sweet . it also gives a bitter character that mellows into a sweetened deal . i 'll have to try it from the mug in the near future . it may turn out differently due to more carbonization released , making it less bitter , dare i venture to say . but , straight from the bottle , it is easier to imbibe if you 're used to dark , bitter ales .

g : erdinger weizen glass a : dark chesnut bpdy , some light escapes around the edges of the glass . there is three fingers of thick creamy off-white head with good retention .  light feel with lots of carbonation .

it smells like a beuatiful blend of the ng belgian red cherry aspect and a very nice gueze . well done .  mouthfeel is a little bit stingy , but from the carbonation and not the alcohol , otherwise the liquid is the right viscosity and creams up ok on the tongue .

a truly wonderful bouquet . taste accents of hops and light fruits , again pineapple , with a delayed afterthought of hops bitterness at the back of the throat . a tasty and sexy organic brew .  m. a little too sticky , it feels syrupy , but without a sweeter taste it fells a little off .

really lovely to look at .  wow this has to be one of the worst ideas in beer history . trying to cross a pale ale with a belgian and what you got is something that is a distant cousin to both . instead of leveraging the style 's strengths this beer doubles down on their worst attributes . a very hoppy tatse that fights like a strong ale . not a fun beer and a true shame that it might discredit weyerbacher 's other great beers .

very sweet aroma as if a tripel plus fauna , citrus and a spiciness i ca n't define .  the mouthfeel of the beer was , like most porter and ale styles , very average . however , the mouthfeel did not detract from the overall feel of the beer .
it is as black as pitch . a nice , pillowy thick 2 finger head formed and stayed for the whole beer .  m - slightly thin and sweet .

body is a pretty golden amber color , crowned by a good amount of thick white head that leaves some good lacing on the glass .  m/d - mouthfeel is nothing special , the steely hop bite takes a bit away .

the nose on this one is very strong . some pineapple , orange zest , and grapefruit along with some floral and piney notes . if this tastes as good as it smells , i 'm in for a sweet , citrusy treat . the taste is , unfortunately , not as juicy as the nose might suggest .  ambrosial start , lots of malt , the top skimpy in feel with the finish having a delightful hop spicy bite , the carbonation moderate and the aftertaste droughty and long lasting .
it 's an awesome smelling stout !  rich flavor in a thin body -- well not that thin , but certainly less than most bocks ( not to mention doppels ) .

aroma smells a lot like centennial and amarillo hops - a touch of tangerine and bubble gum mixed in with the grapefruit and pine . i love it . flavor is fairly sweet up front , with good piney notes , and a strong grapefruit bitterness in the finish . as it is , it 's still really good .  perfect carbonation but that thin , light mouthfeel is where this beer falls a little flat .

the nose has a nice strong hoppy and fruity-peachlike aroma .  not sure if our north american brethren appreciate this but this is , as far as i can tell the first fairly widely available american style ipa brewed in the uk . the american craft brewing industry which has been accused of being derivative is really starting to influence europe which is great . i am all for my uk brewing industry but i do get a little board of the vast variety of often samey real ale bitters populating manypubs . we definitely have a shortage of hopheads brewing in the uk ! and before anyone shoots me down , greene king ipa is not an ipa ! ! !

it has the wonderful spicy aroma that the style should always have . slight phenols , cloves , a sweet bready malt and a beautiful underlying fruitiness are all there . it finishes very very clean and does n't linger at all .  flavor is absolutely nothing like an oud bruin .
lots of lacing sticks to the glass as well , damn good looking beer .  m - medium/light body with little carbonation good with spicy food .
a - pours black with a creamy tan head that dissipates fairly quickly to a thin , but dense , covering . good amount of lacing left behind .  less fizzy than anticipated in the mouth .

smell : this is an outstanding smelling beer . floral , hoppy and piney with a hint of grapefruit and orange . overall : if this beer tasted as good as it smelled and felt as good as it looked it would be one of the best in the world . it is still pretty good , but not what it could have been .  had this during o'briens wet hop festival . pours clear orange with a white ring of bubbles . lots of caramel with some tropical hops in the nose . kind of like a fruitcake . earthy , yet citrusy in the taste . bit sweeter than your normal ipa . grapefruit and blood orange . good stuff .
a deep golden pour teams with a fluffy cream head . good head retention and great lacing . very sexy served in a tulip .  the mouthfeel , i was not so impressed with .

pours to a very dark brown , only slightly ruby colored liquid with a massive fluffy white head that coats the entire circumference of the glass in a perfect frilly victoria 's secret crotchless panty-style lacing . she really is quite sexy looking .  i found that the beer smelled and tasted rather skunky , unlike most other beers that i had tasted and was deeply disappointed by it . it felt ok in the mouth and looked very nice in its green bottle but was not worth my time .

wonderfully hoppy scent with a citric , floral edge . notes of toffee and orange in the aroma . taste does n't quite live up to the aroma , but overall a nice , easy-drinking harvest ale .  heavy hops , but not totally unbalanced . very quenching .

pours a deep chestnut brown , with a layer of foamy white goodness on top . laces amazingly . the more beers i try from this brewery the more i realize they sure know how to make a beer look good .  m - not as thick as i 'd like it to taste considering how rich the smell is . d - very drinkable , with the lighter mouthfeel it 's easier to forget how much you 've had .

it pours midnight black with a huge , dark coffee-with-milk mead that does n't die easily and when it does , it leaves lacing thicker than most beers have head .  thanks to ncvbc for this great extra best by 12/31/08 bottle poured into my sniffer produced a good fingers worth of tan head that turns into a ring of lace around the glass on top of a jet black body aromas of toasted malts , coffee and chocolate with a slight funk ( i 'm glad i am not the only one to pick it up i though my nose was going ) earthiness , sweat malts , light chocolate , molasses good balance of flavors the only real complaint is it is a little thin for a stout good drinkability i could drink a few of these a night easy .

down to my last g'knight so i felt the need to review this beauty and hopefully it wo n't be long before i can get more . i 'll never forget the first time i popped one of these open , the smell was amazing , i could drink it straight from the can . pure sweetness in the nose , a bit of resiny hops , caramel , cake , so sweet you can taste it .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with likely carbonation . that , and the over carbonated pour make this beer a something i would not recommend .

s - sweet raspberry , cherries and candied sugars . t - very sweet , like a slightly sour cherry soda , there is a bit of raspberry and light malt .  m : mouthfeel is decent , goes down reasonable smooth even with the slight burning sensation .

i had it at the bruery out of a bottle , poured into their tulip glass . the head held strong , and had an attractive texture , the color , an attractive bright beer-colored beer .  it was a little thin .

has a very dry champagne-like smell ripe with musty cherries , smells like they 've been sitting in a dank barrel for a while . very appealing smell . overall medium body , slightly tart , cloys in a big way .  hate to say it , but the bottle/case i have is absolutely awful . other than a hint of coriander spice all i got was an overwelming sourness that made this one of the few i had to pour down the drain . they obviously put wayyy too much orange peel in their mix . if you can get past the sourness it is par for a wit bier course . i 'm hoping this was a bad/expired batch because ... .as far as mill street goes imo , stick to the coffee porter ...

wow , this smells hoppy . i have never smelled this amount of hops in an ris , i get a lot of really citrusy hops , maybe some toasty chocolate under it , but the hops dominate , wish i could know when this was bottled . it is really interesting though .  very pleasant indeed . great hop character . this is a fairly balanced ipa . hard to say , it might just be because this particular bottle is more on the room temp side , but i would like more effervescence . a good beer all in all . i will be sure to drink it again , only a little colder and faster . more drinking , less typing ... .
impressive looking beer .  could use both more body and carbonation .

the scent on this beer is very sweet . tons of grapefruit and orange come through very strongly . also get a lot of alcohol in the nose . upon first sip , i get so much thrown at me at once . the hops are a bit overwhelming , as well as the booziness .  mouthfeel is pretty good , but a little on the watery side for a chocolate/dessert beer . with the abv at 6 % and the body a little thinner than other chocolate stouts , one could have a couple of these in one night .

bottle- color of dark orange , with a decent off white head - nose of fresh hops , pine , mint , resin , cannabis , and slight malts taste of fresh hops , slight mint , resin , cannabis , and slight malts - body is smooth , but too watery , and with low to medium carbonation aftertaste of some metallic , hops , and resin  there 's a bit of a hop presence in the finish as a lingering bitterness runs along the side of the tongue . finishes pretty clean , with a little lingering of the hops present , but otherwise very dry . a very drinkable , light beer . perhaps more of a hop presence than other beers like this that i 've had .

liquid is jet black . even when exposed to a light .  the flavor too is ever so slight wine barrel aging with a weird and awkward type sour . it 's really off putting . this barrel aging was awful . this beer is weak and severely overrated . it was awful both times .

a : pours a pale yellowish amber color with frothy white head and lots of lacing on the glass s : smells like major hops , citrus , grapefruit , some pine ... the usual great dipa scents t : tastes just like the smell , but the hops are less prevalent that i expected .  m - ok and average .

: ( looks and smells awesome . dark chocolate color with a small tan head that does n't stick around for too long . this smelled of chocolate before i even managed to get my nose near the glass . smells like hershey 's . i really really wanted to like this beer , but it was tough to get through the bottle and i was sharing it . if only it tasted like it smelled , this would have been great .  m - lots of carbonation maybe bordering on too much .

a big floral hop aroma -- smells great . taste is bitter hopiness , floral and citrus .  5/5 m : medium body and smooth . the lighter body makes it sit not-too-heavy , and it would be easy to partake of a few of these on a cold night .

a : pours a dark black with a massively thick mocha head that seems to last forever ... excellent lacing throughout .  the carbonation is moderate high . i think it is a bit high for the style but the carbonation does not take anything away from the beer .

s - huge pine aroma that is quickly and easily enjoyable . massively beautiful from the get-go , with underlying citrus notes . a perfect , varied aroma that promises wonderful delights within t - slight pine taste , bit of grapefruit , pure hops abound . d - very nice , but perhaps lacking a bit of malt balance making this a bit more difficult to enjoy .  the first time i had this beer , i distinctly remember it being among the worst i had ever had . apparently my ba colleagues disagree , so i 'm giving it another try . there is some faint grassy hops , but this beer is mostly about the malt character . overall , this is way better than i remember . i might have to make this a regular part of my beer fridge ! or perhaps they had n't figured things out when the brewery was just getting started . glad that there 's another quality beer in e-town .
bottle poured into a glass a : a rich and frothy off white head with great lacing and retention .  m : medium viscosity , acidic early and slightly syrupy on the palate , with moderate carbonation .

bottle ( 2011 ) port bottle shop carlsbad , ca dark black with no clarity throughout . thick and persistent light brown head and plenty of spiderweb lacing down the glass .  medium-bodied , maybe just a little bit thin .
pours liquid gold and with a huge porcelain head .  mouthfeel : hoppy and rough , but a bit fuzzy .

swirling it around in my goblet , the word `` viscous '' somes to mind . i could smell this from across the room ... potent begins to describe it . dense raisin juice , port , sherry , cooking wine , soy sauce ... all these come to mind . i 'm glad i got to try some .  mouthfeel : pretty thick and a little syrupy . i 'd actually like a little more carbonation .

s : smells delicious . tart fruit all over the place . fairly satisfying . m : huge carbonation level makes it just a tad unpleasant , but not so much so that i dont still enjoy the beer overall .  small bubbles , slightly thin .

4.5 s : smells delicious ! smells like a smoked pig wrapped in bacon . the smoke covers it up like it covers up everything else . very nice . 4.0 m : heavier medium body .  i think if the mouthfeel was better it would have made a world of difference imo .

an impressive nose . t : mouth puckering bitterness is the first thing i noticed . d , notes : this is very good . the type of beer that bas help move to the best of list .  cons : the low carbonation level does hurt many factors of the beer , but it is such an exquisitely brewed offering , it 's only a minor issue .

smells like apples , tastes like hops . very tasty . the fragrance certainly did not match the taste , which is a good thing .  somewhat smooth feel , moderate-medium body for amber , but still feels a little thin .
aromas are deliciously grapes , plums , candied sugars , and lots of fresh mild fruits .  m : somewhat thick , bread-y . but smooth .

smell : the smell is excellent . the bourbon comes through in the form of vanilla and a touch of oakiness . it is exceptionally tasty and smells fantastic , but i am having a very hard time getting over the mouthfeel .  m - i did n't think the mouthfeel enhanced this brew . too softly carbonated ; not flat , just a bit wimpy .

c : thick and dark h : jet black n : hellllooo cognac ! hints of coffee and roasted malt huge thanks to hopscotch for sharing this barrel aged treat that is good till 2020 ? really ? will the world still be in existence in 2020 ? did you order an imperial stout with your cognac ? this approach is often reversed by brewers , as people like to have the abv hidden in big beers .  the mouthfeel is a little off , too light and thin .
s- i love the smell , the faint raspberry aroma is delicious . t- the taste is okay , weak raspberry flavor give way to a bland wheat taste .  m - a bit high on carbonation and thin in body .

the smell is bright and strong . lots of clover but also a healthy dose of lemon and banana . it is a quintessential hefeweizen smell . the body is a bit weak .  the mouthfeel is thiner but still good .

pours a dark cola brown with hints of plum . finger of cake like head leaves small islands of lace down the side of the leffe chalice .  mouthfeel is slightly thin for the style or maybe just thin for how much is going on there ... .like you are expecting more of a stout mouthfeel .

smell : strong citrus aroma boasting orange , pineapple and sappy resin . they really knocked it out of the park in the smell , what an inviting and pleasing scent . has west coast written all over it . overall : a pretty impressive brew from cisco brewers .  the only knock here is that it was a little thin . m = is it possible to be creamy and watery at the same time ?
absolutely lovely . very inviting .  under carbonated and somewhat thin bodied , there is a coffee flavored finish that is truly amazing .

pours a very deep brown from a 550ml bottle with a two finger head that retains . it 's opaque and pushes pitch black .  trying to think of a sweet red wine , not one i can place , but its defintely tannic , bitter and sweet ... the taste is super interesting , not say its good , but interesting . chocolate wine comes to mine , light feel though . what i do know is that 8 months is too long as it totally changes the beer into something new losing almost all stout character .

a - translucent , super vibrant golden straw color that could illuminate a room . finger eggshell ( always wanted to work that color into a review ! ) head with a nice bubbly ring and a thin white film of bubbles remains on the surface .  body is very thin for a dipa , medium carbonation .

boozy aroma with vanilla and oak apparent , notes of toffee and coconut , roast and chocolate , faint licorice and figs . great texture , full without being heavy , moderate carbonation that provided an airy mouthfeel , a bit of astringency from the kilned grains and wood , slightly sticky .  m : mouthfeel was alright , moderately carbonated and a medium body . nothing too special .

a= a hazy orangish amber color with an enourmous off white creamy head with amazing lacing and retention . really nice looking s= fruity for sure .  m - very thin body , decent mouthfeel , but not great for the style .

the smell had a distinct piney hops character - lots of spruce needles . also present in abundance were the usual line-up of spices anchor employs ; clove , nutmeg , cinnamon , and molasses .  blue moon gran cru is a great choice for all blue moon fans . tastes similar to blue moon , but with a much bolder taste . its a shame its a limited edition brew , and it was quite pricey as well , but somehting worthy to pick up once to try . appearance : it was the golden color of blue moon , but appered to be unfiltered , but there was much more sediment then most unfiltered beers smell : not a bad smell , but nothing speical either taste : great taste , similar to blue moon , but much stronger , what is there not to love about that
that creamy two finger nitro head looks damn sexy .  m - it 's a bit thin for the style .

this pours out the same deep orange color as the last one with the same solid fluffy head , lacing , etc . as appearance goes , there is nothing left to improve upon .  m - nothing special . just a regular lager thing .
pours a gorgeous dark caramel in the glass , with a nice thick tan head .  m : a bit light in the mouth , but it kind of coats your mouth as well .

i really enjoyed this one . perfect copper looking beer .  feels quite creamy at first , almost in a draft-stout kind of way , which struck me as odd . would rather it be crisper and a bit more carbonated , though .

the nose was the winning feature for me . it was a stunning coffee and chocolate explosion . it almost reminded me of a warm bowl of oatmeal with mocha covering it . it was a little too bitter and i really tasted the alcohol .  i know some ba 's knock this onw because its not rare or amazing but i love it . if i am in a bar that i do n't think has a lot to choose from sam adams is the first word out of my mouth . its not too expensive and tastes good for what you pay .

brett funkiness shows its face , but is n't as prominent as in others from similar varieties . like the smell , the brett funkiness is more subtle than others .  m - decent body with a bit more carbonation than i 'd like from this style .

s : smell is exceptional . tons of chocolate and brown sugar . o : a great smelling beer that just has too much alcohol taste for my palate .  the body was light and there was not enough carbonation .

nose speaks of a wonderful sweetness , malty , yeasty , and fruity , but most of all carries a unique candy-like scent . excellent . taste is malty and semi-sweet initially , with some spicy hints lingering and a bit of hop dryness .  mouthfeel : medium and semi-smooth . bottom line : this is one of the most bland beers i 've ever had .

s. plenty going on here in this one . d. a very good porter from left hand . the combination of aromas is brilliant . the taste is lighter than its 5.8 % abv .  i am starting to view the boston beer co. as a-b or miller taking a stab at the craft market but still wanting to appease the masses rather than being strict to beer styles . a big dissapointment for an apa

it pours with a clear amber body topped by a medium thick off white head with a good amount of lacing left on the glass .  slight hint of the hop flower but the malt dominates , sweet , crisp , fresh and pleasing to the senses with the start lightly sweet , satisfactory malt presence , and top light to middling in feel . this is a style where i like the lighter body , as it lets the flavoring hops shine through , quite quaffable , a damn fine session beer me thinks , and i thank royalt for this bottle .

a - pours a very clear rusty orange/chestnut brown with just a short layer of white foam that quickly disappeared s - really nice citrus aroma , mango , orange & grapefruit , really nice smelling beer t - mango , grapefruit and orange and lemon rind , there is a bit of bitterness that seems to taste like the rind not hops .  on the thin side , and i dont get much carbonation .

pours a deep burnished copper with a nice , creamy light tan head with awesome stickiness and retention , leaving plenty of lacing . aesthetically an unusually pleasing brew .  the taste is a bit light for a dunkel but definitely not as light as a typical hefewiezen . there is a malty undertone that one would expect with this type of beer . honestly , i 'm not sure why this beer is n't getting better reviews , i had a weihenstephan dunkel after it and it stood up quite well .

it really reminds me of the nose i get off a really good heffeweizen ( spelling might be wrong , but there ya go ) . it 's a bright and inviting smell and makes my mouth water .  lighter mouthfeel than expected . d - full flavor and light mouthfeel .

smells of loads of caramel , vanilla , sugar , lactose . basically like dessert . far too sweet .  crisp taste - not heavy as expected ... hints of smokey , woody flavors - has the appeal of a coffee porter ... mouthfeel is average .

smells of deep , dark chocolate and sweet milky aromas taste is rich and complex of dark rich chocolate . still an enjoyable brew although i was a little bit let down i was expecting a little more from this brew .  s - some grassy hops paired with caramel malt t - slight hop bitterness resolving into some serious roasty malt , but then it 's all gone fairly quickly with just a hint of woody bitterness m - quite light with just a hint of carbonation on the back of the tongue ; the slight bitterness endures for a whlie d - quick drinkable , though the excessive roasty malt will probably get in the way ; little to no alcohol warmth nice drink ; did n't expect it to be as dark as it is - listed as an american porter , but it 's almost a supercharged brown ale .
pours like a belgium ale , huge white 4 finger head . pale yellow in color . beer looks amazing but tastes extremely mediocre .  m full but not as full as i thought that it might be .
one of the nicest smelling dipas ( imperial pale ? ) i 've experienced t : initially starts out with lots of bitterness from the hops .  feels thin .

the head is monstrous , roaring up into a beautiful puffy column and descending slowly , leaving some nice , thick , shaving cream lacing on the way down .  mouthfeel : i 'm a bit disappointed by the mouthfeel .

the appearance was amazing ! starts out pale in color and gradually becomes oranger in a way that i have never seen in a beer .  the head vanished quickly , but the carbonation level remained high . the aroma was overwhelming sour cherries ... mouthwatering sweet aroma that shows a huge proportion of cherries used in this brew . definitely on the sugary sweeter cherry beer side .
) this brew pours a wonderful brown color .  mouthfeel is fullbodied , and slightly cloying .

s : strong hop smell with hints of citrus , apricots , and sweetness . d : an interesting ipa with the addition of the apricots .  i think i 'm a bit parial to this beer for 2 reasons . it 's not by any means a `` specialty '' beer , it 's your typical lager and since it 's been around since before any of us were born it 's got a nostalgic feel . excellent beer in my books , average for most .

poured a 2 finger fluffy light tan head with excellent retention to 1 finger cap .  with the name , you would think that this is an amber with english hops , but the banana fruitiness dominates any other flavors , even the hops disappears under the bananas . this is the mystery of rhodell 's , how can mark produce such great dipas , ipas , imperial stouts , barley wines , german style ales and lagers , but when it comes to scottish ales or amber/red ales , they all have this same . stupid , banana phenol , making them undrinkable . i dont get it .

rich with oak and dark malts , the aroma is a mine of chocolate , malted milk , coffee , molasses , figs , vanilla , walnuts , caramel , spiced with plenty of caraway , anise , tobacco , and floral hops . increasingly smoky as it warms , and very interesting ; the akavit is not subtle but well-incorporated with the base malt aromas . tangy and earthy on the palate , with a crisp caraway entrance and a long , luscious chocolate finish . juicy and rich yet sharp and bitter , this one balances coffee , citrus , licorice , oak , and red wine and yet it is n't quite as complex as the nose led me to believe . possibly an excellent match for game , assuredly for chocolate and blue cheese .  flavor is more of the same with enough body to keep the brew honest . good mix of sweet and bitter and a weaker mouthfeel that allows for more on a warm summer day .

i took a picture of it because it just looked like a perfect beer to me . that nice dark brown/black with creamy head on top just looks beautiful . not too much in the nose , little bready but nothing else jumps out at me .  yack ! i 've had this lots over the years , but this time it got a major problem with butterscotch . aroma smacks me down wth that butterscotch - ugh . but , somewhere in there is some malt and a little chocolate , good malt . flavor is butterscotch - blaaahh . ca n't finish it . draft lines are clean here too . no more , pleeeeze
a : pours a hazy dark copper/amber with orange hues . beautiful off-white head that clings moderately to the glass .  m-medium bodied with slightly more carbonation than i prefer in a porter .
appearance : the body is a cloudy gold color . the head is a slightly tan color , 3 fingers tall with great retention and lots of sticky lacing .  ) m. ok mouthfeel .

aroma : very complex . banana , clove , butter , bubblegum , and hints of alcohol .  mouth feel is thin pretty characteristic of bbc 's beers which makes this a really drinkable session stout with a lot of flavor .
huge deep malty scents , with lots of caramel and toffee and a nixe bit of earthiness , as well .  t & m : for a doppelbock a little thinner bodied than is usually expected .

appearance opaque brown/black with faint crimson edges when held up to the light . a small creamy tan head tops the beer for most of my drinking , slowly sinking to a hazy covering . lacing is a solid coating around most of the glass , impressive . i can not really taste the oysters or notice any effect they have on the beer .  mouthfeel - this seems a bit watery for my liking , and a bit light too , it does n't take away from the beer too much though luckily , still great . the carbonation seems pretty good , maybe a bit overcarbonated .

amazing . taste almost supports the smell but not to the degree i 'd hoped . if this veered away from the spicy sweetness it offers in the mouth toward the cherry vagueness of the smell i could see this being an absolutely impeccable ale .  the taste is ok. it seems a little flat coming out of the can compared to the tap . nice clean finish , no lingering aftertaste . definiteley a session beer if drinking from the tap .

poured into a 16 oz becher , a near opaque dark brown with a huge rocky head and plenty of sticking foam , truly gorgeous , then it the wheels come loose from the cart .  mouf & gt ; nice , nothing special drinkability & gt ; sure thing

canned on 10/26/2011 a : pours a deep , clear ruby color with a finger of thick light tan colored head .  this is an enjoyable , smooth but tasty strong polish lager . the aroma is fresh , toasty sweet bread , hint of lemon , pine , and rather nice . it has a bit of a czech lager taste to it and the alcohol is essentially unnoticeable . the taste is clearly alcholic , but very smoothly so , with nothing rough opr unpleasant . it has a light caramel quality , bread , and nice , warm spiciness , it 's a bit rasiniy , sweet and spicy with a light bitterness coming to the fore in the finish . it does not taste quite as strong as it is .

a : reddish brown with a half finger of lightish fizzy head , *excellent* retention . insane amounts of lacing remained on my glass thru the drink .  in the glass , the elderberry dominates . the taste just off , sour in a nasty way , more like rotten fruit than any sort of pleasant tartness which might be expected from the berries . we gave this a decent try to see if it would get better , but in the end just could n't drink it .

probably the most impressive head i have ever seen on a beer .  this beer tastes like candy hearts mixed with medicine . it smells like sour bubblegum or something to that effect . coloring is actually pink.. which is unusual . definitely trying to appeal to females with the label , but even as a female.. i thought it was gross . that 's all i 'm going to say .

its pale golden liquid is filled with lively bubbles cascading to the the bright long lasting white head .  the largest macro beer in the country is very disappointing . the feel of this beer is somewhat thin but i liked the bock feel that it had .

poured into a tumbler it produces a 2 inch head that persists and clings to the glass in great clumps . the appearance is perfect pale and slightly cloudy .  m : the body is light but sugary and grainy with a moderate carbonation .
one of the most refreshing smelling beers i have ever sampled .  mouth feel was pretty average , smooth , not very complex so i expected a little more from it in that department .
the nose is beautiful . i get the belgian yeastiness , and something akin to peaches served with a dash of allspice . so far it 's awesome .  seems a bit thin , with very soft carbonation .

pours with a fat thumb head , with decent stout lacing ... smell is amazing , lots of sweet bourbon and chocolate plum ... lots of bourbon upfront but it really is remarkable how enjoyable it is , despite the fact that its like sipping straight bourbon ... this beer would age soooo beautifully ! a wonderful beer that i was honored to have tried at a really fun event , but that open bar kicked my butt in the end ! !  i feel that it felt a little light on the tongue after it went down .

pours a good-looking clear deeply copper colored ale with a tight off white head . very impressive head longevity and sheeting in the glass , this has incredible looks .  m - the mouthfeel is a little light , with little carbonation .
unbelievable . taste , too has a very pronounced graham cracker taste in it , along with pumpkin , of course .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low yet sharp carbonation .
hops . a touch of skunk . excellent aroma . t- hops ( pine forward ) .  the mouthfeel is a bit astringent .

the pungency of the wheat prevents it from becoming cloying . delish . nice flavours , but some darker fruit character would n't go astray . nice . good stuff . a smorgasbord of confectionery aromas and flavours made to order for a sweet tooth .  the body is okay for a stout , but is more like a porter .

very nice ! the taste is more pronouced citrus fruit and pine that slowly reveals the malty backbone of fresh baked bread .  mouthfeel - foam is scarce and small bubbles and light caramel that fades quickly . slightly thin .

a : reddish amber color , clear , no head retention or lacing s : although you get the belgian yeast banana and spicy notes , in the background you can notice the subtle blueberry aroma of real blueberries , not some extract .  mouth is fairly prickly and somewhat detracts from the tasting . i wish there was a little less carbonation and foam here .
s : full bourbon whiskey smell as i find out of all the bruery 's barrel aged stuff . nice vanilla as well .  m : light bodied and well carbonated .

a : nearly black brown , long lasting tan head .  this is a bad beer . not only that , but its a very overpriced bad beer . it smells like grain , aluminum , and malt liquor , and tastes about the same . there 's a tea-flavor going on in there a bit as well . head was pitiful even though it came from a nitro can . a waste of money . please save your tastebuds and dont buy this garbage for 7.50 a 4-pack .

plenty of bubbles could be observed rising through the body , in short , it looked great ! the head produced somegood laceing as the beer was consumed .  this beer was purchased at cyclone liquors , in ames , iowa . the beer was very dark in color and tasted very well . i drank the beer warm and i think it was a good beer . i would try this beer again if it was presented to me . it had a very nice sweet taste for a german dunkel , which i am not a huge fan of .
smell is very hoppy , very floral .  mouthfeel starts lite , then fullbodied . alcohol and carbonation are a little over-pronounced .

very powerful sweet aroma . overall : fantastic beer , will definitely get again .  mouthfeel : the carbonation seems oddly low , but the body is medium light which gives the beer a little bit of oomph that it needs .

that being said the banana scent is there just beneath the other two , along with an almost dry wheaties scent.very enticing . overall : a solid , thirst quenching beer with a wonderful smell and decent flavor.it 's not my favorite in the style but i 'll drink it again for sure .  md-light body and sharp moderate carbonation . foamed pretty good going down the drain .
there is tons of lacing as well . this beer is a very pretty one .  mouthfeel is a bit of a problem for me . the carbonation level is also a factor , making it hard to enjoy in gulps .

750 ml bottle poured into a tulip glass . pours a cloudy corn silk hue with a pillowy cloudy white two finger head . super sticky on the sides with a head that sticks around forever .  the mouthfeel was the only thing that detracted from the beer in my opinion , as i found it to be a little to watery for my personal preference .
a lovely jet black stout color , with a decent froth , though the carbonation is rather light .  mouthfeel is medium thin , with a little less carbonation than i would have liked .

very dark ruby red colored body with tightly knit khaki colored head .  while the champagne-like extreme dryness may put off some , i think it makes the beer truly unique and tasty as opposed to unblanced .

cranberry nose with traces of brett-like peppery suede funkiness ( either from the kombucha or actual brett ) , black cherry , dried peaches , honey , and cider . it 's one of the most distinct and delicious smelling beers i 've come across in a while . it 's clever enough to inspire analysis , while still being relatively drinkable , in spite of the co2 struggles .  mouth feel : a bit thin on the palet , or maybe the aroma and taste make you expect more in the way of mouth feel .

the first thing that struck me about this stout was the aroma , very complex , almost sweet , with what i thought could have been vanilla among other things . the # 1 surprise was the texture and consistency of this beer , i was expecting something much thicker , more like guiness , and boy was i surprised , a much smoother , lighter consistency with a great taste and just enough flavor to let you know you are drinking something quality without being over whelming . it took me more time to get a good overall sense of this stout then i would have expected , a compliment to the complexity of the flavor .  mouthfeel is a bit of a letdown.. crisp but not as crisp as i had hoped . overall drinkability is good , the taste makes up for what it lacks in mouthfeel .

sweet banana like smell with a bit of spice . i really like this beer , but it 's pretty heavy and very robust and powerful .  i can feel it in my cheeks . it does n't have any off aromas specifically , but it definitely has the acidity for it . undrinkable , i 'm pouring it out .

the aromas are magnificent ! espresso coffee as if fresh brewed .  the beer must have been very old , but it 's the brewery 's fault for the green bottle . i took one sip and thought of pouring it out , but then realized i could pretend it was really good and get my friend to try it . he promptly ran to the sink to wash his mouth out . yes , it was that bad . unless you 're positive it 's fresh , do n't buy this beer . i have never had a worse experience .

it pours as close to a pitch black without actually being pitch black . great head retention so this really has it all going on in appearance .  my first impression was the color . the color was an impressive dark brownish ruby . the smell was sweet malt and fruit . the taste had definite apple/apple peel flavors going on .

quickly diminished head , but holds glass well ar - beautiful cascade hops aroma ! i 'm a sucker for that .  a : solid black , modest lacing even at the beginning , but once the beer was gone so was the lacing s : malty , chicory , lingers nicely t : dominated by coffee ; bitter stout ; the oak comes through nicely ; not very complex m : casked , so it does n't really buzz in the mouth overall , a really good beer , but not as complex as i was hoping ; still , very worthwhile

a : ca n't really take anything away from this one , perfect tan head on top of a pitch black body .  perhaps another way to explain the feeling would be a textured shandy . noting the high praise this saison received , i have trouble fathoming such a bad experience .

break out the smoked sausage , the perfect beer to accompany it is here . alaskan smoked porter is beautifully smokey . one whiff makes you think you 're in a great deli , loaded w/ good smoked sausage .  body seems quite thin for an imperial stout .
put it under bright light and it looks magnificent in my flute !  mouthfeel - smooth , yet a litle effervescent .
pours a slightly hazy , deep copper with a 3-finger thick , frothy light yellow head . lots of lacing .  m-lots of carbonation -- almost too much actually . a little more watery than you 'd expect .

smell : wow ... i was n't expecting this at all . incredibly hoppy , honey , almost strawberry jam sticky hop smell . taste : i found it a little too watery at first , which was a dissapointment . another intriguing brew with an awful label from ray mcneil .  again , dried dark fruit seems to be the dominating taste , and as it warms , a sweet cherry-like flavor comes in m : at first i found this beer a bit too prickly and highly carbonated for my liking ; i purposely agitated the beer by swirling and enjoyed it a bit more when carbonation was less severe great beer that i would drink anytime i needed a belgian fix .

a - pours a deep mahogany color with an inch of fluffy golden head . so far great .  the nose is caramely and very malty . a little too carbinated for a traditional barleywine but lines ones gut like the best of the bunch ! being a sucker for barleywines i have to give this beer high remarks .

s : intense volatile pine , fresh grass , lightly toasted bread -- a very attractive , yet clean , smell . d : this ipa is a lightweight when it comes to taste , featuring a flavor profile that just ca n't live up to the remarkable smell . clean flavor qualities are taken too far at times , with only the finish really representing the style faithfully . it is genuinely appealing to sniff and to gaze upon , though .  a bit watery on the body .
s : big pumpkin with plenty of spices . d : not as good as pumpking but still pretty good .  a bit more body would 've made this an excellent brew .

very nice . smells light , not expecting much malt in the flavor . where are all those delicious hops i smelled ? as with many ipas , i find that it smells better than it tastes .  just the right amount of hops . even though you can taste the fruits and spice , you can also taste the high alc % . drinkability : very drinkable , but if you more than one in a session , watch out : ) overall : a better than average tripel .

espresso and chocolate aromas , with hints of vanilla , roast and brownies , quite the vibrant little blend of malt aromatics . slightly bitter and astringent malt , but still decadent and enjoyable , with chocolate and cream flavors .  not amazing but for everyday you ca n't beat it . its good year round and drinking a bunch of them . it is n't expensive either . amber coloration , ok head and lacing , some hops but mostly malt . not overly heavy but not watery . i know the beer snobs disparage it but it does n't have to be sophisticated to be enjoyed .

smell : strong coffee notes over roasted malt . fairly straight forward but the limited dimensions it offers are good in their own right . taste : fairly waterly coffee rinds .  there is a very little carbonation factor in this beer .
smell : fantastic , lots of citrus , pine and bubble gum . it is decently balanced but could use some more malt backbone .  the body is light but somewhat creamy .
a - black , inch and half of tawny head . leaves amazing lacing that should be in a museum as art .  4.5 m - lacks body . a bit thin but spritzy carbonation .

hints of orange and lemon dance around the intense aged oak notes , giving this beer an amazingly original and interestingly complex nose . wow . flavor is much as would be expected after the nose . sweetness rivals the heftiest of wheatwine honey-sweetness you 've experienced .  mouthfeel is average , with enough body to carry the flavors , but is approaching watery at times .

s : smells phenomenal ! booze , oak , and sweet sugars upfront . breadiness on the backend . t : good . not great . has a nice boozy / oakiness to it , not a whole lot else .  m. feel is not bad , light crisp well carbonated .

s- it has a nice nutty character absent form most stouts i 've had . hazelnut and almonds combine with a bit of roasted malt and some coffee to make a nice aroma .  mouthfeel is a little too weak for my tastes , and is the only fault i can find with this brew .

poured into a de molen sniffer . smell : great nose , full of dark chocolate , slight sour cherry , bourbon and vanilla taste : great taste as well , this beer is very complex and still very balanced . the smell and taste are wonderful , for me it seems an attempt of the molen to produce their own cuvee delphine from struise .  well , so ... if it 's a barleywine or imperial or whatever , well ... then it 's probably thin on the mouth , eh ?
odell 's red ale came out of the bottle an awesome red color with a fluffy off white head .  mouthfeel was a bit thin , but the taste was clean and minty on the tongue .

a - poured completely ink black . appears thick and viscous . a small amount of light brown head formed and receded quickly .  actually thought it might be bad but when i drank it there was plenty of carbonation . smell : a toasted malty smell with an almost cardboard smell . taste : very strong toasted smell but more of a bitterness then a sweetness . note : no date on the bottle but wondering if this beer had gone bad . will try another attempt at it but not really looking forward to it .

it poured caramel brown in color with a big , fluffy and frothy off-white head to it . a thin , frothy layer remained covering the beer well into drinking it and left some great lacing as well . exceptional looking barleywine overall .  m - pretty watery and thin .

very sexy . s - great smell , definitely get a heavy does of burnt chocolate , some roasted coffee and other malts . great example of roasted scents . i would gauge that there was a spectacular effort put into tempering this brew to get these scents from the malts . i like sours but certainly not mixed with this style . very bitter as you will note from almost every review but this one had an almost sour milk character that turned me off during my dinner which was centered around beef .  thanks walter a-a nice rich amber , good head , some lacing that turned into a small bubble ring s-a slight bready smell , some citrus ( makes me think of citra hop ) slight sweetness and then tart t- close to the same as the smell , there is a slight tangyness in the middle of the drink , it 's a good thing m- it 's moderately lively not as much bite and tingle i was expecting , a clean wet finish o/d- overall i really like this , it 's not the craziest ipa but it 's more than just decent , drinkability , i can see myself finishing this growler , this is a tasty beer and one i really like
pours out to a very milky pale golden , forming a rocky white head with superior retention and very nice lacing .  decent palate , a little thin like the others in the series , but fairly smooth .
this brew pours an opaque black color . the head is large , and fluffy with a color of white speckled with tan .  very good . sort of on the thin side , but still ok. a good drinker .

aroma is unusual and very pleasant : something akin to meadowland following a spring shower blended with a peatiness and cooked vine fruits .  nothing to write home about when it comes to mouthfeel . kind of a club-soda feel to the beer , tingly . though there seems to be a strange `` romanian roulette '' effect where every sixth beer is kinda soapy .

s - from the first crack of this beer , the smell is great . fruits are in the forefront , with a bit of bitterness . great smell , i do n't think it gets a whole lot better than this . this is still a phenomenal tasting beer , but comparing it to the smell , it lacks a bit . m - mouthfeel is good , slightly syrupy and the bitterness fades at a good rate . overall , this beer is great . i 've had it several times and i have found that if you let it sit for a while , the bitterness dies out a bit , but the fruitiness goes with it .  the wood tannins come across and make this beer texturally difficult . it 's rough and gritty for a mouthfeel .

a : aptly yclept schwarzbier ( blackbeer ) -- dark opaque black with a frothy head and a ruddy hue around the edges . i like the way this looks . s : not much at all .  taste is weak but odd at the same time with a mild rice-sweetness . this is the kind of beer you can share with your friends because most do n't appreciate the imports anyway . i drank plenty of this is my younger days ... when you look up headache in the dictionary it reads `` drink 12 budweisers and take a nap .

when i first opened the bottle i could smell the cherrys right away . it was a very sweet smell which suprised me that the beer was not as sweet as the smell . very nice appearance .  this is almost as good a stout as they come . i like guinness extra stout better because it has more bitterness . but this stout is smooth and easy to drink with a nice bitterness . if you are looking for a stout to bring to a party this is a good one because it is not too bitter . almost everyone i have served this to has liked it .

s. malty , with a hint of hops . most distinctive is a strong spice scent . t. sweet , and again malty and spicy , with the hops much more prominent than in the smell .  ) my only qualm was the the body seemed a little thin .

this is just perfect . pine and citrus are both detectable . but ... ahhh , it smells so good !  mf- raw resinous and sticky , becoming oily , medium carbonation , slightly astringent , dry and grainy in the finish d- well rounded ipa , but not the best around .

this porter poured very dark , with about 2 fingers of just off white head . there was fantastic lacing left on the glass .  taste : sweet malt , raisins , a lot of sweet nutty flavors like pecans , sour/tart dark cherry flavor , ending with a nutty malt characters mouthfeel : really light body , low carbonation , pretty basic .

aromas were fantastic : bready , citrus-fruit and cloves were wonderfully balanced . it was not too strong , but the aromas were apparent .  finishes with a sweet malt taste m- medium bodied with decent carbonation , not as full for an octoberfest as i 'd like but still good d- very drinkable and easy to use to introduce others to a seasonal beer
aroma is piney and citrusy hops .  the taste is awesome m : medium bodied , perhaps a bit too heavy , with decent carbonation , not the best , but is good enough for an apa .

it pours a cloudy golden orange color and smells delicious . the nose had hints of orange peel , coriander , hops and light caramel . drinkability was a little low though due to the over carbonation and the sweetness of the beer overall , but very good . will buy again  m : not as creamy as the better oatmeal stouts out there . still above average for a dark beer , but expected more from the style .

served in a nonic pint glass , the beer pours a clear gold color with a 2 inch frothy white head after an aggressive pour . head retention and lacing are both pretty good .  magic hat usually disappoints me , not that their brews are n't good , it 's that some of them just are n't tasty- till now . magic hats roxy rolles is right up there with ithaca 's cascazilla and troegs hopback amber . a definite seasonal must have for me . great ! ! !

the head very slowly fades to a 1 cm cap atop this impenetrably black brew , leaving beautiful , copious lacing everywhere . perfection in appearance .  it also takes a hit because while it looks thick , it feels a bit thinner than it should be .

the aroma is very roasty and has plenty of chocolate notes . smells very nice .  in my opinion , flying dog brewery has created a great seasonal , smooth-tasting beer with very little bite or after taste . i would definitely recommend it to any self-respecting beer drinker who might be having an end-of-summer party this or any october .

underneath is roasted chocolate malt , light vanilla , and citrus , providing good complementary variety .  m - a little lighter and sparkly than i 'd like at first ... the more it warms and dies down , the better it gets .
pours clear , bright amber with a tenacious head ... got ta love those hop oils .  taste : mirrors the smell , but the flavors are weaker than their aroma counterparts because of a thin mouthfeel .

aroma is crisp blend of citrus and hops slightly sweet , wonderful . best part of the beer do do n't drink this on out of the bottle pour it or you will miss out .  m -- light carbonation . good body with a lightly soft mouthfeel .

really good . t : milder than the smell , with a taste of mostly apples and cider , creamy caramel , and a mild woody gin finish .  the feel is a little odd . it does n't seem to be too carbonated , but the bubbles sting like sprite against your lips .
very good aroma ! taste : smooth and malty but not too much . a bit of a let down after a very nice aroma .  malty and corny .

a : pours a beautiful bronze with ruby highlights . this beer looks fantastic . s : smell is of juicy citrusy hops , with an abundant dose of pale and caramel malt .  medium to thick body , light almost too light level of carbonation with a sweet almost sticky mouthfeel .
wonderful caramel , butterscotch aroma with a delicate spiceness .  it 's light on body , and not especially interesting - but as fruit beers go , this was excellent .

smells and looks like a hefeweizen . tastes banana , tropical . citric . extremely refreshing , great summer beer .  the last 2/3 of my beer was a bit thin , but this was quite refresing and very easy to drink .
very inviting . as the bottle says ... dark and dreamy . leaves rich foamy rings and walls of lacing .  mouthfeel is a little thin , though .

a - gigantic frothy head that is the color of latte foam . the head lingers for an eternity and leaves a mountain of foam in the middle after it has dissipated to constant level . top notch look for a red . looks good though .  m- thin to medium in body . highly attenuated with a soft carbonation .

s - wow , what a blast of aromas : floral notes , pine and citrus smack you in the face . t - it tasted of spicy , piney hops with a sweet , burnt toast maltiness . it is extremely hoppy and fairly easy drinking considering the high abv .  overwhelming carbonation cuts through initial malt goodness , temporarily undermining a tasty complex malt profile .

s : strong piny medicinal hop kick , very strong and spicy floral aromas with a bit of grapefruit rind mixed in , there is also a lightly detectable sweet and grainy maltiness hiding in the wings here as well , very fresh smelling . t/mf : this is were i was a bit disappointed after such a nice nose . d : very nice and fresh and strong hop aroma but that is where the goodness ends for me . still there are worse ipas out there than this one .  mouthfeel is really my only disappointment , as the beer is overall pretty watery . the body feels thin , as the carbonation is there after pouring , but quickly disappears .

the aroma was that of raisins smothered in chocolate , dried plums and cherries and some alcohol . a chocolatey start that gives way to dried fruits ( rasins and plums ) mixed with some bitterness .  mouthfeel : both the carbonation and body are on the higher end of the light range .

i was afraid since this beer emphasized bacon , that it would be like an overly smoked beer that gave a nitrate like amora , but this one is balanced nicely . road tar , malted barley , honey ham , rubber , and charred hickory . absolutely awesome . t- the taste is light and pleasant .  tastes like an aged beer , its very dry and cuvee-like . significant hops.its wierd but it does smell like a barleywine . a bit undewhelming mouthfeel.there was some problem with foam in the taps , and maybe if i had this in the wee hours . still good .
true amber in color with perfect clarity .  it goes down smooth .

s -- amazing smell of dark chocolate and roasted coffee , no sweetness to it , but very pleasant . t -- the coffee in the smell comes through the strongest , with a hint of the chocolate .  this feels thin for some reason . carbonation is good and proper .
nice hop aroma right off the bat . very piney and resiney .  has a very light mouth feel , which makes it a more-then-one beer .
perfect deep burgundy in color with a large , creamy and dense head of light tan foam .  medium bodied and dry .

t : after the aroma onslaught , the hoppiness on the palette is rather subdued . still nicely bitter , with a good pine , grapefruit , bitter orange flavor . d : the aroma is a bit of a tease , but the taste does n't entirely disappoint - certainly a beer i could have again .  smell is a cross between musty and estery at first , then just corn . tastes like corn , but considerably worse than a typical macro . it has some off flavors , that i ca n't really identify . bad .
a fairly large ( nearly two finger ) head of light brown foam sits atop . an ominous looking brew .  like cheap malt liquor infused with citrus and nail polish remover .

very citrusy grassy hoppy aroma . nice tangerines and grapefruit mixed with oily grassy hop . really runs the gambit of all the hop aromas nicely . there 's also a nice residual sweet biscuity aroma from the malt .  presentation 11.2 oz ''ceramic '' bottle with blue foil over the cap no date on bottle . pours with a think creamy head that dissipates as quickly as is rose . light brown with a hind of deep red . a smell of caramel and alcohol , taste is more of the same with a slight earthiness to it . finishes cleanly .
great , great look .  m : medium body with no carbonation . this is pretty much tap water flat . the mouthfeel is sticky with notable warming .
