multilayered rings everywhere - one of the best lace patterns i 've seen from a beer in a long while .  mouthfeel - the one noticeable drawback to this offering is the lack of carbonation . otherwise it felt very good in the mouth .

took a trip down to colorado springs last week , mainly to visit this brewery . aromas of passion fruit , grapefruit and tangerine . medium bodied , and not at all bitter , with flavors of oak , booze and sweet malt .  its perfectly balanced and not overly done . m very medium , which i find most all stone beers to be and i dont really complain about . the carbonation is present and isnt overly aggressive or submissive .
smell is nice ! !  mouthfeel is ok. fairly light body , more than i 'd think it should be at this abv .

pours with an outrageously massive head , a dense , simmering mass of eggshell brown rising over the rim of the goblet like a souffle . what a visual feast !  m : medium light body with medium high carbonation .

nuts , roasted malts , coffee , chocolate ... perfect nose . t : sweet roasted chocolate marshmellows are balanced by a more bitter chocolatey coffee . good stuff .  m - a little thinner than i imagined , though based on the aroma , i might have been expecting a double ipa .

very nice aroma , light alcohol , citrus/pine hops , dried fruit , caramel , doughy .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . starts as sour apples becomes more sour like lemon juice , dry finish ; easily the least enjoyed belgian i have had . 750ml bottle - gift from vintage cellars blacksburg , va .

s sweet and complex on the nose . honey , orange zest , and chinese 5-spice . touch of clean alcohol and fresh bread . light malt character on the backend coddles a soft alcohol note . the finish carries a rolling bitterness , and the malt that balanced the ending alcohol note slowly fades to give way to a brighter boozyness .  had a typical pilsner mouthfeel .

aroma is quite nice , very bready and doughy fresh , fresh yet browned banana , deeply soggy , kinda mushy , with a super nice splice of sweet dry nuttyness and butter . incredible aroma , but stops there and goes downhill quickly as it does n't quite have the taste and body to back it up .  i sent it back thinking it had gone bad , but the bartender tried it and assured me it was ok. m - average for a macro lager .

s - sweet complex dark stone fruits . cinnamon apple fig . with a bit of pimento . mild oaky hickory hop smells . although not as complex as the smells it is yummy .  mouthfeel was somewhat on the thin side , but still quite acceptable .
it has a wonderful smell of yeast and citrus .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with above carbonation .
s - wow . full nose of citrusy hoppy goodness .  the taste is fantastic , but the beer is a little thin and a bit hot ; not a good session beer , but great type of brew to have after a long day .

pours a pitch black with dark brown edges . fine sticky mocha colored head about an inch thick with sticky , sticky lacing . i love stouts , and i love this one .  mouthfeel is about average for an ipa .

first off is 2008 alaskan barley wine . no real visible carbonation because the beer is so cloudy . s - the nose is the best feature of this beer . there are lots of sweet dark fruits much like a dropple bock . could be more complex . t - here this beer takes a turn for the worse .  overall , i quite enjoyed this beer . it 's got a fresh and interesting taste that makes it a decent drinking beer . deliciously fruity hops , nice malt sweetness , comes across as quite fresh . noticeable taste of apricots which i quite like makes this distinctive and something i look forward to drinking . disappointing finish however . lots of interesting things happening up front and then nada . nothing really lingers which is a darn shame , 'cause overall this beer is well worth a try . still tasty after each bottle . mmmm .
a : clear copper , fluffy white head , good retention and lace .  it was n't as smooth as i expected because of a slight chalky feel in the mouth .

smells like halloween ! very welcoming . it sure is an imperial . very crisp , sexy beer . spices are rounded , clove , cinnamon , vanilla bean , and most importantly , fresh pumpkin .  this feels a bit acidic , but not too much . medium mouthfeel with a dry finish .

pours with a hefty amount of two finger thick light tan head , and has a clear copper colored body .  light bodied though , almost watery . in a way this is an ipa-light - some similar desirable flavors and aromas , but less bitterness , less alcohol , and lighter bodied .
poured with a beautiful , thick , creamy huge , fluffy , tan head with brown highlights .  m : lightly carbed , thin , slightly oily , tannic finish .

aroma is predominately belgian funk and gambrinus honey malt . flavor is pilsen , honey , and belgian aromatic malt with just enough hop to balance . yeast flavor is a very nice blend of straight belgian and brett .  it is light bodied and enjoyable . it has a light hops aroma and a light bodied feel to it .
the smell on this beer was very nice . bold citrus flavors dominate and are light and bright .  m : mouthfeel is a bit thin , considering how robust the initial flavor is .
huge head , very lasting w/big bubbles & good lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and resinous , this is really the only fault i can find .

smells awesome ; there 's an herbal hoppiness with orange/tangerine notes , some slight pine , and lots of biscuit/nutty malt with an undertone of sweet caramel . it finishes with a clean bitterness and biscuity malt .  mouthfeel is the only real negative to this one , medium bodied and a bit thinner than i 'd like .
s - cherries , orange peel , and fresh fruits combine to create an enticing aroma . a definite yeasty quality is also present .  mouthfeel was ok ; about the same as urquell .

a : beautiful pour from this 440ml nitro can . bright copper with a thick , creamy white head . great lacing left behind .  nice flavors , with a nice two-row malty sweetness and a huge piney and slight citrusy hop flavor that is very much in front ; good overall , but very unbalanced , even considering the style . goes down fine , but there is quite a bit of hop scratchiness .

very big head on this one . very big and fluffy ... looks like powdery hills of golden snow .  m -- slightly too watery , does n't really coat the mouth like i would hope but it washes down clean with no bad lingering tastes d -- this is it here , i think this is the beer i would use to introduce someone new to ipa 's .

very sharp and fruity hops , with a good amount of grapefruit and pineapple . the hops seem to disappear from the flavor , very surprising considering the aroma . the hops are more tea-like , sitting on top of a sweet bread-like malt base .  from the perfume river in vietnam ( no really , that 's what the label says ) , on to the beer : poured into a mug , it 's a clear yellow color with a soda-like head . this flavors in the beer do n't meld together well for me . there 's more cooked corn , a mild astingency , and a straightforward bitterness that battle each other for supremecy . even at ice cold , it took some work for me to stomach this beer . round off the edges and we might have something more tolerable .

s : wonderful fruity belgian goodness . caramel malty dubbel is a smell warms me up even on a hot evening . allagash has some of the nicest smelling belgians that come to mind .  decent carbonation , a little thin on the malt profile for the style .
nose is really great . a lot going on in there .  m-a bit watery for my tastes but the taste makes you forget about it being slightly thin .

smells wonderful . rich sweet pink grapefruit , pine , oranges , lemon zest . compared to the enticing smell , the flavor is quite a let-down .  m/t : light to medium body , watery and a good amount of carbonation . however with the light body , low bitterness and virtually zero aftertaste , i could session this beer .
s - mostly raspberry , which i found quite appealing . some caramel and roasted malt .  mouthfeel medium body for the style with sharp carbonation .
poured a dark hazy brown , tan head , with good retention .  mouthfeel : there is a lot of bitterness .

poured into a tulip glass . pours a deep dark chestnut brown with mahogany edges and dark golden ruby edges when held to a light source and a frothy two finger off-white head with great retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that streaks the tulip with splotches of soapy lacing .  nice carbonation , but this comes off as a little thin . this should be more drinkable considering its thin body , but as this is a stout , the thin body is a bit of a turn off .
its sweet , balanced and complex , pretty nice . the taste is way to strong and not good .  the mouth feel is heavy with a decent amount of carbonation .
great retention and great lacing .  mouthfeel : slighty watery good .
pours dark black with a four finger coffee head .  m-explosive carbonation . tough to gauge the feel over the bubbles . a bit too carbonated for me .

pours a beautiful bright burnt orange color with a hefty tan head that bubbles up at first and leaves lots of lacing .  first pull provided a mouthfeel that was a little more smooth than i would have expected , just short of creamy .

acidic and fruity nose . fun berry aromas . the nose was the best part of this beer .  very good light lager . hints of barley and hops , with a smooth slightly dry aftertaste . this brew had a short lived white foamy head and lower than normal carbonation . i would highly recommend this to any light beer drinker .
pours a dark brown colour with a frothy thick tan head .  it is a little bit sweet on the tongue . i could stand it to be a little bit more dry .

the colour is pitch-black ; the two finger head is pale beige , airy and uneven . massive amounts of lacing .  beer/brewery - old fezziwig ale/boston beer company ( samuel adams ) city/state- boston , massachusetts style winter warmer abv 5.9 % ibu 27 date 10 dec 2011 serving type 12 oz bottle glassware pub glass appearance mahogany in color with a thin head with a brownish white color aroma- fruity and winter spices , all spice , clove and nutmeg i think taste pumpkin pie without the pumpkin , a lot of clove , also has a bit a of a bitter ( non hop ) after taste mouthfeel very light and bland ob feeling conclusion other than the after taste this is a great christmas beer , not quit a winter warmer as they abv is a little low , but still a good flavor to think of around christmas .

it is cool watching the carbonation rise from the bottom to the top as the beer becomes less hazy as it settles .  mouthfeel the beer is slick on the tongue with strong carbonation . the body is a little lacking , medium-light .

it has a great smell of having trouble explaining other than sweet . this is a very drinkable beer but there are many more much better .  s : candied pineapple , yeast , and hops well balanced t : a typical ipa taste with accents of pineapple ; yeasts and hops , well balanced m/d a bit thin , carbonation too small and too much , abv on the high side and quite noticeable good beer
i know this is a beer and should smell like one but this smells really good to me , reminds me of candy apples when i was a tyke .  the mouthfeel was medium with a syrupy sweetness on the palate .

smells absolutely wonderful ... pungent aroma of hops all the way ... piney , citrusy hops and i 'm loving it ... i want to smell this all night ... terrific blend of piney/grapefuit hops and sweet malts.. thought this was going to be a hop bomb all the way which would have been fine but i 'm surprised at the balance on this one .  it must be said that this beer is a bit astringent on the palate and a bit thinner than i would have liked , but it is still rather drinkable .

a true imperial ipa , copious amount of pine and grapefruit . truly a beer geek 's beer ... my wife hated this beer . this is a well-made beer , and i certainly enjoy haivng one every now and then , but more a treat than a beer staple .  feel left me a bit disappointed , however , as it was thin -- too thin for this big of flavor .

bottle : poured a dark porter with a super huge medium brown foamy head with super great retention and lacing - almost to the point where i am wondering if something is wrong .  on tap this poured as a golden straw colored ale , clear and bright with less than an inch of head . there is an apparent hoppy aroma that followed with a similarly dominant slight-hoppy taste followed by the expected bitters - very tasty . i stopped with one . not to discount its drink-ability , there are just several others i wish to try .

smell : hops across the board , floral with fruits all paired with citrus . great , strong hop scent , but not aggravating in the least , floral .  the only thing i was not pleased with with this beer was the mouthfeel .

smell : best feature . raisins , a bit of anise , nougat , milk chocolate straddling dark chocolate all while riding a wave of mocha coffee . while good , it does n't live quite live up to the aroma . mouthfeel : carbonation is a bit higher than normal .  the beer is a bit too thin for my tastes but is a good sessionable beer .

a nice complex aroma ! the beer smells pretty good , but there a more pungent stouts out there .  good carbonation and medium bodied . flavor is spicy , yeasty , hints of sweetness that gets buried by the yeast . lingering yeasty aftertaste .
the aroma is very appealing . sweet hoppy fruit notes , strawberry licorice , apricot nectar . very nice .  lively carbonation is a bit excessive , but the body is quite smooth .

poured into an imperial pint , formed a 1 1/2 '' dense beige head above the slightly cloudy orangey amber brew . head falls way slowly , leaving a tall monolith of froth in the center , and thick coating all down the glass walls .  mouthfeel : medium body , a bit chalky , tingly carbonation and a dry finish .

appearance : wow . gahhh . it settles in the glass with a creamy brownish white head that persists for ages and carbonation swirling around in the most beautiful pattern , as if this beer was alive . once that settles , a deep , dark brown colour takes over that is almost opaque , save for around the sides . head is small but very creamy and stays around forever . mouthfeel : kinda bad ... this beer puts so much effort into looking beautiful that it loses all of its carbonation .  quite thin in my mouth .

it was a pretty dark brown with a sweet hops and spices scent . it was n't very bitter at all .  it states `` the deep coffee flavors are created naturally during the brewing process by dark roasted malts . '' then later it notes `` stout brewed with coffee . anyway , i 'll refer to this as a steady drinking stout because of its thinness , otherwise it 's pretty enjoyable . not particulary complex but enjoyable taste of roasted malt with coffee . abv seems pretty low as i had two with no noticable effects .

smells great though . tart aromas and there is some great fruity and malty notes there too .  thanks jpm30 . clearly sour taste that sweetens as you drink it . vineous and slightly rich , wood only detactable before the taste buds are overpowered.. great after salty fish . a slightly milder alternative to a cantillon , overpowering the mouth but not for the entire day .

poured from a 750ml bottle into my troubadour tulip glass . a dense and enormous mattress of foam tops the ale almost like a merengue . a sudsy lattice-work of lace remains in the glass even after it is empty .  the motuhfeel is moderately carbonated and slightly watery .
most impressive is that lacing absolutely coats the entire glass top to bottom . color is bronze .  m- the mouth feel is a bit overly carbonated , yet not thin .

crystal clear red-orange body , covered by a huge frothy irish linen colored head , rocky top which rose above the rim . very good lacing . a very vague , almost non-existent aroma , some bread baked much earlier in the day .  apricots . hops undetectable above the jaw-clenching , eye-squinching , head-shaking sourness . awful . ugh . otherwise , it defintely seems to be beer , ( if in no way resembling any version of a contemporary pa ) , but with a sour and bitter fruitiness that pervades , annoys , and overwhelms . the originally enticing head cashed in early and diminished to virtual non-existence before i gave up trying to like this one ; very little lacing to wash out of the glass . wo n't drink the other two in the sampler , did n't finish this one , and opened a sn celebration ale to get the taste out of my mouth .

what an aroma ! ! ! funky , fruity , sweetyeast , vinegar , spicemagic marker , sugar , oak , vanilla , cherries , sour-candies.you cant count all the smells . the taste is equally thrilling.sour and mouth puckering one minute , sweet and succulent the next . this brew is a little sweeter than expected , and very earthy . at times it seems to have a musty , woods-like quality about it . lingering , funky finish .  m : thin mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

it smelled much like a chocolate stout should .  start is lightly sweet , the top skeletal in feel , the finish lightly carbonated , hops shy in their spiciness , a bit medicinal , dry aftertaste , quite drinkable but a touch different than my normal american over the top beers , and frankly scarlet i dont give a damn , im ready for a change .

a nice wine scent . taste is like it smells , which is good .  it has little to no head on it with a soft pour . this beer has a good balance of spices that is not overpowering . the aftertaste is mellow . this is one of the darker ales that i have drank but all in all i would give it another try . especially on a snowy winter day .
a - pour pitch black with a tall brown head .  m - not much fizz , easy drinking if you like it .
a : pours to a frothey tan head with a deep and beautiful copper body . excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit gassy .

smells of cinnamon rolls , predominant oak , very bready , some dark fruits , raisins in particular , some bourbon , unbelievably complex . tastes of sweet caramel breadiness with dark fruit undertones . a nice wave of breadiness follows with something slightly funky , cheesy almost . almost no carbonation , nice sweet mouthfeel , alcohol is scary hidden . a very interesting beer , lots of complexities . that said , i was blown away by the different flavors that passed over my tongue with every sip , one after another , incredibly complex . a very sweet beer and a treat , careful of the alcohol , dangerously hidden .  there is little ( hardly any ) carbonation here , and the mouthfeel really does n't pack a punch at all .

a nice blend is dominated by spices and finishes with a pumpkin quality . overall a great blend of scents . mostly spice flavor with only a minor pumpkin quality .  mouthfeel is probably the most disappointing aspect of this otherwise excellent beer ; the carbonation promised by the head largely disappeared , leaving a slick , full bodied beer with very light carbonation . a nice , sharp bite of carbonation would have been welcome in this case , drying out the finish nicely , but that does n't happen here .

s- large amount of aromatics here ! strongly grapefruit in character , citrus of oranges and lemons behind that , notebook paper , and minute hops profile . t- the grapefruit is a tease . i prefer to smell it to be honest , but that wo n't last forever . the hops become distracting towards the middle , but it is no where near the annoyance of a hop bomb .  m : a little thin in body d : good .

s : nice big belgian yeast nose . one of the best smelling beers i have ever encountered . t : starts off sweet with some raisins . the worst part of this beer and it was still way above average . d : very drinkable .  m - fairly thin body and medium carbonation . nothing special on the mouthfeel .

pretty well on track with many of the other belgians i have had . obviously its carefully produced with natural ingredients from the taste and it looks great .  m - thought it was a little flat , but not bad .
smell : ridiculously aromatic , spicy/floral hops , as well a very fruity malt profile ( plums , berries , peaches ) .  carbonation is a little light though .
11.2 oz , 2007 bottle a : deep brown , not quite black under a nice sized tan head . excellent lace and retention .  m : not too bad , there was a little bit of body .
pours a oil dark black with a big brown head .  my only complaint with this beer is that it is a little thin .

poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1 1/2 '' tan head over the slightly cloudy dark reddish amber brew . frothy head lasts and lasts , with plenty of dwelling lace .  body is not as full as i would like , but this is one heck of a tasty beer .

color is a nutty brown color and very crisp . the head is full and pillowy and stays pillowy and the head and lacing combine and only the middle falls into a thin layer .  a soft , almost too light mouthfeel and a little weak carbonation , the only appearent downside of this brew in my opinion .

very strong hop aromas , lots of citrus fruits like orange grape fruit and spice aromas are very present . it has a very thick tan head , its bubbly and last quite a long time , its body is a dark copper/amber color and is very hazy with lots of carbonation ; lots of lacing . its very spicy and really warms up your tongue .  i wish the mouthfeel had a bit more viscosity ... .but i say that about every stout .
s : citra hops up front . smells of pineapple and other tropical fruits . i 'm in love with the aroma . t : slightly sweet malts .  m - heavy , with little carbonation .

a - a light black , if there is suc a thing with a finger worth of tan colored head . it lingers for a really long time , and leaves nice lacing on my glass .  m - at times , a bit of a metallic feel to the beer .
great retention , light lace . gorgeous .  m - surprisingly , its a bit thin and lacks carbonation .
s : a very rich banana/clove mix , just about perfect . no hops , no nothing .  a little weak in the feel . tons of carbonation couldn'tmake up for the watery texture .

poured from an inch or so above the glass leaves a big off white to light tan head that settle into bubbly sort of carbonated lacing or decent worth above a clear coppery to reddish which also seems to have a golden glint to it , very appealing .  sort of thin . inoffensive , but it really does n't do much for me .
nose reveals a unique combo coffee beans , dark fruits , brown sugar and roasting malts .  m : a bit thin d : incredibly drinkable .
the smell is very good , nice and spicy in a way that is concentrated without being overly intense .  mouthfeel was a bit thick , and it was not quite as carbonated as i would have liked .
very pleasant . t - taste is much like the smell .  slightly sour , a bit thin , highly carbonated . quite drinkable .

nitro-can encouraged frothy tan head , superb retention , some lace , almost opaque hue .  fairly thin and smooth , mild to medium bodied . breckenridge definitely delivers a vanilla porter as i would expect a vanilla flavored porter to be . i suggest toning down the roasted barley and focusing more on bittering hops .

the smell was exceptional and exciting , with a remarkable variety of spicy tones that are too complex to describe . with great anticipation , i tried the first sip , which was heavenly . and then it happened ... a nasty aftertaste that i could n't quite place but did n't like .  mouthfeel is not too bad , sharpness coming more from the carbonation than hops .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever tried . good amount of pumpkin . clean and delicious . lighter side of medium in body . not sure if this is a drastic improvement from regular pumking , but this is surely tasty .  m- light to medium , smooth but still missing a little depth here . d- this is n't what i was expecting , but the hops hit me huge here .

smell : sweet fruit like berries , pear , and some citrus orange . strong spiciness not sure what kind of spices , maybe coriander . a bit musty , but in a good way , as it warms up it starts to smell like bread dough . overall : pretty good drinkability , the appearance is really disappointing , but the ( more important ) smell and taste are great !  bittersweet finish . kind of think and syrupy on the palate .

smell is grainy , nectarine and dried apricot frutiness , caramel , leather , damp earth . very little alcohol noticeable . overall the nose on this is great ! slightly fruity , caramel sweetness , subtle amounts of cedar and tobacco .  mouthfeel : pretty heavy for a porter but very drinkable even in the heat .

small amount of lace around the edges s : roasted coffee and dark chocolate hit the nose first . very sweet smelling , as well as the presence of alcohol t : initially it was more bitter then i expected from the aroma .  mouthfeel was a little thin , that 's my only complaint .

the smell is amazing , strong coffee aroma , more so than any other coffee stout i 've had , easily the best aspect of this stout . the taste is a bit more reserved with the coffee as it 's hard to beat the strong aroma , but there is a good deal of coffee and roasted malt , hint of chocolate , and a decent bitterness in the end .  ginger is one of my favorite flavors . this beer has a wonderful ginger taste , which is exactly what i would expect from a beer with this name . further , there is a decent bitterness & a slight sweetness as well . i 'm not a huge fan of spiced beers normally , but this one is really nice . recommended .

pours a hazy amber colour with one of the most impressive head i have ever seen . a frothy rocky mountain large off white head .  mouthfeel - thin , a decent and sturdy body , carbonation is average .

s - if you like coffee , this is actually really nice . great roasted coffee and espresso aromas , along with a little unsweetened cocoa and vanilla .  body is medium , and perhaps errs to light every once in a while , which does n't help the flavours as much as it could .

the aroma is filled with dried dark fruits , apricots , honey , and wheat toast . overall a good beer , that will become a great beer over time .  mouthfeel is a bit light , to me , for the style , though it seems appropriate for the flavors that this beer brings to the palate .

appearance this oatmeal stout was almost black with a monster head that just blew up on contact with the glass . it was dark tan and left some good lacing .  m - moderate carbonation , medium bodied .
the smell is exceptional . it smells like candy the mouthfeel is really smooth , and not very thick .  m- it is a thicker , heavy beer , with sweet taste .

wonderful , rich , and inviting aroma consisting of bourbon , oak , roasted malt , vanilla sweetness , and some chocolate and coffee . a complete aroma if i ever smelled one , without being over the top or too powerful with bourbon and alcohol sting . subtle , yet rich and complex . a fine tasting beer with a mellow bourbon and vanilla accent throughout , though the base beer still shines through : a rich , chocolatey , somewhat smoky porter . smooth drinking , though full and rich , subtle yet delicious -- really a standout .  feel is thin bodied overall , but well bodied for the style .

a smooth golden color with a nice fluffy white 2 finger head .  i always look forward like most do the annual stone anniversary brews.poured a rich deep amber with a tight and sticky one finger off white head , big hops in the nose with a mix pine and herbal/leaf , there is a gummy , fruity-like sweet note as well.the mouthfeel is a bit sharp i will say it crashes down the gullett at first , it does begin to smooth out after a few sips but still seems a bit harsh.no holds barred hops hit the palate up front with big pine and big herbalness , a healthy does of sweeter alcohol gives a slight burn along with a bit of dark fruit.very good but seems like it something that should sit for awhile , still another fine one from stone .

( a ) - pours a thick cloudy red mahogany color that actually briefly cascaded during the pour . left a giant foamy tan head that left tons of intricate lacing behind as it slowly dissipated .  first sip reveals a much thinner body than i expected and average carbonation .

looks great with a two finger thick off white head , and has a nicely filtered copper colored body .  if you aerate the beer in your mouth , it really releases the co2 . it would do well as a beer to server with medium to strong cheese .

appearance : large , crackling layer of fizz off pour , which descends to a firm , tan crown . deep brown body shines crimson in light and shows excellent clarity . nice head retention and lace .  got this in an abita variety pack ... would be a great session beer if i had the quantity . in general , the abita 's have a really clean taste , little aftertaste ... is that the spring water that it talks about on the cap ? a good dark ale , malt flavor is tasty . pretty brown color . smell is very pleasing .

big fluffy cap of beige foam makes a nice stand and keeps itself steady for a good while before dismantling itself to a heavy skim and lots of thick lacing .  it 's got a little bit of a piney finish that 's quite refreshing . maybe closer to watery , but not bad . d- very drinkable esb .

smell- lots of dark fruits off the starting line . the dark fruit aroma is huge . followed by a hint of banana esters . very inviting , but also oddly fearsome . taste- not nearly as complex as aroma let on . as it warms , it gets better , but not that extremely rich , complex blend of tastes that a lot of belgian holiday beers have . drinkability- good , but not great .  i also find it a little thin .

poured a beautifully clear , clean amber golden color , with a huge 3 finger , frothy , white head . lacing was incredible on this one , totally covered from the top to the bottom of the glass when finished .  mouthfeel is a little bit thin .

the smell was amazing -- probably the highlight of the beer . it got better as the temp increased . overall , it 's a pretty solid novelty beer .  m- smooth , but a tad thin . carbonation is good , as is the thoroughly smooth finish with a tad of warmth .

presentation : it was poured from a brown 12oz bottle into a pint glass . appearance : it has an uber effervescent pale yellow body . it has great clarity and the aggressive carbonation supports a tall bright white head of smooth creamy foam .  it has a pretty high carbonation .

aroma is just perfect . a slice of pumpkin pie in a bottle is what this beer is . picture perfect . easy to drink with good mouthfeel .  a delightful golden color graced by a pale yellow head . i did n't get much lacing , but i believe that was due to a freshly-washed glass ( served at a bar ) . nice hops come through in this one . it is a little bitter and spicy , but also has some good vanilla and tones of malt . not the most fantastic example of its style , but tasty and very drinkable .
refreshing , quite complex , and just the right temperate on the citrus .  mouth feel is reasonably rich .

bottle purchased at liquor world , somerville , ma poured a slightly hazy , very light and pale straw yellow with a tight , bubbly , three-finger , bone white head . tons of cascading , spider webbing lacing formed large ridges that last well after the beer was finished .  this is a seasonal brew , do n't know if it is offered everywhere or if it was given adequate time to chill before serving so i 'll reserve final judgment for later .
s : great smelling beer . c-hops and american malts . potent nose . d : great beer , absolutely delicious , with the delicate touch of a masterful brewer .  it 's ok. mouthfeel is a little heavy .
smell is of citrusy hops , a bit of malt , and some bitterness .  feel is a bit coarse , but just a bit .

in the very bottom of my glass , i can see rust colored highlights coming through . the head is creamy looking and a very inviting light brown that makes me think of `` mocha '' for some reason .  carbonation was fairly low , with thin to medium body .

poured from a 12oz bottle into a perfect pint glass . the bubbles slowly dissipated down to a 1/4 '' layer that left behind tons and tons of lace . this one fine looking offering ... the nose is solid ... piney hops with an earthy aroma mix with a sweet , bready backbone ... seems like this one will have some balance .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin , spicy , moderately dry , and has a distinct saison flavor in the aftertaste .

4.5 s : bourbon and maple come through most prominently . oak and vanilla next . as i sort of expected , most of the wheat gets lost in the previously mentioned powers . i say the bourbon level is just right . 3.0 t : again , maple and bourbon dominate only this time it may be too forceful .  mouthfeel is poor due to the overdone carbonation .

very nice indeed . it 's enjoyable , but quite rough compared to the lovely aroma . m : light , bubbly , and a bit prickly .  drink this on tap at city beverage in durham . i like the color and mouthfeel , though a bit thin for a heavy beer aroma is slightly sweet and complex spices taste is toasted barley , spices , and slight caramel with little head . drinks easy for a heavy beer

strong dance of raspberries , prunes , blackberries , oranges , ribes . you feel it 's still young on the nose too . t : sour taste of raspberries .  mouthfeel was medium with a mild lager sweetness accompanied by loads of off flavors , including apples and grapes .

poured to the expected golden orange with thick off-white head that stuck around for the whole glass , and left excellent lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit watery and cool in texture , it goes down nicely and is a little bit better than water .

smell is quite strong , a pine and citrus scent with a noticeable sweet honey or caramel malt aroma .  the only thing that could be improved on this beer is the mouthfeel . a bit light for my tastes , but like i said it has incredible drinkability without making you get too full too quick .

absolutely wonderful ! t : unfortunately , does n't quite live up to the aroma .  mouthfeel is a bit watery not much body to it , but on a hot day like today , i could take plenty of these guys down .

a : aggressive pour yields 2.5 fingers of pillowy off-white head with very good retention .  it 's almost too sticky and thick to be pleasureable , kind of like a toned-down bourbon county stout . i 'm not a big fan of the finish , which comes off like sweet wort of a stout ( oily and a bit thin ) . m : very thick , with some relief , but then a lingering silkiness .
a - pours nice black and huge heavy sticky head .  m : finish stays around for quite a while , almost too long , really coats the mouth .

smells heavenly ! this thing is full of floral and citrus sharp hop notes . it smells of flowers , grapefruit , clementines , and there 's a little crystal malt and sweet cranberry which i think is a fusion of the malt and hop character .  thin on mouthfeel medium orangish-amber with a 1 finger offwhite head that leaves a respectable amount of lacing . taste : broad caramel maltiness with a warming alcohol changes over to a restrained english hop bitterness . notes : a nice esb , although the abv is much higher than say , honker 's ale . drinkability ranks fairly high but the alcohol content is above that of a session beer .
smell is very in your face . yeast hits you first , with hints of bananas which are definitely prevalent . really nice beer , one that i would love to have again .  pretty average mouthfeel overall .

pours to a beautiful deep dark brown body with a hint of ruby red when held to light . hosts a decent 1 and a half inch rich tan head , leaving some lace as it fades .  carbonation a little higher than i expect in the style but still manages to be exceptionally drinkable .
appearance : a wonderful amber color .  the mouthfeel is where this beer kind of fell apart for me .

the smell was excellent . i happen to love maple ( though i confess it is n't something i usually have in my beer ) , and the rich malty aroma of nutty maple notes was divine . ah , well this is a toughie for me because i 'm sure that this is the perfect beer for my girlfriends who are n't so crazy about things that resemble hops , barley , malt ... or hmmm.. beer .  i purchased this beer in a mix and match pack at the recommendation of the guy working at the liquor store = error . the look of the beer was clear and it drank smooth , but it was accompanied by the 'sour beer face . ' the taste was a combination of failure and shame ( with a hint of fruit ) all leading to the grand finale of a quick pour into the drain .

smell : the best part of this beer in my opinion . extremely complex ! i smell the chocolate and coffee but i am also overwhelmed by the super sweet heavenly smell of vanilla . taste : i was so happy that the taste was so refined , understated , elegant and smooth . drinkability : love it love it .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and somewhat thin , disappointing .

i thought is was a hefe at first , but upon tasting , i was corrected . smells of a crisp hop dryness and mandarin orange . the hops carry over in to the taste but it is backed by an odd cheerios like grain .  mouth : such a light and watery mouthfeel that it becomes distracting pondering the feel when you should be appreciating the tastes . drink : the nearly too-light mouthfeel is redeemed by the drinkability of this brew .
it pours a dark , coppery amber with a frothy , persistent , off-white head .  m - smooth going down , a bit thin , finishes dry .

mmmmm , a smell like none other . besides aroma , this is a mighty tasty beer ; absolutely my newest favorite ipa . i could drink a couple of these at once , but like many highly flavorful beers , not my kind of session brew .  the mouhtfeel was light and lacked body .

this beer looks perfect . theres not as much smell to this one as others like it .  m : starts off creamy , but i 'm pretty quickly struck by how watery this is . the carbonation is decent , but i find this surprisingly thin .
pours a nice dark brown/black with a quarter inch head , typical for founders stuff .  it is about a medium mouthfeel , with almost no carbonation .

this is a beer you have once or twice and then just get it as the `` exotic '' for your gf to help justify the stuff you bought for yourself . pours a light pinkish-amber with a very very light pink fluffy head that faded quickly . if you like strawberries , which i do very much , then the smell and taste will immediately remind you of something more likely to be served at an orange julius or other shake/juice mixer .  the palate is bland , sweet , and clean . the strongest aspect of this beer is its mouthfeel , it is medium , sturdy carbonation , very basic but appropriate .
dissipation takes it 's time but leaves fantastic lacings .  m : lighter than it should be and very creamy and smooth , decent carbonation . f : long creamy chocolate vanilla smoothness .

a - nice slightly tan head that could have better retention , but leaves excellent lacing . beer is a deep reddish brown color . looks great .  rated as a stout the mouthfeel is a bit thin , the carbonation is a bit high , and the finish is a bit less than one would expect .
smell : strong coffee , roasted malt , sweet molasses , and some sweet dark berry aroma at the end . very small amount of alcohol towards the end .  the body is medium with decent carbonation .

aroma is really nice for a bourbon-barrel stout ... vanilla , sweetish milk chocolate , with an underlying fruitiness from the barrel . very tasty stuff ...  m : a bit thin , i was kind of expecting it to be a bit more viscous .

a big , voluptuous head builds with a gentle pour , dark chestnut in color , creamy , and well-retained . beneath is an inky black body with absolutely zero amount of light passing through .  the mouth was a bit oily but not unpleasantly so .

pours a sparkling orange tinged gold , topped with a huge four finger pillowy white head , constant streams of carbonation bubbles , leaves thick puffy webs of lacing .  mouthfeel medium full for the style with carbonation that is a bit too strong for my taste .

it pours a decently frothy tan colored head .  picked up a few of these `` oil cans '' at a local liquor mart . this is the only place i 've seen them . i like the regular fosters occasionally , and have fond memories of it from various parties and times in life . after looking at the color , noticed that the can said `` caramel coloring added , '' so nothing real to go by there . i liked this , i guess , but the drinkablility was hampered by a fakey sort of bitterness that did n't hold a candle to the fuller 's and young 's of the world . kind of caught in my throat . i pick up the regular if it 's on special , but for a real bitter , this ai n't it .

pours a deep , clear yellow gold with a little amber . massive 5+ fingers of thick and foamy head that just lasts forever . ca n't say enough about how great this looks .  kind of leaves your mouth feeling very acidic .

pours a cloudy dark reddish color with bright fluffy white head , great thick malty aroma . has a nice malt beginning to the flavor but is very thin after that .  a little too thick on the tongue , but nice .

a : pours a deep dark brown that is almost black in appearance .  im stoked i can try a beer from this brewery even tho it is a collaboration but ive got nothing but good things to say about mikkeller and heard good reviews on these other two so looking forward to it , it pours a very light honey hue with decent carbonation that leaves a one finger head with sporadic lacing , the aroma is floral hops , apricot , bananna and a nice belgian yeasty aroma too , it has an average mouthfeel for the style almost syrupy and has tastes of yeasty bread , citrus and of course a pleasant floral hop finish with the alcohol well hidden , this is definately an easy beer to drink and if it didnt cost $ 18 ( aus ) i could drink it all night .

pours a clear amber/brown , huge thick off white head forms , great retention , excellent lacing .  this has the syrupy goodness of the 90-minute , but with an added syrupiness ... robust and smooth , like a desert sauce , you could pour this over a bowl of vanilla ice cream instead of a caramel sauce , with its own french vanilla creaminess ... the only thing that detracts here is an odd light metallic twinge at the finish that didnt seem to fit . otherwise , this is a beaut of a big beer with a light profile .
if you like that sort of thing , then here is your poison . the color was very pleasant , very nice eye-candy .  m- just average .
appearance : golden with a nice amount of head that stays with it until the last drink .  m - very carbonated , to the point that it almost stings on the way down .

aroma : the aroma was very nice . chocolate , burnt sugar , vanilla , roasted grains . the aroma made me really want to try a sip .  the mouthfeel has a strange little zing that seems inappropriate for the style .

the aromas promise a dandy ; juicy dark fruit ester , roasted coffee , pineapple , chocolate powder and molasses , and hints of bubble gum . a silky mouthfeel , slightly oily , and a sharp carbonation that does n't bite too hard is quite enjoyable . dark fruits , plum , sweet tobacco notes and some coffee and cocoa but not like the nose indicated .  more carbonation would go a long way .

the first smell i picked up on was tropical fruit smells , including banana and something else ( ca n't put my nose on it ) . there was also a spiciness , and sort of a leatheryness , and a slight maltyness that i find typical of most belgians and pilsners ( pilsner malt ? there was a lot going on in the aroma , which makes me want to revisit this beer and think it through more carefully .  the taste is also fresh but a with bit of watery mouthfeel .

appearance : clear orange in color with a 2 '' head that slowly falls . some mild lacing develops .  m : medium to light body with medium to low carbonation . would have preferred a bigger body by far .

a-pours a really attractive hazed-out , bright orange with a firm and lasting two inch , bone white head that brought about nice sticky ribbons of lace .  m_slightly below medium bodied and very effervescent .
smell- nice pungent scent of pine hops amidst lots of powdered sugar .  m : very smooth , but seems pretty thin in terms of the body of the beer .

beautiful looking lager in the tall glass . looks just as good as the pilsners in czech or germany .  i was not a big fan of the mouthfeel of this one . i 'm all for thick imperial stouts , but somehow this one was much more syrupy than i liked , it felt a little to sticky sweet in my mouth .

really nice . t - red wine grapes , cherries and leather stand out to me , as does the vanilla and wood from the barrels .  with all of the flying dog beers this one has the most bitter taste . yet it does remind me of my earlier beer brewing expreriences ! i always enjoyed the yeasty taste and smell of beer . and this one really has that aroma . flying dog is a great brewery that is slowly becoming a well known micro all over the country ! this only means that they will be bought out by a mega brewery or they will change their formulation all together !

pours a dark , opaque mahogany tone with a solid finger and a half of a beige-colored head . decent retention , good lacing , and a lasting cap .  mouthfeel is off a little bit , maybe undercarbonated .

pours a gorgeous , deep garnet red - almost burgundy - with a large , rocky , creamy-tan head which dissipates slowly leaving heavy lace on the glass . not much for smell - faint floral hops and maybe a touch of sweet yeast .  m - thinner body , bubbly from both the carbonation the spice .

the aroma features the citrusy amarillo hops they note on the bottle along with tons of wheat .  mouthfeel is surprisingly tingly and sharp from the tiny carbonation and i suspect a hop i ca n't discern in either the aroma or taste . mouthfeel is unfortunately a little weak and thin for style to my mind .

aroma is highlight of the beer , a rich , unique blend of dark fruit , bourbon , chocolate syrup and light roast . one of the better heavy seas treatments and they 've somehow managed to salvage a base beer i typically deplore with a passion .  a little thin .

exceptional head and lace . big , rough , chunky , substantial lace . impressive to look at and earns full points on that count .  the mouth feel is medium bodied , smooth yet singular . a light presence of the carbonation followed by some bitterness .

as others may have observed , this is more like `` pumpkin pie ale '' than `` pumpkin ale '' . picture a nut brown ale , with a pumpkin flavor , and the nose of cinnamon & nutmeg and you have this one .  this is a man 's beer . none of this flowery wine swilling critique lingo . light color , smell and mouth feel , who really cares . outstanding dry & hoppy flavor without sweetness . when bought in the 30 pack , cost is about 50 cents each . the best macro being produced !
it smells great but does n't live up to the smell .  body was very light and thin .
aroma : lovely , substantial fruit aroma without overpowering the malt of the beer .  4.5/5 m : crisp , medium body .

2010 vintage look : the beer pours a dark brown color with no head smell : chocolate , vanilla , caramel and bourbon taste : overly sweet ( dark fruits ) and alcoholic . bourbon is very much present , but the alcohol is sharp and disturbing mouthfeel : medium body with low carbonation overall : the beer could have been so nice , could , because the alcohol is so badly hidden that i can hardly distinguish this with a bottle of pure ethanol from my work .  m - medium body , not a lot of carbonation .

pours into 't hofbrouwerijke chalice a deep dark chocolate brown with a huge , i mean huge , light brown head . this is a head that just wo n't quit . it 's stunning .  a really really long aftertaste in the nose .

delicious citrus fruits with resin-y sweetness in the background -heavenly . d : a little too off-balance to be gulp-able , but certainly a yummy beer .  this beer has a flavor i really like m- pretty thin and bubbly , almost reminds me of a bmc feel o- one of my favorite tasting pale ales .

2010 bottle had a ton of suspended sediment in a burnt orange body . wow , aroma is the big winner here . pumpkin pie with crust as it warms ; some clove came thru as well , and even somewhat herbal . pretty authentic pumpkin flavor - vegetable/squash quality , and good amount of spices , incl cinnamon , nutmeg , and clove - but not overpowering . decent volume of malty sweetness / richness ... touch of campfire as it warms . outstanding drinkability - this is the most aromatic and flavorful pumpkin ale you can buy at this level of abv .  a good beer . comes in a .33ml brown bottle , part of a 6 pack sampler from brouwerij van steenberge . a sweet and dark beer , where hops has taken a back seat to the malt profile . not light , but not heavy either . give it a try .

a beautiful site setting in the glass , this blackberry to almost brown elixir of life , the head gargantuan in size , creamy in texture , the color a light chocolate brown , the residual lace a thick clinging sheet .  mouthfeel is a bit fizzy , and another beer where bottle-conditioning would have a positive impact .
the best part of this beer was the nice grassy hop aroma ( dry hopped with fuggles ) .  mouthfeel : typical red stickyness drinkability : i love this beer .

poured a brilliant gold hue with a completely hazed clarity .  ripped some cd 's with itunes and did n't pay much attention to the rest of the beverage until i listened to `` parachute woman '' by the stones and realized my head was already buzzing , hey , is this really 7.0 abv ? even though lent is over , i could subsist on this brew until easter , especially if it is cold and damp outside , but it 's not , it 's warm and sunny , and i have to plant some hostas and spread some weed-n-feed . in theory this beer will go well with my lunch of cold leftover spring rolls ( heresy !

s : tropical fruit city - tangerine , pineapple , mango with noticable pine . put me on the beach in cancun . d : a quality double ipa from avery in colorado , the price in bottles prohibits me from buying this except for every so often , but it 's a quite good beer for hop fans .  the body is sufficient to carry the 10 percent alcohol which is impressive by itself . some spicy notes and an effervescent type of feel to it .

the aroma is nothing short of amazing . it immediately presents with big raisin , molasses , strawberry , and bubblegum . i have had most of the unibroue beers , but this was really outstanding even for them .  tastes like , yeah , tart blueberries ( probably artificial blueberries ) . just sweet & weird & sweet ... really tough to finish one . much like a cheap , too-tart wine cooler .

perfectly balanced , wonderful , and refreshingly innovative . i 'm starting to think rogue bombers might be worth their exhorbitant price out here .  the mouthfeel is a little thin but the taste lingers and somehow gets better after the beer passes through my esophagus .

aroma is tremendous . dark , rich , malty sugars . drinkability is horrid , just alcohol and thickness . cloying . i hope to get to review a better bottle at some point , as i can tell the flavors are there , but this bottle was not something i enjoyed .  mouthfeel is medium with more carbonation that i expected due to no head showing up .

this one pours a dark muddy brown that shows some ruby highlights when held to light . the beer is topped by a nice frothy khaki head that lasts and leaves beautiful lacing .  texture is smooth but only slightly fizzy , leaving a slightly sweet fruity finish .
clear dark amber colour with a smooth , creamy light tan head . good head retention .  mouthfeel : thin yet flavorful .

very alluring aromatically , strong bakery smell , quite yeasty , some wheat a little bit of sweet and citrus thrown in .  i 've been waiting to try this one for some time now and it was well worththe wait ! i could smell it 's fruity aroma as soon as i opened the bottle , it has a nice dark cloudy amber color to it that is topped with a nice thick head . it goes down very smooth and just warms up your mouth , and you can really taste the spices in it .

very well balanced . medium body . very nicely done .  is this someones idea of a joke ? rotten peaches with a kick of dirty feet is not something i prefer in my beer . sour an nasty , she be . i should have know by the pour , cider apple yellow fizzy white head . cripe , im glad i only got 2 bottles of this overpriced ( $ 2.50 a pop ) sour peach soda geez , only 4.5 % . i would have kicked myself in the sack for buying this , but im no longer that agile .

aroma of a quad / stout mix with the figs , plums and spices plus a hint of grape hi-c infused vanilla . full bodied , viscous without being cloying , chewy . the alcohol is amazingly restrained , not even the inherent warmth you 'd expect at this abv level .  slightly under carbonated for my taste but not really a flaw .
black with a glorious creamy beige head with great retention and lacing .  the carbon dioxide is rich but not too aggressive .

the nose ... wow . i get bubble gum and cotton candy , with a strong citrus and floral hop character . this smells fantastic ... eeeh ! ! it 's not a bad thing , just strange . i think it 's too aggressively hopped and unbalanced in the taste department for my tastes , but still damn good .  mf : relatively light body with medium to high carbonation . would like a little more body , but the flavor more than makes up for it .

wonderful looking ale .  t/m - dense oak , leather , wet hay and barnyard notes , freshly cut grass maybe some dark fruits like apricot and/or figs ; short-lived citrus hops up front and a cloyingly long , drying finish . almost reminds me of dry vermouth . the mossy barnyard notes developed nicely . d - the drying effect would probably limit me to just one of these , a nicely developed saison for spring and summer .

pours a deep brown , transparent with an off white head . huge head that sticks to the glass and remains about and inch thick . tight head , quite beautiful .  mouthfeel was the only thing i was n't too keen on- felt a little spritzer-ish .
very heady pour . nice lacing .  mouthfeel is a little light for a beer this big , but that would likely improve with age . carbonation is a tad too prickly for my personal tastes .

the color of this beer i find just amazing . it 's so dark as it sits in a guinness glass , with it 's beautiful smooth head . are there bubbles finer than these ? in contrast to how heavy it looks , it 's goes down incredibly smooth and fast .  more watery flavored than i expected from this ... very light mouthfeel .

there 's even some odd sediment that almost looks like it belongs in hot & sour soup . the aroma is welcoming though - deep , filling , and robust with mocha goodness . the combination of malted barley and coffee hide the barely noticeable smell of alcohol . the taste is also very robust - nearly syrupy without carbonation , but still good .  mouthfeel is light and carbonation fades to almost flat .

this smells real delicious . t - balanced malt hop mix up front with a hint of the fruity taste the smell indicated .  mouthfeel : light/ medium body with excessive carbonation that somewhat hinders the flavor .
incredible looking esb . pours with the cascading effect and settles to a bright amber color .  mouthfeel features more carbonation than i 'd like for a big beer like a barleywine .

this beer pours a very dark brown , almost black , with some slight red tones when the light hits it . it is honestly a beautiful beer to look at , if nothing else !  the mouthfeel is decent , but could be a bit more robust to support the flavors .

750ml bottle poured into a tulip glass . appearance-brilliant ruby color with good clarity-absolutely gorgeous . moderate pale-pinkish head with decent retention .  a wonderful beer . one i have had before , and thought it would be great for the new year . it 's dark brown hue and brownish colored head was delightful . the taste of cocoa and hops pleased my nose . the roasted flavors were soothing , but left a little bit of an after taste .
it pours a rust-colored brown with a roasted 2-3 finger head . this looks as good as any of the big ipas made by stone , smuttynose and company .  medium bodied , highly carbonated .

pours black with red tints , and a small mocha head . smells of roasted malt with sweet notes and a hint of alcohol .  rolling carbonation augments the already full feel making seem more boisterous than perhaps it is . carbonation is too much for me .

caramel and prune or fig in the aroma . lots of malty sweetness in the flavor , along with sticky fruit , but there is a graininess that is a bit astringent in there as well , though very minute . this is a pretty good beer , excepting the tiny bit of astringency .  m - light bodied , not overly carbonated , clean finish , mild fruity aftertaste fades quickly .

it smells awesome , but i 'm concerned that it 's going to taste a bit too sweet . upfront is strong bourbon , which is quite pleasant .  mouthfeel is a little too tingly for me with the carbonation .

a : pours an extremely dark , clear , mahogany reddish-brown with a couple finger of thick light tan head that faded into a thick film . a great network of lacing was left down the glass .  sticky mouthfeel .

smell is pure oranges and very faint hops but the smell is amazing . taste did n't lead up to the smell kind of a big build up and then aahh .  the feel is the only drawback here . it was rather light in body , and thin feeling . carbonation was adequate , but it just lacked that `` near medium '' that i would expect from a dipa .
nose is heaven , sweet green apples , almost like a sour cider .  it was barely palatable : very little carbonation - full of sour , gone-bad notes .
pours a glowing hazy golden with a thick creamy head that retains well and laces the glass .  m - this is like any cheaply made micro lager in japan .
poured an almost perfect ruby/amber , crystal clear with a big sticky tan head .  m- low carbonation and very low mouthfeel .

it is overpoweringly fruity and has an amazing aroma . it pours a cloudy light rose pink with a huge head.you are overwhelmed by the raspberry nose .  t : bitter chocolates and cold black coffee .mmmmm m : a bit thin in the mouthfeel , slight warming in the finish which i found dry .

aroma is rich and complex : sweet , sticky maltiness rich in caramel , accompanied by a ripe fruitiness and a good deal of citrusy hops . i do n't detect any oakiness .  12 oz bottle poured into weizen glass , only glass i could get at my buddy 's house a : great pale golden color , light head with decent retention , great clarity s : great floral aromas t : not a pale ale that is actually an ipa , not overly bitter and slight maltiness m : good carbonation , could be a little thinner o : great pale ale , not just a copy of other american pale ales .

aroma is complex and deep- cherries , plums , cloves , cinnamon , orange peel and nutmeg all seem to float on a platform of caramel and molasses . but what starts out as intriguing eventually becomes overbearing by the end of a 750ml. , and those phenols become too prominent .  m & d - the brew is a tiny bit watery , the doughy character is a tiny bit too small , and so the mouthfeel is n't as full as i 'd expect .
amazing , both the most unique and best smell i have in a beer in a good long time . taste- a strong and front malt body .  the mouthfeel was a bit unimpressive too light in my opinion .

lovely looking beer , and very similar in appearance to the classic guinness look , with a large creamy tan head on top of a dark body .  despite the nearly opaque black color , the flavor of this one is surprisingly light . there are sweet malt notes , a delicious fruitiness and some fairly rich yeasty , estery notes . i keep over-looking this brewery , but every time i try one of their beers im usually pretty impressed . this particular beer is tasty , refined and very drinkable . recommended .

the initial nose is wonderful . first comes the hops . i actually can smell parts of all 3 bastards in here , awesome . the taste is slightly disappointing relative to the nose .  m- the mouthfeel is a little lighter than expected , almost watered down .
appearance : pours a bit 3+ finger thick tight off-white head with great retention . looks great all the way .  mouthfeel- medium body with very little carbonation .
s : chocolate covered cherries , vanilla , mocha , amazing ! t : huge vanilla ( a little much for me ) , oak , bakers chocolate , mocha .  mouthfeel : a bit thin and watery .

raw in your face noble hop aroma . just amazing . poured a tiny bright white head that disappeared when i looked away . the hop flavor does n't approach the strength of the aroma , but that could be a good thing .  chocolaty to dark brown in appearance with a light head . great smell of toffee , roasted barley . taste conjures up images of coffee shops , candy stores , with the roasted barley presence as well as that bitter coffee taste , balanced by sweet toffee notes and a hint of hops . great tasting beer . my first milk stout , and it did n't disappoint .

very little head to speak of , thin collar of dense white bubbles s : deep notes of dark chocolate , carob , molasses , and a hint of coffee . the flavors are very mellow but well integrated . t : the taste does n't translate into being as good as the smell suggested , the smooth chocolate is there , but turns into a slightly sharp flavor by mid palate and has a slightly metallic finish .  m - it drys out in the mouth a little too quickly for me .
serving type : 16oz bottle appearance : pours a darker cloudy orange colour w/ a 1 finger head . plenty of lacing the whole time while drinking .  could use more carbonation .

pours into a pint glass a translucent straw yellow with a billowing white head and and amazing lacing that last throughout the drink .  mouthfeel : a little thin , medium body , low carbonation , medium flavor . underwhelming mouth .

s : a rich citrus , piney hop aroma is released when you open the bottle and once in the glass that 's all you can smell . sweet grapefruit - fantastic smell . t : unfortunately the smell seems more powerful than the taste which seems a bit on the light side .  there was a very light mouthfeel , but an extremely dry , crisp finish .
very heavy hefe pour . thick , deep yellow gold that glubglubs out of the bottle and leaves a giant head .  mouthfeel is grainy and oily , body is medium to thin , carbonation is sharp .
the smell is loud with touches of sweetness . dead guy has a unique taste , that is over powering at first .  feel is also a bit thin and fizzy .

smell : delicious and complex . truly a melange of different aromas . coffee bean , caramel , toffee , chocolate . wonderfully palatable . drinkability : very drinkable . excellent complexity of flavors .  light body with a very active carbonation .

it packs in beautiful cascading , lively carbonation , a firm & rich off-white head and amazing levels of retention . that and a bold black color make for one masterful visage .  m : fairly thick , carbonation seems a tad high .

s : grapefruit and evergreen needles . you can smell the aroma of bold hops from yards away . t : simcoe , welcome aboard .  i had this beer at the great waters facility as we stop in often . i try to take notes on the beers i try but sometimes forget . the attack was very smooth and there was a sweet and smooth flavor with faint hops character at the finish . i do n't think i have had any cask beers at great waters that i did n't like .

strong aroma consisting of citrus bananas , cloves , vanilla and an overall strong alcohol presence . there 's a lot there . the mouthfeel is pretty full although something seems a bit off with a tangy , somewhat sour , very yeasty , citrus ( oranges and bananas ) flavor . i 've had other tripels recently that are better , karmeliet and chimay cinq cents come to mind , but this is a better beer than i original though .  m : average , carb . levels are good .

poured a one finger white head that had good retention and lacing . the beer is a nice amber-orange color and is very clear .  i 'm not getting much in the way of bitterness anywhere here , which combines with a medium thin body to provide very little in the way of a finish .

a - deep dark , opaque black color with a thick head , excellent retention s - gentle coffee-like roasted grain , malty , no hops noticed t - roasted grain characterized by coffee and tobacco flavors ; hop balance but no detectable flavors ; fairly clean for an ale , but faint hints of yeast esters noticed ( but appropriate ) m - medium-to-light body with moderate carbonation d - this is quite an enjoyable milk stout .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied to me . could be a little thicker on the tongue .

however the taste is a shadow of the wonderful aroma , which is a disapointment only because it smelled so nice and i was excited for something special . nice , but i wanted more . overall it is a nice beer from a solid brewer .  thin bodied , and just sufficient carbonation , but i suspect the growler is at fault much more than the beer .

pours dark brown with a hint of red and a moderate ring of pink foam .  all of the good notes that a belgian has , with some american notes such as a much higher rate carbonation , more citric fruitiness . the high carbonation almost makes me question whether or not it 's natural , but i doubt stone would rape this brew with added co2 like the macros do .
simply beautiful cascading action that lasts for over a minute ! superb tan head retention that is not going away at all !  very basic but very good m= average carbonation and average weight .
lots of bubbles along wall of glass . leaves a huge & healthy white cap with bigger lacing along the outside of the body .  the mouthfeel is a little lacking in carbonation too .
a - dark maroon with lots of capuccino colored head .  mouthfeel is medium bodied . lots of carbonation , almost too much .

pretty simple , but really pleasant . 3.5 t : similar to the nose only very much subdued .  had to give it the maximum points for appearance , because even out of an imported bottle , it looks just right . comes in with an alcohol bite that 's almost like an imperial . pertty nice taste , though , and if you had some , i would n't refuse .

this beer was poured a very dark rich chocolate brown with a thin tan head . with this beer being pushed nitrogen , it had a ton of lacing and the head lasted the entire beer .  it is medium-bodied with soft carbonation and seems perhaps more watery than i 'd expect . it leaves the mouth feeling a bit astringent .

pours a cloudy yellow/gold color , with a huge thick fluffy white head . a good deal of carbonation helped this head hold for what seemed like an eternity .  m : a little bit thinner than expected , medium-light bodied with low carbonation , lightly creamy .

pop goes the cork and a soft pour fills the glass with a clear golden color and a dense white head filling the upper half of the tulip .  m - a little water , but it goes down smoothly d - this is a really good beer .
smell - aroma was bery pleasing with a definite berry aroma .  mouthfeel if very alive and crisp at first sip . maybe a bit overpowering on the carbonation .
laced well . smelled freaking fantastic . toasty , dark fruits .  m - a little watery for the style , but not objectionable .

for me , this was one of the most appealing scents i 'd smelled in a long time .  t - again , bicuit and nut . nice and malty , virtually no hop bite , but tasty none the less . d - i have had this a ton in the past , but i only just got around to getting another one for the purposes of reviewing .

awesome grapefruit smell with bitter peel , and some grassy notes . however , this seemed like a head-fake , because the taste revealed less citrus and more apple/maltiness , and a very thin abrupt finish , that was n't as bitter as the nose suggested either . in fact , a very thin-bodied beer overall , in spite of the decent carbonation .  mouthfeel is smooth , crisp and almost watery , with medium carbonation and a medium body .

( s ) - a very fruity aroma with fresh orange peel and lemon . a very vibrant fruit driven profile with hints of a hay/wheat dryness .  mouthfeel too prickly and astringent but medium body is appropriate for style .

growler the bruery placentia , ca a clear light golden with a big and thick foaming white head . the head sticks around for quite a while and eventually leaves thick and sticky lacing all down the glass .  best as it warmed , when the malt flavors of chocolale and toffee become a bit more complex and the mouthfeel seems fuller .

the aroma is strong thick sweet and syrupy . including pine , alcohol , vanilla and oak . overall it 's very nice , i 'd like to see how it would do with another year or two to tame the hops down .  it 's viciously acidic , but tasty . i like acidic ... i 'll drink straight malt vinegar . this is fizzy alcoholic pomegranate juice with nothing to resemble beer to my palate . i would n't hold `` not tasting like beer '' against a legitimate ale beverage , which i 'm sure this is , except that i like beer , and i do n't like this .

smell is heavenly , with the almost overpowering aroma of peaches . there is a slight coating of sweet , sticky phlegm in the back of my throat , but it is sort of pleasing . over all this was a great journey and the buzz is just what i needed .  the beer poured hard but the carbonation ended up being low and the mouthfeel medium .

this pale ale pours a warm yellow with great carbonation and head retention -- a yield which maintains an inch with great lacing .  i almost gag every time i take a sip of this . tastes like day-old miller high life with some bread , chocolate , and coffee mixed in . it looks like cola , and at first it smells like oh , say , a bottle of old milwaukee . if only it tasted even half as good as old milwaukee . please , for your own sake , stay away .
s : chocolaty , coffee , roasted malt , maybe some caramel tones . the appearance and smell had me so excited for the taste , only to be let down by a watery drink .  medium carbonation .

a trace of lacing & head retention s : dates , raisins , steel & port soaked raisins t : rich dark fruits , herbal & leafy hop bitterness up front . started strong , but the dryness & oakyness detracted as this warmed mf : slightlty overgassed , medium bodied & with fair balance drinks easy , but this one could use at least 12-18 more months of aging , not a bad take on the style  m - moderate carbonation-almost too much , dry finish , medium bodied due to the carbonation .

cloudy gold with a large foamy head . head had very good retention , and eventually became a fine lace which left rings all the way down the glass . the appearance aside , this is not a very good beer .  mouf & gt ; sudsy .

appearance : this brew pours with a wonderfully thick head . lacings are plentiful and surface spiderwebbing is consistant and lasting . color is indeed a reddish amber . excellent first impression .  t : wood chips , obviously , tastes like a sauna smells , charcoal , molasses , savory like breakfast sausage , soy sauce , real sharp sweetness that 's broken down by hops lurking in the background and that 's absent at the finish m : medium body , very low carbonation , i 'm surprised this was n't the cask ( it was n't but they did have it ) , dry bitter charcoal finish . the mouthfeel was a big drawback for me , it was very flat , considering this was the draft veraion .

pours a dark brown black with a medium cream light brown head that slowly goes to a thin film that laces the glass .  very ashy , very charred , and it really lacks some body and sweetness to back up the astringency . feel is very light , a shame , because a thick , chewy , silky body is a necessity in the style .

a - a nice looking beer with a dark brown color reminiscent of a good black coffee or coke . head was a good two fingered tan froth , that retained quite well .  great big head , perfectly tempting aroma , somewhat thin mouthfeel .

cloudy peach sweet tea coloring ( for those of you down south ) , golden-orange-ish . s : very fruity , golden raisins , prune , and honey . t : sweet like the smell .  mouthfeel/overall : the body is very light , and it has pretty high carbonation .
smells good . biscuits , the ginger is noticable in the aroma , tea leafs and toffee .  it was pretty smooth for stout and for for the alcohol content . i tried it with a few other beers .

it smells awesome and makes my mouth water just anticipating the first taste !  m - fairly zesty and zingy carbonation that left me feeling a touch bloated after a third of a glass . medium-light body that also has a bit of grain character .

pours a copper color with some haze . it has the consistency of whipped cream and has some of the best retention ive ever seen .  m- a little thin , but not too bad . nicely carbonated , with a slight bitter hoppiness at the tail end .

the aroma is very kinetic - spice , yeast , banana and hops abound . medium-bodied , with a flavor reminiscent of both a belgian and a strong hefe . citrus , spice , hops and bananas all vie for attention . i liked this one substancially more than the 03.03.03 , but i think it would improve a bit with more age .  nice aroma of hops but i would hope for a bit more being a hops lover . the celebration ale , from the same company , seems to hit the spot more than this beer but still worthy of a place in the fridge and still better than many micro beer ipa ii . sierra nevada seems to me to be the only mass beer company that brews excellent beer for `` mass beer '' prices .

smell : wow , mazing ! roasty , dark chocolate , very coffee forward , sweetness . taste : very good , nice and roasty . overall : very good beer , i would certainly want to have this again .  mouthfeel - very enjoyable borderline complex character .

the nose is very complex , a mix of fruity , spicy , earthy and oaky tones . black licorice or anise also comes to mind . there is also a drying , acrid presence . drinkability of this one is lowered by the fact that i do n't really enjoy this old ale . i was really excited when i opened the bottle and i feel let down .  500ml bottle served in a shaker glass.enjoyed on oct11.melon yellow in color.haze appearance.white close & dense crown.good retention leaving lasting lacing collars.citrics & hints of melon to the nose , some banana hues.sour upfront then a pleasant sweet malty flavor comes , subtle spicy hues too.slightly astringent notes.medium body.medium carbonation.rough but gentle finish.refreshing.well balanced flavors .
appearance - nice copper color , cream colored head holds at a solid cap and laces quite well .  the mouthfeel is sort of watery , but it 's alright . this drinks very well .

pours a dark brown as you 'd expect in a chocolate , and the aroma is pure chocolate . unbelieveable aroma . really hoped that the taste would match , but no .  mouthfeel : a bit thin in body but makes up with an even overall texture not much carbonation very wine like with each sip .

devastatingly attractive . dried herb in color . brilliant nose . obviously aged and incredibly smooth on the palate but the cellaring destroyed the hop presense .  the mouthfeel seems a bit week and flat , but it 's not bad .
the nose was sweet , dominated by roasted malts , chocolate , treacle and burnt toffee , very pleasant indeed .  mouthfeel : this is the one downside of this beer ; it 's just a bit thin .

delicious smelling ! t- tart , slightly sweet with more ale grains in the taste . decent , but i was expecting more fruits in my mouth .  m & d = carbonation stings a little more than i would like , has good medium body but mouthcoating , while medium , is a little less than i would have preferred .

smell was delicious . nutmeg , cinnamon , holiday cheer ... everything a holiday ale should smell like . overall this beer was good . i would definitely try the 2012 redition .  taste was pretty balanced with a bit of malt sweetness . overall i liked this one . this is the first beer i have tried from boulder . based on this one , i 'll have to try some of the others that we can get in ct . the website says that a secret spice is added , but i can not really taste any spice . maybe i 'll figure it out by the time i finish the six . good brew .

as for the head , it stood about an inch in height when it first came out . the consistency is foamy and the color khaki . amazing retention and cobweb-like rings of lacing .  i was disappointed by this beer . it 's also obvious a lot of quality ingredients went into this brew . it was as if they intended to toast something , left it heating too long and then used it in the beer anyway . so my opinion may not apply to all bottles of this beer ever made . the finish was so bitter/burnt ( and someone else said aspirin-like , and i agree ) that drinking a whole one was difficult , and i found i did not want another when i was done . i do like brown ales , and i 've never tasted one that tasted like this . if the brewer is reading , this will be an abomination to him . the result is quite nice , with the bitterness now toned down to just one note in the chord and the revelation of some of that band-aid-like taste i associate with belgians . i 'm on the second mixed brew now , and i must say i 'm quite enjoying it this way .

the smell is utterly fantastic , easily one of the best smelling beers i 've ever come across .  flavour is better than expected- a little woody and slightly spicy , with a thick strong maltiness . i 'd like the hearty body on this one , were it not for the turbocharged carbonation .

the appearance is still wonderful , rich , creamy and delightful , although you get less of the wonderful spectacle of the bubbles gently settling on the surface .  the carbonation is surprisingly strong for the style .

this is mouthwatering and powerful . t : follows the nose . though it is not as powerful as the nose imo . m/d : a full body that is low on the carbonation end .  like the aroma , there was a maple hint somewhere in there but it was incredibly hard to get the taste and keep it , it was very slippery . the cloying sweetness kept me from even finishing the beer and my girlfriend refused the rare chance to finish one of my drinks after trying it herself .

oysters ... hmmm ... pours a blackish black with a black interior and black edging . nice looking bubbling dark brown foam . really attractive .  m : the feel is slightly creamy but on the lighter side of medium bodied . could be a bit thicker here ... d : if you like coffee beers i could see someone drinking good amount of these .

beautiful , clear dark copper color . excellent clarity here . a moderate cap of light whipped cream , tiny bubbles mostly , sits at the top . this is as pretty as an ipa can be .  thin to medium bodied with moderate carbonation .
