s - amazingly sweet toffee , ripe berry , tangerine , faint grassiness . t - toasted malt with notes of juniper and huge pine resin hop character . very one dimensional here . m - medium in body with more carbonation than i prefer usually .  dare i say it seems a bit on the thin side . the meatiness in the flavor is not backed up by the body . not bad , but just a little disappointing ... this is a fine stout .

a nice two fingered head forms quickly and had great retention .  a : pours a dark brown with a two finger head ; burnt orange around the edges of the glass when held to light ; lacing is excellent s : smells of caramel and coffee ; very earthy aroma t : tastes like a bitter coffee initially , but the sweetness of caramel and honey slowly creeps in m : i think its a bit too watery and the carbonation does not seem right d : two in a sitting is nice ; i 'm generally not a porter fan , but i enjoyed this beer
pours black and thick . substantial tan head that forms of a billion tiny bubbles then morphs into a very slow fading creamy foam .  m : light but slightly creamy body .

my mouth is watering s - super floral , i do n't even need to put my nose that close to get wonderful citrus and pine notes t - a bit sweet to me . m - sweetness sticks a the tongue to much , leaves a sugary oily aftertaste , decent carbonation o - a good ipa , but not the best  the palate is somewhat thin for the style but it 's still smooth .

the head is very impressive in that it 's a creamy tan , intricate lacing and last throughout the whole beer with a nice semi-thick layer of foam on top of the beer . it really is a nice looking beer .  the mouthfeel is just a little light and watery .

smells creamy/milky with rich , almost sweet coffee , chocolate , kaluha , cocoa , and a touch of green hops . absolutely divine . the flavor is roasty with burnt/charred malts , coffee , chocolate , and a medium bitterness .  m : okay , mostly wet and satisfyingly quaffable , but with a noticeable alcohol presence in the finish .
the nose is impressive . easily the most enjoyable part of drinking this beer .  m : the body is medium and so is the carbonation .

the beer poured out the classic golden yellow color . the bubbles clung to the side of the glass and continued to rise to the surface like a glass of champagne .  it 's sort of smokey but in an artificial way . rubber and alcohol . the rubber turned into a slightly smokey malt flavor but still lingered in there . alcohol dominated any sort of flavors coming through . i just did n't enjoy this beer at all . if i ever cross paths again with this beer i 'll re-review it .

this smells amazing . brings back memories of the cherry topping my mother used to make to go along with her cheese blintzes .  the rye is evident , as is a tangy almost sour note along with the bread . a little over-carbonated ... i found it slightly distracting and that it may have affected my enjoyment of the beer 's complexity . light-bodied and very refreshing . while i have little to no experience with beers of this style , i enjoyed this one and i believe that its a great refresher during the summer months .

hard pour gets a beautiful head to rise up , just a little more than two fingers worth of off-white frothiness . smells phenomenal . a bouquet of citrus hops , with a little bit of floral and maybe piney for good measure . so nicely balanced , just a little bit of bitter and the rest is flavor . the alcohol would probably catch me a buzz after just a couple , but it certainly weighs in a little lower than some comparable ipas , which is nice .  m - average mouthfeel . carbonation on par , but a very thin feeling brew .
smell- by far the sweetest smelling beer i 've ever had .  the beer feels just a bit thin on the tongue .

sour flemish aroma , sour apple , somewhat like a wild ale . numbing sour mouthfeel , with significant carbonation , refreshing . not for a newbie .  drinkability - taste is pretty good , stays consistent throughout , isnt too thin , and has a reasonable abv so overall this would be a good beer to have a few of if you options are limited .
stunning appearance . pours a clear reddish brown with a big and tight tan head .  the mouthfeel is much like an american macro lager , but a bit wimpy .

that 's a good thing in my book . overall a fantastic aipa .  drank in a chalice from a bottle in brussels at delirium cafe.. this is very good lambic . it smells great very sweet with cherries . the beer has a beautiful red/brown color with a white head , not a lot lacing . it tastes sweet with cherries dominating but has a nice sour kick too .

s blackberries . light , hammy smoke . the fruit character is subtle and dry . gentle coffee note .  the beer seems to thin a bit in the mouthfeel . very clean beer for a triple , slightly thin in the mouthfeel , but that helps give this beer a nice clean dry finish .

this is a stunning looking ale : dark-brown with a ruby glaze , bubbles dancing toward the top like a light snowfall in reverse , crowned with a creamy mocha head .  a very special thanks to zeke at the speakeasy for sharing a bottle of this 1995 treat . it still had carbonation in it which was crazy . the beer was very dry at this point . the spiciness of this beer has been cut down from the aging .

appearance ; nice white head . dissipates slowly to a thick film , leaving quality lacing .  this cask had not dropped bright or was a few days past where it should have been , my guess is that they put it out too early or the servers that placed the keg out rolled it out from the back and mixed all of the yeast back into the brew . full of yeast yeast in the aroma and flavour , just down right crappy cask what a disappointment .

smells great . big , overripe tropical fruit and citrus with a little bit of grass underneath . i actually coughed and spilled some while pouring and thought , `` man , that smells awesome ! '' while cleaning it up . still good , just a letdown after the nose .  drinkability : mouthfeel is a little thin , but this is a very solidly crafted stout , up there with the tops in style .

s - the spicy , phenolic aroma hit me as soon as i opened the bottle , and once the beer has a chance to open up in the glass it expands into notes of chocolate , dark cherries , raisins , almonds , pepper , cinnamon , and lots of clove . d - very complex beer that manages to avoid being overbearing despite the high alcohol and big flavors . the smell is absolutely spectacular , reminds me of samichlaus , but more interesting . the flavor is quite interesting as well , and i really like the way it finishes , but there is something about the initial sweetness or phenolic character that i find a little cloying .  body is light and a bit watery , not too syruppy at all .

pours copper hue , with a nice , long lasting , white head and lively carbonation .  very simply -- -if this were n't a trader joe 's beer , it would have higher marks -- i 'd bet anything . at least here on the west coast , there are no examples of this style , at any price point , that compare to this beer . heater-allen , the only contender in oregon , way more expensive and neither as good , nor as consistent as this beer . while not in class with the best german hefeweizens , it 's damn close and an absolute steal for the price .
aroma is a staggering , fresh , really rich chocolate .  m. actually a bit thin , would have liked a bit more substantial body , but it went down well enough .
overall really nice aroma . first sip is a mix of caramel and toasted malts with a touch of fruitiness .  the mouthfeel was its weakest point , i thought .

v=ql-n78agg_y appearance : clear golden , 1-finger head , excellent lacing aroma : hop oil , banana , lemon citrus , hibiscus , buttery biscuit , dry floral notes , hint of pine flavor : medium body , earthiness , dirt , grapefruit , pine , cup-cake icing sweetness , banana , bready malts , lemon rind , medium carbonation , mild bitterness pairings : fried shrimp brew + pairing : buttery dough on the shrimp balances this brew well  the beer feels light but not watery . there is a little prickle on the tongue at the swallow .
s : earthy tart wheat , lots of honey , sweet toffee , and a nice floral hop/heat combination . bit-o-honey candy comes to mind .  mouthfeel is soft and a little heavy .

beautiful golden bronze colour . head retention is superb , an easy 4 fingers . these certainly do have a tendency to 'explode ' upon uncapping , with foam exiting the bottle for several minutes afterwards .  m - nothing special just went down really easy ... .it was n't bad tasting ... .i was surprised how quickly i finished it because it went down fast .

poured a deep brown hue with a two finger frothy off white head . there was very good retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel has a little bit more carbonation than i would like a brew of this calibre to have , thus the 3.0 .

the head falls to an island of loose bubbles , a ring , and dusting that leaves spots of lacing.. mind blowing aroma . orange , mango , papaya , grapefruit , pineapple ... candied hops ! sweet and floral , it tickles my nose and begs to be tasted . i taste tropical fruits , with lots of green and white pepper , it is earthy and reminds me of kind-buds .  high carbonation detracts slightly .
it poured with a big , long lasting , and super stiff foamy cap .  lowish carbonation and a slightly thin mouthfeel .

a- pretty close to opaque brown/black . head is thick and tan , stays frim at one finger . a couple wisps of lacing . o- it 's a tasty beer but it 's a bit too sweet , yet light , for me to think of it as much above average in the styke .  rich , almost like chicken soup broth , and very low carbonation . in the world of bocks , this could be a new favorite of mine .
some lacing s : pretty nice , smells wildly fruity and pretty strong . the great smell is a little too misleading .  mouthfeel lightly carbonated and a tad bigger than light-bodied .
appearance : dark mahogany-brown color , with a solid , long-lasting inch of head . good lacing .  taste : a bit thin for a porter , almost to the point of being slightly watery .

subsequent sips bring forth strong chocolate notes mixed with a nice bitterness.the aroma a each sip is truly fantastic . finished nice and creamy with a strong bitter note present .  feel seems to be about medium in body , but slightly watery , with a lingering semi-bitter dark unsweetened chocolate/coffee bean aftertaste .

in the flavor : oodles of grapefruit and lime , fresh grass , a bit of dank weed , some sweet honey and black pepper . good hop profile ; great for a pale ale . i would n't say this winter offering from ska has flavors that really gel with the season , but it is a nice little pale .  m- actually the mouthfeel is n't that bad but it was really hard to focus on that while i was drinking joan rivers perfume .
the smell really impressed me with the strong clove scent like a cooling pie .  mouth- thin ? it 's a little thin , it lacks depth , and too much raisin for my taste .

s : smell is the best part of this beer in my opinion . strong scent of hops . reminds me of some other good intoxicating herbs . i really love this hoppy goodness !  a bit watery at the start , but , it gradually gains weight as it rolls to the back of the palate .

poured into a tall glass , pours a cloudy almost two tone fire red color . genuinely impressive , that i have never seen something like this before .  the mouthfeel is light , but hey , its a light beer ! for drinkability , again , one of the beers that could probably never offend me .

big fluffy head that towers more than a half inch out of the pint.. pretty white color that leaves lace all the way down the glass ... hop hazed deep golden liquid .  it seems to light and over carbonated for a stout .

lovely aroma of figs , coffee , licorice , lavender , pinesap , chocolate & mint . the dark roasted malts smell so very fresh , almost as if they were right there damp in the palm of your hands .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied .
this beers saving grace is a fantastic odor .  m- a bit over carbonated for me , but other than the crisp nature of most kiwi beers , nice malty and dry .

very nice but honestly could have less of the nutty/bitter flavor and more of the sweet adn sour flavors m/d - very drinkable , a bit more carbonated than i like .  surprisingly light mouthfeel makes it a fairly easy drinker for a 9 % er

pours a honey golden hue , translucent and bright , with generous white head . lots of lacing and creamy goodness on the head . only negative is that it is incredibly watery & light .  m : very carbonated .
very enjoyable . taste is a little harsh , the sweetness takes a vegetable turn .  refreshing when ice cold , pleasantly balanced when it warms a bit .

the aroma is just amazing . it is easily the best smelling ipa i 've had in my young beer tasting career .  but there are hints of dark fruits that seem to disintegrate on your tongue , slight astringent alcohol tate/smelll this is defiantly a very drinkable brew .

t - while the aroma is astounding , the taste does not do the aroma justice . it 's one of my top 5 ipa 's , i 'd say , but compared to the outstanding aroma , the taste is considerably less in amplitude .  m : the body is not as thick as i was expecting . it on the thin side as far as stouts go , but drinks very smoothly . i would have liked a thicker body , but that 's just being picky .

the smell is great . smell of very fresh hops in something that promises to be potent . very weak . can taste the massive carbonation as if it was campaign , not beer . very fresh .  mouthfeel is a little thin and alcoholic with low carbonation . overall this beer has a nice balance of flavours but i feel the barrel presence is a little bit too subtle and the mouthfeel a bit too thin to prevent a higher score .

poured into my delirium tremens tulip . a : pours a slightly cloudy amber/copper color with 3 huge fingers of head that fade very slowly leaving tons of sticky lacing behind .  a- blackness with a espresso colored head s- coffee beans ground soaked in licorice coffee and dark chocolate really bold t- straight up coffee and espresso with bitter chocolate and a slight tang finish m- medium carbonation and a bit watery for the style d- i drink 3 cup of coffee a day who am i to judge ?
great head retention & lacing s : dark fruit , woody hop nosr==e t : cherry & herbal hops , some raisin & fig notes as well up front , plus a touch of candi sugar .  mouthfeel is a bit light .

lots of aromas , raisins , plums , maple sugar candy .  it may not be for everyone but i think this is a beautiful product . flavor is far less sweet than the smell and look might hint , in fact this is gobs of sour black cherry . it 's an instant classic and one of only a handful of lambics i 've liked so far .

very nice aroma here -- spot on for the style -- as notes of fresh orange peel combine with soft coriander spice and a hint of lemon .  long , super bitter piney bitterness , aftertaste almost of pine-sol but i love the hop attack . problem is that it 's too sweet and slightly syrupy , especially evident in the middle . a little harsh and unbalanced overall , big beer and it shows .
the aromas is astonishing , this is the most coffee like of any coffee beers that i 've tasted . excellent .  m : still a bit watered down , but again , it 's better .

the medium amber-copper beer shows bright clarity while building a dense froath of lightly tanned foam while leaving broken patterns of lace behind . a very classy look .  quite watery for the big flavor this one tastes and smells different from the main stream craft ipas , which is a pretty new category i 'll give it that .
smells great . taste : pretty disappointing after the aroma .  m : the only thing that let me down was the thin and carbonated mouthfeel .

aroma is mostly complex stages of hops , it 's easy to believe there are 10 varieties , there 's the big american c hops character combined with the refined english ones . very relaxing to sniff on and ultra-complex , like a touch of vanilla on fresh citrus ( grapefruit ) . in mouth this dances on the tongue , nice effervescence , creamy , full-bodied , complex malt sweetness and an obvious balancing yeastiness . this is a delicious big generous beer . tasting this with my buddy martint , we came to the conclusion that given the choice to pick only 2 beers from a same brewery to have an infinite supply of , hotd with fred and adam would probably win over quite anyone .  last weekend fellow ba das freak showed up with the dundee craft pack sampler . after tasting the pa , ipa , porter and pale bock lager i thought we had stumbled onto something above average , then came the honey brown lager . at first i thought it had a funky after taste but it does n't wait until after . when my dog broke wind i thought i was at a beer pairing in hell . sorry for the negativity but if i can save one ba from this fate it will have been worth it .
this beer looks absolutely perfect .  very low carbonation , strong , hoppy with lingering after taste , a very typical english bitter but not my cup of tea .

the second surly can i got from my man joe aka ineedabeerhere . the aroma is quite hoppy , even with all this time in the can . pineapple , grape , carrots ? you can also smell a bit of alcohol in the furious , but only after sniffing the juice . the taste continues with the depth of the aroma , and i 'm loving it . it could use a bit more sweetness to accentuate the fruity hops .  some hop aroma and flavour , a little to light in the body for my liking .

a - what a beautiful looking beer .  take this beer for what it is ... a nice `` treat . '' it 's not something you will want to drink all night long . but for a nightcap , or change of pace this beer fits the bill . the vanilla taste is not overpowering , it 's there , but not so bold and overpowering that it seems fake .

a-black as hell , 2 1/2 '' incredible light brown cappucino froth head . this beer looks fantastic . s-roasted malt aroma is so subtle it 's barely there .  m-medium body and syrupy with a grainy tough texture . strong carbonation and a slightly messy carbonation in the finish .

the beer smells absolutely beautiful . like bittersweet chocolate and espresso , with some caramel and molasses notes . this beer smells really fantastic . taste is a lot of the same .  the taste is very good , it could use a bit more body but the flavors are great . tons of chocolate and roastiness dominate the profile but there is also some caramel and hops . the bitterness is at a great level in comparison to the sweetness , especially for the style . the guy below me has it right : not quite edmund fitz or blake butte but this one is one of the supeb examples of the style .
the body is orangish gold in color and is ultra hazy .  for the mouthfeel , i found this stout almost watery in consistency .

there is definitely a nice malty aroma as well . it definitely wants me to take a sip . t : the taste is somewhat disappointing to me following the pleasant aroma . there is n't a lot going on here .  mouthfeel suffers a little bit as i feel a higher abv would 've left this coating the tongue a little better . it seemed a little too thin to match its flavor profile .

pours a clear orange , chunks , one of the coolest looking heads ever , kind of a reverse cascading tan , head goes fast , some lace .  t - tastes like a combination of pine-sol and a basic light lager m - who cares ?
bottle : poured a bright golden yellow with a super huge pure white foamy head with great retention and super good lacing .  nothing special here .

poured from a 750ml into a tulip . the look is spot on . moderate gold , huge head , great lacing , very visible carbonation .  had this today on tap @ hibernia in boston . diacetyl ? in an ipa ? and what 's with the low hop profile and mega-sweetness of this beer ? my pint was quite cloudy too . beer drinkers of the world ... this is not an ipa , and it 's a pretty crappy beer to boot .

s- great nose ! pine , citrus , grapefruit , orange , malt , lots of hops yum . start is week middle is weak end is great . m- medium body , nice carbonation , o- this beer has a killer nose , one of the best but its color and flavor are a bit off for me , i would enjoy this fresh as opposed to part of their gabf temporary distribution in denver . good beer , but not world class by any means .  mouthfeel is a bit thin .
a huge foamy white head sits a proud of a light red brown body with slight hazing and tempting look .  mouthfeel : it 's a bit heavy for the style .

there is a lot to this scent , but it is surprisingly balanced , pungent sweetness and hops with subtle funk . good stuff , but it 's a shame it does n't match the glorious scent . mouthfeel is medium bodied and smooth , but a bit watery .  m - a little on the thin side .

oily , thick , jet black with the one finger reddish tan head expected from a russian imperial stout . head fades quickly with light lacing .  not too much that i can to the other reviews here . this beer was nothing but dissapointing . the label does say ipa right ? where are the hops ? i know that it does n't have to be a hop bomb but the flavor just is n't very good at all . i 've got 5 bottles left from this 6-pack . now i have to decide if i struggle though them or i just pour them out .

surprisingly hoppy aroma for the style with a prominent earthy pine presence as well as hints of citrus and tropical . it smells great just not like a wheat beer . clean , crisp and easy drinking with a slightly dry finish .  pretty weak mouthfeel , it 's a bit watery . i 'm enjoying the flavour and aroma quite a bit but the mouthfeel is a bit weak . but lacking in mouthfeel .

good lacing & head retention s : intense almost burnt caramel & malt & some alcohol t : smokey caramel & a little aclohol up front , then a hint of cherry & oak . finishes with dryness , a slight smokeyness & a praline sweetness mf : sticky rich body with excellent carbonation & balance drinks good , but 2 would be about my limit .  very dry with a bitter finish . a little sticky from all the sweetness .

s : this beer smells incredible . huge vanilla aroma that is mixed with a huge coffee aroma .  smell was sweet , with a citrus hint and strong english ale smell . initial taste was interesting , and i was n't sure about whether i would like it . by the end of the bottle , it had become one of the best beers i 've tasted . i would n't recommend it for any parties , but in small groups of like minded people i would say good call . very drinkable beer . looking forward to trying more from the brewery ( if i can find it )

the aroma is like a fresh hop cone very nice . from what you expect with the aroma is a slight let down but that said it is nice . the taste malty to start the taste turns to a earthy hop flavor .  average body and carbonation .
nice copper color smell : could totally smell those pumpkin pie spices . nice !  the body is surprisingly light with moderate carbonation , helping to make this very drinkable .

great hoppy citrus punch to the nose . very distinct grapefruit aroma .  appearance : pours a clear , healthy copper color , with moderate carbonation , yet quickly dissipating foam and nearly no lacing . smell : light scent of fresh hops is predominant , slightly dry with a piney undertone . taste : begins clean , progressing into a moderately dry hop taste ; as the scent indicates , there is a note of piney taste that is part of the dryness of the hops , finishes with a slight dryness that yields clean . drinkability : prime example of the style , well hopped , abv is adequate , and the fresh and clean taste only enhance its drinkability .

i can taste all the spices and pumpkin , but for whatever reason the taste does n't live up to what this brew smells like . it 's a lot weaker tasting than i thought it would be , at least compared to the aroma anyway .  mf : a bit thin , light body , medium to high carbonation d : another winner from sierra nevada .

2010 batch @ harvest fest 10/1/11 a : golden body with fluffy white head and a good cling s : smells like it will be very good : lots of sour-adding oak , some noxious funk and tartness . t : definitely a let down .  i got this beer in the beers of the world gift box for christmas . immediate taste is a lil sharp and bready with a hint of citrus in the smell . it was not an out of this world experience , but it is a very light and enjoyable beer for everyday or get togethers .

aroma : sublime ! super sweet , rich dark ripe fruits coupled with notes of chocolate . an all organic ale , not the best dubbel , but respectable .  perhaps a bit thin for the style , which i suppose makes it a good pale ale for summertime quaffing .
fruity nose classic ipa ( not the barleywine as is sometimes said ) .  m. thin to medium body with a somewhat biting carbonation . ends fairly dry .

s : the aroma is inviting with tons of spice and fruit . fresh ground cinnamon , nutmeg , hints of ginger can be noted . t : despite the aroma , it is a bit off in taste . everything mentioned above is noted but it does not meld together in taste as good as it does in the nose . the beer just has too much going on . d : just too much going on . it is a love it hate it brew .  s- coffee , malty caramel t- more coffee , chocolate , caramel and a little alcohol in there too m- medium bodied , a little watery really , decent carbonation d- a great example of a porter , just the wateriness that draws back from it

the aroma on this beer is a little bit of a lot of different tones , with nothing over-powering , really nice . taste is decent .  it 's a black colored beer with ruby edges . fairly nice nose , with a variety of dark fruits , as well as a bit of chocolate and coffee . really nice nose . flavor is fully packed , loaded with dark fruits ( blackberry , plum , cherry and currant ) , as well as some notes of dark chocolate , coffee and a light hint of alcohol . i like it .
big chocolate smell , hint of coffee .  m : light body , watery touch , smooth with low carbonated in the mouth .

it 's sitting across the table but throwing great scents my way hazy amber orange with some sudsy head juicyfruit aromas : immense , zesty citrus , mint . not much pine , which is a nice change from the norm . good , robust , woody bitterness ( it really hangs on the tongue ) with excellent hop depth . mint .  m : very carbonated .

this is probably one of the best or at least better wits i 've come across that could rival hoegaarden , but it looks awful ! such a shame coz this smells and tastes just like a wit should .  mouthfeel lots of fizzy carbonation , lighter bodied , finishes dry . the high carbonation combined with a thinner than usual mouthfeel really did throw off the beer making the flavors less prominent than i feel they could have been had the aforementioned two things been toned down a bit .

the body is creamy to deep red in colour and darkens as the head settles . consistent layer of lace envelopes the glass . gorgeous .  ordered this one in a taproom and was vary pleased . this beer is solid , as one might expect from north coast . it 's is as good as any pilsner i 've had . it drinks easy , has a hint of subtle fruit flavor , and smells very good . it also pours very nicely from the tap with a fluffy head . i 'd pick this one again on draft and might pick it up as a favor for a host when a house guest .
a - pours an inky black with chocolate brown head , very nice looking beer .  the body is rather thin though .
aroma is a nice fresh hop scent .  m-medium carbonation . medium body , slick .

appearance : pours an attractive caramel sunburst with a solid 2 finger dirty butter crown that shows moderate retention and good lace .  mouthfeel is full and seems overcarbonated for the style , but overall has the typical heavy/slightly syrupy mouthfeel characteristic of wheat beers .
incredibly fresh hop aroma . absolutely unbelievable . must try these galaxy hops for my homebrew soon .  the palate is thinner than expected but not bad .
it looks gorgeous , black with a creamy tan head .  mouthfeel : i wish they would dial it up a notch , needs a better backbone . stopped after one because it needed more body .
looks great . large , stark white head with plenty of lacing . it looked great in the glass but fell apart upon tasting .  m : aftertaste is bitter and body as well as carbonation is medium .

pours a beautiful red-brown with ruby glints , off-white head is large and thick .  not too complicated , but a pleasant experience overall . goes down quite easily ( in part because of the low carbonation ) .

aroma packs in big notes of freshly-brewed dark coffee . nutty caramel notes and an earthy hop presence are in the mix as well . surprisingly , this beer did not overwhelm me with coffee , but despite the excellent balance the nose is still dominated by the bean . overall , i was expecting a bit more from this highly-touted coffee stout .  if you closed your eyes and smelled this you would think your smelling a good octoberfest beer due to the scent of carmalized malt and faint hops . has a carmel toasted nut flavor on the tounge and finished dry . i like the fact that this irish red is a little more bitter than most red ales but still not overpowering . tongiht i will be reviewing 4 of hook and ladder beers as i bought a gift pack that came with 3 bottles of 4 different beers . the beers i got were backdraft brown golden ale pipe and drum irish red ember amber ( a type of black and tan made with their backdraft brown ale and golden ale ) . try these beers if u can find them they are good

amazingly complex aroma of hand-made chocolates . very mild and easy drinking . definately nothing double powered on the flavor . surprisingly clean . very light body . very drinkable .  light copper color with a large head s. malty with a slight resiny hop smell t. more bitter than sweet but well balanced with roasted malt m. a little to acidic and carbonated for my tastes d. a good lighter amber ale that i can heartily recommend

river horse special ale esb pours a deep cloudy gold with a massive pillowy head that took up half the glass .  ( i actually do not care for this sweetness , but the beer still has great flavor ) m : nice carbonation , but the body is a little weak .

a - hazy yellow , highly carbonated , soda pop head that dissipates quickly s - yep , definitely a peach beer , but pleasant .  the mouthfeel was medium/light bodied with a fine , prickly carbonation .

i was up in hell 's kitchen for halloween and my buddy took me to this place scruffy duffy 's ( coolest damn sports bar ever , check it out if your ever in ny ) and would n't let me order anything until i tried a guinness on tap . dark and smooth , almost coffee like .  mouthfeel : i 've always thought this was a little off ... not quite enough spine to offset the sweetness .

served at a few degrees below fridge tempeature in a tulip glass . the color is a gleaming orange , and the lacing is setting up with unbelievable sticky cling . superb ! smell- a bold metallic smell booms out from the glass , incredibly phenolic and overpowering the malts and hops .  this one is a bit light and watery but does have a decent taste .
smells amazing . chocolate and some buttery , boozy notes emerge with warming .  ( m ) - this is where the beer starts to fail in my opinion .

unusual and quite nice . taste : herbs dominate ; white pepper , belgian yeast , and a very bitter , grassy finish .  it was watery with no carbonation , and had a bitter aftertaste . but it had good flavor and decent body , and was fairly clean and easy to drink .

appearance , was this beers strong suit , poured a nice amber , with a frothy meringue-like head , that left broken puffs all the way down the glass , smell was rather vague , sweet malty aroma , dried fruit perhaps , taste waspleasant , rather weak , unsweetened tea-like taste , very light , and slight hop dryness , but a nice beer on a warm day , as it is here right now , mouthfeel , is light bubbly , smooth .  surprised didnt taste as much hops as anticipated since it is called `` hopfish '' lighter on palate than majority of ipas mouthfeel- slightly watery but pleasantly smooth .

this beer looks amazing in the glass . extremely rich orangish-copper hue .  i like a little heavier of a mouthfeel than this offers , but the lighter feel is not surprising considering the crystal appearance .
smell is very strong , very tasty , and actually has a mouthwatering , rich coffee character to it . start is somewhat sweet but very oaky and heady .  maybe a touch too much carbonation .

a : hazy amber with lots of tiny bubbles and a three-finger off-white head that lasted a while . very nice lacing .  pretty thin mouthfeel i guess , but overall its a great balance of flavor and drinkability , something i would definitely buy again .

overall pretty good .  the carbonation is interesting , but a little too fizzy for me , i feel like this beer has a watery quality to it which i do n't particularly like in a porter . it starts out watery , then the carbonation kicks in .

smells of strong peat , as you 'd expect with the name `` islay '' , but there is nice chocolate and roast balance . sweet flavour actually . very creamy mouthfeel , very sweet .  3.0 m : medium body . smooth , but not creamy .

poured black with a thick brown head . the retention was great . very creamy and capuccino like looking head .  s : slightly citrus , faint banana t : citrus & yeast & candy sugar m : bit thin , but not uncommon for a triple o : i am sure age did this one well reading the prior reviews ... think i paid $ 3.50 for it , well worth the price and a good brown bagger at a tasting .

the aroma is a nice blend of peaches , caramelized pecans , wheat , toasted bread , and a hint of bourbon . an interesting and unique dunkel , with an amazing aroma but it 's too sweet to have more than one .  4/5 m : surprisingly thin side of medium , slightly tongue numbing , spritzy .
pretty good .  the body was medium to medium light .

two fingers of light tan head forms and recedes slowly . the color of this beer is truly gorgeous ... smell is sweet and sugary upfront .  not too complex- makes for easy drinking , as does its texture . carbonation level seems low , though as an earlier commenter noted , it is actually just very fine .

this beer pours with the most beautiful colors of orangish-red . it recieved a perfect 5 .  an e-mail from the brewery indicated that twins lager is not the same beer as hauenstein , just with a different label . schells tells me that the twins lager uses a different recipe and yeast than the hauenstein , but a side by side comparison leaves me wondering why they would go through the trouble . i have always liked `` cheap '' beers . the beer drinkers of olden days wanted it cold , crisp , and cheap . but for afternoon lazing back and swigging , there is certainly nothing wrong with a cold bottle of twins lager . twins lager might be `` twice as refreshing '' as the label purports , but , boy would it be a treat to drink an original recipe fitgers again !

the aroma is awesome , with a big black cherry and dark fruit scent coupled with typical bourbon aromas : vanilla , oak , maple syrup . a very well-crafted beer and a real pleasure .  the carbonation is ok ; small fresh bubbles at a decent strength .
the scent is excellent and strong , with a bouquet of citrus .  m. a bit acidic d. overall a nice iipa .

the beer has a golden color with a hint of orange and features a wonderful malty aroma that is crisp and rich . the flavor is also crisp with some malt highlights and a pretty bitter aftertaste , and overall is heavier than i expected ( i was expecting something like a brewpub blond from this since they also offer a pale ale ) . my last swigs still get that great malt aroma wonderful ! !  smell : uh oh , something is going wrong ... taste : blecchhh . my stomach is starting to turn . what happened to this beer ? simply put , the taste is sour and offensive . beef notes : horrible . what was the thought process when putting this beer out for sale ?

the pour results in a fluffy off-white head ; the ale is a nice golden hue . patchy head retention and good lacing on the glass .  i have had ipas that went down a bit smoother but this one is n't bad it still goes down good but with just a little more carbonation and bite .

nose : a nice profile of strong citrus notes , not overly complex , but nice . tongue : what strikes my first is just how malty this is .  taste some roasted chocolate flavors . flavor lingers on the tongue after each sip . not quite what i would consider a savoring beer , but tasty none the less . i could drink this beer around the fire in the winter or after raking leaves in the fall .

the smell is aggressive , and with high standard , quite classic . a vanilla character from the oak treatment adds nicely to the vibrant sweet malty caramel butterscotch toffee brown sugar molasses notes . really nice ! ! the flavor is quite nice as it reflects the nose yet has a surprisingly black licorice thing going on , especially in the really enjoyable aftertaste .  the drawback on this beer is the carbonation - it 's too heavy . sparkly but with a nice dryness in the finish .

i stick my nose to the glass to get a better whiff of the hoppy goodness and i sneezed 3x . this is all about the hops . as the aroma foretold , this beer is all about the hops . the beer is drinkable now , but it is a big beer and pretty green .  little fruityness . light to medium body , oily , light carbonation . could be a little more carbonated .
poured very nicely with a substantial head ( which receded faster than i expected ) and left lovely lacing down my pint glass .  mouthfeel was unremarkable .

very sweet , but extremely complex . awesome . taste is intense sourness and bitterness , which tapers off to not much else .  do not know if this was an aberation , but this caused a lower score in mouthfeel .

smell is piney , citrus , caramel , spices , very nice , reminds me of the holidays , neat cinnamon-hop aroma .  mouthfeel : high carbonation gives the impression of a thinner mouthfeel , and the carbonic acid and alcohol bite knock this one down a little in the mouthfeel rating .

a- pours a deep black color with a huge , fluffy , brown head that leaves tons of lacing as it goes down .  very nice m : medium bodied-a bit thicker than i expect from an ipa or a dipa , but it works well with the oaky sweetness of this beer .

v.07 very nice look - medium head that quickly finds resolve . light perpetual carbonation , with a beautiful deep bloody amber resin-esque look , much like a barleywine/olde ale .  mouthfeel is pretty average , as is the smell ... i ca n't think of anything distinctive about these characteristics .

smell - i thought the nose on this beer was the best part . malt with grassiness . fresh smelling , almost floral . taste - wow ! that 's one bold and bitter finish !  mouthfeel however seems a little thin for this complex brew .

nose is `` oh my fucking god '' chocolate . this smells like a combination of the greatest cup of pure milk chocolate , chocolate milk or hot chocolate with touches of espresso , coffee , dark burnt coffee beans and pure vanilla beans .  a : dark reddish copper ; flat head ; strong carb ; not much lacing s : strong raspberry aroma , very inviting ; occludes other smells t : expected sweet -- it is n't ; the raspberry dominates , but it 's quite sour , draped over a wheat-beer-like base ; i must confess , this tasted terrible to me ; it tasted like nothing else i 've had , so i do n't think this is something against the genre m : good carbonation redeems the experience a bit overall , a terrible beer , for me .

aroma is a study in subtleties . a little bit of roasted aroma , a touch of sweetness . each individual component is rather faint , but together they are very pleasing and inviting .  mouthfeel : light bodied . i might even go as far as to describe it as watery . the carbonation was where i like it to be .
pours a thick black color with a medium beige head .  the mouth is a little lighter than years past .

awesome hop aroma of german noble hops . smells like tettnanger to me ... pleasant , dry and crisp character . decent hop bitterness and flavor .  mouthfeel : a little slick , thinner on the palate than i expected drinkability : a fine porter , would definitely drink again .

the aroma shows some nice complexity of aged bourbon , madeira , charred wood , vanilla & plum with some rich chocolate & caramel touched by just a hint of spicy , floral hops . very nice ! the flavor starts off with some grainy sweetness with a solid caramel character , but gives way to an edgy underlying bitterness that creates a fruity , off-dry , boozy/winey finish .  mouthfeel : thin body and medium carbonation overall : a nice geuze , a bit too watery for my liking though .
a sexy , blurred mahagony colour with patches of head . would leave small remnants of lacing .  a sticky medium body with good carbonation . a bit too sticky for me .

black in hue , opaque , it was served with about a fingers worth of beige head , which was surprisingly frothy . subsequent lacing was very prominent , bubbly lace dominated the walls of the glass . the appearance of this beer is near perfect .  mouthfeel is okay , no carbonation to speak of .

it 's robust enough that i 'd call it damn good . taste is good .  the taste was very light and highly carbonated . overall i 'm really surprised at all the negative reviews of this beer . maybe it 's just the fact i had it on tap , or that it was fresh .
the color was a beautiful amber gold , with some decent lacing . a great looking amber .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is light , as is the body .

: - ) s- nose is wonderful . if you 've had sam adams ' triple bock , it smells just like that .  the mouthfeel is just a touch too syrupy , though it does n't detract much at all from the enjoyment of the beer .

s- toffee , chocolate , oak , vanilla , bourbon , spicy peppery alcohol , caramel , molasses light floral hops , and ripe dark fruit . t- vary malty , overly roasted bitter malts , mild hops , light bourbon , hints of vanilla and oak , some nice dark ripe fruit as it warms .  good carb , but feels a bit thin and watered down in general .

this thing looks good ! beautiful two inches of white plume on top of a hazy orange , slightly red color that provides a light orange glow when held up to the light . the smell is n't nearly as impressive as the looks , though .  i 'm rather late with this review but i had this on tap at nicholson 's downtown and it reminded me of sierra nevada celebration . in fact at the time the original name was celebration ale . i 've since had a few growlers from jungle jim 's and though it 's a quailty brew i 've experienced some diacetyl like off-flavors when served from the growler . still it 's quite enjoyable and recommended . i wish the best to mike and his future brews !

nice retention and very good lacing . clear amber color makes this an all around great looking brew .  m : it feels light- to medium-bodied , smooth and a bit watery on the palate with a moderate amount of carbonation . o : the beer goes down rather easily and is quite flavorful despite its thin body .

huge pumpkin aroma with a bit of spice not unlike pumpkin pie ( which i was eating with it ! ) . my wife loves pumpkin and is not much of a beer drinker and really liked this beer .  light to medium in body .

smell is absolutely fantastic ! huge , un-mistakable aroma of honey .  remarkably good . but pay attention : almost 10 % alcohol , but you hardly remark it . it does not have that much body , but it surely has a delicate taste . i 'm a bit more inclined for brown beers , but this one is really good , and not brown at all .
s- very wonderful aroma here . very nice hop smells come from this .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is too light in my opinion .

pours a beautifully brown color with an uber thick bubbly head that dissipates very slowly leaving excellent lacing on the glass .  the mouth is a tiny bit like flat soda which was the only off-putting part of this beer .

this reminds me a bit of pte with that ridiculously great aroma and bitterness but not quite having the citric hop flavor that i would normally want in a dipa . this beer is incredibly bitter on the back end and the hot alcohol make this beer difficult to session .  m : slick mouthfeel with a medium amount of carbonation that can be prickly at times . body is medium and has a bit of resiny stickiness to it .

bottle thanks to nate , poured into my hill farmstead glass ... dark brown pour with a light tan head , great thick ring , good lacing ... the aroma is strong fresh coffee , lots of coffee bean , a little roast . finish is stale coffee not a big fan .  a completely black beer with a thin mocha head . boris is a thick , almost to the point of sludgy beer with a roasted malt taste with a noticeable but background hop presences . the oatmeal comes into play as a slight cookie taste . overall it 's a great beer that worthy of a try .

smell : smells nice and tasty , with chocolate and molasses notes . very little hop aroma , but still strong enough to balance the brew .  the mouthfeel could use some more body to combat the higher level of carbonation .
a definitive malty , smoky scent with maybe a hint of apple lurking .  has an awful , mouth-burning sweetness , a very artificial flavor , and a sticky-sweet mouthfeel .

excellent . sweet and sour fruits cominate the taste , but caramel malts creep slowly in , along with alcohol , honey , and even some wood . the feel ends up pleasantly sweet and smooth .  m - a little thin-bodied and watery and a little low on the carbonation .

big malty nose with hints of very dark caramel malts and lots of fruity yeast esters . light toasty wood aroma and some chocolate as it warms up .  m & # 8211 ; thin , refreshing , light , plentiful , smooth carbonation .

the powerful blast of cherry and almond aroma is all i get out of this beer . the beer , sadly , does not live up to the overwhelming cherry aroma .  m- medium body with medium carbonation . a bit to high carbonation for this brew but still has a light creaminess to it . nice blend of flavors just mouthfeel is lacking a bit imo . also the head could of been a lot better especially due to how much carbonation .

the head recedes smells great , rummy , oak-y , sugar cane , caramel , coconut , spicy , very layered and complex nose . there 's a little hop bitterness in the taste but all else is overpowered by the rum and oak taste .  smooth , mellow finish , and a thin watery mouthfeel .
s- 100 % hoppy nose . d- decent drinkability . very bitter . wanted more balance .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is quite sharp ; a bit fizzier than i 'd like .
mbc 's big jamoke pours up with a modest carbonation that creates a very creamy beige-khaki brown head that encompasses the very dark brown-mahogany body .  the mouthfeel was lowly carbonated .

the scent is sweet and hoppy . there is also a freshly milled pale malt scent that is very nice . i ca n't wait to drink this beer .  mouthfeel is a little thin and aftertaste is a little too much ... like the brew has gone stale , although i know it has n't .
smells rich and sweet with a nice peaty smokiness to it . overall it 's nice .  mouthfeel is a bit thinner than i would have expected .
poured a dark mahogany with a big light brown head that left some lacing .  parching on the tongue . almost no flavor : slight sweetness up front , trace of bitterness on finish . really .
the smell is of malty blueberries , you will not be disappointed .  m - thin with medium low carbonation d - not a bad amber .
s - great hoppy but aromatic aroma with a warming malty finish . lovely hops they are using .  easy drinking but it has a different mouthfeel , it almost leaves a film in my mouth .

( s ) - plenty of rich molasses & raisin with an even richer vanilla & whiskey-like smokiness . ( t ) - just like the smell with a pronounced raisin & cocoa profile .  the mouthfeel is larger light with a very , very slight fizz .

an interesting double ipa with a very malty edge and bitter finish . smells of floral hops , much caramel and honey and autumn mornings . honestly it smells a lot better than the taste .  heavy in apricots and dates with some coriander and maybe some hidden hops late in the nose . the spice showed more as the beer warmed in the glass . the drink started with a heavy fruit taste , around the middle of the tongue the spice showed up . the finish was lingering hops with and oily attribute followed by a light alcohol heat . all and all a good beer to drink with friends and discuss the merits of beer drinking . but i do n't think it would go good with food and it 's not the most refreshing beer .

smells like delicious ginger snaps , cinnamon and some clove . delicious . it has a medium body with a good amount of carbonation . definitely a sipper , but a very good sipper .  m : relatively light though not particularly carbonated .

this has one of the best aromas of an ipa that i 've ever had . sticky , piney , resiny aroma . i find this to be a very drinkable ipa .  this beer poured nicely with a creamy white head , giving off nice citrus aromas . the flavor was shocking , however , reminding me of kool-aid orange flavor , and with almost as much sweetness . i could n't distinguish any hop bitterness , though it could have used some to balance out the excessive sweetness . this beer tastes as though all the yeast were filtered out , and then orange kool-aid added post-fermentation

the aromas are divine : brandied , sour apples , an array of raw and roasted nuts , oranges , vanilla and pepper . on the palate it was metallic and struggled to deliver the promise of the nose . still , bright , sweet green strawberry and caramel curled in and out of the perfectly flat liquid . apparently this beer was not out of date , as there have been many other reviews this year for examples this old . a shame .  surprisingly carbonated , almost like a lager .

overall , this beer looked and smelled great , but has too much bite to really enjoy .  perhaps a touch lacking in body , but dextrinous enough to help facilitate excellent drinkability . although stoudts fest falls a touch short in malt character and body , but is nonetheless a well crafted , tasty and highly quaffable brew .
poursw hazy amber with a superb , ever-growing head fed by lively streams of carbonation .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .

the beer poured beautifully into the glass : a bronze-brownish coloured pint with a thick off white head . the main thing i noticed throughout the duration of the pint was the excellent retention and lacing that the head left .  body is fairly thin , but that is expected for the modest abv .

beautiful 3 finger head , caramel , frothy and persistent , reddish mahogany nice stream of bubbles , good lacing ; if this did n't look so inviting i would put it on a shelf and leave it there forever !  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with no carbonation .

good head retention that fades to nice lacing down to the last swallow . nice nutty brown color , with visible carbonation .  the mouthfeel is slightly buttery but leans more towars a syrup-like feel . carbonation would be greatly appreciated and add a very unique feel for this beer .

this smelled like the kitchen while my mom bakes banana bread .  mf : the carbonation is n't quite as spritzy as i would hope to go along with the huge sourness , the body is light d : this is a great lambic .

a : an outstanding looking beer . dark plum color with a pinch of tannish head and amazing coating lacing . stunning .  does smell a little like `` beer , '' as my wife would say . so sweet on the tongue . slight raspberry tartness but it is like drinking raspberry sorbet after it melts . it is still trying to recover from the sweetness . a good once in a while beer . sorbet beer , i tell ya .

this is very easily the best smelling beer i 've ever whiffed . taste is very disappointing . the smell is this brews strongest point , but it is also the source of the beer 's greatest flaw .  this was my first encounter with pumpkin ale . i must confess that i could not finish the bottle . i had the distinct impression that the beer was trying to taste like something and not quite getting there . fearing the latter , i tossed the bottle after about five sips .

on tap tonight at fountainhead in chicago ... poured into a tulip ... pours dark brown with nice dark ruby red highlights , good clarity . capped with three fingers of cool whip-esque white head that leaves a bit of lacing ... sweet and sour cherries dominate the nose with bits of oak and vanilla .  my only complaint is that i wish the mouthfeel was thicker . it was smooth , but a bit watery to me .
the smell is delightful . it is mostly of berries , grapes , and a hint of alcohol .  a tad thin .

apples , pears , plums , cherries , and a little bit of orange . interesting . some bubblegum/banana in here also . t- the taste isnt nearly as inviting as the smell , and is kind of a let down . d- after the smell this one sort of fell apart on me . i dont think id seek it out again .  mouthfeel : bubbly and light body . the mouthfeel is a little peculiar and affects my experience .
t- very very nice . lots of chocolate & lots of coffee .  mouthfeel seemed a bit to lean to me .

poured a very nice deep copper with fantastic head and nice lacing .  m : the feel is creamy and medium bodied . rather light for a ris and that really detracts from the beer in my opinion . the mouthfeel is lighter than what i come to think of when i thik of a ris .
this is one of the nicest smelling beers i 've had .  t - great pilsner , very slight hops , clean finish m - light body d - very smooth and very drinkable .

it smells delicious , but it needs more sweetness and less bitterness to balance the tartness of the brett , no fusels , less carbonation and more body .  t- the taste is dry , and more of the wood flavors seem to be more present . it seemed a bit much for the style of the brew . d- it was n't bad , did n't go down as smooth as most ris do , but it was still easy to drink .

awesome . the taste is again huge with cherry flavor without sweetness , cherry pits , a decent amount of sourness , with a good lactic tartness on the finish .  smell is cocoa , touch of coffee , licorice , slight vanilla , a whiff of smoke . taste is thick creamy , dark and bakers chocolate , touch of espresso , end is dry and slightly bitter , a woody aftertaste .

a clear copper ruby when held up to the light with brilliant head retention and honeycomb lacing .  a bit thin , for i think i like them a bit more bodiful , but smooth and flavorful i do think this one , yes .

the aroma is very fruity and hoppy : orange and maybe a hint of apple mixed together . ester 's given off from the yeast is quite detectable too . this is a very fragrant beer . helios tripplebock is crazy for being a german brew , as it is a total hop bomb .  s- smoky wood and scotch , one of the more interesting noses on this beer t- malts , with some nice roasted flavors that come through and then a hit of alcohol m- lighter bodied than expected d- a very interesting and drinkable beer , but one i need to be in the mood for

s- the dry hopping really comes through nicely . it 's quite floral with just a touch of an orange juice aroma .  m - the reason i dinged it on mouthfeel is because it actually left some of that nasty coffee-mouth feeling in my gullet .

great aroma , flavor and bitterness .  mouthfeel- light-medium bodied , high ! carbonation , and leaves a bit of hop on the palate but nothing else ... pretty boring here . refreshing and highly carbonated , this one grabs your attention for the beginning of the drink but then finishes weak .

) appearance : very nice appearance ... shiny amber body , very clear , big frothy beige head with great lacing . it 's a nice looking barleywine , thats for sure smell : odd ... metallic , plasticy pungent hops , sharp candied aromas ... unusual and difficult to describe taste : this is just a wierd beer .  m : very carbonated - almost too much .
pours a slightly hazy amber body with a good inch or so of off-white head that persists and leaves great lacing .  medium bodied and a bit sticky in the mouth .
clear reddish amber with a rich firm tan head .  perhaps a little watery , fuzzy . quite drinkable but somewhat sweet .

a- pitch black with a nice tan head s- roasted malt hits the nose right away , some undertones of black coffee and dark chocolate t- the nose gave the preview roasted malts , coffee and dark chocolate , very nice m- balanced , but i do like my stouts a bit thicker d- an easy dinking stout that i could have often .  in the mouth , it 's rather average , with light carbonation .

poured into a pint glass , this turned out to be a really beautiful beer . it was an amber color with a thick off-white head that persisted throughout the time it took me to drink the beer . there was an amazing amount of lacing .  m : fine , nothing special d : probably too sweet for a lot of people , but i 'm a fan .
a nice balance .  m : upper light body with high carbonation .

very enjoyable smell , roasted coffee , chocolate , combined with a truffle like fruitiness . the alcoholic notes get more and more present , and totally unbalanced .  mouf & gt ; meh . okay . average .

22oz bottle , 2010 bottling , poured into snifter a : pitch black with a thick , light brown one-finger lingering head s : roasted coffee , a bit of prunes .  a - black on the pour with no head whatsoever s - big burnt malt and bittersweet chocolate aroma along with some bourbon , some oak and vanilla in there as well , slight alcohol , as the beer warms up , smells almost like straight bourbon , maybe more like a bourbon and cola t - big bourbon flavor right up front , lots of oak as well , some bittersweet chocolate in the body , finish is more bourbon and oak along with some vanilla , alcohol notes , long finish m - a bit too flat for my taste , full-bodied but totally devoid of any carbonation action in the mouth d - i 'm glad port put this in a 375ml bottle , because this is a sipper , treated this almost like fine bourbon sipping for quite awhile , but i could sip on this all night very interesting beer .

tons of citrus and tropical fruit . big orange , tangerine , and pineapple . light grapefruit and pine . the one complaint i have is that when served at 45 degrees , this was very boozy . once this warms , the booze really comes out which kind of overpowers every hops flavor rather than blend . too boozy , kills all drinkability for me .  the only thing i felt was it could use a little more carbonation to balance the tart flavor and make it more perky .
absolutely fantastic aroma , but let down by it 's flavours .  i found the body to be a bit thin carbonation medium to low .

bottle , 2006 edition , let 's see how it holds up after 2 years , only $ 1.59 at walnut liquorette , in walnut , ca , a : pours a dark brown , with a boatload of head which shocked me , with great retention , leaving lots of sticky-type lacing .  good , but the mouthfeel is distracting . 3.0 m : light body , mainly due to low carbonation . need to get some better carbonated beer .

a : black pour with a nice light brown head .  i wont go through the details but if you are looking for an ipa do not drink this beer . it may sound novel , but black ipa is a retarded name for this , its not an ipa whatsoever . no hop flavor in the taste , not even close . im pissed i paid 4.30 for this . ridiculous .

the appearance is very nice , with a large fluffy tan head and a body that looks very dark brown until held up to the light where it appears a clear dark ruby red .  m- a little too carbonated for my liking , that makes this beer have a little `` sting '' to it ( especially if it is served too cold ) .

poured into a new belgium snifter a - a beautiful clear dusk sunset color , 2 finger head that lingered and lacing through and through and awesome tiny bubbles for days s - pine , citrus , malt , floral , cotton , sweet , grains and maybe a bit toasty t - very nice bitter sweet , pine , orange , melon , pineapple , very hoppy and yet super bitter sweet malty m - coats the mouth a bit with some super bitter sweet lingering .  this is a very good pumpkin beer . picked a 6 pack up at the local market , came home on a chilly night here in rural mi , and my girlfriend and i finished the whole six pack . lots of pumpkin taste , beautiful color , and an overall great seasonal choice . i would n't drink it in warm weather , but on this cool fall night , it hit the spot . i could see picking this up in the future to bring to a bon fire , or to enjoy while i hand out candy on halloween . cheers !
pores black with a thick tan foamy head about 2in .  slight astringent twinge . d- very good `` sessionable '' strong ale .
the smell came off fruity , flowery , and hoppy . great aromas ! !  m - kind of watery , but good carbonation .
the aroma is really great . big hop presence and a flavor profile that screams west coast .  the carbonation is around medium . there is a watery texture to the beer which is not pleasant .

vanilla , oak , maple leaf , faint rum aroma , and most of all ooey gooey caramel - sort of like a caramello bar . t : bittersweet chocolate layered with oaky and vanilla flavors , a caramel filling , and a coffee finish . i would even go as far to say this was luxurious or elegant .  the mouthfeel however is slightly taut . body is clear red copper with sustained carbonation .

nose : this thing has everything : an early combination of chocolate , caramel , and nuts presents a whole pecan pie on a silver platter . all this is followed by some dark chocolate covered cherries and fruitcake aroma . it has a sweet plastic lasting flavor that warns off any hops . has a bit of a smoky swallow which is nice , but does n't mellow the bubble gum . this one is getting thrown behind bars for 3-5 - then we 'll see if it 's more under control .  medium bodied fairly low carbonation .

pitch black with a cocoa colored head . tons of lacing .  cake/nutty malt up front with a huge , thick spiced tea hop flavor headbutt with the swallow . not just season 's best , but saranac 's best . i usually find them to be just an average brewery but this stuff is nice .

do n't be turned off by the little green specks floating around as they are chucks of hops leftover from fermentation and help accentuate the huge hoppy aromas . pours a nice creamy golden color with slight greenish hue to foamy head . aromas of malts and hops give way to dried fruit .  body is on the thin side of medium and the finish is both mildly astringent and slightly bitter .
pours out blackish with a big fluffy tan headskie . looks amazing !  mouthfeel is way more thin than the head and lacing made me think it would be . very quaffable .

delectably hoppy smell . taste is not bad , but does n't live up to the smell . it tastes thinner than i 'd like .  it has a medium body and a fair amount of carbonation , but again feels a bit weak .

it poured black as a tuxedo in a dark closet . it came topped with a dense , dark-brown head that had a lot of staying power .  a-garnet with small ring of foam s-raisin , pancake syrup , faint vinager t-assertive sour front , sour cherry , some malt sweetness , dates m-medium , with average carbonation d-very tasty !

poured black , with a brown head .  ran into the maui brewing company while killing time until our dinner reservations were ready . there was a very slight bitterness in the aftertaste but was well hidden in the passion fruit sweetness . found the beer to start like any average golden ale but the aftertaste was what i really liked about it sorta like an ice tea aftertaste .

a - pours a clear gold with a small head that lingers throughout s - pineapple is the main nose with some biscuit and some other tropical fruits t - spicier and less tropical fruit than the nose portends . hops dominate with a little bit of malt .  m : medium body with a sticky quality when it enters the mouth .

smells like ... .oranges ! ! ! fresh , ripe oranges . tart , citrusy oranges . the beer has strong carbonation , a bit much for my liking ... .almost soda-like in the most extreme case . hints honey at times . needless to say , great pick for hot weather .  m : light to medium bodied and highly carbonated .

wonderful aroma of coffee , milk and bitter chocolate , and a touch of smoke .  no sediment at all when bought fresh . this really brought out flavors you could not taste beforehand . a wedge of orange or lemon is a nice touch also . best served a little warmer than most beers . goes really well with food . a beer you could drink all night especially during a good bar-b-que .

smell : a deep and delightful warm caress to the nostrils . chocolate , molasses , brandy , and oak joint together for an exquisite amalgamation . wonderfully sugary , earthy , and effervescent .  mouthfeel is moderate and relatively flat .

s ) pumpkin pie ... this really has it covered . this is spiced , but not over the top , which made me very happy . a very nice balance of pumpkin and beer . this is quite smooth . nice finish and aftertaste . o ) i have n't really had many pumpkin beers , but i 've heard good things about this one , so i finally gave it a shot . i 'm really glad i did .  body was medium with med/high carbonation and a dry finish .

nice crispy scent on the nose..very citrusy ( orange blossoms and lemon scents ) and wheat filled..pouring a hazy cloud in my glass , some lacing , not much . this does smell like spring !  m : um . it was carbonated and did n't leave any odd off flavours on the palate .
the smell of it was great . the taste was not as impressive , but i did enjoy the chewyness .  mouthfeel is sticky-sweet and dense .

s-really smells quite like a full bore ipa .  this is the least impressive quad from the trappist breweries ... do n't get me wrong , it has a similar taste profile , although not that perfect as a westy 12 or a rochefort 10 , dark fruit , plums , candy sugar , but i did n't like the mouthfeel on this one . too much sparkling going on ... pretty funny thing is i just absolutely endlessly adore the la trappe quadrupel oak aged batch 1 version ... so so so much better then the regular one , especially when the oak aged version , bottled this summer , is coming around fantastic ! i like their dubbel more too .
s : big fresh aromas of earthy grapefruit , and vanilla cookie dough . t : bit of a let down here .  tastes pretty amazing really . watery on the tongue but ends dryish .

smell : complex nose boasts belgian yeast with a sweet apricot note and some underlying white pepper spice . complexities abound . taste : a well balanced tripel with a nice peppery spice and undistinguishable fruit presence . overall : solid , solid tripel . very fine beer .  m : medium-full bodied , zero carbonation , silky . d : lacks the warming feeling that is usually related to a winter warmer .
appearance : pours a deep , ruby-brown body with excellent clarity and a tall , foaming , sand dollar-colored head .  the flavor is a bit harsh and a bit watery , but not too much .
a : black on top , fades to reddish/brown at the bottom when held up to the light . nice lacing . a real gem .  carbonation is ample but the body lacks a little texture .

appearence : pours an incrdedibly clear light orange with a huge , creamy , frothy , mountainous white head that stays forever .  dark dark amber colot cant see thru at all thick white head remains on the glass and laces well the smell is of roasted and caremel malts , like a traditional english ale slightly different then my expectation of an alt but i like the smells tastes like a homebrew very fresh and smooth with crystal and roasted malts through out . to finish not a lot of body or carbonation leaves a dry roasted flavor

great nose . the taste is n't quite as solid with a less dominant sweetness than the aroma . the nose had me excited , but the taste did n't quite deliver and the mouthfeel was definitely a let down .  nice dark brown color with fantnaztic lacing ! smells choclotly with coffee . tastes even and thick with cocoa sweet caramel flavors continuing thru . good for its class this porter represents well , its much better than its younger brother . would drink again .
very nice looking beer in a great setting .  mouthfeel is a little too carbonated & acidic , which in my experience is typical of the japanese beers .
smell is an excellently projected , and wonderfully layered and clean tangerine , apricot , pear and lemon .  light bodied .

the aroma - mango , pineapple , & exotic flowers - is delightful . smells like hawaii in a bottle ! not as grapefruity as i usually like , but i did n't mind the lack at all ; a very pleasant surprise .  lighter feel and dry in the mouth with a little too much carbonation .
very nice . taste : malty and strong with coffee .  incredibly light with cereal grains , very grainy taste , hops are nowhere in site . there are way better summer beers out there .

good god this beer is gon na be great ... frothy tan head that could get up and walk out of the room if it wanted to ... chunky . yummy looking .  this brew is 5.2 % abv and my bottle looks exactly the same apart from the two silver australian international beer awards one from 2007 & the other from 2008 in the top left of the label anyways it pours a dark cola hue with a fast vanishing two finger head and sporadic lacing , the aroma is fresh chocolate icecream and vanilla expresso , it has an average mouthfeel with tastes of fresh chocolate icecream , vanilla expresso , macadamia and it finishes with a light bitter mouthfeel , overall a nice brew that is just lacking that full mouthfeel of a stout in my mind but in saying that its very sessionable and ill definately buy this again .

ah the smell of the hop flowers , dominates this magnificent nose that is also sweetly malt , fresh and clean , the quintessential dry hopped aromas all present , sweet malt start , the top moderate in feel . finish is delicately acidic , boom , the hops slap your palate and cling till the very dry and lovely finish , just plain yummy !  heavy mouthfeel .

it has a lovely roasted , woody aroma and the initial body is a full toasty , roasty malty assault that jumps quickly to a firm , dry bite and lingering hoppy finish . a beer like this is actually a good reason for my pessimism at another certain large brewer 's foreign extra reviewed in february , because this is what that could have been : firm , full and nuanced .  mouthfeel works just fine , but is a little watery . highly drinkable .

with a stiff pour , the brew produces a good two finger thick tan head , with a body that is dark ruby red and copper in color , and is well filtered . head retains decently , and lacing lasts pretty well for the style .  mouthfeel - medium body with a very active carbonation .
in the original struise glass it looks really great .  im augustus gloop : ) m - carb a little low , a little on the sweet side .
very ripe strawberries and a bit of peach . not complaining , though ... one of the best aromas i 've ever encountered .  mouthfeel is very dry with almost no carbonation .
very full and nice aroma , probably the beers best quality . the aroma of this beer is what really shines , everything else is just above average .  very light mouthfeel .
d - this is pretty good ipa .  mouthfeel is decent , this beer seems to foam up in your mouth .

nose brings toffee , yeast , cherries , dried apricots , chocolate , coffee ice cream , and spices . very complex and wonderous . palate gives us sour cherries , yeast , sweetened iced tea , hints of caramel and toast , and some overall tartness . the mouth has some good , sharp peaks midpalate and the finish is a slow , deliberate fade . a very smooth and clean finish overall .  but i felt the feel was a bit thin .
as far as a comparison with guinness , i thought this had a more bitter taste and a thinner body .  mouthfeel is light , and carbonation is set at medium .
taste is very boring after the wonderful aroma . this almost has no taste whatsoever .  mouthfeel is ok. a litte too dry for my liking though .

the bouqet is powerful , with bubble gum , circus peanuts ( the candy ) , bananas , caramel , toffee , honey , flowers , and a hint of the big alcohol that awaits . drinkability suffers due to the huge abv . this went well with a salty , deep blue cabrales from spain .  overall , quite easy to drink and enjoyable though the mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side and not up to par with the style .
positives : great aroma of sweet chocolate .  mouf & gt ; easy , average .
appearance - nice dark brown with a thick tan head that hugged the glass .  m/d - body is a little thin for me , would like to see the consistency just a hair thicker .
there is a smell that i place as a peachy pearish smell .  this beer has a fairly heavy body , a bit too much for my tastes .

s : a pretty complex smell , though coffee beans tend to be the dominant auroma . it 's nicely accented by a faint hint of sweet chocolate . t : there 's a real bright fruitiness that i do n't really pick up on in the scent that compliments ( but not well ) the coffee flavor that is n't so much roasted anymore as it is just kind of bitter . both are underwhelming to say the least , but this taste is n't as bad as it is disappointing .  mouthfeel : it feels like an astringent hop bitterness , but i sure as heck ca n't taste any hops .

) aromas are in the background and define it with a rugged , backcountry character .  mouthfeel : this was my one issue with this beer . it loses carbonation quickly , and with not that much to start with , it is kind of a bummer . a little sticky as well but the taste makes up for a bit of this .

aroma exhibited a very nice floral hop bouquet . light and sweet with a hint of spiciness . this beer smells excellent and is not overpowered by the hops .  m : lighter body , medium carbonation , somewhat watery thin feel to the body , with a crisp finish .

pours black with a dark hazelnut head with some lacing .  have you ever canned tomatoes ? if you have , you should be familiar with the smell and flavor tomatoes have when cooked . this beer had an overwhelmingly strong odor and taste of spicy stewed tomatoes . it was too strong to drink . i know this is not normal for this beer from the other reviews of it i have read ( and the style does n't allow for many strong flavors ) , but it was only days past the best by date and had been stored in a refrigerator . there was also some floating particles in the beer which i also assume is not normal , pilsners typically being filtered . i will come back and rerate , but i 've been told by some fellow raters that i should take this beer into account for my rating .

light-sucking black with a monumental 2.5 finger head of a nice deep tan . great retention and lacing . ca n't ask for a better appearance than this .  m - exceedingly bitter . needs to be a little creamier for this style d - not a session beer .

smells fantastic . spicy , fruity and different . really intriguing . tastes similar to the aroma -- some malty , almost candy-like , sweetness underneath , but with a strong bitterness taking centre stage .  the colour is a light straw , probably the weakest colour i have seen in a pale lager , the head is very pleasent and has some serious glass cling ... the aroma is very skunky when first opened but quickly disappears and the taste is highly sweet malts on a thin body , very nice for dining , not a stadium brew ... i first reviewed this brew in march of 03 , approx 10 monthes ago .
a one finger , mocha colored head has supreme retention and some amazing lacing to go along with it . very nice looking .  the mouthfeel is a little thin , very dry , but well carbonated .

pours bright orange , with a nice soapy head incredible hop aroma , tangerine , grapefruit , malt biscuit and some caramel sweet upfront with a bitter pine , citrus hop bite and a hint of booze very creamy , delicious and pretty well balanced for a double ipa overall it was a very enjoyable beer .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin and watery side though .
big crazy head thats nearly out of control .  mouthfeel : medium body and a finish that is a bit dry . this beer almost flat .
the smell was everything you would expect from a beer as hoppy as this . the smell of hop oil was big .  mouthfeel is just a tad watery .

appearance : pours into an allagash tulip a slightly hazy pale gold with a huge , fluffy , white , large-bubbled head . an insane stream of bubbles rockets up through the beer keeping the head constantly refreshed .  mouthfeel is a little thin , but not offensively so .

gave it a great appearance rating because it totally looks like autumn ! perfect golden brown hue and the thin wispy head perfectly resembles those thin , drawn-out clouds in front of the moon on creepy fall nights .  body is light and the carbonation is lively , a bit too much for my preferences .

this had a wonderful nose of tropical fruits , sugars , and malts , with a little herbal hop bitterness thrown into the mix as well . the taste was more of the same , fruity , sweet and delicious . this did have a medicinal , somewhat metallic , after taste though that kind of reminded me of orval .  mouthfeel is a bit thin for my liking .

huge chocolate in there . big sweet chocolate , dominates with malt and a little bit of roasted grain in the background . t : lots of booze at first , followed by a slight tart flavor , and it ends with roasty goodness . d : nice but the bit of tartness in the flavor really takes away from this .  body is perhaps the one less thanexcellent area , as its a little too light and i would have preferred something heavier and slicker ( more like the maui offering ) .
smells pretty good .  taste is dominating by anis with some candi sugar . body was above average and alcohol was well hidden .

pour was exceptional . the head rose faster than expected , and shot over the top of the mug - but it did n't overflow .  the mouthfeel starts off kind of watery since this seems to be a light to medium bodied brew and leaves a dry , but sticky feel to the lips .

the beer poured into the glass a brilliant clear gold with a thick , dense white head , te head retained well , and when it did recede it left a chunky lace on the side of the glass . a stream of champagne bubbles rise from the bottom , a testament to the carbonation of the bottle conditioned beer .  m : it 's a little thin , but i kind of like it . d : improved because of the thin mouthfeel .
pours a rich opaque sable with a fine-bubbled light tan head .  the mouthfeel is light carbonation , somewhat on the watery side , but very drinkable .
head holds well making this an incredibly good looking beer .  light bodied d- in moderation , this beer is perfect for a 2 beer session .
it has the perfect color for a lager , dark but not to dark .  very creamy mouthfeel .
