poured a beautiful amber color . wonderful lacing . just a beautiful beer .  m : nice light body on it with mild carbonation , which was perfect for this style of ale .

this is a beautiful looking beer . not much lacing or retention , but the color alone gives this one a prefect appearance rating .  m - smooth and creamy ! d - surprisingly good for an american porter .

burnt copper color , with haze-of-yeast and a soft , bright white head that stays around forever .  m - very creamy and milky and chewy , and not heavy in the least , this combined with the fantastic flavors gives one much to savor .

a - pours a very dark brown - almost black - with a two-finger , well-carbonated , beige head that slowly dissipates to a 1 cm head . very attractive drink , as well as bottle which is slightly shorter and wider than most 12 oz bottles .  i keep tasting chocolate ice cream ... dry chocolate ice cream ... not cloy at all ... very fantastic finish and mouthfeel ... german beer ftw will buy again !

this beer pours beautifully with an amber-copper hue and a frothy white head of at least three fingers . excellent lacing . can see yeast particles floating in the glass .  mouthfeel was great , it was very rich and smooth with little carbonation but it fit the stout just right .
a- golden amber with a creamy one and a half finger head .  i love the mouthfeel on this beer , probably my favorite part of it .

glass : snifter temp : cellared @ approx 45 degrees this is perfect appearance for a stout . it 's as black as black can be . the head takes a long while to recede to a nice thick surface covering , over an 1/8th of an inch thick . visually , this is quite an impressive beer .  a nice smoothness develops into a wonderful creaminess .
pours a hazy amber color with a large head that has excellant retention . heavy lacing is left on the glass .  the mouthfeel is one of the best i 've ever had .

this is an impressive looking belgian , from a 355 ml bottle it pours a deep hazy apricot colour with a great deal of carbonation action , and a massive creamy head that gets chunky on the pour , rises above the rim of my chalice glass and holds its form . solid lacing down the side of the glass .  great mouthfeel and is smooth on the palate with a hoppy bitterness that lasts forever .

a - wow , the gentlest of pours brings forth a beautiful ( slightly clouded due to my misjudgment ) light orange brew with the most ridiculous pillowy head i have ever seen , four fingers to start , sticks around for what seems like forever , and leaves great lacing s - pear and apple , along with a little cut grass , lemon zest , lots of yeast , clove and pepper t - smooth maltiness , slightly tart , with a lot of green apple , a little fresh hay , some yeasty goodness .  this is a big , complex , full bodied beer . the huge amounts of malts in this thing are chewy and even feel like they stick to the teeth some .

the aroma , which was really the high point of this beer , was quite terrific -- roasty malt with hints of chocolate and black cherries .  taste- wonderfully intense malt , and a big bready character that thankfully outweighs any unpleasant sweetness that the malts could impart . fantastically effervescent , it rides into the mouth and over the tongue with confident grace ... all the while alive and outspoken .
pours out a rich and dark amber/auburn colour with a big eggshell white head that is big and frothy and has staying power .  super creamy mouthfeel , medium body and carbonation level .
pours a beautiful dark brown , nearly black , with a tan head of about one finger .  the mouthfeel is exceptional and that is all i am going to say about this .

quite nice overall . taste : bit of a letdown here ; there are mild caramel and nutty flavors , but not much depth ... there 's a bit of biscuit on the finish and it 's kind of acidic , almost tart actually , and some mildly fruity flavor that i ca n't quite place and is mildly annoying .  mouthfeel - heavy body with mild carbonation . it 's perfect to me .

a - only a sliver of red around the edge . tall very tight light brown head leaving considerable lacing .  m : the mouthfeel is delightful . fairly thick for an ipa , almost creamy with mild carbonation .

pour yields a really beautifully colored beer , has a rosewood color , with a pillowy white head .  appearance : cloudy burnt orange/brown - nice head retention smell : cinnamon , nutmeg , pumpkin spice taste : hops , cinnamon , coriander , nutmeg - similar to an american wild ale - very tannic mouthfeel : my favorite part very tannic , smooth - the rye dries the palate out so you 're ready for another sip or another bite of food .
it pours clear ruddy amber with a very thick and creamy tan head .  m - the creamiest beer i 've ever had . wow . thick , smooth , perfect .
pours a dark brown with a healthy sandy light tan head that lingers at a fairly thick level and laces the glass heavily .  bear republic really , really nailed the mouthfeel on this one .

i smell orange , tangerine , kind buds , papaya , pine , and hints of rock candy . the aroma is lovely ! it smells like someone is peeling an orange next to me . good , but not as amazing as the nose .  m : nice and light , yet still has some body . very smooth , good carbonation , good residue . exceptional .

it produced a nice , soapy , white head at about 2-fingers . decent retention that left some seriously clumpy lacing behind . this is a vibrant and inviting looking beer .  however , it tastes great and feels great in the mouth .
pours black with off-white/brownish head in one finger thickness that lasts for very long time , generous lacing . perfect .  the mouthfeel is oh so smooth and creamy , just perfect !

buttery , pure milk chocolate sweetness hits the nose at first , then is ceded by notes of carob and suggestions of chocolate covered candied orange peel along with coffeeish , borderline burnt roasted barley . real chocolate never wavers in aroma , remaining constant and assertive .  mouthfeel- damn , this sh*t is creamy ! smooth , medium carbonation , but goes down super smooth . nice light bitterness in the aftertaste .

huge sticky head alone has a personality all its own . gorgeous golden haze pour that has no room for improvement , while in a class all its own .  sweet malts are offset by crisp hops together producing a wonderful balance and mouthfeel . sooo smooth !

a : this beer has the darkest head i have seen . i would describe the head as dirt brown .  the mouthfeel is light , with excellent particulates that roam the mouth . a most excellent brew that i would n't hesitate to try again .

smell is a tart , floral aroma with crisp , clean edge ; simply put , it 's delightful . this ale 's taste is a crafty hop blen dover a clean , crisp start .  m : smooth as silk but liquid is very thick and creamy . low carbonation .

a - moderately vigorous pour yields an over the top , dense , styrofoam khaki-colored head . decent sticky legs , too . impressive !  smooth and creamy , very soft carbonation . booze is extremely well hidden .

a - pours a very deep dark red , with ruby highlights throughout . there is lots and lots of thick , fluffy tan-ish head . it has excellent retention leaving a thick ring on top after it settles for awhile .  mouthfeel is truly wonderful , with a heavy , syrupy feel mixed in with a light tingle from some hidden carbonation and the alcohol itself .
reviewed 11/1/2009 ( bottle coded 8899 ) : pours a clear brown color body , with a big tan foamy head , very lasting .  super creamy mouthfeel w/o any overcarbed bite .

the closest thing to bourbon county stout ive ever smelled . a wonderful nose of raisins , oak , vanilla , bourbon , chewy chocolate , cocoa , rum , and god knows what else . it seems there are citrus hops that are mixing without dropping a beer with the malt and creating this rather sweet fruity start . finishing with bourbon and a touch of alcohol bite . overall im pretty happy with this beer . huge thanks to crushedvol for this extra .  m-grand canyon deep and gordian knot complex . amazingly tantalizing on the palate . while it looks still in the glass it bursts with palate stimulating carbonation with each sip . like an amusement park in your mouth ! this is a highly enjoyable and palate stimulating sipper . a mighty fine drinking brew .

the smell was so pungent i could smell it a foot and a half away , which was great . this beer was a great pleasure both to see and smell . taste : immediate bitterness that is the mainstay throughout the beer . perhaps , the appearance and smell had me too excited , but i was somehat dissappointed in the taste .  the mouthfeel on this beer is abosolutely amazing , almost like carbonated cream , it is wonderful and invites another sip immediately .
very fragrant , reminiscent of wit .  t/m - well carbonated , providing a prickly yet very smooth feel as it rolls across the tongue .
simply great to look at .  again this is a beer with a very good character but i still feel it does n't perfectly balance m- incredible mouthfeel .
extremely full smell , very good . t : sweet dark fruits up front then a booze laced chocolate and toffee .  m- great body , great carbonation . feels good .

paid $ 24.50 or so for the mixed case via lancaster county ... the beer pours a slightly hazy amber color with a large white head , exceptional retention and a dozen or so lacing effects , almost a perfect pour .  m - rich and thick , very chewy .
ripe pineapple , carmel and piney hops dominate the aroma .  excellent mouthfeel , low carbonation .

deep brown to black color , sempiternal and frothy head , tons of thick clinging lace , both a light chocolate color , with a toasted grain , coffee , and semi-sweet chocolate nose .  m : perfect . syrupy feel at first , but it does not over pollute your pallate like some brews .

saranac black lager is a dark and clear tawny brown beer with a thick , lumpy , light beige head that has oily bubbles ; outstanding retention and lacing .  finishes dry with nice mocha notes & a touch of charred grain mf : very oily & smooth as all hell with low carbonation & nice stickyness .

a - dark brown . reddish when held to a light . nice lacing on the glass .  bitter black chocolate moves into the woodiness and finishes boozy m- creamy , full-bodied , coats the mouth and boozy heat d- really impressed with this one .

aroma - dark fruits with a caramel and sweet malts .  round velvety texture , excellent carbonation , and ( as you would expect ) some warming . exceptionally satisfying brew - if not my absolute favorite from unibroue , it is the one i return to most often .

ever so slightly hazed with micro sediment . retention is great , and the head lasts for the duration of the glass , leaving concentric rings of lacing .  the malt is well back but the beer still has a nice light body . the palate is a great balance of all that and a nice honey quality in the background .
it was truly beautiful , and left something more than lacing , almost a vanilla milkshake looking coating on the glass .  it 's just smooth and thick enough to feel perfect going down .

a : golden , almost apricot in appearance with about a 2 inch head and tons of carbonation . s : i detected victory 's hop profile a mile away ! yeasty , with citrus notes .  mouthfeel is sublime . kind of like a benign dreamy tingling that coats the palate evenly .

on tap at strange brew in manchester , nh 2/2/11 a : light yellow , almost hay colored , hazy . 1 1/2 inch fluffy white head , leaves tons of lacing , almost completely covering the glass .  a full bodied beer that is creamy smooth and goes down really easy .
probably the prettiest lacing you will ever see on a glass . effing beautiful .  m : wonderfully smooth . nice creamy texture that does n't stick too long in the mouth .

pours pale yellow with a huge foamy white head that leaves tons of sticky lacing .  a faint bit of tannins in the middle of the tongue starts the finish , which is incredibly long with trailing , vineous notes of chocolate and spiced orange peel . ya it 's a bit like those warheads candies , but it 's tucked in such an incredible silky richness .

served in a pint glass poured from a 12oz bottle a : pours a deep black color with thick foamy head reminiscent of chocolate milk .  m/d : a full , silky smooth brew with low ( perfect ) carbonation .

appearance : dark brown to black , almost opaque . pouring leaves a thick tan head that takes a while to go away and an island of foam that remains the entire time .  subtly carbonated , with a medium-full body and a delightful smoothness .

this one is dark apricot , almost orange , in color and quite hazy .  mouthfeel is where this beer really shines , and makes one understand why some folks are such lager fans . the balance in this beer is amazing , with everything seemingly in the right preportion .

pours a golden straw , as clear as an unmuddied lake of deepest summer . dense white foam fills the glass , then gradually settles to a solid rocky head that forms big sticky patches of lace .  the mouthfeel on this is exceptional , so smooth will alcohol masterfully controlled .
appearance : deep brown to black with a creamy one inch white head .  m= perfect dryness and crispness .

looks like a perfect ris : pitch black with barely no brown around the edges , even when held up to a bright light . an incredibly creamy , frothy and sticky dark khaki head forms and sticks around for quite a bit . impeccable .  not the stunner i was hoping for m- beautiful mouth feel . i sure hope this is not the `` great sculpin '' i 've been waiting for for that past few years .

belhaven- twisted thistle ipa appearance- dark mahogany brown with a huge thick head .  m : the feel is exactly how i like my imperial stouts . there is a decent amount of carbonation in there as well .

appearance- beer pours clear and golden with a half finger of creamy white head with ample lacing on the sides of the glass . carbonation rises from the bottom of the glass as if this were a pilsner . very nice on looks at least .  mouthfeel was phenomenal - silky smooth and with a slight hops bite on the tongue , giving 'way on the finish to a great caramel sweetness .
massive head over clear copper liquid .  the mouthfeel on this beer is almost perfect . a nice smooth drinkable beer .

a very strong and pleasant aroma . tastes light honey sweetness and clove up front with perhaps a bit of orange zest fading to bready malts with trace hop bitter finish .  the mouthfeel was phenomenal . to have a cask conditioned beer is such a treat , and i 'm glad my neighborhood bar always has one beer on cask .

a : lovely dark red-brown , nearly opaque , with an antique-white froth that 's thin but resilient .  visual appeal : a bubbly , misty bar of shining gold , appealing streaks , almost continuous effervescence smell : very reminiscent of hard apple cider , mild hop aroma , strong yeast , really grew on me as beer warmed flavor : pilsner malts and bohemian hops and very strong cloudy yeast flavor lingers a long time , feel warmth of alcohol on back of palette , hints of citrus but not strong enough , i 'd prefer this a little sweeter , however mouthfeel : lovely effervescence plays with whole of tongue drinkability : heavy abv -- sipping beer , definitely would not drink more than one at a time my first ever belgian ale , right before the yank memorial day weekend , and i 'm definitely feeling it ( the ale , that is . ) i have `` gained a level .

a : pours a dark , um , brown in the glass with some light penetration indicating it 's not opaque . the head is pretty fizzy , with two fingers of creamy beige bubbles generated at first , before receding into a half-finger cap on top of the brew . some streaks of lacing as i drink .  the body is very full & rich with just the perfect amount of carbonation .

a : solid black body topped with three full fingers of rich , dense , medium-brown head that just barely poke above the rim of the glass ; incredibly persistent retention and a practically solid sheet of lacing .  the carbonation is very low ( natch ) , the body silky smooth , and dead creamy .
a : pours a beautiful deep mahogany brown . a large beige head forms and sticks around . lots of lace is left behind .  first sip reveals a soft creamy texture with mild rolling carbonation .

the haze really detracted from the appearance for me ... ... but it made up for the look with the smell . i honestly smelled this for a few minutes before tasting . the smell was very citrus like , with lots of malt and hop spice .  mouthfeel : exceptionally smooth and silky as can be .

appearance : light yellow in color with a large soapy head that stays around the whole time . the head on this beer is remarkable and deserves recognition . at first the beer was fairly clear but later i swirled some yeast in and the beer became cloudy .  really coats the mouth for an excellent mouthfeel .
smell : the highlight of this beer ... beautiful clean aroma of light fruits with a backbone of belgian yeast and a moderate citrus hint .  mouthfeel : about as perfect as could be asked for .

smells fucking amazing . this is the best-smelling beer i 've ever had . it smells like exotic , spiced , fresh-roasted coffee , like you 're standing in [ trendy east side coffee shop ] . really good , but not quite on the same transcendent level as the nose .  perfect . d- a remarkably smooth beer , although a bit mild .
it smelled wonderful . caramel notes and slightly fruity .  f : wonderfully thick .
bear republic tribute ale is a very clear , very lively , deep crimson brown berr with a huge , lumpy , beige head .  m : very creamy feeling , small bubbles , not too sticky .
d - looked great , smelled great , and tasted pretty good ... but seemed like a watered down glass of blush wine .  full rich mouthfeel , particularly fun after back-to-backing the hansenns cassis .

huge , billowy head of marshmallow fluff is perfectly `` belgian '' - big foamy clumps of lace are all over my glass .  body is velvety , full , round , and waiting to be enjoyed like a dangerous fruit i have in mind heh heh . finish is a fascinating contrast between exquisite and coarse , not too long and proly not a session unless ur into gettin hauled off .

this beer pours absolutely beautifully , pale yellow in color with a massive and i mean massive head .  the alcohol burns just a bit in the back of my throat , but overall the mouthfeel on this is amazing . d- wow !

a . great appearance . 3+ fingers of super dense head . excellent retention . great appearance , lackluster smell , very interesting taste , good mouthfeel , drinkability good and overall uniqueness good .  exceptional body .
biggish , crusty , light tan head leaves lots of hard , sticky lacing . very pretty .  '' love the mouthfeel .
perfect looking beer .  mouthfeel : full bodied , chewy , carbonation is spot on .

pours a murky , dark dark brown colour , only a sliver of colour really visible . head is stunning : beige , dense , small bubbles that wobbles on top but retains , with a beautiful , vibrant cascade when poured . lace is clingy and thick , like coffee foam . that 's a stunning beer .  this was the first belgian i ever had . it has a very creamy smoothness that i really love . finishes long and dry with more fruityness .
well , this beer pours pretty nicely .  the taste is a rich velvety malt with an amazing mouthfeel and a fully satisfying richness .
this pours a hazy reddish orange with a 2 finger head of foam . it looks fabulous in my nb goblet .  very big and chewy mouthfeel

a- pours a very hazy yellow-orange with a thick white head that lasts a long time and leaves lots of lacing . exactly what this style should look like .  body is medium-full for style , and this is just about perfect on the way down .
a- a dense golden/honey color . a nice spongy two finger head with great lacing to the end .  great mouthfeel .
slight visible carbonation , a very nice looking brew .  solid mouthfeel , smooth and dense with animated carbonation .

on-tap at beachwood bbq , on to the beer : the head retention is great on top this coal black beer . great , thick lacing sticks to the glass .  interesting effervescent mouthfeel makes it a pleasure to savor .
opaque amber-brown pour with a dense , 3-finger white head and tons of lacing .  really big round full mouthfeel .

lively grapefruit , bright citrus notes abound . what a lovely burst of pineapple and fruit aromas . so very inviting . taste - resin and oily entry , coating the tongue with the expected presence of hops to the max .  high level of carbonation with tons of tingle on the tongue . another excellent beer from ommegang .

out of a bomber this beer was a true , opaque black color . the retention was very good ; it soon became a fluffy cap that also left very good , consistent lacing .  it is exceptionally smooth and drinks perfectly for the style .
when i poured it into a typical pint mug , this beer instantly excited my eyes . beautiful dark liquid with a thick tan head .  m - full thick body , chewy and creamy at times .
what a great looking beer .  the mouthfeel of this bastard makes the beer for me -- incredibly soft and smooth for strong ale , probably the result of the oaking .
appearance : pours a perfectly clear , deep yellow body with a tall , bubbling , white head . looks nice .  mouthfeel was full , thick , and creamy with a rich sweetness on the tongue .

330 ml bottle poured into a tulip glass . appearance - the beer pours a hazy golden orange with three fingers of pillowy off-white head .  first sip reveals a smooth silky textured beer with a fairly thick body and gentle rolling carbonation . there is a sticky sweet residue on my lips after each sip and the boozy warmth lingers as well . the booze factor makes this a sipper and it is a little sweet and boozy to drink a full bomber .

motor oil black with a head like you would see on a rootbeer float .  mouthfeel is oily with a full body and fine carbonation for a smooth chewy feel . surly always hits this aspect right on the nail and this beer is no exception .

pours a hazy golden-orange with a rocky , fluffy 3 finger white head which recedes to a dense blob resembling an orange soda and vanilla ice cream float . solid ring of retention and loads of soapy lace .  a great take on belgium ale ; apples , pears , lemons , apricot and orange flavors nustle their way thru a carbonated full bodied swig .

pours a good head that has a beautiful big lacing , and it has an orange copper color to it that 's appetizing . there 's only a slight amount of sediment at the bottom of the glass .  it is very creamy and very smooth . it 's like chocolate silk . very delicious .
really great smell on it . can definitely smell the hops coming out . lots of earthy , dirty , grittiness to it .  m : the mouthfeel is what really sold me on this beer .
smells great . spicy , malty , slight peppermint .  mouthfeel - great smoothness , i was inclined to take a deep draw at the outset , very quenching . restrained carbonation adds to the smoothness .

fine bubbles rise vigorously to create a large , long-lived fluffy white head atop a bright goldenrod colored body .  the aroma is bold of chocolate and roasted malts ... the taste is very mild for a stout , blended extremely well between the sweetness and the roastness ... the mouthfeel wins top honors , this is even smoother than samuel smith 's imperial stout , absolutely incredible mouthfeel !

man , this was more of a teaser than anything ... could n't drink a whole pint if i wanted ... appearance is dark with webby head that sticks to everything it touches..the drink is so sweet and finishes semi-bitter , i feel like i just ate a sweet treat with each bite .  mouthfeel is just perfect - thick , rich , and creamy , with a slightly oily sheen that coats the mouth and throat .
smell- unbelievable aroma ! overall- has a great aroma but falls short with the taste .  exceptional silky mouthfeel .
the first thing you notice on this beer is the gorgeous pour .  m : incredibly creamy leaving a nice coating around the mouth that tingles slightly .

poured from a 750ml ( purchased at uncork it ! on grand ) into a pint -- the wheat beer glasses were all dirty , and it 's been a long week ... pours a gorgeous cloudy golden color with a nice foamy head ; it looks the way witte ought to look .  super thick dark chocolate flavor , light coffee flavors , good coffee bitterness near the finish super creamy , heavier in body , extremely smooth and hopefully i 've mentioned the creaminess overall , i love this stout , give me more

the aroma is jam packed full of rich bourbon right up front . hints of chocolate and licorice in the background with dark fruits . the pallet has a nice chocolate flavor to it with some vanilla notes . overall a nice treat here .  mouthfeel is astonishingly smooth and creamy for such a rich , complex ale .
black with a solid 1 finger tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  great bubbly mouthfeel , no aftertaste at all .

odor : rich citric aroma , tangerine , slightly lemony , floral backbone , some red fruit in there as well , pleasant and mellow . consistency : big carbonation , too much for my taste at least , it is straddling the line between gentle and tingly , no doubt that it gets in the way of the flavor a bit .  wonderful full mouthfeel .

nola brown ale , draft a big thick rocky head , deep ruby red color when held to the light . a nice looking beer .  the mouthfeel of this beer is great . they do an excellent job with the carbonation and creating the perfect body for a beer .

when you crack the can open you can hear the tsss of the nitro kick in , then it pours a full pinto of nitro head which slowly ( but faster than on tap ) dissipates into the body . nose is a bit roasty and creamy , nice and smooth .  mouthfeel : true german feeling on this beer . medium viscosity , rolls across the palate smoothly and is perfectly carbonated . great overall feel and authenticity .

i must admit i havnt tried this beer before and have seen it around heaps and have just avoided it for some reason so finally decided to finally see what its like after hearing mixed reviews and set the record straight , it pours a jet black as night colour with very nice carbonation that leaves a two finger cappicino laced head with heaps of visible lacing , it has aromas of strong alcohol and mocha malts and almost smells similar to a bourbon and coke not a very nice smell , the mouthfeel is above average with a mediumish mouthfeel at the start with hints of raisins , chocolate , coffee and some hops right at the creamy finish and im so glad the taste is so different to the aroma very nice , i cant believe a beer can look this good , smell bad and still taste beautiful anyways would drink again .  mouthfeel : truly phenomenal creamy medium body with the slightest touch of syrup likeness .

aquired through a trade with xpimptasticx , thanks wanted to try for a while a- well , it looks harmless , it looks like a regular dipa except it had hardly any head and no lacing but ... that 's where the similarities stopped s- incredible smell : blood orange , booze , hops on performance enhancing drugs and a faint mango in there t- sweet booze , like a orange hop liqueur or triple sec .  perfectly carbonated with an amazing mouthfeel .

this beer has the most incredible smell in the world . '' the big wafts of vanilla , caramel , and butterscotch fill the nose and is absolutely delectable . i could enjoy the aroma of this beer for hours . one bomber was enough for me , and i was pleasantly surprised .  m : absolutely wonderful ... smooth & creamy .

poured out of a bottle to a beautiful dark color . really a beautiful beer .  m- medium body and creamy soft carbonation lends to this one being a great sipper . d- pretty smooth but balanced , could have more now and will definitely have again .
also , a wonderful , frothy , mocha head retains throughout .  mouthfeel is full and rich , easy to sip and enjoy . sweetness hinders the drinkability a bit , one bottle at a time is enough for me .
s : very fruity , dark fruits ( raisins , plumbs ) and malts . t : very fruity , specifically raisins .  mouthfeel : has a great mouthfeel . it has exceptional smoothness .
dark brown in color and the tan head retains its character well .  mouthfeel is medium-thick but amazingly silky . carbonation is moderate .

pours an effervescent honey color with3+ fingers of cream colored head . insane lacing & head retention s : grapefruit & lemon , fades a bit as this warms t : follows the nose , plus pineyness , slight breadyness & a touch of leafy hops & dryness hiding behind a ton of grapefruit up front .  m - perfect . exactly how a dipa should be .
the transition in the glass from beer to froth is almost seamless , pretty impressive .  amazingly full body and mouthfeel for an american wheat , yet is crisp and refreshing at the same time .

this brew is really gorgeous . nice hint of red , obviously , but the cloudiness swirls around and give the beer a nice look . head is off-white and puffy ; almost too big even with a careful pour .  taste- for a double ipa , this beer is not on a mission to wreck the palate ... with so much flavor i 'm surprised that the malts weigh in so heavily . solid . it 's sudsy ( the name of my beloved late parakeet ) and sublime . drinkability- one real attribute about this bruiser of a beer is that the abv ( 10 % ) is completely hidden ... it 's nowhere in any of the above categories . this is more like a nectar , thick and juicy , garnering respect for each sip .
it pours a burnt orange color with a large cream colored head and great lacing .  mouthfeel is very soft and full bodied with light carbonation .

in a chalice , 50f : very pretty beer ; opal and ruby . head is on the darker end of the brown spectrum , but fades quite quickly . the lacing that remains is quite attractive . bourbon hits pretty hard in the nose , swiftly eclipsed by coffee .  m/d : full bodied , very smooth , velvet like .

a - this looks darker than some stouts i 've drank . great looking head .  the texture on this is great . with the silky texture and sweetness , this is a good sipper , but nothing you 'd have more than 2 of in a single sitting .
the beer pours out a very dark brown that is almost opaque expect for the edges .  taste & mouthfeel : thick , full-bodied texture goes well with the rich and yet smooth malt flavors .

overwhelmingly the finest ipa i 've ever sniffed . perfect . m - very good . nice carbonation and appropriate chewiness without being syrupy .  while there was no head , the carbonation is just right ; the body is no thinner or heavier than it should be .

beer also appeared to be quite carbonated smell : hot-day-amn . the smell of this one is trump tight . the eastern spices are like aroma therapy . those clove-ish spices blend with the hops and a sweet fruit scent to create an enticing aroma . taste : from the second this one hits your lips you just know that this is an `` americanized '' tripel .  however , the mouthfeel of this beer is phenomenal , on the tim of your tongue it tingles , in the middle it is smooth as silk , on on the edges it is a touch syrupy ( amazing ) a good beer , but not worth the price they charge for it .

light lacing , but the clarity of the body makes this look awesome ... the aroma keeps this awesome start going , a perfect hop balance between the citra oranges and some pine from the simcoe ; orange pine . some added grapefruit just makes this even better ... the awesome start is equally matched by the monumentally failure in taste , this is horrible . tastes like licking a lawnmower bag , citra pine resin bomb , with alcohol , disgusting ... mouthfeel is as bad and hurts the taste even more , too much carbonation , way too bubbly . a terrible taste , this needs to be avoided .  unbelievably smooth in mouthfeel - bittersweet chocolate and bitter roasted notes played effortlessly on your tongue .

beautiful aromas of freshly baked banana bread , vanilla coke , toasted candied coconut . definitely will be cracking some more of these open in the future , alcohol is well hidden and i tend to consider rr a bit too hyped but this is a very nice beer .  feel is pretty rich for the style , although it 's medium body it 's almost full really , with such a rich , smooth feel . excellent . honestly , it 's not very typical of the style at all , but i 'm not letting that change my rating .

pours a light , burnt orange , very clear . the beautiful amber-orange gives it an amazing radiant quality , looks delicious and refreshing . also great for the beach , on a deck or patio watching the sun set to match the color of this gorgeous beer , especially since it will go great with chips and salsa .  amazing mouthfeel . creamy and finely carbonated .

i noticed a nice hop bouquet on the nose which suggests it was dry-hopped . maybe it was n't , perhaps just really fresh as the beer had a born on date suggesting the beer was less than two weeks old .  velvety mouthfeel and smoother than sinatra .
amazingly slow head cascade action . clear from yeast or other floaties .  the mouthfeel is dead-on creamy .

how many citrus fruits are there ? this one has aromas of all of them -- i 'm picking up kumquat , grapefruit , lime and tangerine ( piney rind ) at the very least . all those citrusy hops i smelled are seriously restrained in the taste . from classic to extreme , from belgian to beefy american , from populist to just plain weird , dogfish head 's got it all . i 'd be their bitch in a heartbeat .  mouthfeel is a heavy but perfect . heavy with lots of lactose , light but fizzi carbonation .
one of the best smelling beers i 've tried .  m- very , very thick and chewy . also quite heavy .

the duchesse pours with perfect presentation . moderate amounts of milky tan head , with a moderately hazy brown body , including hints of reddish hues .  everything blends nicely in ot 's thick , chewy , oily body . minimal carbonation here , and it works nicely .
pours a chill hazed golen amber with a very impressive white head that melts to a very thick lacing .  m/d : full creamy body with light carbonation , pretty drinkable for 9 % .

ths one poured a dream , you shoulda seen it , looked like a photo from a beer book . billowy head sticking out of the glass all proud and boastful , very cool .  m - absolutely creamy and delectable ! the amazing , tiny bubbled froth envelopes and contains any alcohol sharpness that would otherwise make this 8.0 % beer a bit fiery in the swallow . superb . d - the mouthfeel makes this otherwise straight-up scotch ale an incredibly drinkable beverage . but be careful ! at 8 % , this beer is like getting a two-for-one special in each pint !

above this is a lovely 2-finger head of dense light-brown foam that shows mediocre retention and nice lacing . great looking brown , and only the sub-par retention kept it from getting a perfect score .  mouthfeel is where this one shines , smooth as can be and perfectly carbonated , a light yet creamy quality .
pours a 1+ finger tan head over a brilliant bright gold liquid .  m- full body in the mouth and sticky on the lips .

330ml bottle poured into tulip dec9 2010 a super hazy golden orange with tiny suspended particles being move around by a shitload of bubbles . a gentle pour leaves a massive 3 finger head that forms a dome over the top of the glass and just sits there for a while ever so slowly falling to a thick film with a island in the middle that looks like a little brain s a little yeast and pineapple with some other fruits i ca n't quite place and some booze t what i smell but with a little more booze , some cereals and a nice little blast of hops .  m - perfect . excellent balance of thick and creamy yet smooth and light enough to drink without too much concentration .

a : pours a clear copper color with a big rocky head . great sustain and tons of thick , sticky lace on the glass .  m- creamy smooth with just the right amount of carbonation and a nice , dry finish .

a- nice burnt orange coloring with a decent head and great lacing s- unbelievable aromas ... the tropical fruits are just amazing . you could mistake this for a glass of juice . t- kind of a letdown from the smell , but really the smell set the bar ridiculously high . this is definitely one of the better iipas i 've had the pleasure of tasting .  wow . the thick and creamy mouthfeel is perfect for the winter months and so warm .
pours out an apricot color with a good deal of carbonation in the body and a huge , creamy head with dimples all along the top .  the mouthfeel is a true hallmark of this beer .

it 's hard to make a stout i dont enjoy but i am not so sure about this one . the color is most excellent ( pure pitch black ) and it poured with a nice head but unfiortunately it did n't last and left very little lace on the glass .  mouth : velvety good . nice water . sweet , full , but not thick . medium to full bodied .
pours dark amber-brown with moderate clarity and a nice and thick light tan head .  a bit astringent . fantastic , full body with a very creamy feel -- pretty impressive .

slow pour with not alot of head . incredible color . just beautiful dark ruby . the sun shined through it and it almost looks like a red wine .  the mouthfeel is chewy , thick and amazing and the light carbonation is just right .

well it was a damn fine pour in to the imperial pint glass right to the top a deep clear copper , with a quick to vanish one finger head.somewhat downhill from there i have to say aromas of hard water and fruit but light and that clear/green bottle skunk but i wont hold it against the actual beer itself.flavors are ok it has the english fruitiness a touch of brown sugar and iron but not much hop presence just a light herbal note in the finish after a few sips.quite light for a 6.5 % alc beer goes down easily just nothing to make u want more , a decent beer none the less to be had .  wonderful carbonation .
excellent lacing and a fully lasting head .  full creamy mouthfeel with a low carbonation . thick , thick mouthfeel .
the aroma was wonderful with a sweet hoppy smell .  mouthfeel : fully body , lower carbonation , love it .

i 've always put off reviewing this thinking perhaps i 'm not getting it at it 's freshest , but it is perpetually average so here we go ... start with the positive.. good looking beer .  taste again where do i start ... sweet , spicy dark fruits soaked in alcohol ( raisins , currents , dates ) , toasted caramel notes , bready , some brandy / rum traces , biscuity , warming alcohol , spicy hop bitterness forces itself through the sweet maltiness , light madeira wine hints ... feel - so silky smooth ... rich and creamy ... light viscousness.. low drinkablilty for this one - a beer for savouring and sipping slowly ... overall - a phenomenal beer ... highly recommended .

dark , but clear with ruby/purple highlights . fine beige foam , really sticky with sheets of bubbles coating the glass . good head retention too .  m- extremely smooth with the right amount of carbonation d- this one goes down too easily .
a - clear dark , ruby red . head is thick , creamy and immovable .  smooth grit with comfort .

bonus points for advertising their smaller drafts as 14 oz , instead of the misleading `` pints '' of many establishments . bright white head that leaves great lacing , a ring for every sip .  the mouthfeel of this beer might be its most remarkable consistency ; velvety , silken slickness .

it has a great aroma . lots of sweet malt , floral notes , and honey . it 's a little too sweet , but still good . i also get a slight undertone of cloves .  in my mind , this is the perfect feel for an imperial stout .
a - dark ruby with tan head . gorgeous lacing .  the mouth feel is awesome . i let a full gulp roll around from cheek to cheek just to let my tongue play in the surf .

pours a hazy light blonde colour , with a very fine bubbled and retentive white head . really its absolutely spot on for the style .  very thick with just enough carbonation that completely fills the mouth and leaves a bittersweet flavor lingering on the palate , and a bit of a syrupy feel on the back of the throat with just a bit of alcohol heat that is perfect for the style .

appearance - 4.5 poured gently into my stange , three fingers of solid , thick , pink head formed over a burgundy-red body that is quite transparent and looks to be highly carbonated . the head retained well and left plenty of lacing .  m : wow ! just so damn smooth .
superb retention .  very palatable and no alcohol taste at all m - silky smooth , great carbonation .
just an over-sized glass with great markings . excellent to look at . a clear golden pour with a very generous head .  unbelievably smooth . feel is so outstanding for a heavy dark lager .

deep mahogany in colour , crystal clear when held up to the light . the head poured thick & white then retreated to a light surface covering , still maintaining the lace on the glass .  the mouthfeel was very very thick and creamy and not as thin as say a sierra nevada .
bourbon colored with an excellent 3 finger head that rises a good 1/4 inch above the glass . very foamy head that last a long , long time .  m - huge , thick , syrupy , creamy , perfect carbonation .
pours with an excellent appearance , thick tan head with small dense bubbles and a clear hazelnut color .  m : the best feature of this beer . rich , creamy , and silky as it goes down .
smell - like other little creatures ales , the hops really hit you as soon as you sniff it . passionfruit with a fair bit of malty sweetness .  m- incredibly smooth with a nice carbonation .

s - the first thing that hits you is a bourbon alcohol smell , which is quite potent . the aromas are incredibly complex , i 've never smelt anything like it . it is incredibly sweet , it makes your teeth ache just at the thought of it ; maybe this will lessen with cellaring .  the taste is initially of a very light porter and with a clean aftertaste that becomes a fruit sensation on the palate . the hop/malt balance is the real achievement here and it really contributes to the supreme drinkability . the smell upon opening the bottle is not an effective contrival of the taste that this beer is hiding as it only gives you an idea of the rooted flavor that is to be unleashed , the supreme balance and sublime flavor . great bier .

very pretty in the glass , big foam head that would n't quit through the whole bottle . heavy orange color .  the mouthfeel is dry with a long and deep finish which is full of blackened malt and char . very very nice .

pours a promising nearly opaque with a brown creamy head .  a - bright golden orange color with some chill haze present , two fingers of white frothy head that leaves thick froth-lace s - not too much rye here , just hints ... hops and bready malt t - hop bitterness up front , sweet bready malts in the back , only a hint of rye in the middle ... the malt backing is about as significant as it gets ... taste 's more like a straight up ipa than most rye beers i 've had m - hops tingle the tongue and give way to very thick , chewy malts that slide down nicely ... full-bodied and very enjoyable d - this is a reeeally well-balanced beer , i just wanted more rye flavor .

the beer itself is not opaque and almost black . very nice looking in the glass .  m : one of the most enjoyable mouthfeels i 've ever had in a beer ; medium-bodied and moderately carbonated , immensely smooth and surprisingly creamy . d : i thought that the taste here was good , not great ... but the amazing mouthfeel and complex flavor keep drawing me back in , and at much faster rate than that of many beers whose tastes i prefer .

man what nice looking beer poured a brilliant yellow with huge rocky head , watching it come down right now , smell was yeasty and slightly fruity.the taste started out a little yeasty with some slight fruity notes ending mineral like.nice complex ale even better than what i thought it would be .  s - sweet malt , molasses , licorice and red grapes t - sweet dark malt and licorice with a pleasant spice finish m - strong carbonation with a chalky finish that subdues the strong alcohol taste nicely d - very strong licorice and spice flavors combined with a great mouthfeel that balances the alcohol

absolutely one of the most beautiful beers when poured into a dimpled stein . amazing ruby red with a thin layer of beige head that dissipates quickly .  m/d - the mouthfeel and drinkability are exceptional . this is a simple brown ale that i could knock back one after the other .
amazingly attractive .  m : thick and creamy , the mouthfeel holds up to the indulgent theme set by the flavor .

damm , skippy , now thats what a stout should look like ! deep , cream black pour . an absolutely beautiful , thick and fluffy brown head , clings to the side of the glass endlessly .  m : very viscous and full . smooth carbonation and a nice stickyness make the mouthfeel very complimenting to the taste .
the beer poured into the glass crystal clear medium maber with an off-white frothy head which lasted to lace the glass .  t- pretty solid all around . very smooth , robust , and thick .

brown/red/amber , on the clear side , nice head that lasts . maybe give it a touch more opacity . edit : if they just called it a winter warmer and dropped barleywine from the name , why , it would probably just be average and not bad .  the mouthfeel is what really sets this apart . having had very few english cask ales , i do n't know if this is gold standard , but it is the best mouthfeel i 've had on this style beer .
when it finally does begin to recede , huge chunks of rocky foam are sticking to my glass . surprisingly beautiful to look at .  creamy but thin body .
attractive looking brew here .  mouthfeel is full but not too heavy .

giant billowing white head . the dense creamy , soapy head leaves giant lacey patches and a tantalizing heavy layer for the duration . color is a thickly hazey amber red with a big old carbonation tornado at the center .  great relaxed flavor , it has a nice sweetness to it , a good malt body ; it would be a great beer to drink while out on the river all day , as it has a wonderful flavor without having too much ( it was made with this in mind , according to one of the brewers ) . goes down extremely smooth with a great crisp , sweet aftertaste . ( had on-tap at the star city vfd brew fest fund raiser .

on tap at ebenezer 's 2/13/11 a : pitch black and completely opaque . massive 2 finger mocha colored foamy and rocky head that was there to the finish . i ca n't recall many big stouts with such an impressive looking head .  t : the taste was about average for a stout , almost identical in flavor to guinness m : amazing mouthfeel , so creamy and so smooth .

this beer pours a slightly hazy orange copper colour , with lots and lots of creamy , rocky , light beige head , which has crazy retention , eventually revealing some nice webbed lace around the glass .  mouth is extremely crisp , clean with tremendous carbonation and a nice light body .

it 's a solid gold with a sprightly white head .  the mouthfeel on this ale was great , and i think the mouthfeel of just about any beer is enhanced by cask conditioning . it had a nice thick feel on the tongue .

s : the smell is unbelievable . tons of robust , fresh raspberries blended with a nice cherry and lemony tartness . slightly acidic smelling with a hint of vinegar . not as robust and/or flavorful as the smell led me to believe , but this is great nonetheless . mouth puckering raspberry goodness to start , followed by some lemon rinds , dry oak , and slight vinegar . it was very good , but we all thought it was lacking something .  smooth as hell , perfect weight and carbonation .
not a terribly complex smell , but its really appealing nonetheless .  mouthfeel is very full and round .

bottle poured into a dogfish head signature glass it pours clear copper color . a fluffy eggshell white head is very long lasting and intricate lacing across the glass .  the evil spirits pass by , leaving behind a faint citrus peel flavor as a reminder that they now own your mouth . it 's insanely smooth and creamy ... absolutely perfect in that aspect .

head is a bright off white , watery and light , not much retention or lacing ... outstanding aroma , very funky floral muskyness , some nice brett ... taste has some nice things going , this is a musky sour brett saison , not sweetness , makes no bones about it . crushable musky saison , well worth trying .  mouthfeel is very delicious with some creamy notes but some nice crisps and sharp grassy hop notes .

very nice . mouthfeel : a little thin and watery . taste : i was a little disappointed after the wonderful aroma . the flavor was very muted and somewhat watery , not unlike the mouthfeel .  the mouth feel is perfect , medium-thin , medium-low carbonation .
a : pours a wonderfully bright golden/orange color .  mouthfeel is really impressive . very gradual on the tongue and extraordinarily balanced .

the aroma is spicy with loads of malt and touch of hops . the nose is spot on with what i think a marzen should smell like . overall a decent marzen .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , substantial and even sticky .
appearance : pours an incredibly rich , thick molasses/mahogany . you 'll be hard pressed to find a better looking beer than this .  mouthfeel : delightfully creamy and full-bodied . very pleasant .

the imperial stout was very black in color with a dark brown head . very pretty .  silky silky smooth on the mouth , it makes it feel as light bodied but if you take the time to get a feel it 's almost medium . just fantastic . o- this is deffinitely a good saison , the mouthfeel is the highlight .

pours out somewhere between a hazed and cloudy light apricot body with tons of bubbles feeding a fluffy , rocky , and dimpled head .  mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and creamy - almost reminded me of a nearly flat ginger ale , with more depth/body .
this is one great looking brew ... . both big and small bubbles and what appears to be a layer a grease on the head .  just a hint of carbonation on the palate - utterly smooth .

a : beautiful two inch creamy head . incredible creamy yellowy orange color with micro rising carbonation .  a very heavy body that is infinitely swishable in your mouth and extremely creamy . this beer is truly fascinating .

a clear , dark amber , dark caramel colored beer emerges and is topped by a super creamy , white head . lacing is so dense i can barely see through the glass .  all the great flavor of the bottled lhms here , but perfectly creamy and full in texture . this only further reinforces my belief that nearly every big beer should be served nitro .

reviewed 11/16/2008 ( tap @ the stables , st. louis , mo ) : very cool presentation in a kasteel glass with a castle on the stem of the goblet-like glass . pours a very dark blood red body , with a lasting frothy pink head .  you can feel how well-crafted this beer is : perfect body ... thin , but not too thin ; carbonated , but not overdone ; hoppy aftertaste , but not a tastebud destroyer .

pours a three fingered cream head that slowly fades to a thin layer , leaving a good lace .  mouthfeel is thick as hell and creamy , perfect for a big ris this is smooth as hell , much smoother than beers with this much ash flavor usually are .
smelled like coconut sugar pie , the nose is great . dark .  thin in the mouth but heavy on the tongue . perfect for the style and the season .
enjoyed in a pint glass a : moderate pour yields 1 finger of thick dark brown head that sticks around .  the lush velvety texture takes control of your mouth .

poured into my duvel tulip glass , poured a rich thick borwn that cant be seen through , a rich creamy five finger head rises to the top and stays awhile , the smell is rich grain and alchoal with a sweet fig overtone , the flavor is figs , hazelnuts , molasses , honney , sweet malt , a hint of folaral hops then malt for days .  m - very smooth for such an alcoholic beer . disguises the bite very well .

hard to imagine the being sweeter , loaded with caramel , chocolate , toffee , brown sugar , molasses , prune , fig , plum , cherry and apricot fruit , orange marmalade , bubblegum , candied nuts , on the hops side has pine and flowers , nothing too biting . in spite of this theres more room for more focused clove , ginger and pepper spice , quinine and earth . this forestalls the eventual onslaught of caramel , toffee , molasses , maple syrup , chocolate and so on , the orange to lemon citrus retains that syrupy and candied character . more yeastiness here with that bubblegum to banana touch . plum , fig , date , cherry , apricot , peach flavors , nice mix of darker and lighter fruits . booziness elevates as it warms , more rum notes and feels like it goes to your head faster . one glass is really all you need .  m - smooth , silky , full body with the perfect amount of carbonation o - great brew !

appearance- beautiful aroma- smells like raw dark chocolate and smokiness taste- bitter chocolate and smoke overpower at first . one of the less complex stouts i 've had .  the mouthfeel is the standout . it 's thinner but soo creamy and velvety . the oatmeal gave it the feel i had hoped .
a big fluffy ice cream scoop of a head , eventually smooths out to about a quarter inch . for a lager this is a very good looking beer .  mouthfeel - big , bold and smooth with lots of carbonation .

a : pours a rather hazy orange with about three fingers of off-white head . head retention is great , with the head keeping a chunky/frothy look , and leaves thick lacing down the sides . o : overall , its ok , the look is amazing , the smell was a little off , but the taste was solid .  the mouth feel is amazing on this beer .
great look to this beer .  mouthfeel : great thickness ; fully coating the mouth with great flavors . the mouth is great and just thick enough .
the smell is amazing -- like a nice plate of blueberries .  the mouthfeel was awesome with silky smooth liquid and superb carbonation .

the pour produced a billowing 3 '' head , hazey and unfiltered looking straw pale yellow . the head is slow to recede leaving an ice cream float like retention layer of large froth .  the mouthfeel , though , was the best part . it fills your mouth with mousse like consistency with very round edges .

the smell is very strong of nutmeg , cinnamon , pumpkin . this is an excellent pumpkin ale . the scent is so strong you will convince yourself that a pumpkin pie is baking nearby .  m : medium in body with a really smooth and creamy feel on the tongue .

black boss porter , poland the bottle is very bold and to the point , solid block cap , impressive . poured into pint glass : this beer is rich black color with a creamy brownish head , the head is small but retains well and long . the nicest red/mahogany color come thought when hit by light .  the carbonation is perfect . i love this .
excellent lacing . great looking ipa .  mouthfeel . amazing , thick rich and seems sweet but comes together .

smells great . huge floral and citrus hop aromas with a bready malt that asserts itself more as the beer warms .  m : the feel is excellent with fine carbonation lending a creaminess that is top-tier and a clean scrubbing finish with the right balance of crispness and aftertaste . d : an fine tripel with classic light fruit flavors mixed artfully with pepper and spice and a top-notch mouthfeel compose a very good brew .

a - dark as night with amber hue creeping in with the light . thick head that lasts the entire time drinking it slowly and leaving very nice lacing .  mouthfeel : low carbonation leads to thirsty gulps .
330 ml bottle , a : pours golden orange with an extremely long lasting rocky white head with nice belgian lace .  the first thing i noticed actually was the incredible mouthfeel .

huge , mocha head forms and stays around for a long time , leaving copious amounts of lace down the side of the glass .  m : the best part of the beer . very creamy while still having a touch of that hop thickness you want .
a : pale straw , great carbonation , crystal clear , and a lovely full head .  incredible mouthfeel .

i poured this one from a 12oz brown bottle into a tulip pint glass . a= this stout poured black as night with zero light penetration . with a very aggressive pour , the dark tan head rose a full 2 '' and took a long time to settle to a thin cap .  mouthfeel is probably the best part of this beer .
pours a nice dark black color , with a huge , chunky , creamy tan colored head , great retention .  still i thought the aroma was alittle weak , but once it hits your mouth it is amazing .

pumpkin pie spice is felt throughout and makes it absolutely wonderful . absolutely amazing . going into this , i knew that southern tier made some great beers . i had no idea this would be one of their best !  super easy going down with a perfect dry finish .
pours jet black with a thick , luscious brown head .  medium bodied beer combined with very active and tight carbonation combines to create an exceptionally creamy beer .
had a pretty nice look to it . pours dark , dark brown with a dark colored frothy head that lingers .  hard to imagine this almost perfect mouthfeel sticking around too long .
fosters lager pours a crystal clear light golden color with a beautiful thick foamy head that rides way above the lip of the glass and stays .  perfect silky creamy carbonation .

lots of big , flaky , dark specks rolling around in the carbonation ... looks pretty cool .  the finish lingers for a while , almost spicy with a slight alcohol burn m - pretty ideal for this style i thought .

a- pours a brownish color with red hues noted against a white background . the clear nature of the beer allows me to see the carbonation , which is modest looking at best . the head is plentiful and puffy looking , retaining well and leaving behind a thick film of dense foam on the glass .  a thick , milky mouthfeel , with tiny , spritzy carbonation carrying the rich flavor through your mouth .
amazing looking beer .  outstanding mouthfeel ! very drinkable .

a - beautiful hazy orange , loads of carbonation , four fingers of fluffy head with good retention . very little lacing .  nice touch of bitterness lingers as i contemplate the rich , full mouth feel . nice beer , much more approachable than the expedition .

not sure if i need a spoon for this one . pours thick as anything i have ever seen .  the best part of the rwanda gatsinga coffee stout is in my opinion the mouthfeel which is extremely smooth and leaves a pleasant malty coffee-dominated aftertaste and a smile on your face .

poured from the growler into a shaker pint glass . a : clear , dark brown color with garnet highlights ; over one finger of light beige foam head . heavy lacing remains on the glass .  smooth and rich on the tongue .

a= pours a nice looking hazy golden amber color with a nice cap on top . great looking beer .  entering the mouth , i immediately take notice of the huge mouthfeel on this . this is fluffy , powdery , quaffable , and has this charming soft carbonation that is typical of great beers . palate displays a superb spicy bitterness executed in incredible balance and harmony ( this and the mouthfeel are the 2 attractions imo ) , gentle woodiness .
from a bottle , poured into a pint glass a - deep black color with a mocha head .  m - exceptionally impressive mouthfeel , it 's extremely smooth and rich tasting .

served in the `` new '' sam adams lager pint glass , the beer pours dark , dark brown ( might as well be black ) with an inch frothy brown head . head retention and lacing are both pretty good .  perfect carbonation to it .
aroma is like smelling a bag of fresh hops ( this is going to rock ) .  great mouthfeel - full yet fluffy , almost leaving my tongue numb .
served in a wine glass . a beautiful copper amber color with a thick creamy head .  m- full , smooth mouthfeel .
a half inch of rich , russet-colored head temporarily lays upon a very dense cola brown body .  ideal texture for an ipa .
this beer looks fantastic . orange side of golden , clear with a big white , fluffy head .  mouth-feel was velvety smooth and creamy .
app- a nice dark brown which looked alot like maple syrup .  the mouthfeel is excellent . it has a medium body and good carbonation .

the aroma of this beer is really something -- it 's powerfully strawberry , like sticking your nose into a jar of jam . very appealing , assuming you 're really into the idea of strawberry beer . but i was disappointed with the taste -- it 's less strawberry lambic than just strawberry juice , a powerfully sweet , syrupy brew with no real malt or hop presence .  mouthfeel- medium bodied ale for sure and had small amount of carbonation . very creamy , and left a easy feel on the tongue .
s- banana aromas dominate with subuded peppery yeast notes .  this has an excellent mouthfeel .

not faux-bacos as many low-end rauschbiers often are ... but honest to god bacon . once you get through the scent , there is a wonderfully salty and sweet beer underneath , that makes you want to keep drinking .  m : very smooth and full bodied with a low carbonation .

it pours an orange yellow glow through the haze . the head is massive , billowy and ice cream like in its consistency .  mouthfeel is absurdly rich and creamy , silky smooth and slurpalicious . ) it 's the best feature of this brew . i mean , i like the taste , love the mouthfeel , and would enjoy having two or three of these , but that abv is on the high end .
smell : oh baby can you say citrus hop bomb ? loads of grapefruit and a touch of lemon .  mouthfeel : perfection . the bead is neither too large nor too small .

on tap at rogue in portland , or . appearance : black , opaque , thin cover of dark tan leaves heavy lace in the heavy rogue goblet .  some of the best damn mouthfeel you will ever get in a beer too .
s- totally amazing smell . just like pumkin pie .  m - perfect for a porter .

i `` stole '' a proper beer glass in the hotel bar ... a : it pours yellow to golden with a large creamy head that leaves great lacings when it dissipates .  added points for excellent mouthfeel and drinkability .

bottle enjoy before month notched-sep served in a pint glass the beer poured a crystal clear , deep , orangey-amber color . a two-plus finger tall crop of light beige froth topped the liquid . the head had excellent lasting power and it deposited a thick , drippy blanket of lacing along the top half of the glass .  ( m ) mouthfeel is perfect for this beer .
a freind brought this brew over ... a : perfect look for a belgian ale . deep dark ruby color like an iced tea .  excellent mouthfeel and not too heavy .

when settled it left a beautiful two finger head which dissipated only slightly and remained until the very end . the body is a nice golden yellow/orange .  i really this the mouthfeel is perfect on this beer .
pours a reddish , apple cider , clear brown . nice whitish head which hangs out for a while . really looks the part .  m- feel is exceptionally clean and smooth .

nitro-tap , nice pour into a pint glass at henry 's 12th street tavern in portland . color is brownish-black , thick tan head has excellent retention all the way to the end .  m : awesomely smooth .

11.2 oz bottle poured into duvel tulip a : perfect . billowing tan head barely contained in this glass . settles to leave full layer of fine tan lacing . as you sip the soft foam coats the side of the glass in sheets not patches .  it has a wonderfully creamy mouthfeel that makes each sip a pleasure .

bottle : poured a golden color ale with a huge pure white foamy head with great retention and lacing .  excellent body d - pretty solid imperial amber / ipa ( ? ) .
pours a very dark brown with a nice frothy one finger of off white head that sticks around a while .  the mouthfeel was buttery smooth as silk with full body and low carbonation .
jet black in color with a large milk chocolate head .  the carbonation is spot on and that 's what makes the mouthfeel .

a : very cloudy amber with a gorgeous fluffy white head that dissipates slowly . the bottle conditioning is excellent , so a vigorous pour is unnecessary unless you want a glass of foam . excellent brussels lace .  mouthfeel is perfect . not too thick and good carbonation .

let 's start with first impressions : this big beer makes a big impression on appearance . dark and sinister looking , the rough-textured mocha-colored head sits atop the black body like a russian fur cap . lacing is full and sticky .  where this brew really stands out is the creamy mouthfeel . that smoothness works to perfection with sweetness , but does n't work quite as well with bitterness .

bam noire pours a dark brown that approaches black . ruby red highlights can be seen along the edges of my chimay chalice . fully inch of creamy tan head that refuses to die down . tons of thick webbed lacing .  very excellent mouthfeel and drinkability .

poured into a tulip . the beer pours black with a huge tan head at least three fingers . great retention leaving some sticky lace behind .  it 's definitely thick , but it does n't feel anywhere near as syrupy as it looks . o : this beer has a great appearance and mouthfeel .
excellent retention . something you could stick your finger in and feel the foams welcoming grasp .  it is a full bodied beer with perfect carbonation .

clear golden body wit a 3-plus finger foamy , clumpy white head that never really goes anywhere . big old patches of lacing on the glass . if reviews were based on looks alone , this beer would rate very well .  full bodied and silky .
a absolutely beautiful looking beer .  the mouthfeel was amazing . nearly full-bodied .

one beautiful looking barleywine here . it almost glows a nice dark amber color .  feel is really nice as well , lightly creamy and buttery with super calming smoothness and a bit of chewyness with a slightly bread dough drying in the finish .
great looking beer .  m - creamy and rich . the carbonation is very laidback ... almost feels as if it floats on the tongue . very soft ... puffy , in a way .
a - pours a thick 2 fingers of tan head that sticks around for quite some time .  m - creamy and full in the mouth , so good , this is just what i want in a marzen .
s - awesome on my nose well hopped .  mouthfeel is incredibly thick and heavy , like drinking warm honey .
man this was incredible . citrusy herbal if i had to put some words on it .  fantastic mouthfeel .

a - it 's impossible to score higher , beautiful beer ... thick fluffy white head that resembles the frothed milk of a latte , dark gold to light copper , carbonation rains towards the head ... such a beautiful looking beer .  m : medium body with a fantastic carbonation balance ! amazing here !

very impressive lager appearance .  the taste starts with a slight carbonation . the carbonation builds to reveal a sweet velvet feel . a milk chocolate flavor with a roasted finisht showcases a great mouth on this beer .
it has a great thick fluffy dark mocha colored head perched upon a jet black body . the head was still present a good 5 minutes after pouring .  m : perfect . it 's thick without being cloying .

a : red-brown , fluffy off-white head , awesome retention and lace !  taste & mouthfeel : smoothness is impeccable within the moderate body , big doughy biscuity malt flavour is the showcase of this brew .
in a tulip the beer was near black in color with a light brown head . the head lingered well , and left abundant lace .  full bodied , super creamy and smooth . very nice .
perfect head retention & lacing s : slight hops aroma t : some fruittyness up front .  the silky smooth mouthfeel was fantastic and carbonation was spot on .
terrific lacing up the glass !  ( m ) - this is ridiculously smooth despite its hop dryness and woody bite . great carbonation level and balance .

( a great place ) poured a wonderfully rich yellow color . it was cloudy with a half inch of creamy white head . nice lacing with this beer .  the mouth feel was excellent and one could tell the cask was being maintained properly .

pours a nice bubbly clear gold under a 1.5 finger what head with very nice contour and retention , and outstanding lace . really looks nice .  mouthfeel : excellent light and crisp mouthfeel which is perfect for this style .
a - absurdly large head - tons of lacing all which sits above a golden brew .  mouthfeel is quite exceptional .

a : pours pretty much a pitch black in the glass , with a hint of mahogany translucence around the edges . the head is thick and cream-colored ; retention is outstanding , and it leaves nice lacing down the glass . truly a pleasure to see .  m - medium body and low carbonation , so incredibly smooth . perfect mouthfeel .

light brown head is over an inch high on the pour , looking billowy soft like a cloud . head retention is good as it eventually recedes down to a 1/8 thick cap but sticks to that throughout the glass . nice clumps of lacing stick here and there adorning the glass .  m : great carbonation feel with a nice medium body . amazing here . perfect !

it poured the dark copper of an old penny with a massive creamy tan head .  good and special beer , cloudy , double fermentation , yeast , hops , malt and wheat are present in smell ; taste fruity , and floral like grassy and herbs ; good for mexican haute cuisine , try with pasta and salads ; mouthfeel exceptional , well balanced and litlle strong for the palate ; 96 % recommended .

smell is predominately malty , bit of alcohol is present which is surprising considering this is a 10 year old vintage , lots of dark fruit and candied sugar .  mouthfeel is very crisp and smooth with some thickness from the yeast and bite from the hops .

appearance : pours with a massive amount of head , ca n't even pour the bottle in one try . awesome lacing . the beer itself is black as black can be , without even a hint of any other color around the edges . drinkability : this beer is a beautiful thing to behold , with amazing lacing .  mouthfeel is full bodied and super smooth . very enjoyable .

clear golden amber body with a steady level of carbonation and head that leaves a quarter inch of film like white head ; crystal clear .  mouthfeel is exceptional ! this beer is smooth , silky , creamy .

a : huge , creamy , tan head with insane lacing . very dark red-brown , but not utterly opaque . it certainly looks impressive . s : surprisingly neutral .  m. just perfect for what it is . very smooth and thick .

a- nice pour into a standard pint glass , about 3 fingers of nice creamy/airy/cloudy head , great release . deep rasberryish/velvety red rusty color . nice consistent lacing throughout .  each sip of this full bodied beer is smooth and creamy with light carbonation . this beer is so smooth it goes right down .
this ipa is perfect specimen as far as appearance . it is a cloudy gold in color with a nice foamy long lasting head that sticks perfectly to the glass .  mf - perfect ! soft carb .

22 oz bomber pours copper to orange with a 4 fingers+ offwhite head with effervesence . great lacing & head retention s : fruit & oak-like notes taste : apricot & oakey notes up front .  the mouthfeel is silky smooth and really rounds the beer out nicely .

d : nice big i.p.a. , best smelling i have had yet , very flavorful and the malt has been kept in check and the hops can come right through .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is outstanding . it sparkles just enough to give the palate a good tickle , but not so much that it scrapes away all of its flavor .

served in a tulip corsendonk glass . a - beautiful golden with a nice airy white head .  very light carbonation and a perfect body for a porter , combined with what i have already mentioned , makes this a very drinkable proposition .

poured a 355 ml bottle , dated 15 nov 2007 , into a tulip . a : poured a massive 1.5 fingered creamy head , in a tulip this appears huge . the color is a glorious tawny . the carbonation is rising nicely in the glass and it seems as if the head is hardly going anywhere .  mouthfeel : perfect , just like champagne .
appearance- very dark , almost black pour . fat 2 inch head just about overflowing out of the glass and excellent lacing .  m : glorious . so creamy and good . reminds me of a cask pour .
magic hat roxy rolles is a dim , deep reddish amber ale with a huge , frothy , rocky , creamy yellow-tan head that has excellent retention and lacing . looks superb .  perfect in this sense .

a : distinctly black with a fluffy , pillowy 2 finger khaki head that resides to a one finger head . very impressive lacing .  the mouthfeel is full and warming , in fact , this beer is a huge belly warmer .

poured nice gold color with a generous stiff white head .  m - this is one of my favorite parts so far about this brew . moderate amounts of carbonation that whirls around your tounge and warms it in the process .
poured ~4c into a perfect pint glass . nice white head that is laying there forever and leaves nice lacing .  mouthfeel is fantastic .
a tawny amber gem in the glass , champagne bubbles like fireworks , and an incredible mountainous head .  a nice chewy , creamy malt backbone makes each sip a pleasure .

a : dark caramel ale with a finger of whipped toasted cream foam . this sticks around for quite some time before barely retreating to a quilt of the same . sheet lace . excellent clarity .  m- creamy and full-bodied . what else would you expect from the style ?

pours a beautiful light honey color , having little to no head kept it from getting a better score .  excellent medium mouthfeel , that is slick yet dry - i could drink many of these but i am confident that time will lend complexity -- - please !
it lasts forever and settles to a nice pillow . usually old ales have no head at all . i 'm amazed this looks so good .  mouth : full mouth on this one , just right for this style of beer .

presentation : 750ml brown bottle , corked and caged , with great label , poured into a belgian-style chalice that 's been in the family for 3 generations apperance : absolutely stunning dark garnet brew with huge ivory whipped cream head , lots of carbonation with amazing cap retention smell : big powdery belgian yeast tones , a bit of juicy dark fruit , light phenols and spice ... it all melds together nicely , but nothing really jumps out individually , it 's a bit understated actually taste : much bigger/spicier than the soft aromas suggest ... .there 's lots of sweet spice up front here , with ( cloves ) ?  the texture is amazing . thick and silky , but because of the low abv , drinking this is just too easy .

poured into a tulip . this beer is a beautiful gold . stunning and fragrant .  sweetness with great balance . great example of what a tripel is supposed to be . drinkability : extremely smooth and creamy , incredibly so , on par with a westy blonde . extraordinary tripel !
appearance : nice easy lacing with a light head , lively , golden color .  great full and luxurious mouthfeel , witha soft , albeit intense carbonation that really lifts the brew .
this beer pours a golden color , with a thick and fluffy white head . the head fades slowly , leaving a nice lacing .  what i really loved was the mouthfeel . very good for a lager style beer .

whoa ... a : freakin ' black as my heart with a big tan head and lots of lacing . i really do think dark beers are the nicest to behold .  first sip reveals a smooth and slightly creamy texture , carbonation is almost non-existent as cask ale should be .

looks amazing . s : very nuty , caramel malt , lightly roasted coffe , dark chocolate , mild booze .  m- wonderfully creamy . the carbonation is spot on . one of the creamiest belgian beers i can think of .

12 oz bottle , unreadable stamping on cap , poured into a flute . a : poured a nice tan one fingered head . blackness with dark red shading on its edges , great lacing appears .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel . very smooth , lightly carbonated .
s : the nose is awesome . coffee . just so much going on .  the texture is likewise decadent , being somehow both silky and creamy .

an absolutely beautiful pour generates a very active three finger head of dark brown chocolate colored head that quickly faeds and leaves no lace .  mouthfeel - smooth , evenly carbonated , and a perfectly solid body .
poured from a bomber into a snifter a - exceptional ! dark , almost ruby like color when held up to the light .  very nice full bodied mouthfeel . easily drinkable .
a very nice looking sample .  the mouthfeel is luxurious , thick , and chewy . amazing . i am impressed with this brew . flavors are great and the mouthfeel is unearthly .
head is enormous and very thick and creamy .  mouthfeel : wonderful balance all over the pallets and each taste-bud . the slightly raised abv can give cause to the minor warmth in mouthfeel .
a dark body that exhibits a reddish tinge when held up to the light , with thick lacing spiraling down the side .  exactly how i like my stouts to feel -- heavy and chewy .

pours a big white head that takes up half a tulip glass , then settles to a half inch of meringue . body is dark yellow with some wit-like cloudiness .  smooth , airy , luscious , divine mouthfeel . tremendous ! a wonderful bsda .
pours a very inky black with a dark brown creamy head . very oily and sudsy , looks great .  this beer 's greatest attrubite is , in fact , its spectacualrly creamy mouthfeel .

pours almost a coffee brown with a hint of amber red in the bottom of the glass . nice 2 fingers of off white bubbles tops the glass .  mouthfeel is wonderful for the style ... crisp , wet and fresh with a punchy finish . this does n't look or smell like a euro-pils ( much closer to a craft brewed american pils ) , but the mouthfeel is nailed and compares to the fresh pils i had on tap in europe .
pours very dark brown with a large very foamy light brown head that leaves tons of drippy lacing and holds a nice rocky island and cap .  mouthfeel is thick with smooth and creamy carbonation .

very nice . i was frightened from all the soy sauce talk , but the aroma really sucked me in and eased my fear .  the mouthfeel is , in a word , glorious . smooth on the tip of the tongue , then seeming to evaporate off your tongue leaving a crisp , somewhat spicy finish .
a- pours a creamy 2 finger tan head over a black body . if this was labeled nut brown , i 'd be thrilled .  mouthfeel is just about right , not too thin .
this pours a beautiful black with a one finger tan head with incredible retention and good lace .  mouthfeel : fantastic . rich without being syrupy . carbonation is just right .
