appears pitch black with a thick light brown head .  initially the softness of the carbonation and the sweetness of the fruity flavors makes it like a sweet soda ( can anyone remember tahitian treat ? again with the yeast character and the near rancid presence ( the brett i presume ) , yet the overall soft flavors and soft feel are greatly appealing and enjoyable . the light , fine and bubbly carbonation brings an element of childhood fun to the drink ( how about fizzies , anyone remember that ) as it brings a tickle to the nose and tongue . light overall feel and great softness . soft and light and tasty ( again in a soda pop manner ) .
pours a bright , clear , light orange color with a nice looking head .  perfect mouthfeel .

bottle into an english pint glass appearance - dark brown/red hue reminds me of high grade saddle leather . a very handsome brew , sir .  extremely smooth tasting beer . bodied is so full its nearly chewable . mouthfeel is full and round . finish is clean and very smooth .

the initial pour formed a small head of small dark brown bubbles . as the head died , it left a clinging vine lacing stubbornly letting go of the side of the glass .  m : one of the fullest and creamiest dipas i 've ever had .
golden yellow with a full white head that melts to a quarter inch covering of sticky lacing .  m- full bodied and creamy . very smooth and silky in the mouth . full bodied but not heavy .
apppearance was a dark black color with a medium frothy brown head that dissipates fully .  mouthfeel is creamy smooth , thick body , low carbonation .
this is more like it ... pitch black . pours a thick brown head that quickly swells to 2 inches and then recedes to 1/4 inch .  the feel is big and thick .

smell - strong sweet vanilla smell . maybe popcorn , or rather , popcorn flavored jelly bellys . but in a good way . does n't get a perfect score on smell though , cause i 'm not really picking up any pumkin character .  the mouthfeel is great , for the bittersweetness from the roasted malts provide the ideal amount of oomph to an otherwise creamy body .

dark-brown/mahogany color with a full creamy tan head and good carbonation which leaves sheets of lace .  thick with just a little bit of slickness and just enough carbonation . sly fox oatmeal stout is a solid beer with a fantastic mouthfeel ; probably something i would order again .

probably the sweetest ipa i 've run across . aroma of candy and berries . nicely hopped with clear strawberry and other berry notes .  mouthfeel is damn near perfect for an o'fest , i think . impeccable balance .

pours a slightly hazy reddish golden with a big pillowy white head that retains well and laces the glass .  smooth and thick ( of medium thickness ) , with small abrasive bubbles ( in the best possible way ) . wish i had let it chill a little longer to see a greater range of flavors as it warmed , but still a nice experience .

when tapped , delivers a nice , cascading head that leaves neat rings of foam as the glass emmpties . a very inviting dark brown beer in the glass , with the taste of a fine dark malt character .  body is n't the first thing you notice , but once the distraction of the sour wears off , you realize this brew is very smooth , neither tacky nor sticky , nor drying . carbonation can be swirled up , and compliments the feel of the sour in your cheeks quite well . all in all , a crazy departure from the normal dfh offerings and dang fine weissen .
thick dense white head with great retention .  m : one of the most silky smooth beers i have had in quite a while . i would love it on cask , although the low carbonation is nearly perfect .
but honestly , the more i smelled it , it truly just smelled like banana bread . smells fantastic and tastes ok . i ca n't imagine buying it again .  the feel of the beer was smooth as silk .

the beer pours a jet black liquid ; impenetrable by light . the head is a nice coffee color , about an inch right up to the edge of my pint glass . the head retention is excellent and the lacing on the side of the glass leads down to a creamy top of the beer even when almost gone .  the mouthfeel was silky smooth , and i think it was the best feeling oatmeal stout i have ever had . the low carbonation perfectly complemented the medium body , and the smoothness from the oatmeal made it a joy to drink .

the most beautiful foamy head i 've ever seen , and it lasts forever in the duvel glass , sitting atop a gold so intense it almost glows .  m : the mouthfeel is perfect . full and creamy with a little grittiness in the texture .
the appearance made it look superbly delicious .  the mouth feel on this one is perfect . the head retention is outstanding and just adds to that smooth , creamy , malty , citrus finish .

left tremendous lacing all throughout . simply the best looking stout period .  mouthfeel is as silky as they come , the sensation over the tongue is as pleasurable as quaffing god 's nipple lactations . taste is , however , the killer here because it 's just not as explosive as the complex nose and full body could easily have supported .
pours with a light two , five-finger head that stays forever , leaving a good lace .  t/m : mouthfeel is perfect on this beer .
the chocolate yeti has perfect color in both the body of the beer and the frothy dark brown head .  exceptionally velvety mouthfeel on this one -- noticed that right away .

a- beer pours a slightly hazy oranghe-red with a nice foamy white head that stays around for a while before settling to leave some very nice lacing .  mouthfeel is very smooth , perhaps my favourite part of this beer . full bodied with subtle carbonation , it feels just right .

a heavenly delight of a smell taste : 2.5 this beer is incredibly sweet . loads of candy sugar in this , i am sure . this beer has crazy sweetness its very cloying .  m : as expected it has a wonderful feel to it that only a belgian can give . thick and creamy with a medium weight that gives way to an extremely crisp finish .
amazing body color , rich and golden , yet leans towards the orange .  mouthfeel : fantastic . great carbonation , no real aftertaste and washes easily over the palate .
lots of roasted malts and black coffee in the nose .  m - thick , very smooth and very viscous with little carbonation .

poured into a goblet carefully to leave behind the yeast sediment . nice thin creamy head , that leaves great lacing all down the glass .  mouthfeel - exceptionally smooth , with an awesome eveness that carries the taste for a while .
looks pitch black with firm tan head .  the palate is delightfully smooth and creamy . overall , this is an outstanding dipa that is sure to fill anyones hop fix for the evening .
a : the pour is deep deep burgundy with a really large thick creamy off-white head . the slow dissipation leaves lacings galore .  mouthfeel is so big thick and creamy .

presentation : poured into a tulip glass from a 750ml brown magnum . a : mahogany brownish-red with light tan head . almost blood red when held to a light .  this beer has an amazing mouthfeel , very full and luscious , super smooth .
it has a very deep black color and tan head that make it beautiful to pour .  the mouthfeel is absolutely perfect for a porter , so smooth and silky .
d : this looked and smelled great , but the flavor just was n't that enjoyable , and the body was only ok .  great , creamy mouthfeel .

wonderful tropical fruit and floral aroma that from my experiences is ever present . the centennial hops are very distinctive as they come out in the aroma and flavor .  really great mouthfeel of this one has won me over .

a- body is a moderately pale amber hue that pours with a nice 2-3 finger foamy white head . body is uniformly translucent and has the head has great retention with lots of lacing left all the way down the glass .  slick mouthfeel with perfect level of carbonation .
pours pale gold with a massive crown of stiff white foam .  m- great mouth feel . very smooth and not over-carbonated .

drank on-tap at atwood 's tavern , cambridge , ma served in a stemmed glass gorgeous appearance . thick , lasting rings of lacing coated the glass .  caramel , mocha , strong booze , brown sugar , raisins , figs , chocalate t-malt , mocha , booze , brown sugar , caramel , raisins figs , chocalate m-spicy , creamy , thick , barely carbonated d- pretty thick & filling .

tasted june 22nd 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - a clear blood red , one finger tan head and some lacing s - alcohol , wine barrels , sweet dried fruits , earth , oak , french vanilla and more sweet and alcohol t - alcohol , lots of sugar , sweet malts , tons of sweet dried fruit , black cherries , wine barrels , raisins , charred oak , molasses , carmelised brown sugar and vanilla .  huge bodied and full ( again , suggesting iipa classification ) . this is a beauty on cask .
the appearance is nice and perfect to style : pale orange in color and crystal clear .  m : full-bodied , a very firm and brilliantly sructured beer .

poured into tulip glass from 12oz bottle ... a- bright crystal clear gold . large two finger fluffy white head . one of most beautiful dipa i 've seen .  the mouthfeel is great ... medium on the palate , but slick and well carbonated ... compliments the black pepper flavor perfectly .

a : jet black with a nice dark mocha head that sits just barely above the beer . perfect for the style s : has a very nice mellow scotch smell that is not too harsh along side a slight sweetness of vanilla and honey .  mouthfeel - per style it is dead on ... fairly dry and actually not sticky compared to other barleywines .

poured this 12 ounce gem into a british pint glass and really enjoyed this smooth stout jet black appearance with 2 fingers of foamy tan colored head and retention ; this brew looks perfect , and staring at that glass rekindles an image of a british pub aroma of a sweet , biscuitty , and dark chocolate notes rich , full bodied , toasty malt , balanced with some hops which accentuate the side of my tongue , and a finish with a bit of zing that lingers on the palate .  the mouthfeel is very smooth , with minimal aftertaste .
pours from the tap to a pretty chocolate brown with a thick tan head that lingers well and leaves good lacing .  creamy , silky mouthfeel .
excited to try this one ... a : looks perfect . deep murky copper color with a thick 1 inch white head that fades decently .  a great feel that has a body that replenishes itself .

30 cl brown bottle poured into a pint glass ( it 's the only glassware i own ) . a : super-thick , rich , creamy , mostly white foamy head . in fact , the head was so thick that this small 300 ml bottle would n't fit into my imperial pint glass without waiting for some of the head to thin out .  m : full-bodied , silky smooth , velvety rich and downright luxurious in the mouth . these guys have this whole mouthfeel down to a t. notes : malty rich , fruity sweet , and explosively spicy , this bspa is quite enjoyable !

pours an almost transparent golden/light copper with an amazingly fluffy 3 finger head from an extremely gentle pour .  mouthfeel is very thick and chewy , silky and long lasting on the palate , near perfect .

) , puckered 10/06 slow pour in a tulip glass poured murky pale orange with a huge rocky fully lasting white head with good lacing .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , like an expensive champagne and it finishes very dry .

color is pure copper , exactly matching the unoxidized metal . beautiful . the head was outstanding , but i did make an over-aggressive pour . it faded to a normal cap , but didnt stick to the glass well .  amazingly full mouthfeel .

smells like a rich and fruity tripel and is very inviting . as far as taste , the hops kick in first and are then followed by a slight hint of the tripel .  m : lovely . sort of creamy , without being too heavy .

i got this beer from the local gas station and thought i should try it because im a big fan of seasonals . the appearance is great just like every other goose island .  appearance : amber , clear carbonated , medium head smell : alcohol , grapefruit , and citrus taste : alcohol , grapefruit , malts , hops , and slight caramel mouthfeel : smooth , slightly hard finish , can feel the carbonation ... it is amazing how smooth and unbitter this beer is for a beer with its abv drinkability : i will have this again , but may be one of the few that prefer the 60 minute ipa .

aroma is great . i really get a spicy sage aroma on this one . a sweetness from the herbal notes really plays perfect with this one . really a perfect nose . taste is spot on too .  m : full body , and shockingly creamy . this brew is extremely smooth of the mouth .

poured into a tulip ( i do n't know why it just was handy ) a - pours a good light golden color , about 2 fingers of fluffy white head that creates some really pretty lacing and has a lot of carbonation .  starts with roasted coffee flavor , mouthfeel is incredible smooth .

aroma is by far the best part of this beer . a veritable tropical drink in this beer ! flavor does not follow through from the aroma- surprising . i detected minimal hops in the aroma , but they are there quite blatently in the flavor .  m - perfect ? perfect .
one of the best smelling beers i have tried .  beautiful .
pours a copper/red color , nice big fluffy head to it that sticks around with a lot of lacing .  perfect ris mouthfeel .

pours with a beautiful long-lasting head and a very nice effervescence ; there is a constant stream of bubbles rising from the bottom of the glass till the last drop .  mouthfeel is a great aspect of this beer . a big , creamy , velvety beer . soft and velvet from the oatmeal , low carbonation .

it 's a very appealing smell . taste : part belgian wit and part apple cider blended together . the smell is really good , but the taste is a bit disappointing in comparison . the good aromas in the smell do n't show up in the taste .  mouthfeel is silky smooth , really nice . body fairly full and the beer leaves an impression all the way over the tongue .
pours a huge head with crazy retention that wo n't leave the glass .  finishes fruitty & spicy mf : huge & well balanced this was bit ponderous , but tasty .
pours a deep black with a tan head .  mouthfeel is velvety and smooth . great length on the taste .
a pretty good looking beer .  m- the first thing i notice with this is how smooth and creamy it is . d- a very enjoyable english barleywine . tasty .

app : deep amber clear . very thick fluffy white head w/lace .  this is so creamy and not too carbonated , its just enough to get both senses of substantial and refreshing . quite thick , not so much as syrup but a few steps under . one please , fills the stomach nicely , not too harsh on the throat or stomach . it has a nice balance between warmth and coolness in the stomach .
a - pours a dark , murky brown with ruby highlights .  m - smooth as silk .

appearance - cloudy orange , wonderfull perfect thick creamy head , good lacing . perfect !  m : full-bodied and lightly carbonated with a soft and creamy texture . alcohol noticable in a nice warming effect .
this does throw a great looking pour into my glass .  the mouthfeel is great and smooth as can be .

rgc pours a deep red-cognac color with generous carbonation and a settling tan head .  my favorite thing about this obviously the sweet rich malt character which adds to a very nice body for a beer of this alcohol content .

22oz bomber into pint glass a nearly white head disappeared quickly , no lacing , hazy golden orange amber gives a nice appearance 3.5 s a really good apricot scent dominates its aroma you pour your glass 4.5 t apricot takes the lead on the flavor but there are sweet bread and grains now also .  mouthfeel is just perfect . the way this thing finishes it has a slight peppery aspect but it is dry and clean .

bomber into a shaker glass , the boont esb is hazy burnt orange with a tall , rocky light khaki head , that took a while to subside to a thick skim leaving decent lace . very nice !  the mouthfeel is amazing . the belgian in this beer seems to come from the relatively light body but firm and billowy head that rollicks around my mouth .

appearance/pour : nice dark amber with a surprising stream of carbonation rising from the glass bottom etch . head which dissapates to a nice ring with small foamy clusters . thick lacing and a dense sound while pouring- sounds thick .  mouthfeel is superb . almost perfect , well rounded , full , with a snappy finish .

even the airy foam atop this beer has pungent , dry , fruity hop characteristics.. as i find out as my nose and lips accidentally come in contact with the crown . aroma pleases with juicy hop aromas.. not overwhelming and no alcohol detectable . a nice brown sugary malt presence here balances.. unexpected but nice . some apple aromas as well as something spicy like yeast .  m : a great , great medium body , that grazes you at the tail with sharp carbonation .

i had this on tap and have to say was extremely impressed by its beautiful golden color , and fine head .  mouthfeel/overall : this beer is every bit of full bodied ; thick , chewy and creamy . everything an imperial stout should be . overall , a very good imperial stout that i 'd love to have full time access to .
a : pours a dark brown/near black with a tall light brown head that sticks around and leaves some very nice lacing .  mouthfeel - very smooth with a rich body and muted carbonation .

the aromas were delectable , with a balance between the banana and the spices ( clove & coriander ) with the banana just edging them out . they are all there , just much too subtlety .  mouthfeel is thick and chewy , as it should be fir a beer of this strength .
big firm plush head , one of the most impressive i have ever seen . opaque black hue as expected .  mouthfeel is thick and creamy , very nice .

the way the carbonation and creamy foam mixes with the super dark body of the beer is gorgeous . through the glass , it looked like the bubbles were cascading like a waterfall , only upwards . anyway , the body is opaque and the head is super creamy and tan in apprearance . the head stuck around for a long time and left decent lacing .  mouthfeel is perfect ! not thick like a stout , but with enough meat to be very smooth and coating .

) , 2011 scorched crimson brown color ; fairly dark . the head does recede but retention is solid and there is a good bit of lace .  full bodied with creamy carbonation and a lingering sweet licorice finish .

very pretty beer . deep dark brown , with a huge , tan head that stays for a while and leaves lovely lacing around the glass . just gorgeous .  it 's as smooth as silk - perfectly suited as a dinner and desert sipper and easily the best porter i 've had the pleasure of tasting .
has a deep amber colored body with great clarity . leaves very thick lacing behind .  full , thick , rich mouth feel .
the yeast notes are exquisite . not very earthy , mostly ripe fruit with a bit of funky complexity .  mouthfeel is great . just the right level of thickness here .
nice lacing and strong retention . pretty !  the way this tastes is absolutely nothing like the way it smells ... m - full , pleasing mouthfeel . the best part of this beer .

a : pours a crystal clear amber color with a fluffy white head that sticks around for a long time . without a doubt one of the best looking ipas i 've had in a while .  very full body that stretches the cheeks . just such chewy hops .
quite impressive - i just could n't stop bringing this one to my nose .  the texture is rich and creamy and coasts your mouth in deliciousness .
appearance : poured a nice , thick dark tan head which persisted nicely . color is very dark brown -- pretty much opaque .  excellent in the mouth .
pours a beautiful light honey color . have n't seen a pale lager with such nice color .  mouthfeel is full and round .

appearance is very much like celebration . orangish amber color with a very nice head - great retention , lots of lacing .  m= smooth and crisp . feels resinous as well which is great for an ipa . d= super drinkable .

fantastic . i 'm a big fan of floral ipas , and not so into the bitterness . delicious . reminds me a lot of abrasive in this respect ( the floral/citrus vs. bitter balance ) , though not quite on that level .  the alcohol is kept well in check allowing the finish to cascade over the palate with a ton of character and wonderful texture . strong , long finish .

smell is incredible . a big sugar smell is predominant accompanied by nice dark malts . there is a nice thickness to it as well , that makes it incredibly smooth . drinkable beer for a strong abv .  sour , some cherries , but most of all very tart and bone dry ; element of french cheese in it ( brie ) , some cream ; m : lovely alcohol , nice tartness , very drinkable ; o : not too complex but but very good kriek , which i will buy whenever i see it .
i have to say that the smell of this is fantastic . t : wow , the taste is a bit of surprise .  easy to drink due to it 's creamy mouthfeel and pleasant flavor .
smells really really good , actually . i suppose old men are always less handsome when they take their clothes off .  m - perfect body .

a - incredible crimson-amber color with a lasting two-finger off-white head .  the mouthfeel is absolutely perfect . it goes down full-bodied yet absurdly delicately and dries the mouth a perfect amount for the hop zing this one has .

appearance : slightly hazy , ruby-amber pour with a voluminous ( and tenacious ) , light-tan whipped-cream head . recedes to floating dollops ... lace everywhere !  it 's thick , creamy , rich , and robust .

s - about 0.2 seconds after the cork popped , the air was almost filled with a rich , dry oak smell . lots of brett in there as well .  m : the mouthfeel is dense and creamy and frothy ... and almost stout-like . excellent .

this beer poured slow , and was pitch black in color . the head was medium sized , but brown , with small bubbles . looked beautiful !  overall a really complex , fantastic stout , one i 'd be happy coming back to over and over .

it smelled of the mediterranean sea and beautiful , long-legged , not to be fucked with , italian women with sensuous lips . a very sweet , lemony ipa that is excellent for what it is , and enjoyable , for a time .  visibly effervescent , the mouth feel is perfect ... classic rich micro bubbles lend a smooth creamy texture .

but not rahr and son 's w.w. from the get go the pour was great a beautiful reddish brown with a head that stuck around for awhile . and lacing that covered the glass throughout the few minutes it took for me to gobble this one down and lots of sediment in the bottle .  in the mouth , the tiny bubbles announce and incredibly smooth and balanced beer , with a roasted , slightly sweet flavor .

poured black with a rocky mostly lasting light brown head with excellent lacing .  smells like a smoke beer ... .i get a little chocolate in the nose ... but the roasted smell is overpowering ... taste is sweet on the front end ... and an overall smooth taste ... .with a little bitterness on the back end ... very nice feel ... .creamy and smooth perfect for the style ... .velvet like smoothness ... drinkability is not bad ... although it is a stout and it weighs you down ...

stunning rich and assertive peach and banana nose . unfortunately , flavor , character and body do not follow . however , nothing in body , flavors or character could lead one to conclude that aging will help this dull , simple and short flavored beer with a fantastic nose . smell it ; do n't drink it .  m- great mouthfeel .
s - smell is terrific and pops way more than a lot of nitro beers i 've had .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy .

a big frothy tan foam sits atop the brown liquid . reddish hues appear when held to the light , along some clarity . very nice .  pours a rich copper with a creamy one finger head that that settles nicely leaving some light lace , deep intese fruity aromas with some underlying but very noticeable pine.wow a big flavorful barleywine very pacific coast piney and resiny upfront with a big fruity alcolholic finish the alcohol really hits.just a sublime creamy mouthfeel and pretty slick going down the hatch and it warms the insides.wow truley and awesome big brew a night cap that cant be beat .
rich reddish brown colour with a creamy beige cap .  this brew is a tremendously creamy medium-body with a tantalizing , light bite about the tongue what can i say !

bottle ( 2011 ) port bottle shop carlsbad , ca transparent golden with a thick and persistent nearly white head , with lots of lacing left down the glass . gorgeous pale ale .  medium body and a wonderfully sprtizy carbonation keeps it light and makes the tartness manageable .

a : the can exploded ( mostly into the glass ) with creamy head and produced the beautiful downward drifting bubbles that makes nitro-things look so interesting . two fingers of tight , creamy head .  altogether pleasing to the tongue and brain , it also had a beautifully full mouthfeel from the oustandingly appropriate delicate carbonation .
tall , nearly white head with good retention and great lacing .  mouthfeel was full and rich . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .
a : a dark brown pour with a ridiculously huge fluffy light brown head .  m/d - medium to full bodied with an excelent feel .

beautiful nitro thick creamy tan head over a black body . has a lovely way of settling to a creamy solid chunk that wo n't spill out of the glass if you tilt it .  feels wonderful on the tongue , perfect for a summer or spring day .
bottle - a - 2 finger head w/ great retention , cative carb . and a golden-amber color s/t fruit/spice/funk .  thick creamy mouthfeel and mild carbonation . smooth silky mouthfeel is lucious .
pours a lighty hazed burnt orange , huge cap of frothy and sticky white head , great retention and lacing .  carbonation was nice and light , body was perfect .
pours very dark , almost black with dense head that does not dissipate till the end of pint , leaving thick and dense lacing . amazing .  perfect carbonation .

pours an opaque brown with a khaki head that never seems to leave the beer . you can slightly see carbonation bubbles when you bring the glass to the light . very nice lacing .  this beer feels absolutely perfect in the mouth .

a : always love the look of a good nitro-poured stout . a bit of translucent dark ruby around the edges . s : first stout i 've smelled ( excepting a bad bottle of a cream stout ) that was n't pleasant . smelled earthy and like a cheap red wine , which was good . this beer was pretty watery and the main flavor i could detect was of earthy pine .  superb mouthfeel . excellent amount of carbonation .

intense hop nose , complex , very piney , leafy with a strong minty/evergreen aromas with a sight sweet malt note . the hops were overpowering hard to smell anything else . would have expected more maltiness with the dark color , really got fooled there .  m- the mouth feel is excellent for this beer .

poured a strong tight head that calmed down into pretty lacing on the top . very nice deep lively amber color with rising bubbles from the bottom .  m- smooth and velvety , perfect carbonation o- great beer , bottle is on par with the draft .
a : amber color has good clarity and minimal carbonation . off white head is a little fizzy , but has great retention and leaves heavy lace .  the mouthfeel is excellent .
a : very good looking brew - copper/red clear body with white head .  m - extremely smooth .
clear walnut color with a lot of fine streaming bubbles and a rocky , long-lasting head .  mouthfeel is smooth and rich , medium-full body , with wonderful carbonation .

nutmeg , cinnamon . enjoyed !  the balance here is seriously excellent though , and the mouthfeel is probably the best i have encountered in an ipa , period . truly a creamy elixir , perfect carbonation .

medium-light yellow with a nice ring of head that leaves pretty decent amount of lacing .  a big rubber sensation , great deal of that , with a fair amount of barnyard funk and a carrot flavour as well . beautifully textured feel - full-bodied but smooth with a great earthy feel .
makes a nice , thick head with staying power . deep , dark brown color with a lighter ( and nicely creamy ) brown head .  its very smooth and velvety , very nice .
looks good , smells amazing , but the taste is very underwhelming .  extreme balance and smoothness in this beer , its quite good . big full body with a champaign like fizzyness . im impressed .

a : damn near perfect in my book . nicely hazy , radiant golden orange color . it 's got a big , soapy head that settles into a cap and leaves big sheets of lacing . so far so good .  m- mouthfeel on this is incredible . medium to full bodied , chewy and creamy , moist , and not a hint of alcoholic bite .

liquid is a dark amber topped with a thick finger of brown foam and dense and substantial lacing . carbonation is also very prevalent , making this model stand out much more than previous years . visually stunning .  m - perfect feel to this medium bodied brew .

snow-white head was thick and pillowy , and lingered through the entire drink , and reduced to excellent lacing up and down the glass .  in addition , there are hop oils , caramel , some sweetness and perhaps molasses along with a medium body that is oh so smooth and coats the mouth well . delicious and well balanced .

it really fits the style .  m : soft , smooth carbonation , big and viscous body , excellent finish . there 's very little more that i want from a big ris d : i drank my bottle in an hour and was craving more notes : i did n't really expect much from this beer because nh have n't really impressed me with much of what they 've done but hot damn , this was impressive !

the aroma was very fresh , like a breeze on a river , ( stunning ! ) floral hops and hints of citrus along with caramel malt ; a sweet and inviting blend . muted orange rind , grapefruit notes and a doughy malt/yeast blend were present but the bitterness that sat atop them i found unpleasant .  one of the best mouthfuls ever !

rich , deep aroma , with cherry and caramel hints , laced with alcohol . wonderful burnt-amber color . harsh start , but a clean finish . not an easy drinker ... but good for sippling . overall , this is a very complicated and interesting beer .  perhaps my favorite aspect is the full and very creamy mouthfeel .
deep brown pour with a gigantic , rocky , tan head .  feel is thick and full , nice and creamy .
the beer pours a delightful orange/amber with a heavy off-white head .  feel : low carbonation , medium body that is extremely smooth for so low abv , very nice drying finish .

a - dark , rich copper color , clear . large head that reminded me of fluffy meringue .  the feel is super dry , tannic and superb on the palate , rough , sticky , and full ... easy to drink as this crushed by the girlfriend and i in about 15 minutes .
has my favorite froth for this style , thick and sticky , goes nowhere fast and the color looks bread .  full bodied , heavy on the palate and full of flavor . i love it .

appearance - as billed , this pours totally black and opaque . a big dark mocha cloud on top resembles the thick top of a chocolate cappuccino or something . thick , creamy , lucious .  really wonderful . the mouthfeel is the most impressive and outstanding attribute of this beer .

attractive , crystal clear dark bronze hue . topped by a thick , fluffy head that recedes into a persistent one fingered layer .  aroma is finely balanced between sweet buttery/caramel-like malt and big herbal hops . while the taste treads the high wire between hops attack and malt sweetness the same way the aroma does , the hops edge out the malt on the tongue . without feeling heavy , this has both a creaminess and stickiness that works well to match the aggressive hop profile and carry the candy-like malt sweetness that rides along . bitter and resiny in a way that inseparably welds flavor to texture , and really helps define the beer . feel-wise , it 's magnificent . while my description of the taste sounds like the description of a big-ass double ipa , it manages to pack in a lot of flavor without going imperial . the sensible abv helps with that , and this is basically an all-around excellent , clearly california-fied version of the style . another fine brew from the typically hop-heavy moylans .

a : this is simply a great looking beer , pours a deep rich carmel with quckly dissapating head s : slight maltiness , and , unexpectedly , some barnyard funkiness , but very faint t : starts off malty but quickly gives way to mild hop bitterness , finsishes pretty dry ( like the dry maltiness of a helles ) m : pretty dry and clean on the palate , although , disapointingly , had almost a watery mouthfeel d : pretty solid sessions lager that would be a good find on tap .  the mouthfeel is great on this one too , effervescent and full at the same time .
bottle in 16oz.sierra nevada glass leaves a beautiful 3/4 inch head . a-tremendous color , nice floaties , great lacing on the glass .  m- awesome thick mouthfeel on this seasonal .

pours a light tan , two-finger head , fades slowly and leaves a good lace . nice clear , deep amber color .  m : really a standout porter . carbonation is perfectly dialed in and gives a very subtle tingle on the tongue .

a : awesome when poured from a nitro bottle , cream to brown to almost black right before your eyes . nice caramel colored head and lacing that hung around throughout .  mouthfeel/drinkability- sublime mouthfeel , super-easy in the mouth .

a : pours brown with a really tall tan compact head that sets slowly into rich lacins .  and even so , it is still incredibly smooth , and the alcohol flavor can not be detected . the body is huge . one of the thickest beers i 've had the pleasure of eating . very good stuff .

this beer was so pretty that i had to stop and take a picture . a beautiful translucent golden color with a billowing white head .  mouthfeel is perfection . perfectly carbonated and very refreshing .

it 's wonderful . t- initial malts , some yeast , bread and biscuity notes , and strong warming alcohol .  easy to drink , amazing body ; feels perfect to me . d - overall this is a very good doppelbock with an amazing mouthfeel ; felt like i could have had a few of these .

a- beer pours a very rich , deep dark bown color with a nice mocha colored head . the head settles slowly , but not completely for a long while , and leaves some good lacing s- the nose on this is mainly of dark roasted malt , some coffe can be picked up as well but not very overwhelming at all .  it seemed to just coat my whole mouth on its way down .

this smells just terrific . the flavors on the palate generallyh replicate the nose , except they 're not as intense and the brown sugar and chocolate seem to dominate the flavor profile .  the rich , smooth , roasted chocolate flavor works well with the silky body . this is definitely highly recommended , as the beers tend to be from great lakes brewing company .

smells awesome . if this tastes anywhere near as good as it smells , i will be happy . the smells are simply fantastic - if i have another bottle , i may just let it sit and inhale the fumes rather than actually drinking it .  m-medium carbonation with a great creamy finish d-hmm i actually like this a lot ... .i 'm very confused by the other peoples ' reviews ... the taste is n't too complex but its otherwise a great drink .

the brew pours a slightly darker golden color with a huge , creamy , rocky white head that sticks around for a while .  m : medium to thick bodied . the carbonation works well for the brew , and there is a lovely creamy finish that really melts in your mouth .

the reserve special black bier was a beautiful sight resting in a dark horse souvenir pint glass . it was black as night with a dark tan head indicating the level of roast of the malts used .  mouthfeel is superb . great level of spice , perfect carbonation , medium body .
nice retention and awesome patches of lacing .  it is full bodied and creamy in the mouth .

an isabelline crown persists and leaves luxurious cascades of sandy lacing - those bubbles that stick rest atop viscous legs suggesting snow dusted mountain peaks . aroma is highly potent - it hits you from the moment the seal is popped . brown sugar , high quality aged sherry , vanilla , coconut , dense brown bread , faint clove ... the list goes on . the flavor profile closely follows the aromatics , but everything is present in a lesser degree . lots of flavors come and go - abbreviated tastes of bread crusts , licorice , and dried tropical fruit . the finish is quite nutty and hints at leather as well . almost like an armagnac it is a beer well suited to contemplation . the oak notes contribute a great deal without becoming overwhelming ( brandy barrel angel 's share i 'm lookin ' at you ) . definitely worth seeking out and sticking in the cellar ...  m - this is by far the smoothest ipa i 've ever had . the pour from a hand pump straight from the cask creates the perfect texture for this beer .
looks fantastic ! the head leaves plenty of lace after a couple of minutes .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth & this is a perfect beer to sip on on a lazy pm with no kids in sight !

a - in a word , beautiful . a rocky off-white rocky head sits atop a lovely ruby-red body . one of the prettiest beers i 've had the pleasure of drinking .  silky smooth on the tongue and exceptionally creamy .

based on notes poured into a thistle glass with an effervescent amber with 4 fingers of rocky eggshell colored head . great lacing & head retention s : ever-so slight sweet berry smell t : malty , fruittyness , a hint of warming boozeyness up front .  the mouthfeel is exceptionally smooth and creamy , terrific . thanks bif for the sample .
appearance is great - absolutely opaque black , dense foamy coffee colored head .  wonderful body .

a - dark caramel brown in color with some golden hues around the edges of the glass . hue , foamy off-white head with excellent retention .  mouthfeel : thick and smooth in every sense of the words -- a very pleasant experience indeed !
clear dark ruby appearance . creamy , somewhat bubbly , beige head sits on top .  this beer has a smooth , creamy mouthfeel .
looks really nice with the carbonation streaming up all the sides . great retention with the full finger staying around the whole time . great rings of lacing .  typical stone excellent mouthfeel .
it is a very pretty looking beer when poured into a pils glass . straw blonde colour with a thick white head that lingers for a while .  nice full bodied and well carbonated mouthfeel .

a- pours a splendid black color with a thin milky looking head that lasts the entirety of the beer and copious rings of lacing .  the creamy , delicious texture pairs well with the flavorful personality of the smoked porter . the dancing carbonation paired with the brews creamy-smooth feel and intense flavor essentially block dopamine receptors in your brain .

exceptional aroma . very hoppy , and you get it at the first sip , then the sweetness , finishes bitter , with all the hops of an ipa but more subdued .  mouthfeel is outstanding . super thick and syrupy , that flavor coats the palate forever .

i was much more impressed by the pour and visual of this beer than by taste or drinkability . nice puffy styrofoam cloud of a head .  silky smooth thick bodied with a perfect amount of light carbonation and a ridiculously long lasting , balanced tart and sweet aftertaste .

honestly , a fantastic looking beer .  actively carbonated , yet still seems mellow and full . strikes a perfect balance between crispness and creaminess , just heavanly . strikingly balanced for the how big and malty this beer is .
very sticky and lacing all the way down the glass . looks fantastic .  mouthfeel : crisp , clean , and exceedingly refreshing .
exceptional appearance .  mouthfeel : spot on in my opinion . medium to medium-lite body with perfect amount of carbonation .
beautiful looking beer .  body is medium full with a great velvety smoothness .

pours a beautiful slightly hazy amber color with a large two inch off white head . excellent retention and some great lacing .  mouthfeel is phenomenal , rich and creamy it 's quite thick and chewy without going over the top .

it poured amber in color with a creamy-brown 3+finger head that lasted quite a while . it left gobs of sticky lacing all over my glass .  very smooth and rich taste though and perfectly balanced . wonderfull to drink though think it should be drank as i do n't think that more age makes this one any better .

creamy khaki foam tops off this american porter , the surface has a light sheen to it , forming uneven crags and peaks that push above the rim . sticky lacing is left all around , clumped in almost cartoonish 3-d . cola ruby color in the light , with slow trails of carbonation .  rich roasty chocalaty with a fabulous creamy mouthfeel . mouth again is just amazing . another great brew by troegs .

a nice thick , tan head upon a body of darkness . not much happening in the nose .  the mouthfeel is thick and rich with a nice amount of bubbly to round it out . the taste is full , many-layered . . . wonderful . a little vineous though .

i love watching the show that this beer put on then it is poured into a glass .  like other fine belgian beers the carbonation produces a surreal creamy consistency that serves to deliver maximum taste .
great looking beer .  great palate , though . even when it gets warm , great warmth and sliky smooth syrups .

on tap at the austin ginger man . the aroma had a sweet wheat flavor along with banana , lemony citrus and a moderate clove spiciness . very flavorful and well rounded hefewiezen aroma . i get lots of clove flavor throughout the beer .  extremely satisfying in this regard .
the strong , sweet caramel nose immediately kicks the salivary glands into gear .  mouthfeel is utterly smooth with just a hint of carbonation ... placidly perfect .
dark brown with good clarity , this beer has a dense , light brown head with excellent retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is the star here . it 's plush , velvety ... is nice .

pours a very appealing ruby red with a tan-ish 2 inch head that leaves some of the best lacing i 've ever seen .  bordering on chewy as you work toward swallowing . carbonation was excellent on tap , just enough to contribute to a dry and clean finish despite the initial sweetness of the beer .

black with reddish tints if you look hard enough . looks really good . fluffy foam settles to a thick , dense mass .  m - full body , viscous and chewy with low , delicate carbonation , very smooth across the palate with some heat from the alcohol/bourbon content .

clear copper with orange accents , forming a large , pillowy peaking light beige head atop fine bubbles . moderately strong carbonation .  the carbonation is fantastic -- beer feels creamy and smooth- almost velvety .
a - has two full fingers of ultra-fine reddish-tan head . what a beauty !  extremely smooth mouthfeel and very easy to drink .
back to the smell - oak , but the lovely old sort . . .  but the mouthfeel is absolutely incredible .

expiration date april 2008 , sampled january 2004 pours a beautiful ruby color . it is vry highly carbonated , which creates a thick creamy light brown-tan head .  great creamy thick mouthfeel , light carbonation .
poured a very deep brown with a massive brown head and tons of carbonation .  the feel is creamy , rich and smooth . just the right amount of carbonation keeps it full , but not overly thick .
looks very lively . this looks amazing and out of control .  mouthfeel : amazing . creamy and smooth , thick .
pours up a beautiful grapefruit color with a very thin white head .  thick rich and creamy mouthfeel . for such a rich and big beer it is remarkably smooth .
lacing is phenomenal , it sticks around the whole time , leaving great looking webbing on the glass .  thick lushious body and moderate carbonation .
looks pretty solid .  silky smooth , it has just the right touch of carbonation to keep it full but not too thick or syrupy . awesome ! overhyped ?

very attractive layered orange and brown color with creamy head remnants and a spicy , fruity , malty nose .  m - very rich and thick , has a nice little burn and pop at the end from a combo of carbonation , abv and hop bitterness .
the appearance is a perfect amber .  m : exactly what i look for in a beer : full-bodied and creamy with abundant soft carbonation .
poured with a firm sturdy , foamed up head .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , very smooth and creamy . overall this is pretty damn good .

top of the line nose on this one , just fantastic . my first impression was damn ! the consensus was this was an excellent beer , & there was a marked difference once it warmed - a collection of `` yeah , it 's ok '' changed to `` damn , this is good '' after 10-15 minutes . really glad i got to try this one , thanks again tucker !  the aroma speaks strongly of roasted grains , as you would expect from a stout , while on the tongue the beer has tremendous body .
a : dark orange to amber in color , ring of head with nice sticky lacing .  mouthfeel is about perfect , and the body is about perfect for a bock style .

bottle and served in my expedition snifter ( along side of the 5 & 8 ) : a - very dark with some ruby highlights and the best head of the three with a good creamy lace upon the glassware .  the mouthfeel is full and velvety .
appearance : very dark , as the name would suggest ... but some brown tinge . quite a nice head , with moderate retention and nice lace .  moderate body , excellent smoothness .

pours a brilliant copper ; a vigorous pour produces only a one-inch head but a nice , tight , foamy one .  a very smooth , luxurious malt backbone enhances the mouthfeel , but a bitter smack of hops reminds me that i 'm drinking an ipa . quite enjoyable .

12 oz bottle poured into a pint glass a : pours a clear light golden amber with a fingers width of sea foam white head . the head dissipates to a solid thick film and leaves a surprising amount of lacing .  first gulp of this was outstanding.. nice creamy , mouthfeel to it that just bombards your mouth with sweet , delicious beer flavor .

very still with incredible lacing s - dry roasted malts , sugar and bread , a touch of spice t - earthy roasted malts , dry corn , very malty with a mild hop finish m - nitro tap gives a creamy smoothness that makes it super sessionable o - really great !  this beer is on the lighter side of medium-bodied beers and boasts an exceptionally pleasant mouthfeel . carbonation is perfectly balanced , i could n't imagine any improvement here .

a : poured with a large , white fluffy head that was very long lasting ... never got below 1-2 fingers size . body is a beautiful , dark orange color , with excellent clarity .  the mouth feel is the richest and thickest i have ever tasted in a beer !
gorgeous . big , beautiful , creamy head over a glowing murky golden body .  m : creamy and delicious . everything is dead on here .

the beer pours a nice deep dark brown with nice thick and creamy tan/brown head . it is gorgeous and the combination of dark beer with quite a dark head makes it seem to me the perfect beer to drink if you are ever invited to sit across from an english professor in a leather armchair in front of a fireplace in his mahogany study/library while smoking a pipe .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel .

2008 version pours a deep , rich-looking mahogany brown body . hazy . off-white , foamy head slowly fades with nice lacing . good looking smells up front of alcohol and hops .  maybe i could not taste the `` rare '' but this really sucked compared to the 2008 classic gueuze which is a fantastic gueuze .

captain lawrence st. vincent 's dubbel is a great looking dubbel that tastes pretty good . a : red orange colour and a great 2 cm head that lasts very well . highly carbonated .  body is right- light , lively carbonation , not cloying or excessively dry .
wild blue is a red wine colored drink , with a small pink head on top . pretty good amount of lacing .  feels right in body , but the taste is just off .

s - lively lemon oil aroma , very fresh and unique . lots of spicy wheat and slightly fruity yeast . the aroma is spectacular , it smells like oil squeezed out of a fresh lemon peel , though the flavor is not quite as good .  yeast , stale hops , a little grass , so boring with a duvel quality ... the taste is equally as bad , bitter toffee , light stale hops , way too much yeast , sour finish . pass .
very nice . the taste is quite good , mostly dominated by malts .  the carbonation and mouthfeel were appropriate for this style .

a- c'mon ... its a guinness ... and i think this is one of the prettiest pouring beers out there . pours a dark coffee color , the head resembles whipped cream and is a khaki half a finger head . great traces of lacing all the way thru to the end .  there is a little tart cherry , but straight blonde base beer is like 75 % of the beer equation . i 'm not sure if there is wild yeast in the bottle , but it does n't seem like this beer has developed much over time . the sourness is only noticeable , and in the end there is a good deal of artificial sweetness in the finish of the beer that is very off-putting . truthfully , it 's better than a lot of back-sweetener fruit beers but if you think this is a lambic like cantillon , you are mistaken .

once the head settled with a good half inch left on top the beer was a dark solid black . it looked eerily similar to guinness .  mouthfeel - some good body , oily smoothness per the style . carbonation is moderate .
pours with a vast amount of co2 . produces a beautiful light tan head that sticks around forever . the body is dark amner in color .  mouthfeel : light-bodied and crisp .

a- pours a light amber with a quickly dissipating head s- wow , this smells incredible ! it smells like cinnamon , nutmeg , graham cracker , pumpkin , and brown sugar . d- it 's highly drinkable , however the alcohol is not as well-hidden as in some other st imperials .  i 'm thinking of a breakfast bed . the beer was thick and the foam was velvety . the drinkitbility was okay for its thickness . however , the taste was terrible . a quick slam of semi-sweet citrus that is too heavy on the lemon . the beer ends with an unbalanced bitterness for more than half of the drink .

a -- beautiful dark amber color with two fingers of head using a standard pour . very dark for an ipa . great lacing as well .  was pretty decent mouthfeel : smooth and crisp , went down easy drinkability : good enough on a hot day and goes great w/ bbq .
smell- this smelled like pure chocolate and coffee , my mouth was watering upon the smell .  the mouthfeel is smooth and oily and the carbonation is alright .

appearance- beer pours a clear golden with a substantial two and a half finger head of eggshell foam over the top and lacing clinging to the sides of the glass .  medium bodied ; good amount of carbonation .

12 oz bottle poured into an '08 osa pint appearance- pours a deep brown with a large dense tan head , sticks around forever . incredible head retention and lacing .  saccharine all the way . how can you add fake sweetener to bier ? the beer is best described as diet raspberry 7 up . i already go to the gym 4 times a week so that i can drink all the fabulous beer i desire . flavors were overwhelmingly sweet , and tart . complexion was shirley temple , and body was crisp .

16.9oz bottle - 2006 vintage - served at 45 degrees into a large snifter appearance : charcoal black and completely opaque . vigorous pour yieds a 3 inch head that is thick and creamy . caramel colored head with great retention .  i believe the bottle i got was 8.75 percent.. looked pretty good for a esl , smell and taste reminded me very much of great western extra gold.. very malty with a nice solventy sweet-like alcohol burn ... carbonated perfectly , making it halfway drinkable , still hangover juice as far as imports go.. cheers !

i fricking love the way this beer looks . huge foamy white head , brilliant dark golden color with a cascade of carbonation bubbling up the side .  mouthfeel - explodes in the mouth with carbonation , yet maintaining a noteworthy smoothness afterwards . the body is sturdy but not overly big .
a : very dark brown color that does n't allow you to see through .  m : probably the best thing this beer has to offer . very smooth , with just a little bit of unwanted bitterness and carbonation .

the cascade hop explosion was still there , but i was able to handle it this time around and i really enjoyed it . ruby-amber color , bordering on red . awsome color .  mouthfeel - good feel , not too thick , kind of creamy , decent carbonation .
it has a really nice , spicy aroma with a solid grain backbone .  this beer does have a nice smooth , dry mouthfeel .

this notes of grapefruit and pineapple . just thick hop notes here so ripe and fresh it was like heaven just smelling this . smooth and mellow delivery of the flavor , though not as strong as the aroma would have led me to believe . light alcohol notes as well and a really good medium feel to it . something i would love to try again as the aroma itself was worth the price . this was damn nice  m - solid and full , with good carbonation .

pretty good aroma wafting from this especially when warm , distinguishable espresso and coffee grounds with baker 's chocolate , coarse grains and a earthy woody note , not unlike campfire smoke with the addition of some licorice . great aroma and feel , solid overall .  the milk sugar cuts through and makes it a bit artificial and like one of those creme savers candies . creamy on the palate with sugary milkiness with some of the same strawberry flavor and other general fruitiness , a touch of tartness in the finish . weirdness in the finish ... not medicinal but has a certain harshness and fake tasting combining with the artificial fruity sweetness like many of the shorts beers , nice to try , but i did n't have any desire to finish the 12oz .
very appealing , sweet malty aroma with caramel and toffee notes .  feels very creamy but that does n't make the beer more drinkable to me .
pours a dark black color with a thin brown head .  however , the mouthfeel was very nice , which lent a overall smoothness and softness to it .

bottle poured into a pint glass appearance- beautiful ! one inch light tan head that slowly disappears .  recommended by bert from bert 's better beers . smells like dark chocolate , burn caramel , and vanilla -- sort of like an chocolate chip oatmeal cookie . smooth roast malt , dare i say a tad burnt . there 's a mild pharmaceutical character in back that i 'm not a fan of . i drank half this bottle one night and the second half the following afternoon .

smell ; perfect balance of rich , nutty and sweet malts and citrusy hops . beautiful aroma and the american hops work nice with the rich malts . taste ; starts with a sweet , sappy , resin flavor , mixed with white sugar .  mouthfeel is pretty good , goes well with the style of light and highly carbonated .

pours a deep copper color with a big creamy tan head that lasts forever and leaves a great looking lace all the way down the sides of the glass .  there 's actually a nice amount of body to this one .
appearance very cool bottle art . beer is a deep rich mahogany brown .  mouthfeel was smooth and taste was of sweet malts at first but finished quite bitter with a sharp hit of hops , alot of hops .
great looking beer .  the mouthfeel is very full and hearty almost meaty- sort of flat .

s : striking tropical fruit , pineapple , lots of oranges , kiwi fruit , very nice . my kind of nose in an ipa . d : the nose tricked me into thinking i was going to get something great , but this beer still impressed me just going on the previous scores .  m - good carbonation and a nice balance .

it was quite amazing . nice bitter coffee notes , with more chocolate notes and sweet malts than with the aroma . this was smelling great , drinking good and going down easy .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with smooth carbonation .
impressive looking beer .  mouthfeel is nice and thick and well carbonated . the best part of the beer .
s - the aroma is pretty impressive , and accurately captures the smells and intricacies of apple pie .  good mouthfeel and texture for a tap beer .

smells delicious . sweet raisin and toffee come through very clearly .  as hard as i tried , i couldnt find any `` beer '' flavor in it ... it was almost like it was one of those syrups you would see vendors putting on shaved ice and making a snow cone out of , it was that sweet . the mouthfeel was good , thick , syrup-y , heavy , and coating like an imperial/double stout should be .

the aroma is a very nice rich creamy milk chocolate . the best part of this beer is that the aroma is so strong , it is a major component of the beer even while drinking the last swallow . nice feeling coming out of a bottle .  mouthfeel is good bordering on to thick .

smells heavy of cherries , very good smell . taste is just as heavy with the cherries .  glass : new belgium globe aging notes : one year at ~60f in the dark bang for the buck ( oz* % / $ ) : 22*6.2/10 = 13.64 a : orange , white lacey head , slightly cloudy from yeast s : horse-y farmhouse brett with hints of orange t : brett dominates ( horse-stable hay , a little dung almost ) , notes of orange m : silky , coating , lingering , pleasant o : worth drinking , a little one-dimensional with the brett .

the color is incredible . i 'm not sure how you give this appearance anything other than a 1 or 5 . excellent retention , settling to a thick film and rings of clumpy lacing .  mouthfeel - nice body , pretty crisp .

the nose of this beer is simply amazing . pure fresh cherries , almost like a top notch but soft lambic . some light caramel and hops could be smelled as well , but mostly fresh fresh soft cherries . light caramel tone , but just very clean and malty . the bottle is a little disapointing to be honest , but on tap this beer is simply amazing . fresh cherries and soft clean crisp malt .  a - opaque black color with a small head that disappears quickly s - rich chocolate-like aroma , mild yeast esters , some smokiness , no hop perceived t - roasted malt flavor dominates , some yeasty esters and mild hop flavors take a secondary role , very gentle mild hop finish with some lingering smokiness m - smooth creamy medium body with moderately low carbonation d - this is a decent enough oatmeal stout . the head and retention is disappointing , but the smell , taste and mouthfeel are acceptable .

outstanding complexity . tastes like various coffee creamers ( amaretto , irish cream ) poured over pumpkin pie .  well , the bottle states this brew has a `` rich dark malt complexity '' among other things . unfortunately , i do n't care for that rich dark malt complexity at all in this red ale . i like my red ales `` red '' , but without an overpowering harsh chocolate/roasted character . i did like the hop character which is mingled in with the other flavors . i also liked the color and clarity of this brew . overall , this brew just did n't work for me . oh well , that 's why they make lots of different brews , right ?

drake 's denogginizer pours a surprisingly dark amber . an aggressive pour results in more than 4 fingers of ivory colored foam sitting atop the beer .  oily mouthfeel with next to no carbonation . quite thick and heavy , coating every area of the mouth .

a deep mahogany appearance with thick lacing on the sides gave this a beautiful appearance . i emailed the location and i guess what makes it unique is its cross between a red ale and a stout .  mouthfeel was smooth , light , though i do n't know i 'd go as far as crisp .
extreme amount of head over poured just from opening the bottle . dark almost brown color .  mouthfeel was really good for a light beer . liked the carbonation , and felt richer than it tasted .

glass : chimay goblet temp : cellared @ approx 45 degrees bottling date : 04-23-08 pours an exceptional clear golden amber color . minimal head that retains a light lacing all the way down .  mouthfeel was good and very drinkable ; however , it was slightly bitter ... something i was n't expecting this to have considering the malts .

it looks like a very refreshing and tasty beer . crystal clear straw colored beer , again looks very refreshing .  watery quality to the flavor . has a creamy quality and a smooth carbonation , but i ca n't recommend this beer other than for that .
it was not , however , all that interesting . great black color but overall not much in the way of belgian character .  the mouthfeel is very smooth , with fine/sharp bubbles .

wow , this started off so well , looking great and smelling great , but simply fell apart at the taste .  mouthfeel : well-carbonated , as expected from the heady pour drinkability : low- i could n't get over the tire flavor , which is a shame because every other aspect of the beer was delightful

lovely , bright cherry red color ... head is large at first , simmers down quickly ... aroma : mmmmm ... .complex ! quite a rich and invigorating aroma , i postpone consumption to prolong my time drinking it deep into the nose ... really nice !  m : fairly light , highly carbonated , and very soft . i like it .
bottle holiday wine cellar escondido , ca black as can be with a thick , persistent light brown head . perfection !  m - good . a little sticky .

s- a little woody , sweet malt with a real nice smell very nice t- has a very earthy taste , kinda a bit of caramel but some definet wood tones , spicy , maybe a little cinnamon . pretty good but caramel isnt a personal favorite flavor m- kinda light for its darkness but overall a medium body pretty solid , hits the tongue well and lingers a little while d- a nice beer , the caramel isnta personal like but for those who do its a really good beer  dark brown/amber body . it is a very smooth and a sweet sipper . some hops , caramel , candy sugar and oak . not much bourbon . i was way excited to try this and actually find it to be rather average .

the head is quite impressive , off white in color , composed of thousands and thousands of tiny bubbles .  has a medium body which is needed to carry all the hops and alcohol . low carbonation lends a nice texture without letting the flavors being cloying .
really , this is an outstanding looking beer .  m : good mouthfeel , its crisp , refreshing , light bodied with moderately high carbonation .

the smell is very rich in aromas . i detect very strong honey notes , like wild honeysuckle . the taste is actually not as exciting as the smell , but still delivers a great complexity .  the body is somewhere between medium and full , with a creamy mouthfeel .

big whiffs of tangerines , honeydew melons , bubble gum , concentrated pineapple juice , honeyed graham crackers , and lesser notions of iron-rich blood , spicy tomato juice , and grapes- via a lightly woody and vaguely oxided sense of madeira . for as varied and intriguing as the nose is , the taste is fairly straitforward and unnuanced .  mouthfeel is quite nice and full .

nose is quite complex with some really nice notes of oak , vanilla , chocolate , roasted malt , and some light coffee . the taste does n't mix these together quite as well , but is still tasty . great feel coming from all different directions and quite drinkable for the big beer that it is .  highly carbonated .

bottle opened with a nice hiss and poured a solid black with a smallish tan/brown head that lasted forever .  everything about this beer was pretty light - light , crisp malt scent ; light fruity taste ; light body . feel - 4.0/5.0 - refreshing , which was really nice .

a : peppery spice with citrusy fruit , somewhat leathery . a : clear golden yellow with a tight white head f : dry , with fruit ( apple/citrus ) and spice up front . o : good interpretation of saison . nice and dry with plenty of character . there 's something tangy tht decreases my overall enjoyment .  m - very dry with hop resin in the finish . medium bodied , with a high carbonation .

smell : sweet citrus hops that smell incredibly fresh . the sweet malt balances things out well , but still lets the hops shine . overall : this beer smells awesome and the taste is a bit of a letdown . that being said , it was still quite good and i would have another .  m. medium-high carbonation , zesty on the tongue .

one of the best aromas to come around in a while for me . very decadent chocolate here ... sweet , silky ... you can really smell the cocoa nibs here . a slight hint of hop bitterness as well but this is a very chocolatey aroma . the body is a bit light , and the taste is certainly full of chocolate , but is more of a mix between a sweeter chocolate and a bitter , roasted chocolate . this marriage keeps it from becoming cloying or just being too bitter . what was a pretty sweet and rich beer on the nose was n't quite so on the tongue .  m - medium body and low carbonation .

the smell is outstanding , very malty and reminiscent of autumn .  there 's also just a hint of citrus from the orange peel ( or orange oil extract ) the smooth mouthfeel and moderate body is not unlike that of a german hefeweizen .

the smell- incredible . at first , very sweet smelling- hints of pineapple . for such a strong beer , it finishes very abruptly , leaving you with just a tad of malt . overall , incredible .  body is on the full side of medium . moderate carbonation .

amazing mix of bitter hops , tropical fruit , pine , etc , etc . really amazing ! taste follows suit -- -an assault of hops and some light malt . very nice , but nothing i 'd want to have more of one of . had a touch of heat from the 10 % abv on the finish . overall a really good brew -- -glad i tried it finally .  adequate carbonation .

i thought the smell was magnificent ! ! the taste , too , was sweet and fruity , but nearly as sweet as the smell , which is good , seeing that that would probably have been overpowering . i do not really have another barleywine with which to compare this one , but as simply `` a beer '' this is a fantastic brew ...  very smooth without being too full bodied .

pours out a thickly hazed golden-orange . gigantic , solid off-white head . consistancy and appearance of cotton candy . great looking , but lacking elsewhere .  goes down smooth , no bite , and finishes with an appropriate amount of stickiness . carbonation is on the lower end of the spectrum . nice feel .
poured a medium copper hue with a huge chunky white head . there was very good retention and sticky lacing .  this is a medium bodied , well carbonated beer .

incredibly pungent and tropical aroma . the distinct nelson hops really shine here . one of the best aromas i 've ever experienced from any dipa . an absolutely wonderful dipa . honestly , i never expected a dipa this good to come from karl strauss -- count me in as very pleasantly surprised .  m : it has a nice smooth body .

the aroma is of peat , caramel , nuts , and chocolate . i really like the uniqueness of this aroma . the taste has more caramel than the aroma . overall , this is a really , really good scotch ale .  good carbonation .
a very good porter , poured dark ruby brown color with strong tan head that i impatiently dove into smelling its aroma of chocolate , burnt malt , sweet caramels and hops .  m - nice . thick .
a- pale translucent body with thick white head . great head retention . leaves behind plenty of lacing .  carbonation is right on par .

s - nice aroma . some sweet vanilla and oak notes are punctuated by earthy and herbal hop .  taste is a very light malt sweetness upfront with a moderately bitter finish of good length and crispness . a pretty uncomplicated beer , good for the style , a good lawnmower beer .

the appearance is simply beautiful . a rich brown that seems to be characteristic of most trappist ales . this actually sort of reminds me of the way eku 28 eisbock smells , which is odd for a trappist .  the body of this beer suits the style with the usual level of north coast drinkability and feel to it . definitely the best feature .

they share the same appearance if poured into the same glass , and the head is excellent . the taste is almost identical , with the can version being perhaps a little more bitter . i think these nitro cans are a great invention .  being of fan of bocks , i was fully prepared to love this ubiquitous doppelbock . it was kind of sweet and malty , smelled great , felt nice going down -- quite satisfying . there was a slightly funky smell to it , and an even funkier taste . i thought that was more common in highly hopped beers . at $ 10 for the four pack , i hate to try it again for fear of wasting my hard-earned beer money .
bottle from the lcbo the 2008 vintage has held its own agaist the 2007. black with a lovely tan head .  this beer has noticeable viscosity and a big thick feel . minimal carbonation .

a : amazing head on top of a dark yellow body launches up to the top of the glass and hangs out forever , ending its long life in a spiderweb of beauty . glass is soapy all the way down . this beer could not look any more inviting .  hints of chocolate up front , but quickly overrun by the massive spices . reminds me of chewing on a mixture of green baking herbs , and about as pleasing on my palate . an interesting brew to say the least , but not one i 'd purchase again .

the look is awesome : clear golden color with a great head and excellent lace .  after smelling , i picked up on a semi-complex mix of belgium candy , malts , cherries and alcohol . it sat heavy on me and did not taste refreshing to me . i enjoyed this beer and can tell there was definitely quality & craftsmanship involved in it 's making ; but it 's not the best tripel i have ever had .
great head , expected cascading upon serving .  mouthfeel is crisp and drying , as it should be .
the beer smells pretty good , very hoppy like one would expect from this type of beer .  the feel is between medium and full for the style and enjoyably so . moderate carbonation nails the feel .
smelled pleasant . fruity with nice hop smell .  the mouthfeel is notably well contoured . dark and hearty though at times cloying .

aroma was outstanding . rich and full with dry , whole grain oats and sweet , cereal-like notes ( kind of like sticking your nose in a box of quaker oats ) . drinkability however was quite good .  m -- thick , slick d -- very one dimesional brew .

a : poured into a tulip , leaves 3mm head throughout the session , light brown or burnt meringue in color . simple , but effective lacing .  lovely thick aromas of blackstrap molasses , dark bitter chocolate , strong coffee and deep roasted malts ... awesome aromas to this one ... lazy and flat tasting ... strange bitter almost sour taste present ... . not much in common with the aromas ... thick oily mouthfeel is great but i ca n't get by the taste of this one ... drain poured this one ... maybe a bad bottle but as is , a big disappointment ...
appearance : clean , clear golden body . very nice looking .  pretty refreshing , not overwhelmed with carbonation .
pours a beautiful dark orange/copper color with a good head retention and lacing . i love the color of this beer .  it is medium bodied and smooth in the mouth .

somewhere there is a aroma i ca n't describe , but it is very familiar . marvelous aroma , but it ca n't keep that promise .  you do n't get much of the sweet malts you get from the aroma so it really confuses the senses and does n't make for an enjoyable experience mouthfeel is heavy and it sticks to your mouth for minutes .

a- pours a pitch black hue with brown and amber highlights , small tan/brown head that is mostly sustaining , fair amount of lacing throughout s- fruity scents dominated by raisins and dark fruit ( as advertised on the label ) , i am also getting tones of apple , peach , belgian candy , sweet caramel/toffee malts , and a modest alcohol presence t- initial taste is raisins , raisins , and more raisins ( almost cloyingly sweet ) , followed by a variety of fruits and spices , yeasty/bready/sweet malts , a little bit of chocolate and belgian candy , finishes with sweet malts , a touch of bittering hops and warming alcohol presence m- medium/full bodied with good carbonation , nice slick texture that coats the tongue in sweetness d- 9 % abv is well-masked , but this definitely a sipping beer to be enjoyed over time ( much like a port or desert wine ) .  mouthfeel is light bodied with good carbonation .
a : poured perfectly dark brown with an abundant creamy light brown head . great retention and fantastic lacing .  m : medium in both body and carbonation .

a : very nice translucent amber color with a half finger of white head . good head retention .  the carbonation on this beer is very light with a medium body , the beer itself has a sliky relaxing feel with every swallow . its has a mellow feel to it nonetheless . overall this an average beer that im sure has its audience who will think less of it and people like myself who may not dislike it but not exactly like this beer .

) aug. 15 2008 @ hop cat ba / brewery grand opening event , served in tulip glass . opaque black , creamy tan head , beautiful bubble suspension after pour , wow ! looks thick smells of roasty heavy malts , dark fruit , smooth and creamy , mmm taste is of thick heavy bitter chocolate , hot alcohol , rich and smooth , compared to keg this is way mellowed , not as harsh and easier to drink , amazing ! , raisins , chocolate , slight coffee , earthy peat , mm mouthfeel is oily slick , smooth , creamy , viscous , a sipper for sure - delicious !  thick and smooth mouthfeel .

pours the blackest black with no light coming through .  body was medium , and the liquid was fairly smooth overall . 3.03 rdev -19.5 % look : 3.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 3 | feel : 4 | overall : 2.5 1366
a : very dark brown with appealing 2-3 finger , rocky , off-white head with very good retention and abundant lacing in rings .  mouthfeel is very light and well carbonated .
a- it looks really good poured in a glass .  i like the thick , syrupy mouthfeel as it 's quite comforting but the taste gets old fast and just is n't complex .

i wish short 's would start putting dates on their bottles ... appearance is black , slight reddish/dark purplish hue that shines through the edge of the glass . dark tan and creamy head with purple hues .  good , solid creamy feel with enough dryness to get you through .
sweet tropical notes , mainly mango accompany a major amount of hops in the scent . there was a lot i liked but overall very good .  m - light to medium carbonation with medium carbonation .

2008 vintage a- almost stout-like in appearance , no head , fizzy swirl of carb in the middle of a color-devoid structure ... s-vanilla , cherry , oak , intense , strong , amazing smells ... .omg ... .there is n't a single hint of sour beer behind this nose . simply smooth vanilla and cherry ... awesome ... .ca n't remember a better nose on a sour ... . t- starts off smooth , nothing much going on *served at 39 degrees f.* then spice , phenols , tartness , tanginess , oh man ... this is great ... . m- solid brick of a mouthfeel , with a few glimmers of carbonation ... nothing exceptionally nasty about the 'brick ' that i speak of , but it is different ... .all together a different beer but for mouthfeel , i 'd expect something flat to taste like this , but in all it provides the right amount of carbonation ! duchesse on crack ...  '' m - actually a nice and robust mouthfeel , i just do n't really want to feel this beer in my mouth because it tastes kind of terrible .

beautiful tan head with steady retention .  the flavor that by far took the lead was chocolate ! there 's an overpowering ( and for me , disappointing ) chocolate aftertaste in this beer . mouthfeel- smooth , no complaints here . drinkability- well , the bottle looks cool as you drink from it !
the smell is strong pundget and fruity , sweet and tangy . overall , pretty good .  it was somewhat thick with some carbonation , and had a hot aftertaste .

pours garnet with 4 fingers of off white/sand colored head . insane lacing & healthy head retention s : sour , vinergary notes up front that dissipates to not much of anything & then comes back t : sweetness & sourness do battle up front , along with serious dryness .  notes : brewed with 100 % scottish maris otter malt ( used in distilling ) and fuggle hops , this is quite the unique beer , albeit it is also excessively raw and aggressive in its flavours . the hops are a way too perceived in the flavour and aroma for the `` scottish-style '' , hence the experimental beer placement .

s : this smells like heaven . endless raspberries , need i say more . it 's not as good as the legendary new glarus raspberry tart , but this beer is certainly fun and tastes great .  m : nice carbonation and pretty effervescent .

an agressive pour was neither necessary nor desired to result in a glass 1/3 full of beer and 2/3 dense , off-white foam . robust carbonation , with many small bubbles .  let me first say that the brugse tripel used to be one of my favorite beers . nowdays its called brugge tripel and the taste changed slowly ... but a lot of small steps make a big one and today this beer is nothing what it used to be . smell of spices and a little hops , not fresh at all and a dull taste make it just a drinkable beer but nothing great like it had in the past .
this is the only barley wine i have every tried , and chances are it will be the last . some people love this stuff , not me , not my taste buds .  m : medium bodied , good amount of carbonation .

deliciously hoppy nose - massive sweet fruit backed with gritty , resinous hops . extremely fragrant , and powerful . palate is less robust , with a subtle , but pleasant hop character riding over the top of a smooth , buttery sweetness . this leaves it extremely drinkable - very smooth and refreshing . an excellent and tasty little ipa .  mouthfeel is medium , carbonation average-high with some pleasant warming feel .

a : pours a clear amber to copper color with small white head and pretty nice lacing around the glass that clings nicely .  m & d - this beer is great on its own , too light and carbonated and malty for me , but suits a nice dinner perfectly , goes well with food and that was its intention so i must review it within its intentions and the style , for which it is very good

s- super hoppy and sweet with a mixture of predominant pine flavor and underlying grapefruit notes ... absolutely exquisite . t- taste is very reminiscent of pliny the elder but possibly better balanced .  m - good mouth feel . somewhat unique in feel .
pours a two finger white head that fades slowly , leaving a good lace . nice crystal clear amber color .  the body is light-medium with good carbonation .
