s- very complex with sweet milk chocolate predominating mixed with a good amount of raisin , smells like a raisin candy bar in a good way . t- not as complex as the nose but still tasty . lots of chocolate with a finish of the whipped cream , the other flavors seem lost in the mix .  m : good mouthfeel .
a : light brown tea-like color with a large three finger off-white head and good retention and globs of foam grabbing the sides .  big body , low carbonation .

the aroma screams bourbon : oak , vanilla , cherries . very tart with a good amount of carbonation on the back end . flavor speaks of bourbon and pineapples with a solvent like characteristics from the alcohol .  mouthfeel is round and full , thick and sticky .
excellent lacing . a great looking beer .  there 's moderate carbonation to it as well .

very pleasant and layered . t - very hoppy at first , but the finish balances that out with a mild and sweet maltiness .  amazing . while the style is not my first choice for a beer , i 'd been told that i really needed to try something from unibroue and this one was it . i taste coriander and a lot of other , complex flavors that i am too n00b to identify . as for aromas , just a very pleasant yeast smell .
the color is a beautiful ruby red , almost purple in the light .  mouthfeel : really thick and chewy . this part would be enjoyable in a good-tasting brew .
s : strong enticing smell of toffee , vanilla and butterscotch . t : much the same as the smell .  mouthfeel is quite decent .

a - gorgeous golden yellow color with a light head s - big malty intense smell , exactly what i expected , but more intense t - almost a dryness to this taste .  very tame malt , very little hops , and weak alcohol that 's more like aftershave . definitely not over-carbonated , the texture fits the style . actually the best element of this beer .
a - deep amber in color . i think this was the creamiest , most wonderful head that i have seen .  m - pretty thin and definitely refreshing .

s- huge cherry notes with wheat right behind it . this has that waxy taste to it that is just very unappealing . great smells and mouthfeel to it , but i can not get over that medicinal taste .  it is very finely carbonated , giving a tickle on the tongue .

aroma was very pleasing . deep and rotund hop nose is neither too flowering , too citrusy , and definitely stops shy of being too grassy . really a unique aroma , something that has become kind of rare these last few years .  feels nice in the mouth .

a- poured a dark black , with a nice head that faded quickly . the head was chocolate brown in color that had minimal lacing . i was very excited to taste based on looks .  taste - 3.0/5.0 - light `` summer '' type beer , prob good if really hot , some malt crispness feel - 4.0/5.0 - smooth , light , refreshing drinkability - 2.5/5.0 - would have again , if it was hot , but not enough flavor make this a go-to beer

the aroma was simply amazing ! i was champing at the bit to drink this . very sweet smelling . reminiscent of belgian candy sugars and granny smith apples . it was n't unpleasant but i did n't expect this from the aroma . overall , an impressive beer .  m- medium viscosity with a well integrated carbonation .

s : some spice notes in the aroma -- cloves , cinnamon , and nutmeg -- followed by sweet caramel and vanilla aromas . there are some floral notes in there as well as a touch of sweet citrus . t : similar to the aroma , spices come up front but do n't overwhelm .  m : it has a nice mouthfeel .

a - hazy amber , huge top , some lacing s - lemony citrus , honey , nice floral hops , very clean t & m - malt upfront with a unique flavor that i ca n't quite place .  the best part of this one is the mouthfeel ; to my surprise , it is rather thick , at least for a beer of this style .

the beer pours a nice orange color , and an aggressive pour yields an initially massive off white head , that fades to a one finger height before lingering . an impressive amount of lacing in generated , almost enough to garner a 5 .  the mouth is pretty nice , feels rich but easy to drink .

a - golden and slightly hazed with coppery highlights and a foamy , cushiony head that jets to the surface and clings to the glass like glue as it subsides . head retention is fantastic , and would be even without the aid of the etching at the bottom of the glass . fantastic .  mouthfeel : light/medium with a tart , crisp finish drinkability : i really do n't crave another of these ; this certainly would n't be a lawnmower beer for me conclusion : just kind of unsorted ( also kind of an odd bitterness on the finish ) ... i tried this a year or two ago and was n't a huge fan ... now that i 'm reviewing it ... i 'm still not .

smell- huge pine , bitter citrus , terpentine ? love it ! big aromas have me very excited about this beer . taste- the pine needle flavor instantly greets me , along with a nice bittersweet malt finish . there is a lot going on here , and i can taste a duality of hops types playing here .  this beer tastes like sheep shit . this may appeal to some people , but it 's definitely a very unusual belgian ale . i enjoyed drinking half of this beer for the experience . it 's so pungent i laughed out loud . it 's always fun to be exposed to a radically different flavor profile than you 're used to .

smells great ! you go the same whitepepper honey spice wheatishness of duvel only with a wonderfully crisp , weedy background . tastes very nearly as good as it smells . big nodes of weeds , pollen , and wild flowers backing up a spicy , crisp , lightly lemony belgian pale .  mouthfeel is about the only thing going for this one . medium body and appropriate carbonation .
smells exactly like strawberry jam with a very subtle hint of tartness .  m - nice and creamy in the mouth , goes down smooth .
a massive , three-inch head rose up to the top of the tulip glass . lacework aplenty . a real beauty .  the mouthfeel is medium to full with decent carbonation .

from notes a - good dark black body with a medium brown head s - delicious sweet chocolaty bourbon t - dry smoky bourbon and vanilla . o ( d ) - tasty , great smelling . a 6 oz bottle split 4 ways can make it difficult to judge . but very enjoyable  full body , syrupy like samichlaus . very similar tastes and mouthfeel .

pours a very clear budweiser gold , with a fluffy white head . in a big glass mug it actually looks refreshing . the can looks pretty cool .  the mouthfeel is moderately thick and full for a pilsner and has a creamy texture . the citrusy hops create a crisp bite towards the end .
the retention was downright insane and it essentially sat there like whipped cream . beautiful looking beer .  body is medium and carbonation is mild .

whatever anyone says about guinness , i think that it is an impressive looking beer . it poured with a nice two finger head and the foam never left the top . the color is black and slightly hazy .  light body and nice and creamy . moderate carbonation .

same good looks as the others . bronze topped with a healthy dollop of buttercreme . while mildly interesting as a laboratory on ahtanum , it 's clear that this hop wo n't headline any solo tours .  '' the mouthfeel is good . its quite smooth and slightly creamy .
pours beautiful dark brown with red edges , almost black with a huge tan head that sticks around and leaves walls of creamy lace .  decently carbonated mouthfeel , and medium-bodied .
smells pretty decent as well . quite delicious , really .  m : about the same consistency as the boston lager .

s : the bouquet is quite vibrant , with grapefruit and pineapple jumping out of the glass .  for a big mouthfeel , this simply does n't have a flavor to match . very nice mouthfeel , good bite up front , a bit of carbonation in middle that emphasises the rye flavors , and a crisp finish that is actual slightly ruined by the lingers smoked flavor .

there is a strong , heavy caramel smell to the beer .  char davies , the artist in 1998 , made a fully interactive immersive visual/aural virtual artwork called ephemere , which furthers the work begun in osmose started in 1995 and displayed in the national gallery of canada in ottawa on june 26 , 1998. who cares ? this beer is almost close to a champaign ( and i would think that the yeast probably is champaign ) . also there is bitterness , which is nice to know that at least there are some hops to the so called beer . it is not advisable to use apples with fermenting , as the yeast creates funky flavors from apples , but this is much better than expected . although i would not want to drink this beer on a regular bases , thus low score on drinkability , i think it has a great taste like a grandsmith apples i use to eat as a kid .
a - frothy and thick white head standing a couple inches tall with awesome stamina . the body is a hazy yellow .  the mouthfeel was the best thing about this beer .

appearance - pours dark enough to block out all light . a big bubbled mocha head springs up and i have to quell the pour a bit to calm things down . it caps off and forms a nice creamy cover with large spacious bubbles of foam below it .  a nice mouthfeel with some decent nuttiness and a tasty touch of roast .

the smell starts off with honey sweetness and pine resin which follows into vanilla aromas from the oak and the citrus aspect of the hops . some alcohol is present but it is n't overbearing . its like smelling a liquified custard of vanilla and orange zest .  mouthfeel is fine . medium bodied with the right amount of carbonation .
cascading clouds settle into a perfect looking glass of beer , dark with beautiful thick creamy head .  mouthfeel is solid - fairly light , appropriate carbonation .

exceptional smell of toffee , caramel , nutty . wanted to eat something that smelled like this . slightly bitter note on the nose . sweet with a more bitter nutty taste .  and of the 6ix , cranberry lambic will likely catch your eye first and disappoint you the most . if you are like me the word `` lambic '' leaves you with a dumb look on your face . you can relax because this is not a real lambic . just as champagne is not champagne unless it is bottled in champagne , france : : a lambic is not a lambic unless it is brewed in pajottenland , belgium . aside from that minor detail a lambic is brewed using spontaneous fermentation and possess a clear vinous finish , cranberry lambic does not-and that maybe a good thing . do n't drink this cold-i 'll be honest , this beer is n't great , but it does deserve more credit , the balance between cranberry and yeast is impeccable ; the finish is crisp and light like a wine , less the vinous/lambic feel . it does great before , during and after dinner , this unique `` boston lambic '' is worth an unbiased try .
smells wonderful . taste - tastes buttery and lemony .  the mouthfeel is very nice.. feels heavy , thick , smooth , and not over-carbonated .

the smell is unique , all the normal bready , earthy notes are right up front but the herbs in the background really add a nice complexity to the beer . mmmm sage . the taste is just as unique as the smell . the herbs give it a bit of a medicinal quality that is n't as enjoyable in the taste as the smell . citrus right up front but the herbs are all i really taste after that . $ 3.69 i think .  m : creamy and spot-on carbonation .

$ 3.99 lovelly cloudy orange beer , with a large thick creme coloured head . nice looking beer in my half liter germen mug aroma is of yeast , spices ..phenolic , leather and earth nice stuff .  very nice feel .

a- this one pours out an opaque black as night colored body with a small coffee colored head on top .  it has a canned fruit essence to it , but i ca n't pick up what kind of fruit . first couple of sips and i get a strong cherry pie filling flavor . i eat a lot of fresh cherries in the summer so i do n't automatically associate cherries with pie filling . not overly sweet but it does have a tart tang finish . a unique beer that i appreciate as well done , just not to my tastes .

a - true definition of exceptional . great head that retains some of its head throughout the pint . lacing was also exceptional . a very attractive beer .  m : crisp and clean , moderate levels of carbonation and warmth . medium body .
looks pretty damn nice .  m : the body is medium to full with a fairly high carbonation . this is actually one of the best things about this beer .
d- a decent ipa but i prefer dc 's stout and american pale ale to this offering .  m : medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

s. smells like christmas . hints of cloves , allspice , and roasted nuts .  served in a pint glass mug a : pours a clear bronze color with about an inch of thick head s : a smell provides a nice rye scent with a very sweet undertone contributed by the honey addition t : very nice smooth tasting beer , has a slight hint of honey and perhaps a slight rye note but other than that there isnt much to comment on , smooth and slightly sweet but thats about it m : very smooth in the mouth with a slight bite on the tongue as it is drank d : high level of drinkability , very subdued taste that is great for a hot summer day but leaves the drinking looking for more otherwise .

delicious and only $ 7/pint..hells yes please . angry and black it pours with a dark brown head , roast and alcohol dominate with some hop aroma , very faded , a little smoke , a little coffee .  pretty solid .
a : huge snowy head , billowing above the glass . classic belgian carbonation , bravo .  mouthfeel is decent medium bodied and goes down smooth .
the smell is filled with some nice hops with a good bit of sweetness .  the mouthfeel is crisp overall .

poured into duvel tulip glass , half beer half very thick foamy head . very solid beer .  the mouthfeel is thick and oily with a mild burn going down . have a bottle of this is all i can handle , which is good because the full bottle would have me a little too buzzed .

s : a great big whiff of piney , citrus , and florally goodness hits the olfactory receptors . i 'm expecting a decent malt backbone here . o : this was only my fourth offering from 3 floyds ( alpha king , apocalypse cow , arctic panzer wolf ) and i 've been impressed with most .  medium full bodied , somewhat creamy .

a - black with a huge coffee colored head s - smells delicious - very sweet , chocolate malts . the most balanced smell to a stout i have had the pleasure of knowing .  m : the mouthfeel , on the other hand , was quite good . d : it 's certainly very sessionable , with a low abv and a really nice mouthfeel , but the flavor is just so weak that it 's difficult for me to really recommend it .
overall : interesting . definitely worth a try .  m : easy drinking with medium-body and low-moderate carbonation .

s : this beer smells great . a very nice balance of booze with piney/citrusey hops . was slightly underwhelmed by the flavor after experiencing such tantalizing aroma smelling the beer . it is still a hearty and satisfying , flavorful brew .  very creamy and full . very dry .

aroma is nice roasty and slightly nutty coffee mixing with a caramel and chocolate sweetness , hints of maple syrup . a good breakfast stout , the aroma was fantastic , but the taste was not as complex .  this is my first review and hope it looks well , even if not my favorite beer . leaves a malt taste on the roof and tongue . this is the first scottish ale i 've tried . for comparison , i love dark ales , like ommegang abbey belgium ale and founders breakfast stout . bottle serving .

beautiful fucking color .  taste : a wink of hops , than the shows over , a surprisingly dry finish mouthfeel : decent - nice restrained carbonation , ever so slightly creamy notes : this is the driest , and least bitter ipa that i have ever experienced .
smell : sweetened chocolate , floral notes .  most everything else about this beer was great , looked good , good mouthfeel , but the taste .

the aroma kick is amazing , a strong citrus , fresh piney hop nose . overall , highly drinkable , in the west coast pliny type tradition .  m : the carbonation is pretty much just right , and it 's smooth .
beautiful amber color . medium just-barely-off-white head that is nice and dense . very lasting lace .  mouthfeel : thick and what you would expect from a ris .
pours a vibrant and dark golden orange . totally clear with a slightly off white head that is sticky and thick .  nice creamy mouthfeel .

poured black , with clear mahogany highlights , with a large mostly lasting light brown frothy head with good lacing .  flavor is malty and sweet , and on the finish , bubble gum ! mouthfeel is firm , and drinkability is high .
great foamy white head .  mouth feel is smooth and clean , with an average carbonation level . overall , good aroma , blend , body , and feel .
very nice and original beer - more body would have been better but still a great treat from a great brewery .  moderate hops with lots of body , almost chewy .

at first is it a bit sour and funky , but then takes on some earthy hop characteristics . the nose is really complex and interesting , but that does n't translate flavorwise as this tastes much more straightforward .  this is my first , of hopefully many reviews , so bare with me . once they were chilled i poured them into a pint glass and sat back with my favorite tv shows a- pours a dark red almost brownish color s- smells like your average porter , did n't really pick up on too much vanilla t- taste more of chocolate or toffee but with hints of vanilla m- pretty smooth , goes down easy without any bite o- not sure if i would buy a case of it , but its good when thrown in a variety pack

this beer black and entirely opaque with a thick and persistant off-white head with flecks of tan in it - very nice looking beer .  boiled pasta water finish . good carbonation . twinge of acid is perfect .

bottle : poured a clear light amber color bock with a large frothy off-white head with great retention and some very good lacing .  the feel was light , clean and crisp . damn , and after smelling this hefe , it had so much promise .
pitch black opaque pour with mahogany glints and a nuclear glow of a khaki cap .  mf : soft and medium-bodied . coriander and crispness does n't stand out enough .
the lacing is astounding . pretty appealing .  mouthfeel was good , carbonation was adequate .

a pint of the black stuff , or the priest , looks as good as ever , enjoyable to watch it settle over a minute or so .  m - full bodied and chewy with a moderately dry finish with some alcohol noticeable .

light brown pour with red highlight and a voluminous foamy light tan head . good retention and some nice lacing , though the size of the head on pouring does make me concerned that this has carbonation issues ( thankfully it does n't ) .  mouthfeel is pretty good .
pours a four fingered faint pink head that slowly fades to a thin layer , leaving a good lace . color is nice crystal clear amber .  buttery thick mouthfeel .

a gorgeous midnight pitch-black , with luscious creamy , light-tan head , almost a finger thick . impressive sticky lacing .  flavor was very strong ginger , and this made the mouthfeel quite crisp and pretty good .

smells and tastes of molasses , raisins , brown sugar and bourbon soaked oak barrels . very pungent and boozy in the nose and finish as well .  taste is mild but the mouthfeel is full pleasantly full and quite nice .
still , the beer does n't follow through on a great aroma .  the mouth-feel is thick almost porter-like with the cooling of the alcohol evaporation .

poured from 12oz bottle into trusty milwaukee brewers pint glass a- deep lushous brown with nice 1/2 '' head that sticks around a while to keep me company s- some faint malts , all in all not much going on in the smell department t- a lot of different but very faint flavors . it looks amazing and feels great but the taste is kind of lame and i detect little to no smell .  the mouthfeel was decent , medium with adequate carbonation .
gorgeous . a few streamers feed the head , which retains ok and leaves nice lacing .  finish is very grainy and `` off '' lol mouthfeel : full-medium , creamy body with moderate carbonation .

a : pitch black , slightly viscous . excellent head formation and nice lacing . this is how an ais should look in the glass .  mouthfeel was smooth , slightly thick for a pils , and with a nice carbonation bite .
pours black with a brown head .  very refreshing in the mouth , its best quality .

firstly , i dont know if the nitro can should be listed alongside the on-tap version , because they are completely different , as the on tap version is far superior than the widget-can . anyway , if kept well , the pour is the classic we have all come to know and love .  the mouthfeel was full and sweet .

poured a snny yellow with an impressive bright white head that stayed and stayed- rendering a lot of uneven side lacing .  m : medium body , low to medium carbonation . smooth and creamy . d : something does n't quite work for me .

it has a deep , copper/mahogany color with stunning clarity and a beautiful head . such a nice looking brew !  nice creaminess from the malt . probably the driest amber ale i 've ever had . usually not a bad thing , i like dry beers , but this was too much , there needs to be a little sweetness there to bring it to life . should n't be called an octoberfest and would n't try again .
smells sweet and malty with a really nice hop presence . i 'm excited to taste based on this smell .  mouthfeel is good and thick , finish is dry with a moderate dose of alcohol present .
this beer looks great , clean and clear , good carbonation and head .  this one is crisp and carbonation is at a good level . body is n't as light as i had expected ; this one 's medium-bodied .

there was also a good bit of effervesence in a brew that was a beautiful golden-yellow color . there was decent head retention throughout and the `` belgian lace '' that was left behind was beautiful .  mouthfeel is nice and balanced , although approaching thin at times .

the smell is pleasing . tons of sweet banana and light belgian candied sugars . a nice belgian yeast is present in the smell , with nice sweet lemon scents . a nice beer overall , but not as clean as i would have liked to see .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a velvety texture , and appropriately low carbonation .

may be the blackest black i have ever seen .  hoping it 's one of those better in a bottle beers i 'm returning to give it another try . so far so good . maybe , and i 'm stretching , some neutral hop spice . this beer makes me try too hard . these hops should be hops should be ashamed of themselves . good malt base to support hops , were they present . bottle is equally bland as on tap .

brilliant cloudy , fuzzy , bubbly orange appearance with a perfect 1/4 inch puffy head and a pleasant hoppy aroma .  it 's fairly pleasant in the mouth . combine the crisp and refreshing mouthfeel with a decent flavour and this beer would be worth getting .

also present are dark chocolates , licorice , spice , robust yeasts , sweet malts and some caramel that all lead to a very complex and pleasing aroma . the taste is not as complex .  mouthfeel : light body , medium carbonation , but the bubbles do n't really `` prickle '' the tongue like i thought it would . a very nice and smooth carbonation .

a -- pours thick with pitch black color and a dark one finger head in my snifter . m -- the pour looked thick but it obviously was an illusion because this is watery and leaves a gross aftertaste d -- hugely let down by this beer , might have to drain pour it because of the aftertaste .  very rich flavor of dark malts and smoke , with hints of coffee and chocolate as well . the finish is almost all smoke , much too intense for my liking . ive used this many times in making caribou pot roasts in the crockpot . they even have a recipe on their website , which is delicious . i was informed that this beer has won more medals at the great american beer festival than any other beer , quite an accomplishment .
i really enjoyed the look and eroma , very subtle nutlike smell .  the mouthfeel of this beer ( outside of taste ) was great . great carbonation , bitter hop aftertaste , medium bodied .

pours a dark brown with hints of red at the edges , crackling four finger light tan head settles to a finger tall , and remains all the way through , leaves temporary sheets of lacing that fade ( probably due to the abv ) .  the body and carbonation levels are appropriate .

this is a fairly average offering in liquor stores round the calgary area , but it is one i can never pass up : this is a very flavourful beer by any means , though it is the most mass-produced of the scotch ales . i love the hue of amber/red glow to this beer . the colour itself is almost appetising . the aroma is my favourite part of the beer . sweet candy , or blueberry gum , rich sweet malt that evokes red licorice , candy cane , sweet bread , sourdough , and other sweet confectionaries . the taste is not as full as the aroma . this is a sweet offering from the time it hits your tongue to the time it leaves your breath : up front there are cherries and irish-red tastes . the hops are there , adding a touch of balance and grass to the finish . the mouthfeel is well carbonated , full , and heavy .  mouthfeel : crisp and refreshing .

very pleasant . t : this is too light for the style .  orange , darkish color , looks a lot like the two previous hop project beers i had . the flavor also left a lot to be desired . the last hop project beers i had were both quite intriguing and sadly this was just boring as far as the hops were concerned . oh , well , hopefully i get to try more of this crazy series .

the appearance is an exceptional golden hue with a slight red tone . a very minimal white head is apparent with smile delicate lacing along the side of the glass .  the mouthfeel at the start was mildly crisp and finished dry and smooth . the unbalanced flavors knock down the drinkability for me .
s : some malty caramel and butter . tons of ripe fruit . t : malty and buttery again with some honey .  the mouthfeel was quite good , though . well carbonated and it felt good going down .
as black as an overcast night in the woods with no light . thick creamy , milky , tan head .  medium bodied and smooth .
poured a orange copper color with great carbonation and a huge head from the bomber . lots of lacing and plenty of suds left over as i drinl .  ) mouthfeel : in one word , thick .
a fantastic aroma if you ask me ! great stuff !  this beer has a high level of carbonation with a very crisp and clean mouthfeel .

n : this is a beautiful , mouthwatering nose . smells very close to liquid pumpkin pie .  m : chewy and viscous . if anything , the aging has tempered some of the trademark trainwreck mouthfeel and flavors of base dark lord , so i 'm impressed .

a - dark as night with a tall creamy dark tan head .  quickly hops dominate and overwhelm with a slightly unpleasant linger . smooth with a light bite . it 's not too bad until the hop bitterness overwhelms and turns this into just another hoppy ipa . all the other flavors disappear without anything to redeem it beside bitterness and a nice feel .

650ml bottle poured into tulip july2 2010 a clear deep amber with a massive light beige head that has great retention eventually forming a brain like island leaving plenty of lace all the way down the glass s big grapefruit hops with a fair bit of sweet malt t again loads of hops but with an unexpected mild nutty chocolate a little different but pretty good m slightly sticky with enough carbonation to give it a slightly creamy feel d a 4.25 option would have come in to play once or twice with this one so i drop the 4.5 here , for a strong ale it 's very drinkable and i would drink it again without thinking twice unique beer with no doubt , nice flavors from the hops and lots of malt character .  we 're okay though , as next time we get a samuel adams winter sampler pack , i 'll give her my cranberry , and i 'll have her boston lager . it 's not a bad beer , it 's just not to my liking . i ca n't even really say why . a bit sweeter than i 'd like , and just nothing that stands out and says `` i 'm great '' .

an amazingly rich and creamy nose with strong aromas of toffee , cream , and roasted marshmallows . body is very good . drinkability : whatever hesitancy i had after seeing how it looked following the pour were overcome by the amazing aroma . a solid , flavorful drink that i would kill to try on cask .  mouthfeel : medium body , medium carbonation overall : this beer has almost no taste , pity

pours jet black with 3 fingers of brownish , mocha head that just screams ice cream float . tons of sticky lacing & very good head retention s : roasty malt , rich , dark & fruitty with woody hops , & booze once warm t : roasty malt , dark choclate , herbal hops along with molasses , leafy & minty hops up front .  the mouthfeel is decently crisp while not out-of-control with carbonation .
pours black as night with a brown head . definitely looks the part of a big ris .  m : crisp , clean , would call it refreshing if it tasted better .

the first thing you notice is that this beer smells very floral and sweet , perhaps the most beautiful smelling beer i have ever had .  the aroma contained notes of malt , hops and a discernable alcohol content of medium strength . it had a stong alcohol flavor that was very over powering the other flavors . it was smooth yet burned as it went down . truely a devilish brew !

i bought it because i thought it was a summer pale ale , as the label says its an ale . aroma of lemon zest , cracked peppercorns , sunflowers , corriander , earthy hops and some gritty grain aroma .  the flavor is a bit better as the taste of both a good belgian tripple and a solid ipa can both be percieved ; however , the flavors compete for dominance instead of blending harmoniously . i think the problem here is that tripple is a big , expressinve beer . with exit 4 the subtle flavors are masked behind a second layer of bold expressiveness . i love the brewery for pushing the envelope and i look forward to buying the next release in the series . with innovation like this , flying fish is sure to hit a huge winner sooner than later .

appearance : deep mahogany brown tone with a nice full more than two finger sized tan head leaves perfect even lacing scatter evenly around my glass .  the mouthfeel is slightly creamy and very enjoyable . this drinks nicely . there is a lot going for this though , the mouthfeel in particular .
it pours really good it looks just terrific in my pint glass .  it was smooth and had a decent mouthfeel to it , with some nice malt flavor .
on cask at the guildford arms in edinburgh poured a golden yellow , with a white creamy head and excellent lacing .  mouth feel is completely crisp , refreshing , and clean .

s - beautiful wet hopped aroma with a citrusy and piney profile that is extremely fresh . there 's also a bit of bread and caramel malt present .  the same color , mouthfeel , and drinkability were there , just the hopiness , aroma , and flavor , as well as most of the bitterness seemed to have blown away .
on a fairly gentle pour into a pint glass this pours with a huge ( 2/3 of the glass ) of white billowy slightly tan head .  mouthfeel : lightly carbonated and creamy .

this is apparently a modification of this location 's recent belgian ale , and also has an addition of pineapple . a- red-copper , thick white rocky head lasts very well and leaves some lacing . there is a bit of haze as well .  hard to rate , as i appreciate that it is flavorful , but do n't like said flavors ... medium-light bodied , creamy , and well carbonated .
very good appearance and smell overall .  mouthfeel : nicely carbonated and good level of thickness - probably the best part of this beer .

appearance : the look of this beer is exceptional . it is a burnt brown color with a huge pillowy head . there is tons of sticky lacing that makes this beer look geourgious .  mouthfeel was nice - weizenbock like . bananas , black beans , chile peppers and/or pepper jack cheese with some creamyness amidst the carbonation . interesting , no doubt , and worth seeking out if you want something really different .
pours a completely opaque pitch black . light brown head with some big bubbles around the edges .  medium mouthfeel .

nose was wood the wonderful blending of currant . an herbal note of something meaty in the nose . funk like that of brie cheese skin and a bloody fruit . there was some mineral wood interaction with the fruit that gives it a food palatable quality , but it was quite subtle . overall i would only have this if you 're eating some sort of exquisitely cooked fish .  mouthfeel : medium bodied beer . very short aftertaste with his beer .

the beer poured in a dutch beerglass gives a very nice white head with a dark coppercouloured fluid . the smeel is average , ca n't really say what smells reach out my nose but it 's not spectacular .  the mouthfeel was good , but the drinkability hass to be chopped down due to the smell and the taste of this beer .
appearance : pitch black . very dark head .  mouthfeel is nice and full and slippery without any carbonation .

very nice 3 finger head that was creamy with a great deal of structure . deep orange/amber in color and quite translucent . great lacing and a touch of visible carbonation . this short description is not an indication that it was n't great .  m : super-smooth , eminently drinkable . lighter body , but crisp/clean finishing .

a- pours a hazed apricot color with an amazing soft bright white head that initially contains a lot of carbonation you can hear . soft , tight thin cap remains .  m/d : light and smooth feel on the mouth , drinkable but not something i will ever get again .

a-light amber , hefe , with creamy foam on top , lasting few minutes.appearance is big plus for this beer .  palate : very enjoyable . great , smooth , and light on the throat . it would be stellar with cheese .
on-tap at the toronado . dark orangey brown with a nice 1/2 '' head of thick white foam that leaves killer lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is medium and creamy .

this is my first bigfoot so we will see how the talk stands up ... a- really dark ruby red in my snifter . big sandy , fluffy head perched atop . at this point the head seems unwavering . but it eventually faded leaving all sorts of lace .  mouthfeel is actually pretty nice , medium body and carbonation with a creamy quality .

s : oaky , boozy aroma , some dry roasted grain ( roasted nut , coffee ) , brown sugar , sweet caramel , with hints of leather . i like it ! t : it picked up some bourbon and vanilla from the oak , as well as some brett . good stuff .  mouthfeel is fine for the style .

i do n't know if the age helped , but this smells fantastic ... deep milk chocolate ... . nice bourbon and vanilla notes ... hints of brown sugar and cinnamon ... really a great nose . flavor loses anything from the nose ... a bit of dark cherry essence rounds out the ris flavors ... fudgy toward the finish.. oak seems a bit musky/tannic.. medium body with good carbonation .  aside from the taste , mouthfeel is actually pleasant on the palate . good medium body and carbonation is about right on the tongue .
really delightful . very nice aroma sits about halfway between a brown ale and a porter .  mouthfeel is good .
a - beautiful copper color . great off white head .  the mouthfeel is fine . it is a low/medium bodied beer with good carbonation .

poured from a 550ml bottle into a weisse glass . a : this is really interesting . thick , creamy , almost beige head that disipates slowly and good stickiness . the color is red when held to the light , but almost a chocolate brown away from direct light .  the mouthfeel is surprisingly creamy and not too heavy . the drinkablity is pretty low , not from the booze , but extreme bitterness , which overwhelms the decent , but not exceptional malt .
color was a dark brown with amber highlights .  feels slick , not very carbonated , and heavy . alcohol warming is powerfully strong . lacks balance and drinkability .
pours pitch black and thick , and makes a milk chocolaty looking huge amount of foam .  wine like alcohol warmth , and a vinous texture , i rather like this feel and good carbonation .

poured into a large wine glass , very dark , giant creamy brown head ( very enticing ) .  mouthfeel is medium , well carbed , nice on all fronts but where it needs to be . big failure , in my opinion .

smells wonderful ! t - flavor is a bit subdued , really disappointing after such an amazing nose . more tart cherry , with flavors of brown sugar , vinegar , tobacco , and high quantities of oak .  m- nice carbonation while retaining a good smoothness .

the aroma is exceptional as you can smell this ale when you pour it out of the bottle . deep dark fruity ester mingle with a citrussy coriander spiciness make for an excellent aroma , this is the first beer i have tried in which the aroma exceeds the flavor . the rich aroma led me to a letdown as the flavor was much more subdued than i expected . the body of this ale is an immense letdown as a scotch wee heavy imo should have a bit more viscosity and sweetness but this is a rather thin ale in terms of body . the scotch ales always throw me off due to the lack of hops and for some reason i have a hard time enjoying tha malt flavors unless they are balanced by a signifigant amount of hops .  the mouth is thick and malty . as far as drinkability , i have to say that i would be really happy to have one of these if i was alive 4000 years ago but for now i 'm going to have to go for something else .
appearance is beautiful . pours an oaky golden light brown . leaving a dense one finger head on top of the beer .  the carbonation feels pretty crisp .
incredibly clean , with absolutely no imperfections in the malting or hops . extremely delicate . the flavor is incredibly clean .  the mouthfeel is good , but obviously does not improve the flavor !

smell : pine cones and grapefruit at first then the malt comes through real nice . taste : hoppy as expected but where 's the malt ?  mouthfeel is crisp and a little sizzly . refreshingly light bodied and clean .
s : smells great ! coffee , chocolate , smells sweet .  a little sticky and a very bitter aftertaste .

very dark , nearly black , dark ruby edges , huge three finger head that falls slowly , becomes rocky , excellent lacing , and a cap that sticks around throughout .  light and creamy mouth feel with obviously knocked down carbonation .

s : the best smelling coffee oatmeal stout i 've smelled to date .  ) and is a deep rich molasses s : once again , may have been too cold for phenols to waft up t : slightly sweet really tasty m : nice and cold d : pour me another
pours a dark brown with a large tan head that had very good retention . it certainly looks good .  the mouthfeel is the pinnacle of this brew . full-bodied with a dry crisp feel .
i enjoy just about everything this beer has to offer .  m : thick , chewy..medium carb .

poured into a chimay goblet.. well , the name does n't lie ... this is a pitch black with a creamy but small head ... laces unbelievably though.. this almost has an ris look to it with its perceived thickness.. this has one of the best aromas i 've ever experienced ... it has all of the aspects of a great stout with an added extra of smokiness that reminds me of a nice thick cut bacon ... it 's just wonderful ... it 's loaded with roasted malts and i might even get a little touch of hops here as well.. just magnificent ... very rich roasted flavors here ... loads of dark roasted malts with that smoke that i was getting in the aromas mix wonderfully with a tinge of hops on the finish ( although not much ) ... there 's a thickness to this that belies the export stout style.. i would guess ris or double stout all the way here ... there 's a meatiness here as well that i would assume comes from the smoke.. it 's a nice brew , i know that.. i 'm really digging it ... i 'm very glad i got to enjoy this brew.. it 's loaded with rich dark flavors and the aromas here are ridiculously delicious.. the whole experience was terrific.. very nice export stout.. very drinkable although at 8.5 , it could hurt you quick ...  mouthfeel is fine and not heavy .
old plowshare stout is a very dark reddish brown ale with a frothy , bubbly light brown head that has great retention and leaves lumpy lacing .  mouthfeel : good .

pours a three-finger white head that fades slowly , leaving a good lace . nice , deep crystal clear amber color .  pours a cloudy , almost 'chunky ' looking way -- looks a bit similar to an apple cider ( non alcoholic kind ) . caramelly sweet too . vanilla . taste is what kind of throws me - again , both the oak ( taste of whisky barrel ) and smokiness are there . i like both of those favors in my beers , but combined , my jury is still out : like they are competing for my affection . alcohol is quite present too , which seems to go well with the aforementioned whisky oak . a lot going on in this brew .

an aggressive pour into a duvel chalice builds a 1 '' tall , khaki-brown head . retention is good and leaves an inital ring of lacing around the glass .  m - crisp and refreshing o - overall pretty meh .
color is an absolutely gorgeous golden amber that promises an excellent brew .  m - pretty good .

outstanding retention and lace , strong carbonation . looks beautiful in the glass and the lace is breathtaking , but the flavor just falls short of expectations .  mouth is medium bodied , but with some good tingly action on the back of the tongue , so also good .
guinness is one of the worlds greatest beers , hands down . rich , tasty , creamy , heartwarming .  m : lovely long bitter aftertaste .
s- smells of coffee , hint of chocolate , a little sweet . enticing .  m- pretty good body , minimal carbonation but works for the beer .

a : pours a cloudy , medium brown color with two fingers of billowy , pale tan head . exceptional retention and lace , vigorous carbonation .  mouth feel is more medium bodied than the wheats i 'm used to , a nice change and the full blast carbonation leaves one a happy advocate overall it is lacking smell , good in flavor , great in feel .
poured from a 12 oz bottle into a snifter a : pours a redish gold color with a 1 finger pinkish white head . excellent retention , minimal lacing .  medium mouthfeel .

brillient , copper penny colored pour with a full , thick head of near white froth that retains and laces very nicely . just the way i want my ipa to look .  m : medium bodied with a medium carbonation .
poured a nice pumpkin orange with a big frothy white head that left spots of lacing here and there .  carbonation done very well .
pours out to a lightly hazy light orange-amber ( not bottle conditioned ) , forming a tall & whipped off-white head with very good retention and lacing .  carbonation was crisp for a medium body .

like the looks of this . full thick head .  i have the mom version the head was initially strong , though sudsy and it fell quickly . carbonation is plentiful from the surface of the brew come hop aromas -- minty and herbal -- and coriander . it does n't smell as though an authentic yeast was used , which fits my preconceived notions for rogue 's methods the flavor confirms my american yeast suspicions . light fruity flavors , strong hop contributions , though little spice .
its pours a beautiful copper with a thick white head .  mouthfeel is light body , medium carbonation . fairly nice .
pours a cloudy gold with a beautiful creamy two finger head that does n't let up much .  there 's big citrus/grapefruit hops , but then a nasty onion/vegetable taste . mouthfeel is fine .

there is the overpowering scent of nutmeg , cinnamon and some other christmas seasonings . the taste is about what you would expect from the smell . the cinnamon and the nutmeg dominate so much that it almost fails to taste like a beer .  mouth is no complaints , it 's low-medium body with relatively high carbonation .
a : the beer is a deep dark brown color , with a large brown head that fades slowly and leaves a thick lace on the glass .  the mouthfeel is good - smooth with a right amount of carbonation .

other regards it 's pretty good : poured with a large foamy , frothy , fluffy , off white head that lasts a while and some lace .  mouthfeel : medium-plus body . medium carbonation . some oily viscosity to the mouthfeel .

appearance- fairly standard for an imperial stout . smell- huge malts bombard the nose with notes of chocolate and coffee . the spiciness was really surprising here .  m- mouthfeel is nice . medium body with a good amount of carbonation .
'' the appearance was awesome . huge head all the way down the glass .  the mouth is smooth and light .

a- the pour yields an opaque black body with a small khaki colored head composed of tightly knit bubbles . the head is long lasting and leaves complete rings on the sides of my glass .  m - nice light feel with a crisp finish , accentuated with a alcohol warmth .

aroma is smack you in the face hop blast appropriate for a pnw ipa . taking dry-hopping to its logical extreme with several whole hop cones in each bottle .  m - tongue ripping bitterness . medium to full body and tingly carbonation to go with it . good .

a -- pour a cloudy pale gold color with two fingers of head that recedes fairly quickly but leaves some lacing on the glass s -- smell is spices , banana/clove , light wheat malts .  mouthfeel -pretty good . foamy , not spritzy . nice and full , for a lager .

the body of hop head poured an absolutly beautiful copper-orange color , with a sizable custard head . retention and lacing were both excellent , thanks to a constant supply of carbonation from below .  m : creamy to a crisp finish with a good carbonation throughout .

this beer pours with a thick and foamy head . wonderful active bubbles slowly float to the top to form a thick white head .  m : dark beers always feel good in the mouth . this one isnt super smooth , but the feel is good .
a : beautiful . three fingers worth of foamy mocha colored head . lots of lacing here .  m : a nice , medium body .
it pours a thick , viscous black with a large dark tan hea that slowly recedes .  m : lots of carbonation , but a pretty smooth medium body nonetheless .
reddish copper in color , impressive head with incredible retention and massive lacing down the sides of my pub glass .  2.5 t & m : mouthfeel is fairly viscous and silky .

a very intriguing nose , wow , minty , citrusy , lemon-grass , soft licorice notes , very pleasant even with its slight funk of oxidation . this is actually quite nice even with its funk , i could deal with a little less carbonation .  the mouthfeel was sticky and thick . there was tight and crisp carbonation that was nice .
pretty tasty with a great aroma .  m : silky smooth feel . i like the finish . smoothed out my palate .
head is enormous and really nicely laces . retention is amazing .  - well carbonated , dries the mouth a bit . nice smooth body , probably this beers highlight is the mouthfeel .

*reviewed on 06.07.2005 starts off with a golden clear base , medium white fluffy head , head retention for all 60 minutes and impressive lacing effects . luckily it was n't a typcial belgian ale but a cheap bud-like lager .  good medium body with great carbonation .

the second the cap is popped , the aromas come rushing out and literally fill the room . it smells like i 'm chopping up fresh oranges and pineapples as i pour this beer ; remarkable ! this beer takes me longer to finish than most dipas this drinkable because i stop to sniff this beer before every sip ! it is not exceptionally bitter but a rather sweet and citrusy ipa . there is n't a lot of malt getting in the way of the hops , hops , hops . a superbly drinkable dipa .  m : a bit chewy for me albeit nicely carbonated .

poured from a 11.6oz brown bottle with a white cap marked `` bottl 2006* 12 % '' into a tulip glass . easily one of the longest lasting , largest frothy heads of foam i have ever seen on any beer . appearance is a rusty yellowish orange color , cloudy and semi-translucent .  m : fizzy carbonation that smooths out a little into the sip and works well with the body of the beer .
appearance - black with murky auburn brown edges . nice semi tan head with great retention and lacing . super sticky on the sides , just beautiful .  pretty slick mouthfeel .

awesomely complex . taste : chocolate , chocolate malt , coffee , chocolate syrup .  m : fuller side of medium-bodied with moderate carbonation that tickles the tongue and throat . this aspect of the beer is really nice .
poured an opaque ink jet black with a nice khaki head with good lacing .  thick body is very good . it 's just passable for now .
a : an average pour produces 2 1/2 fingers of a foamy , rose-stained white cap . respectable retention .  m- good carbonation and substantial body , not bad here .

from a bottle this poured a pale golden color . very clear , well carbonated with fine bubbles of co2 and topped off with a very attractive creamy head of foam . this certainly looks like a premium beer on the highest order .  it has a very soft mouthfeel , a little like soda to be honest and you can barely notice the alcohol .

s - gorgeous nose on this . roasted coffee , chocolate , toffee , caramel with a bit of a piny hop smell poking in there . still it 's an interesting brew with a complex bill . lots of malts lots of hops . still definitely worth a try ( all of their stuff is ) .  mouthfeel : nicely carbonated , and nice and creamy . feels good on the tongue .
a : a modest pour generated a black body and a massive head of over two fingers . the head was dense and sticky .  m - medium bodied with some soft carbonation .
a : i love the color ; a hazy gradient of orange and red hues that is literally shining in my glass , it would make a perfect sunset . beautiful .  good carbonation .
this beer poured a black body with a thick dark tan/black head . a beautiful sight to see .  mouthfeel : light-bodied but not watery . it had a nice feel to it .
s : very hoppy . has a floral , citrusy sweetness that is very deep and pleasant . faint candy smell also present .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with moderate carbonation .
poured a deep thick black with a nice dark tan head that dissipated quickly .  feel is pretty smooth , nothing weird here .

it reeks of pumpkin pie without being too aggressive with it . the pumpkin pie aroma does n't dominate the taste and it actually tastes like a beer instead of some kind of pumpkin pie flavored wine cooler .  m : dry and crisp but smooth as butter .
a brown/mohagany body held a creamy three fingers of head made of tiny nitrogen driven bubbles . strings of lace remained on the sides .  m- decent carbonation , light and airy .

smells quite spicy , with cloves and cinnamon and orange peel coming through the hefty alcohol and sweet malt . excellent . a sip reveals a creamy , yeasty , sweet beer , very different from your normal eisbock .  but it does n't make me puke ( and it tastes better than bmc by a sconch ) mouthfeel is nice . kinda creamy mixed with crisp .
seems very complex , i love it . t : disappointed from the smell .  m : very fizzy , light on body , about right for the style .
s. funky sweet spiced berry nose - lots going on here with a nice play of sweet and spicy battling it out .  fine mouthfeel , nothing objectionable , but it 's not a stand-out lager either .

a= pours a beautiful dark brown almost black color with a great two finger perfectly toasty looking head on it that holds awesome retention and wonderful lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel - good smoothness , a medium body on par with the style , crisply carbonated .

smells wonderful . cloves , banana , caramel , fruitiness . nice comfortable warmth from the alcohol . not something i could see drinking a ton of at a sitting , but delightful as a one off .  m : creamy mouthfeel with prickly carbonation .
very inviting . smells very welcoming , but lacking in other areas .  m : tingly carbonation , medium body and refreshing enough .

this beer was poured unhurriedly into a flute . lots of swirling carbonation and three solid finger s of thick creamy head .  feel medium body , pleasant texture , some drying and bitterness in the finish .

beautiful looking beer : brown with auburn highlights ( no i 'm not a hair stylist ) . a pleasure to look at .  smooth in the mouth with nice , crisp carbonation . nice feel , but flavor is not there .
pours a deep brown with ruby highlights into a tulip . creamy off-white/light khaki head leaves excellent lacing and retention .  m : creamy and sticks to the mouth for awhile .

strong vanilla notes , sugar , and faint chocolate aroma..southern tier really has a knack for completely nailing the nose on their brews t - do n't know if i could drink any more than the 9oz i was poured . this is incredibly sweet , and extremely rich . a perfect dessert beer .  smooth and refreshing , light to medium bodied with a slight tingling on the tongue .

big hop aroma -- a bit sugary , citric and piney . lots and lots going on just in the scent , and i can feel the back of my tongue tingling already .  mouthfeel- medium mouthfeel ( for the style ) . carbonation level was perfect for bringing out the bittering hops .
pours brown with ruby hints . there are two healthy fingers of head ( boy , is this a live beer ) and the retention and lacing are top notch .  m/d : a medium body with good carbonation .
pours a very nice amber , just the slightest bit of haze . nice thick , dense , head . excellent lacings .  mouthfeel is medium-light bodied , a nice creaminess to the carbonation .

dissipates slowly and exhibits great retention with beautiful lacing .  but , also an odd smell kind of like salami . this must be some nasty phenol created by the yeast . a bad yeast flavor here and a lot of it . i usually love unibroue brews for that complex yeasty quality but for some reason this one tastes a little off . that lunchmeat aroma and now this bad oily yeasty taste make this beer almost undrinkable . i doubt it considering it 's called edition 2004 , we 're in 2005 , and it 's 10.5 abv .

a - murky apple juice with and incredible pillow head ... slow to leave , chunky lace left .  m & d : the texture is soothingly carbonated , quite good for a fruit beer , while the body is consistently light against the richly sweet flavour . the downside of using lichee for brewing is that an aftertaste can turn quite `` simplistically acidic '' , but this beer shows a decent balance in the end . compared with the other lichee beer produced by another taiwanese micro-brewery ( takau ) , this one comes a bit too rich in sweet lichee-juice at the expense of more complexity , yet the overall mouthfeel and a clean aftertaste makes up for it .
excellent retention and good lacing as well . looks intimidating .  very syrupy and flavors linger on the palate . very unique . strongest beer had to date .
the nose is creme creme creme . the taste to too strong for the brule , which takes away from the nose of the beer .  velvety . good amount of carbonation .

remains hazy as it warns , unlike the 2010 . among the best sour aromas i 've had the pleasure of experiencing . t : fruits , oak , and brett share the spotlight . great blend of the three flavors . m : body is thin and weak , yet nicely oily . d : sessionable , even at $ 40/bottle .  mouthfeel is good , soft and tingly .
head stays for a good while s- smells identical to apple pie .  m - good carbonation and it finishes clean . good light to medium mouthfeel .
this beer smells amazing but its taste is over the top .  mouthfeel is light with a good spike of carbonation .

appearance : pours the color of a tripel ; that burnt golden orange appearance . head is gigantic and rocky which dissipates slowly into a thick rocky soapy lacing that clings to the glass tenaciously and refuses to let go . it even have yeast in the bottle which i found out on the last pour of my bomber . so really proper looking for an imperial ipa and the color of a tripel . i 'm giving this a 5 ! its a beautiful beer smell : this a very hoppy beer .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . fair carbonation .

blood red color with a thick pink foamy head the color of blush wine .  first off , i can tell that this one is slightly skunked , but i ca n't really blame the brewer for this one as i am also able to pull out some nice mellow caramel malts and a touch of biscuity-bready goodness as well . nice mellow malts , not too sweet , but the hops come through for a bit too much bite from what i look for and love about english pales . the hops come on a little too strong and linger too long , not really allowing me the chance to savour the mellow malts as much as i would like . there is a slight sweetness about it that reminds me of fresh apples although not the biting green apple off taste . this is different , and nice , but not my first choice for an english pale .

smell : smells fantastic . sticky , sweet , grapefruity , piney , lemony with a touch of pepper on the back end . i will try again , just because it was so delicious .  mouthfeel is this beers strongest point as it is so watery it does n't feel harsh or overly alcoholic .
good size 2+ finger white foamy head that looked more soapy as it receded . excellent lacing , dissipated to a thin head that lasted till the end .  m - pretty thick , smooth and a bit refreshing .

pours a very hazy orange-amber with a massive , pillowy , long-lasting head and great lacing .  m- really good carbonation , low abv and the nearly great sweet/tart balance make it actually react quite nicely with the mouth .
appearance : a big , rocky , dirty white head of both large and small bubbles . loads of lacing .  medium mouthfeel .
a : aggressive pour yields 1 finger of dark tan pillowy head with great retention .  meidum bodied and relatively smooth .
pours a golden-yellow with a huge white head . lace is all over the glass . beautiful .  m : light-bodied , crisp , very clean , refreshing .
it 's a good inviting smell .  m : very viscous , pretty smooth .

s - sweet hop delight . much stronger hop aroma than doppelbocks i have had before . earthy hop aroma with a very sweet scent as well .  mouthfeel good . creamy and subtle carbonation . cant complain about this .

2011 batch 1 - 750ml bottle poured into a cbs snifter a : black as night . gorgeous finger-and-a-half dark brown head that leaves a nice full cap throughout consumption .  medium bodied and decent carbonation .
came out of the tap a deep brown , almost black color .  strong carbonation . m. very bitter and the carbonation is clean and tart .

the smell is really where this beer shined - a rich aroma of nicely roasted barley - coffee and chocolate predominated as well as a milky lactose aroma . this beer fell flat on the taste ( or maybe that 's just in comparison to the nose ) - it started off sweet , but never really delivered on all the flavors i had smelled . still , kudos for the nose . i probably wo n't be purchasing this again .  feel is good - light , crisp , medium bodied .

s : about what you 'd expect from an ipa- flowery , with lots of citrus . i 'm detecting lemon , melon , and other tropical fruits . i 'm used to lemony scents from ipas , but this one has something different- it 's the distinct melon i 'm getting from the nose . t : very `` clean '' tasting , lots of citrus at the beginning . the ending is quite bitter , but not a much as some ipa 's i 've tried .  m : creamy and nice . decent carbonation keeps it from sticking to you .

the smell was fantastic ! a hop bomb . nice hop finish lingered on my tongue . i 'm anxious to try the imperial version of this brew .  good mouthfeel , crisp , medium body , good carbonation which is refreshing for a warm weather beer .

a- pours nice brick red/ very light amber color with 2 fingers worth of off-white head s- mixture pine and citrus hops and small bready malt and some alcohol makes it selft present t- getting a sticky resiny pine limited amounts of the bready malt alcohol and nice slight bitter finish m- medium body , carbonation is low , alcohol hangs around a little in the finsih o- this beer has some hype and for me it doesnt live up to it . that being said , i like my ipa 's more towards the citrus side , and this is piney .  low carbonation and good mouthfeel .

appearance is near perfect for this style .  aroma : hops . the crystal hops dominate the aroma . the malt is there , but overpowered by hops . but i do n't taste the balance that an esb should have . the hops weigh far more than the malt in this beer . notes : this tasted like a very good ipa , but did not have the balance i was expecting , for an esb . a great beer , but did n't fit the style as well as i would have liked .

smell : strong spice and citrus , bubble gum taste/mouthfeel : thin but refreshing , banana , spicy hops this witbier was very good . i think the appearance of the beer itself lacks a little but the smell and taste makes up for it .  starts off clean and finishes with metallic hops m : silky smooth , good carbonation d : why ?
poured a illowing ornage with a big white head and excellent carbonation . thick pour and cloudy .  m - good mouthfeel . a little heavier thanks to the lack of filtration .
this beer was very jeckyll and hyde for me . the smell is also terrific : citrusy , apricot , peach ( as others have noted ) .  light to medium bodied , with a very smooth mouthfeel .

carbonating is correct level o : the aroma is great , but the taste is way over bittered with pine .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and crisp . good carbonation , but the overall trainwreck of flavor in the brew makes this one hard to take down .
a nice perfect one and a half finger head rises from it that 's a tan color and has great retention and some spotty lacing .  m - light-medium body with plenty of carbonation .

rodenbach grand cru , abv : 6.0 % . s : big aromas of red wine , cloves , ginger , oranges , berries , juniper and liquorice . like a mix of glgg ( mulled wine ) and julmust ( a swedish type of soda , drunk at christmas ) . t : rich , sour flavours of red wine , cranberries , apples , oranges , cloves , juniper , liquorice , brown sugar and black pepper . it 's unusual to me ( but i like it ) . i do n't know what to say - it 's the sourness that does the job for my tongue . while i 'm all alone in the dark , the aromas and flavours bring a lot of memories and other stuff to my mind - i think i 'm going to enjoy more of beers like this in the future .  mouthfeel is as good as you would expect with an aerator . all in all , you can drink it for the mouthfeel but do n't drink it for the taste .

poured a slightly cloudy , amber to copper color with . nice frothy two finger off white lasting head . ample lacing cling to the glass .  mouthfeel is good - medium-bodied , good carbonation , smooth .

decanting the beer , it pours much like any other solid brown . lots of lacing . a solid look . where the look is no surprise , the hop aroma at the onset takes me back a bit .  m- very little carbonation . very full syrupy body .

aroma : an amazing , complex aroma which far exceeds any other pils aroma i have smelled . lemony , peppery , summery , yeasty and malty all zipping around my nose . taste : does n't live up to the aroma but is n't bad .  long , earthy , dry finish . interesting , somewhat unusual brew .

the aroma is very enticing ... it 's fruity and easily smelled from afar..thankfully this is not overloaded with cinnamon as was my fear ... instead , there is a rich perfumy sourness of rotting apples , musty basement and faint tobacco . very nice , and not tainted with fusels as i have noted in ron 's prior entries .  mouthfeel is nice , good carbonation , but seriously , ca n't get over that ham finish .
a : fantastic clarity , golden , and a relentless head , a 3 millimeter head is still visible after 20 minutes , leaving rings of lace in its wake .  m : mouth feel is pretty good .

baltika # 6 porter is nearly black in colour but has a slightly red hue when held to the light . a handsome porter .  mouthfeel is smooth , for sure , with mellowed out carbonation and a surprising absence of slickness , considering the alcohol .
aroma is nice : lightly caramel with a tangerine citrus hop character . does smell nice though !  nice carbonation and creamy mouthful .

its smell is sweet and pleasant , and reminded me of peaches . i dare say red stripe is the best smelling lager i have ever come across , although i admit my range of experience is not the widest on beer advocate .  mouthfeel is about right for style , perhaps a touch undercarbed , but all else is acceptable , though it showcases a flavor profile best left behind the curtain .

this beer pours a hazy honey golden orange with a huge fluffy white head , that leaves some seriously sticky lacing . i could only think to myself that this is an absolutely beautiful beer .  m - a fairly heavy mouthfeel with all the sweetness .
appearance : a hard pour gave me about three fingers of sturdy looking off-white foam . good lacing and head retention .  creamy mouthfeel with the addition of oatmeal in the mix .
decent lacing . a very attractive beer .  it 's very creamy and goes down easy . i 'm really disappointed with this .

the overall aroma is pretty sweet smelling and i enjoy just the smell of it . did i mention this smells really good ? taste - scotch flavor with a malty flavor to it . overall - it 's a beer that smells better than it tastes .  m : medium-high carbonation fits the style nicely .

lots of small bubbles , highly carbonated s- big lemon , hay , banana , citrus , and funky notes t- this is super bitter , lots of sulfur/salty qualities on the finish . tons of nondescript bitterness , if only the taste matched the aroma .  syrupu sweetness , not cloying , with hop dryness in the blend . this is what imperial pilsner is supposed to be ? what happened to the pilsner part ?

hazy blond in color with a steady stream of bubbles rising from the bottom of the glass to form a huge , thick , rocky white head that lasts for the entire glass .  the tastes match the smell for sure , but this thing is way too sweet , it tastes like a thick maple soda . extremely malty , alcohol definitely makes itself known .

aroma is powerfully sour and very champagney . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .  light-medium caramel malt sweetness up front , continued in the middle with a hint of earthy hop bitterness , finishing with a more of the same . medium mouthfeel .

pours cloudy yellow orange with thick creamy foam indefatgiable white foam .  as i drink more my palate adjusts but it does n't ever really get over the off flavors m - pretty thick , not too carbonated , nice mouth coating qualities d - burnt coffee does not go down very well , plust the thickness of the beer limits my ability to quaff this completely i like coffee , i like stouts , and i like a lot of coffee stouts ( new glarus and founders breakfast stout for instance ) .
draft at teresa 's in wayne , pa pours a very dark brown with foamy tan head that forms a lacing that lasts throught the whole glass .  mouthfeel is medium , clean with a bitter hop aftertaste .
pours a amber ale color with a super looking coffee colored head with tight tiny bubbles that also remits some great lacing .  good carbonation .

smell is beautifully complex & bright , like i just walked into an herb garden : really picking up on the rosemary , floral notes that are big but gentle , something kind of savory like oregano , maybe some basil or mint notes in there . seriously , this is fantastic , i do n't think i 've ever smelled a beer like it .  it has good texture .

pours a dark brown/black color with some dark ruby hues when held up to the light , excellent amount of head that fades at a good rate to leave some lacing .  the aftertaste lingers nicely , and the mouthfeel is firm . full bodied and smooth , but lacking an extra punch .

well after all the hype i had to give this one a try , pours motor oil black with two finger tan head , smells of alcohol and burnt espresso , tastes the exact same , if i were to roast some espresso beans until they were charred all the way through , then threw them into a blender with ice and vodka , thats exactly how this tasted to me .  m - medium bodied with good carbonation .

color me surprised that this is a stout at all and then an ris ? big ipa nose . big old ale taste - tons of smoother , sweeter dark malts . more like a normal stout , i suppose .  the feel of this beer is it 's crutch very creamy and boisterous keeps me tasting over and over .

the hop aroma is like sticking your nose in a bag of cascade hops and taking a deep breath .  ) the body is a hefty medium , bordering on the truly heavy , with a light moderate carbonation and a fairly chewy feel . harsh .

anyhow , when you have a need for hops , this one certainly takes care of the fix . aroma , yes , just like it should be- huge citrus , flowers , grapefruit rind , oranges , probably lemons and limes if i was n't diving in so fast . this beer has a nice solid body holding in a creamy , milky nectar thats very smooth . the finish is bitter but smooth , maybe a little woody from all the hops . it only lacks a little malt complexity in the flavor , the malt seems a bit basic but does hold up well to the hop explosion .  really nice body all around ... overall - i would really enjoy this beer if it were n't for the bubblegum flavor , it 's really off putting and not very pleasant .
pours out a bronzed hazed cloudy yellow color with two fingers of fluffy creamy white head .  m : solid mouthfeel , carbonation is pretty much spot on .
this one is jet black with an enormous off white / light tan head . this head is quite frothy and laces incredibly .  light body with good carbonation .

poured from a 12 oz bottle into a pint glas 2 inch off white head on top of a deep coppery garnet , modestly carbonated .  still for such a big beer it had a great body , just not sure if i would want more , until it got about 5 years on it .

a clear copper colour with a 2 finger head of foam . it 's ok , especially during the hot days of summer . head retention turns out to be excellent as is the lacing .  mouthfeel - it does have a pleasant rich/buttery mouthfeel .
aroma is very enticing-sweet caramel malts and fresh bread dough dominating along with some flowery and piney notes .  mouthfeel is thick and smooth , no watery sensation at all .

a very fine looking beer .  the body is nice and thick , with a flavorful malt profile : sweet medium caramel malts with a bit of roast character . hops , by the way , are almost nonexistent , which would n't be bad if not for the oxidation , which makes the faint floral flavor seem dull . overall not bad , but has the same type of oxidized or maybe just oversparged flavor common to other corporate breweries like gordon-biersch .

really nice nose on this . a big whiff of belgian yeast , revealing dark fruits and a faint hint of very bitter cocoa . after a few nose dives in this one i 've become a bit used to the yeast smell and richer chocolate notes are revealed as well as a faint alcohol aroma .  the mouthfeel is it 's only saving grace . it 's a light bodied beer and is very drinkable , although i know this will be my last one .

pours a light amber color with a massive bright white head that just keeps growing and growing , the lace on this beer is incredible it coats the entire glass . gorgeous looking beer .  nice lively mouthfeel .

a bit of lacing & zero head retention , really dragged this score down s : pumpkins & pumpkin pie spices , cinnamon , allspice , & nutmeg t : pumpkin , cinnamon , nutmeg , dryness & brown sugar up front . spices start to dominate as this warms , cinnamon & nutmeg especially , plus some squashy/pumpkin notes as well . finishes warming with nutmeg & cinnamon mf : medium bodied , fairly low carbonation & a nice warming sensation , expected a bit more malt depth though drinks pretty easy , the abv is well hidden , but lacks the total package of say , an ichabod , but i would certainly grab a sixer of this during the fall every year  medium body , good crispness .

s-awesome aroma of top quality chocolate starts things off ... then a little bailey 's irish cream notes ... .caramel ... the more i smell this the more of the irish creme coffee notes but light on the java ... also some plums , and raisins ... .really a great smelling beer . t-dark unsweetened chocolate ... .charred raisins ... licorice ... good amount of pure hop bitterness ... .a lit bit like rogue is in the hopping ... .some alcohol is flexing its muscles and is quite evident ... .exudes what you 'd expect from an impy.. m-rich , and full bodied..velvety.. d-damn nice impy that ranks on the top tier ... i like a couple others better than this but that is no knock on this beer because there are really some kick ass impy 's being made these days ... a must try if you like this style..  mouthfeel : light in body . very crisp throughout . clean aftertaste .
very lovely appearance . aroma : roasted malt , oak , dark chocolate , molasses , hints of brown sugar and coffee .  mouthfeel : light bodied beer . moderate carbonation .
the beer poured a beautiful translucent red colour with a 1 inch tan coloured head .  m : full body with mild carbonation ; slightly clinging .

pours out great , an excellent pitch black with a nice tan head and good lacing .  golden in color , slight haze ( nothing wrong with that ) , definite aromas of honey sweetness . lingering sweetness in the palate with a slight funk . interesting beer and something that one might only need to consume once .
looks great . almost pitch black body with a massive tan head that is both dense and puffy . head retention is excellent and lacing is substantial .  m : good thickness and carbonation .

good strength and good harmony between the components . the nose is awesome , but that 's the only thing that is .  low carbination , medium body . smooth on the palate , the beer says nothing , if it does not say sour cherries .
there was very good retention and excellent lacing .  good body and mouthfeel .

bottle to a tulip pours a clear red body , and by red i mean excellent vibrant red . has a fizzy white head that doesnt stay for the party .  body is pleasantly creamy , almost akin to that of an esb or pub ale .

aroma starts off with some vanilla and slight chocolate , but really comes to live as the brew warms . banana 's , plums , lots of malty goodness . taste is caramel , dried fruit some alcohol as she warms . definately worthy of the hype .  m : perfectly fine . quite smooth , medium/full-bodied with a hint of ethanol .

this is the first tripel i 've ever seen that does n't pour like a homebrew . it is pleasantly clear with a rock-solid white head . then , after perfectly maintaining its integrity for five minutes , i look away for two second and it completely collapses for form a nice ring-around-the-beer with some craggy lacing left behind .  nice crisp carbonation to keep it refreshing .

the beer was poured into a champagne flute . appearance : this may be the singularly best looking beer i have ever seen in a glass . the head was very tall and proud with an off white coloration . the retention was perfect throughout the consumption of the beer . the carbonation was explosive rolling boiling bubbles .  m = moderately carbonated . good .

smell is strong and at first of piney , grassy , spicey hops with some citrus not all that different from an ipa . some caramellly and toffee smelling malt and a bit of booze hits the nose as well to differentiate it . taste at first is boozy . it is supported by the hops , but they are n't nearly as dominant as in the aroma . plenty of malt sweetness is there , but some fruit flavors appear as well . overall a very good beer , but it falls a bit below the expectations set by the aroma .  pretty much just a tingly water . very smooth and somewhat refreshing beer .
pours a jet black wth a huuge , really tight brown head that retains really well , beautiful !  the mouthfeel is full and nicely carbonated yet still somewhat creamy .

coffee and lemon aromas , very rich and inviting . thick , thick , thick mouthfeel ... molasses , some coffee , and a dense and vaguely cherry flavor . bitter as all get out .  appropriately light in body without being too thin .
s : lots of bacterial funk , acid , and dark fruit , very fragrant and pungent .  m - nice average mouthfeel .

aromas begin with dark dark fruits , leather , oak and light light bourbon . as it warms more you get apple skin and vinous grape notes . really complex to say the least . overall i am really pleased with this beer .  mouthfeel is spot on for the style , light and crisp and a bit dry .

heat is starting to mellow with a year on it , and the fruity development of the nose compliments the flavor beautifully . freshness indicated that this beer needs some time , and boy was i right .  i liked the mouthfeel , smooth and gentle .

a- pours orange-amber with a massive , foamy and creamy head that retains amazingly , gives duvel a run for its money . the cloud is as big as the head of others .  smooth with a creamy but dry finish . i walked away thinking that the `` smoked vanilla , coffee , and birch '' was meant to be flavor descriptors rather than actual ingrediants . all of these elemtns were way too weak to be appreciated for what other beers can do with them . call it a single , nix the mention of the adjuncts , and this beer would be alright .
s - big citrusy hop aroma with a hint of some sweetness in the back .  m- medium body , pretty solid mouthfeel , nothing special but solid .
pours a three finger cream head that fades slowly to a thin layer leaving a good lace .  m - good mouthfeel , and strong carbonation d - an okay beer , but a bit disapointing .
appearance is very nice golden orange .  the palates leads with a thick , malty mouthfeel up front and a sticky , resiny bitterness in the back .

poured from a pint can , this beer really looks like it was just pulled from a nito tap . intense creamy head topping a brown , almost black beer .  m- the body is full . the carbonation is at a nice subdued level .

a : bright red with an even keel of carbonation rising to fluffy beige head . gorgeous head does n't waver for a moment .  m & d : very good , sits well and fairly easy to drink once you get the first one down

appearance : pours a very hazy apricot/orange color . great thick & foamy white head with excellent retention .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a soft prickly creaminess , along with some easy slickness in the body that helps that raw feeling finish go down . just a smidge of alcohol is felt but it is n't overly noticeable .

smell : awesome . juicy citrus hop hit the nose hard . taste : does n't quite live up to the smell , but still very good . the hops are more herbal with some citrus in there as well . still very good and really glad to have tried this .  - 3.0/5.0 feel - coats the mouth well , with a bit of pepperly aftertaste .
