guinness pours ruby black with a beautiful creamy white head that lingers for quite a while .  soft prickly carbonation does cleans the pallet , of this light to medium body beer with moderate astringency and warming alcohol .
frothy tan head .  nice mouthfeel for a pale ale .

pours a cloudy amber brown into a wine glass with two fingers worth of frothy , white head . the lacing clings to the inside of the glass for dear life , and is quite exquisite .  pleasantly carbonated on the palate , with a dry finish .

pours a deep golden yellow with an inch or so of resilient white foam . offers good retention and sticky lacing .  crisp , clean mouthfeel with flavors of dry , pale malt . at first , i found myself wanting more flavor , a la boston lager , but the mouthfeel and resulting drinkability really brought things back up for me in the end .

aroma is incredibly full and delicious . very very nice aroma . the flavor is just as incredible as the aroma . cherries , both sweet and sour are here in abundance , as well as a bit of graininess , and almost a thin flaky pastry flavor .  taste : muddled and uninspired mouthfeel : absolutely thin and lacking in every way imaginable .

excellent so far . i suspect this might be what us pale ales would smell like if we got them fresh . taste is hop heaven , with serious bittering going on on my palate . good experience , but , at 12 bucks a 500ml , compared to local brews , it 's marked down 1 point , it just does n't compete  mouthfeel is disappointing ; thin and watery , with too much carbonation for my taste .

this one is really impressive out of bottle , with a deep , opaque brown-to-black color topped by a huge , fizzy beige head that settles to a persistent ring .  the body was disappointingly thin for such a big beer , allowing the unwelcome alcohol notes to really come through .
beautiful smell of bourbon it 's you first then caramel , vanilla , and a hint of oak .  it seemed to have very high carbonation .
smell- granted it does n't smell like a dipa to me , but it smells more like an english barleywine , which i love . super rich caramel scent with a minor in the hops dept .  mouthfeel - watery .
smell is great - lots of mild coffee and dark malts , burnt bread and sweet caramel .  md - thin and not much of a body to it .

s : perfumy nose ( muscat ? ) with grapes and chamomile flowers , pungent , with hints of honeysuckle . t : there is a belgian yeasty estery upfront which is nice . after that the grapes really come out , particularly the gewurztraminer which i 'm a fan of since i love alsatian whites . but anyways , it 's a fun beer to delve into , tasty for sure . a marriage of northern french wine and belgian beer , it makes perfect sense .  mouthfeel is entirely too thin and watery .

t : hugely ( and distractingly ) sweet . almost medicinal o : a very complex sipper of a beer that i found overly sweet . enjoyed the non-ba version much better .  not much to say about natural ice other than that it is cheap . little taste that i could discern , but nothing abhorrent at that . maybe some sweetness , a bit more complex than some of its stablemates . of course , it is highly drinkable , which is the point . pressed for cash and desirous of a little buzz ? you could definitely do worse .
s-this beer has one of the most pleasant aromas that i have smelt in a long time .  thin to medium bodied with very little carbonation .
the smell is sweet , spicy , almost vinous , and very complex . each time i think i have an aroma captured it changes into something else .  2/5 m : thin and watery with medium carbonation .
smells great . taste . a decent iipa .  m. thin with no carbonation at all . d. i thought the flavors were interesting , but this beer was much too thin and flat for my taste .

aroma is a deep roasted scent that makes me think of chocolate cake baking . color is solid black with good carbonation and a thick tight head .  very pale straw yellow color , hazy but filtered look no aroma noted water like very light bodied taste and looks like water ... . however better than most would give credit to seeing how its bud .

the aroma is amazing , i must admit . the feel is definitely most disappointing . this thing smells amazing , and tastes good too , but the feel is a bit rough around the edges , and adds some unfortunate difficulty to the drink-ability .  m : medium bodied beer but it is a bit light on carbonation . feels dull and flat .
a- pours a tar-like black with a tan head .  feel is thin , dribbly and loose .

i smell fresh cat piss , pine , grapefruit peel , fresh , fresh fresh hops ! ! ! ! still hard to live up to the smell . the mouthfeel is good and i have to say that if this beer was on tap i would stop for a pint or three every day .  the mouthfeel is very thin .

poured from a growler into my new holland high gravity series glass a - black as can be with a small circle of tan/brown head s - tootsie rolls with a hint of hersheys chocolate . is this really a beer ? t - tootsie rolls with a hint of hersheys chocolate ... seriously though a little more going on in the flavor however .  mouthfeel is watery and boring , with a decent carbonation level but not much else to write home about .
the brothers consistently nail aroma . bubblegum and tart cherry with moderate roasted qualities and a faint hint of wheat twang .  the mouthfeel is one of worst i 've ever had with a saison .

cabernet scent is definitely apparent and quite unique . beyond the fruit and wine qualities , the aroma is a bit subtle .  tragically the mouthfeel is watery and the carbonation ( which others had noted ) , distracts from the overall experience .

s -- tropical fruits dominate . this is like a mix of a belgian tripel and and ipa . very crisp and refreshing nose . t -- not quite as good on the palate , a little too dry of a finish but still a pleasant taste . m -- on the thin side and too dry , average d -- nice beer , but nothing that stands out to me .  it was flat on the tongue and mouthfeel was very weak .

aroma : heavenly . roasted malt , chocolate , a hint of coffee , and i detected a hint of whiskey aroma that was very pleasant . taste and mouthfeel : slightly chewy but not quite creamy .  i am dissapionted in the carbination as it is nearly flat with a medium/light feel .

the smell is the highlight of this beer- nutmeg , pumpkin , vanilla , cinnamon and a gram cracker crust smell that emerges as it warms up . tastes like pumpkin pie spices with a hop kick up front with a delicious carmelized sugar like on top of the pie in the middle , delicious . unfortunately , the finish and aftertaste is so dominant of nutmeg that all other flavors are lost . drinkability up front is exceptional but the negative finish makes it average . if they could balance out that nutmeg finish , this would be the best pumpkin beer i 've had .  appearance : dark amber color with a nice 1/2 '' off white head ... unfortunately this reminded me of a pop on the pour smell : pine , hops , citrus taste : kinda watery , slight citrus ( maybe cascade hops ) mouthfeel : thin drinkability : could do two in a night , but i 'd rather drink something that tastes better

aroma : smell is incredible natural smelling apricot tones this one smells very nice , i am impressed not overly cloying and no off tones to boot . very natural smells like apricot juice , good stuff .  far too thin and light for a bock . carbonation was assertive , but the body just felt thin and watery .
appearance & gt ; looks like an giant-sized perfect pull of espresso .  mouthfeel - one of the most water beers i 've had .

big piney and resiny hops fill the aroma , backed by a pretty sizeable maltiness . tobacco and bread come to mind . the malts may dominate the hops in this aipa , which almost always results in an iffy beer , that has you questioning the style .  thin and tingly mouthfeel .
this is a lovely slow-sipping beer .  although the mouthfeel is thin for a stout , the flavor is pretty good .

beautiful fresh dry-hop aroma . the malt is not hidden , though , with a pale malt aroma blending in with the floral hop resins .  biggest disappointment was the mouthfeel which lacked any crispness/carbonation at all ; practically flat and way too light .
definite beer geek cologne going on .  it seemed really thin & watery , not offering up much complexity as i swished it about .

subtly fills your nostrils with sheer weight as well as clove , coriander spice , lemon peel , vanilla bean , has a lively yeastiness , some banana notes , while light of touch it 's never not there . the fruit mainly banana , pear , apricot , more skin and pit than flesh .  mouthfeel : this beer is almost watery yet with a hint to tannins that leave my mouth dry and scratchy . the beer had a watery texture in my mouth and the flavors were not in balance with the nose . while it did have a light mouthfeel and i am used to drinking hoppy dry beers , this beer would have had an easy drinkabilty yet with its unbalanced flavors i had very little desire to do so .

yeast totally non-flocculating , so even a careful pour would have left 1/2 the bottle behind if i didnt take some yeast . aroma was typical ommegang , sour and spicy with vapors of peach and cherry . palate was less sour than aroma and about 1/2 way between duvel and ommegang ommegang . the `` fine dose of yeast '' did cause massive rumbling in my plumbing later that night though .  the mouthfeel was flat and very dissapointing .

a fragrent nose brings about thoughts of raspberry chewy candy and a bit of candied malt . enters the mouth with a long creamy tart feel . notes of crisp apples , fresh raspberries , and even end a nice mellow malty sweetness is faint on the end of the palate . i speak a lot of the sour and tartness of this beer but it is not to harsh but well balanced with a touch of woodsy malt sweetness . enjoyable for the style but drinkability says i still need to share the bottle with a friend .  the mouthfeel lacks more . and flat .

aroma of tart dried apricots , fresh apricots , canned apricots ... uhh , pretty much just apricots . quite a great smell actually , as i like apricots ( this is why i ordered an apricot ale ) . decent apricot ale , maybe a shade better than the apricot wheats i have tasted off the shelves , but not the game changer i was hoping for .  above average taste for an adunct lager , but not great by any measure . this is definately better than budweiser , coors or miller , but not exactly to die for . foster 's price point is right about miller/bud level , but always slightly higher . it 's worth the extra coins if you 're on a budget . much more enjoyable than the run-of-the-mill macros .

enjoyed from snifters and beer a gift from the brewer himself ... ap : deep dark body , roasted brown head , awesome retention .  flavor : then , i drank some & everything went downhill . it was watery & disappointing .

the smell is very fresh , crisp and clean ; truly wonderful . lots of citrus and pine aroma coming off immediately , mostly grapefruit with some floral grassiness as well , with some biscuity malt in the background . i could smell this a mile away and loved it . t : taste follows nose for the most part , leading off with citrus-pine hops with a sweet biscuity background . it 's fairly bitter , but the malt sweetness balances it just enough to keep it extremely pleasant and crisp . the taste was very fresh and very clean , ending as it began with a gentle , bitter , floral hop bite . the smell is exquisite , and the taste is juicy and not as dry as many similarly citrusy-bitter ipas , making it a bit more drinkable . with all the smaller breweries popping up in boston , and many focusing on more boutique styles , it 's great to see a new , local ipa that seems to be doing everything right without reinventing the wheel .  palate is watery with that adjuncty grain flavor , but not too offensive . easy drinking .
s - nutty , chocolaty , malty aroma .  m : this feels fairly thin ; the flavors fall quickly off the tongue , resulting in a watery finish .
appearance gorgeous , cloudy orange body full of sediment with a decent head .  the body was very thin and the beer lacked substance .
pours a massive , incredibly thick , dense and chunky white head that is long lasting .  m : very thin and watery .

taste is a bit of a let down compared to the amazing aroma . a really good ipa .  coppery colored amber with a sudsy froth top that subsides to a foam slick , no lacing , body is very thin and under-carbonated . perhaps as an effect of my bottle not being quite as fresh as it ought to be , i am detecting absolutely none of the fruity notes commonly perceived by other ba members ... .and this really hurts my overall impression quite a bit .

a-amber with sediment and good frothy head . the color an intense head gives this one high scores .  has a malty aroma , enticing , maybe some wheat too ? fizzy palate , mallty taste , fruity , not very lingering . thirst-quenching .
smell is fantastic ! nothing but chocolate covered toffee in the nose , the lightest bit of roastiness , and a hint of nuttiness . i love it .  mouthfeel is thin .

22-oz bottle opened at local beer tasting ( underground bluz ) . a beautiful brew . this beer can do some damage because you wo n't want to stop drinking it !  very light bodied , an ok mouthfeel.. just way too watery and thin , not much for taste , just some lemon zest on the after taste .

as soon as i opened the bottle , i was smacked with a heavy hoppy smell , easily reminded me it 's an ipa i 'm dealing with . s : an amazing combination of hops , pine , citrus , maybe some grape . t : interesting , with the token ipa hoppiness being the most notable aspect of it all . d : daunting at first , especially for me , not a huge fan of ipas , but i have to respect this beer . the dynamic flavor-smell combinations are remarkable , and though it 's not my favorite , the never-departing flavor may be the reminder that it is something to be reckoned with .  i was again surprised to find a very thin mouth feel dominated by carbonation which seemed to accent the minimal hops to make them more pronounced .
black color with a solid brown head . head does n't retain for very long , but wonderful lacing follows this brew from start to finish .  m - watery , light carbonation .

i had this beer tried next to or , poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : a pitch black color , very tiny white thin ring of a head , pretty poor looking ... s : smell is awesome . tons of hoppy citric and grapefruit notes , with some sweet honey and vanilla ... t : wow . a bit of a letdown very little hop bitterness and a strong cloyingly sweet flavor with little complexity ... m : smooth , could use more carb ... d : a decent enough beer , but its the worst between either and or !  not thick at all , but lacking carbonation .

s : wow , tons of hops in the nose . a slight sweetness is detectable underneath it , but almost all hops , and in a big way . t : again , up front i 'm getting lots and lots of hop bitterness , with just a tiny bit of sweetness on the end of it . as it warms , i can get more malt and some caramel , too .  slightly watery body and bland carbonation .

a beautiful deep amber with ruby and copper hues . frothy white head with superb retention and lacing down the glass .  a - medium to dark amber ; almost no head , but what little bubbling there was at the edge of the glass managed to leave a slight bit of lacing s - there was nearly no aroma , and what was there was nothing distinctive t - good malt/hop balance with pleasantly surprising bitter finish m - far too thin and too little carbonation in this sample ; a bit of a sticky finish d - though it will not be mistaken for a world-class brew , this one is easy to suck down since it is thin and flavorful ; without the sticky finish , it would score a half-tick higher

s : love the nose on this one ! was expecting a typical citrus hoppy aroma , but instead it was a more roasted/toasted & earthy .  mouthfeel is thin i wish it had some body to it would make it much more palatable for me .

if you like hops , you 'll like this . it is overloaded with hops , but very very tasty .  the palate is not unpleasant , with plenty of that molasses , clove , and dried fruit and some decent maltiness , but this beer is very light in body ( hence my unusually low `` mouthfeel '' score - i rarely dock or add points here unless there is significant deviation from stylistic expectations ) .

2009 vintage a- deep violet , crimson red just a beautiful awe-inspiring color and massive towering head that seems to be independent of the beer and an entity all onto itself .  body is a nip thin . a bit too still , but more carbonation would have blasted through the empty body of the beer , making it even less desirable .

the sweet malts balance this very nicely . m & d : medium body beer , nice level of carbonation , makes for a semi-creamy mouthfeel . just an outstanding ipa .  the mouthfeel is unbalanced as if the carbonation and the liquid will not merge . for as much noise the carbonation made on opening the bottle , it seems quite on the palate .

half inch head and thick head retention s : straight dole pineapple orange juice or something like it ! phenomenally citrusy . t : more dole juice ! crisp bite at the front before smooth finish . o : delicious ! very unique . probably could n't have more than one but very enjoyable . the fruit juice character is pretty interesting , that 's for sure .  the mouthfeel is way to under carbonated and watery for the style .
aroma is rich : sweet chocolate , vanilla , with strong whiskey notes . overall a decent beer , but somewhat a let down .  mouth feel was very thin .
a - beautiful amber body with intense white huge head and sheets of lacing remaining for an insane amount of time .  very thin , and barely any head .

pours a clear yellow with tons of head and lots of lacing . not typically a fan of the pale yellow look , but this one had an amazing head and great retention .  the mouthfeel is syrupy and shows none of the carbonation that the pour hinted at .

this may be the best smelling pilsener i 've ever experienced . lovely complex , floral hop aroma . pleasant light grained malt in the background . overall , a superior beer .  thin mouthfeel with average macro carbonation . touch of caustic mouthfeel in the middle with the bitterness and petrol notes .

12oz bottle to pint glass a : very creamy brown with a puffy tan head that has decent retention and some lacing . i think the look of guinness is my favorite ... does n't get much better .  mouthfeel is thin for a ris , almost watery .

2008 vintage , into tulip . the nose is utterly complex with interplay of sour , sweet , fruity and sherry aromas . the sourness takes after balsamic vinegar which is quite intense denoting an aged example , as do the obvious sherry-notes . the malt is quite rich with caramel and slight chocolaty character while fruity esters are reminiscent of raisins , plum and black cherries . a very faint mushroom-like bitterness indicates that brettanomyces has been used to add sourness to this one .  crisp to the point of being overdone , loads and loads of soda like carbonation . notes : ho hum , average , run of the mill , mediocre ... etc .

s : i thought i died and went to heaven the first time i smelled this beer . caramel and toffee aromas dominate with some hints of berries .  i recently bought a bottle and had it at home and was supprised to find that it really was not much better than the average super brewery light beer . the taste is almost nonexistant and unlike some mega beers has almost no aftertaste at all which for this beer is actually a benefit . i would compare is most to a pbr .

very interesting . smells sweet but different .  its rather thin in the mouth , and doesnt ready leave me wanting more drinkabilty - with its high alcohol , and bitter mocha overload , this beer doesnt do it for me .
the nose is amazingly sweet .  skimpy in body , vapidly dextrinous and approaching watery in mouthfeel .

not overly complex , but interesting enough to keep your attention . d-i polished off the bomber effortlessly . really goes down nicely , and the alcohol is hidden fairly well .  mouthfeel is flat but this is the only disappointment .

beautiful beer at 6.8 % abv certainly packs a punch , a - perfect for the style , a big fluffy head fell away at moderate pace , lacing well , pours a hazy orange s - a highlight for me , big amarillo hop aroma , citrus , fruity no negatives in the aroma dept . t - a little bit less than a std dipa bitterness but still kicked liked a wild goat , beautiful flavours , crystal or other malts coming through m - well controlled and certainly right for me .  mouthfeel was thin and tingly , and the initial flavor was sour fruit , which was fine , but then it too was quickly overtaken by the taste of grains .
coffee dominates the nose and overpowers the other smells that are underneath . nevertheless , the smell is very enticing .  the palate is thin .

s - strong tropical fruit aroma with hints of mango , lemon , and other citrus fruits . a slightly sweet smell from the malt is a welcome addition to the strong hop presence . d - the nose was much better than the taste .  m - this bottle was flat . this gave the beer a thick and somewhat unenjoyable mouthfeel .
wonderful aroma ! it 's fantastic !  mouthfeel 2/5 mouthfeel got too watery as the beer warmed .

thick foamy off-white head with excellent retention and lacing .  for some reason i do n't taste the citrus like everyone else does ... m - thin and flat . propagates through the mouth pretty easily though .

say what you will about guinness ; yes , i know they 're a bunch of gimmick happy corporate whores , but one thing is undeniable ... there is no other beer on the planet , that looks , smells , or tastes , like a guinness on tap . the cascading effect is awesome . for the first third of the glass it leaves a solid wall of lace all the way around without a break in it . held to the light it 's surprisingly clear and reveals a fiery red hue .  the body is very thin and watery and the carbonation level is medium low which does not compliment this beer at all .
a wonderful sweet , almost fruity smell after opening the bottle .  the palate is thin .
a - great clear amber . good color with a few bubbles rising up . a decent foam layer was left along with a collar of lacing .  mouthfeel is equally watery .

the smell is amazing . coffee dominates , and while i 'm not a coffee drinker , i like the smell of it .  smells basically like apple juice . watery . also , the carbonation that was so present during the pour now seems dulled . for all its faults , in the end rogue makes a malt liquor that achieves what you usually want out of the style .
smell : cocoa powder and chocolate . sweet but not cloying so . really digging the aroma . taste : where 's the sweetness ?  not the worst tasting beer ever , but very thin and watery .

black raspberry desert chocolate . slightly smokey and tart in the back . vanilla , fudge , and chocolate . d : described as an `` experimental '' beer , this one is definitely unique . worth a try as i 've never experienced a prominent chocolate raspberry taste in my imperial stouts before and i think i like it !  m : super thin with no carbonation .

aroma is great - nicely hopped and strong chocolate . flavor is a big disappointment after the promising aroma . too grainy and acidic with a harsh nut-skin flavor .  m : thin body with almost no carbonation at all .

not very much in the way of hops , nothing really stands out . i loved the nose , but the taste let me down just a bit .  nose : it 's aroma is a little bit malty , a little bit citrusy flavor : the taste has some lemon/citrus notes w/ some hints of maltiness , but the big thing that you notice is how fizzy this beer is . it 's far too fizzy for me .

aroma was an incredible with scents of spicy dark bread .  finish really kills me as bad oaks comes off ... mouthfeel is the true downfall of this beer , watery light with no depth ... easy to drink but not good enough that i would .
smell : nice light & refreshing hoppy pine aroma .  alcohol is very well masked for a 6.5 % way too much carbonation for my liking .

flower essence , hop oil , a touch of malt balances out the smell nicely . taste and mouthfeel- much of the same that is in the smell is evident in the taste as well .  mouthfeel is very watery w/ average crabonation .

aroma : it has that rare smell that is as full and alluring as you 'd hope it would taste : banana bread , roasted chestnuts , cloves , hints of chocolate , estery and phenolic notes . the finish is very clean , with lingering bits of pepper and chalky dark chocolate . mouthfeel : it has a very smooth feel even though the carbonation is quite prickly . the dark malts give it a fuller and more flavorful character than most saisons , although incorporating them also reduces the peppiness and refreshment of a traditional saison . would i get it again ? : yes . it 's a solid beer , and though not the pinacle of its style , a welcome alternative to traditional saisons . bottled : february 25 , 2011 served : may 6 , 2011 price = $ 8.99 at whole foods ( nyc ) additional notes : - international bitterness units : 30 - malt : pilsner , rye , crystal rye , black malt - hops : pilgrim , saaz  m : watery , high carbonation .
very nice sherry character to it with a hint of a woody edge .  m - super thin , kind of dry .

the beer has massive yeasty bready smells . the beer has a very good combination of fruity ( apples , grapes , pears , plums ) jelly smells . oddly enough the smells of this beer bring back memories of my grandmothers kitchen smell .  3.0 m too thin for my taste and my experience with better scottish ales ( like oskar blues ) .
very nice . the taste is very unique .  a nice chocolatey finish that lingers for a while on the palate is the best part about this beer . m : poor .

a-pours a deep amber ... .little head.. s-nice sticky sweet aroma of caramel is most evident ... also some mild chocolate notes ... .the more i smell this the more impressed i become ... .some dark fruitiness is there in the way of plums ... .also some very mild spicy black pepper ... t-the dark fruits lead the way here ... black cherries , plums , perhaps a little bit of raisins ... the spicy peppery impression blends nicely ... the caramel is strongly evident too and borders on cloying ... not tasting the chocolate but it is definitely there in the aroma . i was jacked up hearing this was the style chosen for this year as i have been mildly disappointed with the selections in the past five years ... this is a decent dubbel ... i immediately bought two six-packs of this when i saw it and i anticipate purchasing more .  the mouthfeel is quite disappointing due to carbonation that is much too high for a stout and a body which is not thick or creamy .

begins with a very strong and pleasant aroma , sweet and alcoholic with raisin notes dominating and , upon further reflection , a hint of lemon ( ? the strong aroma and dark color leads one to expect a full-bodied , malty sweet meal in a glass .  taste is very light and mouthfeel is weak .

it smells distinctly like pineapple cake . i mean you get the sweet pineapple and a really bready smell underneath . probably my favorite smell in a beer ever , different than the norm for an apa . definitely does n't live up to the smell but i enjoy it . the carbonation level is good and there is n't really a harsh aftertaste . there certainly is n't anything off-putting , and i would recommend it to anyone , at least for the sake of smelling it .  the mouthfeel is astringent .
pours a clear gold with a 1/4 '' head with great retention .  however , the mouthfeel hindered any solid punch this drink could have had with its extremely watery and light feel .

glassware - imperial pint appearance - dark amber/red in color , which makes sense . nice two finger white head that leaves a lot of really great lacing on the glass .  the body of this is way too light for a porter .
the scent is a wonderful molasses .  the problem is that the beverage is thin and flat on the palate and leaves a really unpleasant metallic aftertaste .

aroma is very pleasant . sweet .  mouthfeel : body is thin and water and a little flat ; finsih is wet and is like drinking malt flavored water . the flavors are mild and meek , the body is super watery and does n't offer much , so i do n't feel i will be drinking this again .
fantastic smell of sweet banana and a slight tart cloves .  thin mouthfeel .

the foam was wheat in color , bubbly , thick , smooth and left a ring around the glass til the end . the color was a dark burgandy/all most black with an orange red highlight in the light .  this beer is incredibly watery and light on the palate .

aroma was intensely hoppy yet smooth and balanced . piney and floral hops , citrus and fruity esters came through strong along with a touch of candy-like sweetness . cascade hops and hop oils soon became bitter and biting and left a noticeable film on my tongue . unquestionably , this was the most bitter and unbalanced ipa i have had to date .  the mouthfeel is pretty sad on this one . very watery and thin .
golden colored and pours a huge white fluffy head with good retention .  ok. m : kind of thin here .

the aroma is sweet and rich , on the softer side as barleywines go , well balanced between caramel malts and woody hops .  on first taste the mouthfeel seems a little thin . all in all tasty , but quite thin and seriously lacking in body .
appearance : crystal clear . white head . nice lacing smell : smells like a triple .  mothfeel is very light and watery .

this beer pours with a lot of carbonation - almost too much - an absolutely massive head barreling over the top of the glass a la snow-cone .  tastes like someone put artificial flavoring in carbonated water .
smell is excellent and unique . predominate smell i get is apricot .  m - thin , watery , overly carbonated .

wonderful nose on this beast . but it is n't very rich . its kind of one dimensional . has big hop character , big malt character , roasty , chocolate , caramel , but that 's about it .  fizzy carbonation and no body .

black pour with a tall , frothy , tan head .  caramel , coffee and cocoa are there , but overall balance is towards the dry and bitter mouthfeel - 2.0 lightly carbonated , bordering on flat and a little watery .

the beer poured a hazy golden color with a massive white head .  mouthfeel is also watery with not much body and no carbonation but essentially pretty drinkable due to the fact that is just resembles colored water .
huge tan head after a normal pour , looks very nice .  too thin .
s : a lot of hops here , citrus and floral , smells incredibly fresh , like sticking your nose in a handful of hops .  mouthfeel is boring and watery .

during the pour , this raspberry lambic style has a fantastic bouquet of raspberries and frothy pink head .  a - light , clear , yellow color with a thick head that dissipated quickly s - beer , cheap beer t - beer from a can , cheap beer from a can m - thin , flat , not much d - went down smooth , probably because i 'd wisely iced it down with some ice and rock salt so it would get really cold .
appearance : pours a beautiful dark amber with a finger of light tan head that leaves some lacing and a ring around the edge of the glass .  the body is light and really deters the taste .

really nice looking brew , deep copper colored body with a creamy cap of head that lasts forever.very little aroma with only the slightest hint of spicy hop .  the flavor was spicy and malty and the mouthfeel was tingly along with a burning sensation as it is swallowed .
the smell is wonderful . tannin , grapes , apples , apple peels , raisins , caramel , touch of cocoa , and a hint of alcohol .  m : this beer is almost flat .

the smell was full of bourbon , as expected , that blended well with the fruity aromas expected from a tripel , along with spiced notes .  flavor is of arange , and body is highly carbonated . prickly mouthfeel , and a bit boring overall

smell is a rich dark chocolate with some dark roasted coffee . very sweet aroma . taste is more of a dry cocoa , but still chocolaty .  nearly flat carbonation and medium body allow a solid diacetyl mouthfeel , which is done well if you like it that way .

looks find s- awesome citrus hop aroma , much more aggressive than i expected from a tiny , 4 % bitter . insane ! lovely m- body is overall pretty thin , nothing to see here o- awesome sessionable beer .  that being said i want to keep track of beers i have tried and will start to try reviewing beers i drink ) from a sampler pack found at specs liquor . tastes flat to me . no alcohol taste that i can tell of and not a whole lot of flavor . goes down easy and not much of an aftertaste .

a floral citrus smell hits you hard with a smell of some sweetness to it that seems to be hiding in this hoppy beer . mouthfeel- a good amount of carbonation to it between medium to heavy in its feel , about average in my opionion drinkability-is n't the best but with conditioning you can become very use to it and then it becomes very appealing . just brilliant .  m - watery and sticky . its almost a thin beer .
served in a pint glass , it pours dark brown with some tinges of ruby red in there when i hold it up to the light .  mouthfeel : seltzer drinkability : would be good but the mouthfeel sucks .

i 've been avoiding this beer , but my wife bought me a sixer so here we go ... poured into a sa perfect pint glass , and it looks pretty good with mounds of soft and pillowy head , and a golden/slightly hazy body .  overall , feels unbalanced , too much carbonation and a little too dull .
s - warm citrus and honey . grapefruit . t - grapefruit , seedless rye bread .  very watery . the mouthfeel was thin and watery as well .

a great aroma greets the nose , with soft cherry fruits and lots of toffee sweetness . a hint of floral & piny hops lingers in the background -- -very barleywine-line , which i enjoy . the flavor has the typical wee heavy malt profile boosted by a vinous barrel note . overall , a great special release from real ale , and probably one of their best beers i 've had to date .  i thought that the mouthfeel was kind of watered down ... it needed more `` oommff '' .

big fluffy two finger head that wafts the hop aromas well , tons of lace and excellent carbonation . color is a kind of murky dark amber . smells great . i love it , the quintessential california hop heaven . tons of grapefruit cascade , melon , guava , apples , cherries- all with a subtle fresh-cut woodsy pine backbone and soothing aroma of fresh mountain air .  the body is thin and watery ; one hardly notices the beer until it is gone .

it 's bronze , perfectly bright . it 's foamy , with a good head and strong laces . this beer shows that a beer made to please the most people can still be made with great quality .  not oxidized , just old and flattish . flattish and heavy , but slick as well , drinkability suffers from the lack of carbonation , hard to finish this bottle .

super sweet aroma with lots of yeast an plenty of sweet , dark fruit . some toffee aroma as well . sweet flavor , though there 's a little sharpness there as well that reminds me , again , a little of port .  the mouthfeel was then utterly unimpressive . overall , the drink looks good but the taste and feel are way too thin and watery .

smell is downright incredible , with lots of oily hops , citrus , and a complexity i ca n't describe .  this is a drinkable brew that definatly packs a punch , but it 's kind of one dimensional and thin .

wonderful aroma . warm and oaky , molasses . almost get a bbq sauce scent , very spicey like a worcester sauce . very interesting tastes in this one , unusual .  feel of almost flat carbonated water .

color was a little hard to see as it was fairly dark in the bar but appeared to be a very deep red , that while really dark was no opaque . slightly off-white head that left excellent lacing on the glass . not sure if it was the branded oversized wine glass or what but this was probably the second best looking beer i 've ever seen .  mouthfeel : way too big-bodied , way too carbonated , and way too uneven .

very very nice . very complex .  it does n't taste bad or good , kind of like water . it tastes like bubble water with a hint of sweetness . it 's for getting your swill on , and nothing else . too bad this is what most americans think of , when they think of australian beer .

earthy , weedy , hoppy , piney ! a real west coast ipa . love it ! not for the faint of heart hop haters , but awesome for hop lovers ! definitely interesting with tropical fruit hints in this one . mouthfeel : deliciously crisp and oily .  it has a below average mouthfeel - boring , too watery and macro-brewish .

aroma is great . rich dark chocolate . wow , what a disappointment after the aroma . mouthfeel is nice . a shame that a beer that smelled so good did n't live up to it .  the mouthfeel was thin and not terribly hoppy on the palate .
beautiful color , deep dark amber with beautiful smelling hops and some nice plumy undertones .  m - light and fizzy , thin bodied .

aroma is as good as it gets ; fruits , flowers , grass and everything in the yard makes this smell like a spring day ; impressive . medium to light bodied , its taste is interestingly hoppy with a lot of fruits , but the bitterness is not prominent , and it is well balanced by an underlying sweet maltiness which increases its drinkability a lot . for the sake of comparison , this was on a small tasting with alpha king and arrogant bastard ; the taste is better on the other two ; but drinkability and aroma are better here .  overall flavor is nice , but the body is way too carbonated .
quite a nice choice of fragrance hops . looks and smells phenomenal . taste , i just ca n't wrap my tongue around it .  thin watery feel .

d - the aroma is very nice , but the flavor just does n't live up to it ( an unfortunate trend i have noticed with dieu du ciel ) .  m : very thin and watery -- it has a consistency not far from kool-aid .

an immense hop punch to the nose . extremely fresh , bitter hops practically leap out of the glass . further in i get notes of orange and citrus , wrapped into a pleasing sweet malty undercurrent . superb nose . t. alas , after such a superlative smell , how could the taste hold up ? it 's a fantastic smelling , `` lite '' double ipa that is easy to put down .  mouthfeel : not much carbonation and the body is kind of watery .

very nice start of a semi-grainy and fully malted pilsner barley . delicious .  pours a clear golden copper hue which leaves a creamy fast vanishing two finger head and creamy lacing , the smell is herbal grassy hops and some honey malts thats it , the mouthfeel is light and watery and has tastes of honey malts , herbal grassy hops , fresh cut grass , pale malts and finished with a mix of herbal grassiness and toffee and overall i definately would not buy again and the bitterness is only very light avoid cheers .

o : for a beer that shares the great smells i associate with world-class english barleywines and doppelbocks , chimay grandrserve certainly disappoints me in other categories .  a little thin overall . mouthfeel : light-bodied and lacking . way too light and delicate of a beer to have an abv of 7.5 % .

a - scotch / almond color . beautiful head with great lace .  i picked up a carton of this pretty cheap the only downfall its in cans anyways it pours a golden amber see thru colour with nice carbonation that leaves a bubbly two finger head and sporadic lacing , the aroma is pretty macro with grains and a feint bubblegum aroma , it has a thin mouthfeel with a rather grainy taste and isnt nothing to write home about , its definately better than the macroswill that sells for much more and easier to down but its not a beer that i would drink if i wanted a nice beer with character .
great color , substantial head on pour . beautiful appearance .  mouthful was watery and a bit disappointing considering the color and head .
dunkel malts smell really nice , along with promising upfront bitters .  the body was light and very watery .
aroma is excellent ; spicy and piny .  m : bitter , almost no carbonation , light to medium body .
poured an opaque brown , as expected from a stout , with thick , pillowy tan head and excellent lacing .  m- thin highly carbonated .

a : pours a bright light amber with a large dense head that reduced into a delightfully thick dense foam dollop that floated on top of the beer . very active carbonation and fantastic lacing . head stayed forever with very impressive retention .  the mouthfeel is surprisingly flat .
beer pours black with a creamy brown head .  the mouthfeel was very thin for a stout .

smell is very appealing indeed : very fresh , clear orange , a bit banana , defenate floral hoppyness , and also some spicyness/clove .  mouthfeel on both is not much , just clear water with a bit of beer bubbles .
smell : good bold nose .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with almost no carbonation .

a - very good , very light golden orange - pretty decent head retention s - the most unique citrus nose of any dipa i 've ever encountered . upfront dried fruit basket and grapefruit blast to the senses . i can pick out the citra hops , that for sure . bitter dry , crisp finish . very , very good beer .  body is very thin , drinkability is ok , but there 's not very much to this beer .
sampled on 4-7-09 pours a clear deep red/brown , with a huge , foamy , clingy , off-white head that leaves crazy thick lacing .  mouthfeel is very thin and dry on the mouth .

a : what a gorgeous beer . a good pour yields a 1.5 finger head that fades quickly , and leaves a decent amount of lacing around the glass .  strong roasted malt character with a twang of hop bitterness , but really light and pale in the mouth with a watery body . no creamy mouthfeel , which was somewhat disappointing , but it was overall enjoyable . clean , pure and watery finish was n't quite what i had hoped for , as i was expecting something a little more milky/creamy/smooth .

aroma is of caramelized sugar and taffy ; it really does smell just like creme brulee .  hard to slam the beer that got my through college but ... . the twelfth tasted like the first . not really whatt i consider beer anymore but my in-law says it is more of a beer than budweiser ? could there be a reason you can by `` cooler-packs '' in multiples of 6 !

smell is very floral and fragrant , wow , fantastic . as it warms , you get more classic nw hops , pine and citrus .  not much depth at all m- lacking for a stout -- - no creaminess and it 's pretty thin overall d- wo n't seek this out again and i hope the rest of the breweries selections are better -- - really loses you in the mouthfeel

deep golden to light amber colored with a big head that settles into a nice thin layer of foam with moderate lacing as you get through the pint .  palate scraping astringency . the lack of carbonation particularly makes me wonder if i should have given this more time in the cellar to condition .

smell : this one is all about that distinctive fruity grape note ( thinks welsh 's grape jelly filled grape bubblegum ) in the beginning that then gets washed over by a classic cantillon urine and yeast wave . truly unique and highly enjoyable . taste : same as the nose but more integrated and not as grape dominant as the nose .  it tastes ok. kind of watered down . cant taste any malt or hops . it was too bubbly , seemed over-carbonated .

s - the nose is vibrant and bursting with citrus hops . a little bit of malt and grass , but this is mostly all hops . rather than getting the fresh , juicy hops of the nose , they are overshadowed by a bitterness that just seems out of place . lots of potential here , especially in the nose , but unfortunately it just has a bit too much bitterness .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and just way too thin and watery for an oatmeal stout .

curiously the nose offers more malt chocolate than expected , sweetens the already concentrated apricot , peach fruit scents as well as the floral dew , nicely piney , however , the grapefruit citrus lacks focus , nothing here to suggest bitter hops or aggressive bite .  m : medium body with lower medium carbonation . the mouthfeel is thin and watery .
the color is a deep , very pretty dark amber . this is a beautiful beer .  watery mouthfeel in terms of a stout .
s : pumpkin exactly as it would smell in fresh baking . a nice blend of cinnamon and spice present .  mouthfeel : medium body , watery texture , very low carbonation .
very pleasing . t - this beer smelled and looked so promising but the taste fell so short .  thin to medium mouthfeel with zero carbonation -- lifeless .

aroma is very fruit dominated , and not by any single one . peach , lemon , starfruit , lime , mango ... it 's an intoxicating tropical melange . some contrasting oak and fresh yogurt notes are there too , lending some harmonizing 'wild ' elements without getting too funky . flavor is moderately puckering , tart and verging on lemony sour . hop elements are present though indistinct in the mix , lending some possible leafy orange tea notes , and residual bitterness .  very thin mouthfeel , almost tasted flat , nothing special .

advertised as a belgian-style golden ale , from looks and smell alone it starts out as good as any of the actual belgian pale ales have tried . this is still a wonderful brew for the smell and balance alone , but as a belgian pale ale is pretty much my favorite style in the summer months i 'm probably more critical than most with this style .  good lacing down the glass s : coffee , sweet bready malts t : coffee , slight harsh maltiness also slight hint of chocolate m : light very thin bodied beer .

smell is a wonderful grapefruit burst .  the malt is lightly roasted , but mild with candisugar and syrupy cane sugar . add to that the thin body caused by a lot of sugar and it will add up to a c for me .

there 's something indescribably beautiful about a stout in a pint glass s - a wallop of chocolate and dark roasted coffee , some malt and alcohol notes , but the smell of fermented hot chocolate rules the day t - same as the smell .  it is entirely too thin for a stout .

aromas were the strong point for this drink . deep blackberry aromas mixed with bready , wheaty textures . although nice and light for a summery day , its strong blackberry taste ( albeit weaker in comparison to the blackberry smell ) did not really make this too refreshing or crisp .  thin watery and light in body o - did not even reach moderate expectations of being a porter and tasting barrel aged , just not very good in my opinion .

it 's black as the devil , not a hint of light going through this , and a thick brown head which lingers for awhile .  where this beer falls off is the mouthfeel ; it was like coca-cola without the carbonation . drinkability would be pretty good i guess , if you can get pas the average flavors and thin mouthfeel .

one of the most appealing scents i 've ever came across : rich malt with heavy caramel sweetness and pronounced chocolate qualities , strong esters of fully ripen figs and dried cherries ; aromas are perfectly mellowed and reminiscent of good port-wine . rather airy initially butt seems to be quickly loosing carbonation trapped within medium body and gets rather flat . overall , a good bsda with remarkable ripen fig & dried cherries aroma . ( 330 ml , into tulip )  mouthfeel is thin .
1,000 review a- awesome copper red appearance , great foam and nice head when poured from a bottle .  carbonation a bit high . fails on this point . d- easy going macro lager .

smells great , like a sweet belgian with lots of yeast and fruit and candy . taste was unbelievably tart and dry , especially after it smelled so sweet and dubbel-ish . lots of smokey coffeey and mineral water .  m - no staying power .

oured into my tulip ... rich active head rises fast and descends slowly ( very opposite of cycling ... ! ) ... sticky , frothy umber head laces thick and intricately , like some kind of rorschachian frieze ... color is a lovely rye whiskey burnt orange . i think the mouthfeel ( too much carbonation ) is what keeps this from being stellar .  feels thin and watery on the tongue with a low level of carbonation . bitterness is harsh and detracts from drinkability , mouthfeel is unsatisfying , and the flavors are n't interesting and complex enough to yield repeated enjoyment .

smell is exceptional , with a peach and plum smell up front with a bit of malt and hops to follow .  smell is not overwealming , but seems sweet with hints of yeast and hop . watery , yeasty , sweet ... more corn than i thought there would be ... taste relatively one-dimensional , unfortunately . fairly drinkable though ... inoffensive and cheap ...

s : bakers chocolate , ripe dark fruit , sour oak barrel , t : roasted chocolate malts with a strong acidity from the bourbon barrel . weird kind of taste .  body a bit lightweight , no real follow-through or length .

12oz bottle app : huge 2-3 finger , tan head . devilishly dark and opaque . makes you think it 's truly from a monster .  immediately upon entering the mouth it felt very watery and light for an 80/- .

smell was very appetizing , a rich sour cherry with a bit of roasted malt . taste was not nearly as robust , pretty much just a strong stout , a nice bit of burnt malt and coffee , coupled with a nice tartness from the cherry , but not nearly as rich and complex as the aroma had me expecting . mouthfeel was very rich and creamy , medium body .  the mouthfeel is medium-light bodied with a watery texture , and a little too much carbonation .

this one starts off with a huge citrus aroma . this is led by a strong grapefruit aroma and some fresh earthy hops .  taste is rich and sweet , slightly nutty , but this beer really sufferes from it 's thin and watery mouthfeel .

lightly spicy with some typical weizen-like notes of clove and yeast . this is quite a fruity smelling brew with alcohol esters being fairly pronounced . for a beer that smells quite deep and intense with character , the flavor falls a bit short and is not nearly as complex . as the brew warms up , some chocolate grain notes become evident .  mouthfeel/ drinkability : the carbonation isnt stinging and seems appropriate . the body of the beer seems far too thin .

s - heavy red wine , oak characteristics and obviously a brett brew t - follows the smell , close your eyes and you might be deceived that you are n't drinking a beer almost .  mouthfeel was pretty watery and went down quickly .

good retention and lacing ... the aroma is pretty nice , sweet candy wheat , honey , floral finish ... the taste really is disappointing , borderline bad . pretty disappointing for me after such a great aroma . i ca n't recommend this .  a : it 's still carbonated , that 's something at least . too fizzy .

very interesting . concrete and ginger . refreshing and smooth but a bit more bland than i expected based on the wonderful aroma . nicely mellow and subtle .  the sweetness died out in the taste , however , which was flat and slightly watered-down . a weird bitterness gave an unpleasant mouthfeel but still not difficult to drink .

aroma is big sweet , multitudes of dark fruit , caramel and quiet peat moss . quadish exceptional highly complex flavor , something for everyone . sweetness not equal to the expectation from the nose . the evolution of the taste is significant .  mouthfeel is watery . this style needs more body - the maltiness is there , but there is very little roasted character & not enough creaminess .

sweet and sugary , but delicious and unique . alcohol is absolutely brutal on this bitch as the heat slaps you in the face with the force of 10,000 fighting japanese midget minnow farmers .  m - thin , watery body , moderate carbonation , slight bitterness in the finish .
sm : this smells really good . nice , big , citrusy hops .  but i felt i owed it to myself to see if smaller carbonation meant bigger taste .

poured into a duvel tulip , between the brilliant dark amber body and the tight , creamy head it fills the glass . simply beautiful - my wife heard me say something to that effect , took a look and said `` wow ! that 's pretty !  fairly watery on the tongue . i was exited for this one after smelling , but the lack complexity on the palate coupled with the watery mouthfeel made this one a disappointment .

the nose is extremely complex -- clay soil , caramel , butter , farmland , and fresh aromatic hops are all in there , along with some more elusive intangibles that are conjuring up all sorts of images of rural europe for me . on the tongue , the caramel sings out with a spritzy edge , the hops keep it interesting , and the butter moves to the forefront , but what really does it for me is a slight sour twist towards the end -- reminiscent of those flemish ales that ive recently fallen in love with ( such as duchesse de bourgogne ) . this says to me , `` drink with food !  pretty nice . the body is as thin as water . that leads to a very drinkable beer , actually , since it goes down ... well , like water .

very enjoying ! t - malt is smooth , caramel sweetness is restrained and some dark fruits show up .  medium body , almost non existent carbonation , sweet sticky syrupy mouthfeel . i think the lack of carbonation ruins the mouthfeel and makes this taste and smell overly sweet .

smell : the aroma of the beer is full of hoppy promises . oily pine tar resins combine with a citrus and tropical fruits explosions of grapefruit , lemon , mango and pineapple bombard my nose .  mouthfeel is indeed excessively thin , leaving a slight tingle of carbonation , but otherwise going down like iced water .

the aroma is quite nice - banana , bubblegum , wheat , chocolate , coffee , and maybe some citric hops .  s. nonexistent . m. also nonexistent . just plain and unoffensive . light beer on amber side ? nothing to brag about but goes down like water . above average in it 's class .
copper color with two fingers of creamy offwhite head that really stands up . leaves nice lacing .  it 's highly carbonated , and extremely astringent .

while really good , not as good as aroma . overall : really good . would have liked the flavor to measure up to the aroma but you still ca n't go wrong with this one .  m : taste was below average for me , but the mouthfeel is even worse . super thin . light carbonation and no body make this almost watery .

another great beer from denmark , this little country is no slouch in craft beer world.poured into an imperial nonic a near jet black except from some chocolate brown highlights when held to the light , a large blooming lighter mocha colored head atop.to me the aromas couldnt get any better , a fantastic display of chocolate and resiny hop , maybe the best aroma of any stout i have come across , if you like the hops no matter the style its spot on.the mouthfeel is a little sharp and not as full on as i would have liked.bitter chocolate , dark fruit , and a healthy dose of resiny hop make for a well rounded flavor profile , if that mouthfeel was just a little more smooth ! a really good beer that is close to being great , love the hop play going on .  but the overall mouthfeel is unbalanced , with simply too much fizz against a generally thin texture .

it 's a hazy orange-red-brown with a 2 finger head of foam . a great looking brew .  m - kind of flat on the palate with very little carbonation . hop profile caught me off guard and the mouthfeel is pretty weak .

the smell was magnificent , and like i said i wish it had been in a snifter to catch more of these floral and citrusy aromas . outstanding .  the mouthfeel is very thin and highly carbonated , very reminiscent of your typical macro lager .

s : great smell , fruity although i can not place exactly what fruit .  i 'm going to have to go against the gimmick and with the style here , the mouthfeel just is n't there . i 'm not impressed at all , it 's like a half flat beer that you 've left on your desk whilst reviewing a beer and forgotten about it only to come back to it 30 mins later . the shining point of this beer is it 's drinkability .
a - a leathery brown color with a one finger offwhite head . great lacing that clings to the glass the whole way down .  very light in body with a slick mouthfeel at first that becomes almost slimy .

the smell is surprising sweet with peaches and apricots on top of the big citrus hop base . this is an interesting dipa though i wish the flavor measured up to the unique aroma . still worth trying .  mouthfeel was quite thin and highly over carbonated .
on-tap at the clark street ale house . awesome yeast funk and they really nailed the look .  very thin , and watery . lower carbonation .
aroma is fantastic , reminiscent of triple sec and cognac . an intriguing failure of a beer .  the body is a bit thin and feels too bubbly .

s : the aroma is fantastic . natural lemon scent and orange zest , mostly lemon .  carbonation is minimal , almost flat . again understanding its aged but this beer is pretty sweet and without some degree of carbonation to clear out the palette at the end it becomes cloying .
sweet marshmallow nose . banana/clove presence is notable . massive . sweet with spice and alcohol warming .  m : thin body and light carbonation .

smells of rich dark roast , light coffee , fruity yeast and light alcohol . when cold , all i could taste were roasted flavors , a sharp carbonation , and a woody , slightly smokey hop flavor , maybe chinook .  water with a little spice and alcohol . the smell is the best part with mainly cinnamon . the taste is one dimensional cinnamon with a super light water taste on the back . no malt or pumpkin to be found . not a good beer nor a good pumpkin ale but if someone handed me one i would have no problem finishing it . also you could down 3 or 4 no problem and being $ 6 a 6 pack you ca n't beat that .

very strong baking chocolate smell - the kind that smells delicious but is really dry and ends up too bitter when you taste it . what a deceptive beer - first you notice it because it is a ris in a can , then it looks and smells great , and then it just lets down big time in the taste .  head falls into the liquid way too quickly and seems to look more like bubble bath suds that the typical beautiful belgian head . certainly is the high point of the beer . alcohol comes a little too strong on the palate and seems to take over the other flavors . flat on the tonque . outrageously overpriced and overrated .

aroma is wonderful . incredibly intense malt tones and a nice sweetness detected .  for a russian imperial this is even for 9.7 incredibly weak and watery it 's the first thing i notice . the mouthfeel on this is not good , it 's even weaker than most american stouts i 've had .
an ending swirl murks up the brew nicely . massive thick and rich eggshell ice-cream topping floating on top .  a bit too sticky on the mouthfeel .
smell is pure hops , limes , lemons ... .lemon marange pie ! great brew . memorable !  mouthfeel : absolutely no carbonation .

very interesting beer . you can smell the hints of black & blue berries which is quite nice . it 's got a sharp taste of fruit , it reminds me almost of a fruity wine .  thin , watery , overcarbonated .

the smell is extremely interesting , behind the hops it just reeks of fresh peach to me . i kept sniffing the beer throughout my time with it , just because it was so much fun to get that strong of a peach smell from a beer .  mouthfeel is very light and watery and it has a similar taste as many other bmc beers , however it does have some light maltiness to it that most macro lagers lack .

nutty aroma with lots of caramel , hay and oats seem to scream out at me .  not much at all going on except for some sweetness and a very slight bitterness that gives way to a watery finish . not the worst macro lager by any means .
very double ipa , and enjoyable . taste is more subtle than i was expecting , bitter hops all the way through .  mouthfeel : very carbonated with a thin , almost watery feeling .

bright grapefruit and citrus with a very sweet candy malt aroma . candy coated hops ... yum !  the carbonation seems artificial , which really brings down the quality of this lager to something like a henry weinhards ( goes for a good taste , but it all seems somewhat fake ) . without the strong carbonation this would have been a common sight in my fridge , but as it is sieraa nevada summerfest will only make occassional appearences .

the smell is exceptional . tons of different scents .  mouthfeel : medium-heavy body . makes my mouth feel like sandpaper after a taste . after reading other reviews , and letting the beer warm a bit , i & # 8217 ; m starting to appreciate it more , but i & # 8217 ; m thinking i & # 8217 ; m robbing the cradle a bit with this sample .

dark fruits and double fudge with a wisp of grass ... .nice ; profile is a bit of a letdown from the aroma . a very good approximation of a london stout although a tad thin for an oatmeal stout , it is very decent .  sweet crackery finish , m - thin with very low carbonation .

on to the beer : little is wrong with the appearance . the head is thick and sports plenty of its original self , peach colored body has the `` glowing '' illusion at some spots . it 's just one bitter mess with some soap and soft waves of phenols ( more specifically , pllastic ) that do n't belong and the beer becomes even more unpleasant .  mouthfeel is thin .

body is somewhat lighter expected while pouring , but looks black in the glass s : oak and coffee , come sweet roasted malt . t : slight sweetness .  the presence of tannin explains how , while quite watery , satan red is also quite drying .
the smell is amazing , dense spectrum of aromas floating out of my glass .  m : i was disappointed in the mouth feel . the light mouth feel really hurt for me .
s : bold and healthy hop aroma . perfect ipa smell . t : dry and hoppy .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and watery .

served in a wheat beer glass . beer is yellow and hazy , forms a big white head of small and medium bubbles that leaves some lacing on the glass . looks good .  it is a bit bland , the mouthfeel is way too watery .

s- some nice fresh fruit hits the nose immediately in the way of some fresh apple and the caramel moves in next .  color very pale green or lemon odor , which suggests more concentrated lemon juice only freshly cut lemon slices , but preserving a small mouth , perhaps a bit too much . the lager that is the basis must be extremely low in taste because the body is still very watery , just a few hints of lemon , no sugar but not bitter unfortunately .

a nice white head , great retention and lacing ... the aroma is fantastic , so fresh , just plucked pine needles with pineapples and an assortment of tropical fruits ... taste is equally great , bitting pine and alcohol of a dipa , but muted and so drinkable .  light body , short finish , little texture , too much carbonation at the front .
appearance : pours a clear orange color with a big 3 '' head that lasts quite a while .  mouthfeel : a bit on the fizzy side - really scrubs the tongue .

under all of this , i can still smell some gumball and barnyard odors . an amazing smell and likely a very unique one . t - more grapefruit pith and that same pine , but i still ca n't figure it out .  limp bodied and watery , with no real aftertaste .

two brothers heavy handed ipa : terrific aroma , very full and noticeable from several feet away . some heavy malt syrup aromas coupled with flowery hops make the aroma very appetizing . slick mouth feel .  `` simple '' is the best word i can use to describe the taste , but it does deliver with scorched malts with a touch of lactose . my biggest complaint with this beer is the mouthfeel- it 's way too watery .

smell is awesome -- the smoked pork hits you first , followed by hints of raw sugar , honey , apples or pears , and black licorice . first few sips have an element of 'burnt'-ness to them , but once you get used to it , it 's quite pleasant . there 's almost a saltiness to it , with some background flavours of coffee , chocolate , and strong malts .  mouthfeel : medium to light treading dangerously close to watery .

source/serving : 650ml bottle dated 2/19/2010 ( 6 months old ) smell : delicate and complex , but not dynamic . very nice overall .  it drinks as a light beer ; it is very thin and weak , much unlike guinness .
very unique . i could tell from smelling it that it was going to be sour , but had no idea the extent of sourness .  m : bubbly and very thin .

s - very pronounced chocolate aromas , backed by roasted malts , some earthy , pine hops and a touch of coffee as it warms t - follows the nose , with the hop character very subtle , and the coffee barely making a presence as it warms .  body is way too thick , sweet , and syrupy .
smell - pretty nice smelling . lots of blueberries as well as some malt .  the mouthfeel was flat leaving a watery feel in the mouth .

by far the best smelling pumpkin beer i 've had , and one of the best i 've had , period , in a long time . t- not quite as good as the smell , but still pretty good . cinnamon , nutmeg , pumpkin , orange creamsickle , and alcohol .  i do n't taste any pecan ... m : thin . not to impressive in this dept o : do i love it ?
the pour is beautiful . intense rich brown/black , with a two finger dark brown head .  mouthfeel was thin like water , very little body .

s - roasted coffee , dark berries ( raspberry ) ripe fruit , dark chocolate , little bit of booze ( bourbon ? i 'm all for interesting beers , which this very much is , but i have had straight bourbon that goes down more easily .  it tasted mostly like water with a very light toffee/sweet taste in the back of the tongue . that 's it . it was very drinkable in the same way water is drinkable . when a brewer wants you to chill his beer , there must be a issue with the flavor at cellar temps . i ca n't believe some people consider this to be the flagship for the style .

very vibrant fruity/floral aroma with a hint of peat , grain and sweet caramel malt . all these blend perfectly together to make a fantastic aroma . certainly the best aspect of this beer . it tastes very much like the aroma - fruity berry , white grape flavors with a little herbal spiciness . the flavors are n't as rich as the aroma would suggest . a really nice beer overall . i genuinely enjoyed it , but i only with the flavors were richer .  the body is light and really lacking .

the smell is phenomenal , with loads of tropical fruits , pineapple , passion fruits , grape , mango and green apples . this boquet is really amarillo , and everything amarillo can be . any possible malt-notes in the nose is totally subdued by this awesome onslaught of amarillo !  mf : it 's medium-bodied at best despite the label 's claims of `` full bodied . '' speaking of which , it has a soda watery type carbonation , not at all the `` luxuriously smooth '' of the label . i have to say that they could get the mouthfeel under control ( i 'd imagine this is less of an issue on tap ) , it would be hands-down my favorite irish stout .
it has a pleasantly pungent , complex smell . all sorts of flower and herbal along with some mint .  the mouhfeel is weak , watery , thin .

appearance : copper-brown color with a nice 1/2 '' head ; looks great when your pour it smell : not much here , surprisingly ; i sense a little bit of hops and raisins taste : similar ; hops and a raisin sweetness to balance it ; the taste isnt as hoppy as regular arrogant mouthfeel : nice , thick , full-bodied drinability : goes down ok ; you ca n't chug it , but then again you would n't want to this is n't quite as good as regular arrogant , but i 'd like to give this oaked another shot  the mouthfeel is confusing as it feels too thin for the amount of sweetness on the taste buds .
aroma : very sweet and pleasant smelling . a little fruity with banana 's the predominant smell ( in terms of its fruitiness ) .  mouthfeel is overyly fizzy and thin .

it 's supposedly a witbier heavily flavored with raspberries -- and just a touch of honey . the berry aroma is all-consuming . 8 inches from my nose , it 's attacking my nostrils like a schoolbully . if i 'm picking raspberry seeds out of my teeth with new glarus rapsberry tart or lindemans framboise , i 'm picking the raspberry jolly rancher wrapper out of my teeth with this one . intensely fruity .  it does bring vanilla to mind . the sweetness almost removes it from the style of beer . far to thin for a brown ale .
on-tap at bruery provisions a : the pour is just about black with a finger of dark brown head that displays impressive retention .  m=fairly thin , a little medium . watery .

definite lactose on the nose although emphasis is placed much more firmly upon the strong roasted and baker 's chocolate qualities of the beer . once again , lactose shows itself with a vaguely milky start and a kiss of sugar at the finish ( along with bitter chocolate ) .  good for a lager , but way too much carbonation really throwing this beer off .

beautiful box package , dated 2004 , opens to reveal a classy looking bottle , numbered 85352 . this pours into a tukip a dark amber/light brown , with a thin head .  the worst part for me was definitely the mouthfeel , which was waaaay too thin .
smell is quite tart smelling , bit of sweetness , can easily make out the raspberry aroma .  mouthfeel : lacking . too light for the style .
very nice . t : sugar sweet ( touch of brown sugar ) along with some malt sweetness .  mouthfeel is weak and watery .
insanely sticky , a spectacular pour .  m/d : a very harsh crispness in the mouth and to much carbonation for my tastes .
very aromatic . t - chewy malts with the same fruity ester present in the nose .  thin on the mouthfeel and the carbonation is way too high on this one making the thinnes hard to handle .

aroma is impressive for the style with some sweet citrus in the form of oranges and light grassy notes . i definitely think it gives the beer , especially the aroma , a unique character . better than i was expecting .  mf : too thin and slippery !

i love nitrous beers - they have this amazing waterfall effect as the head settles . the beer 's head was a nice creamy tan color and featured some light coffee/mocha scents . appearance - 5.0/5.0 - love the waterfall effect of the nitrous , tan creamy head - very full taste - 4.5/5.0 - silky smooth - coffee and light chocolate taste feel - 4.0/5.0 - no aftertaste , extremely smooth in mouth smell - 4.0/5.0 - very light with coffee/mocha accents drinkability - 4.5/5.0 - way better than a guiness - very tasty , smooth - i will be repeating this beer .  m = thin . thats it .

1 pint 6 oz tall dark brown bottle with a racer checkered flag on the label with red and yellow print , pewter cap . great retention and clumpy lace .  very complex and interesting m : disappointing ! very thin for a barley wine .
aroma is of hops , sugar and vanilla . this beer is mostly sweet and overly oaky with an almost cloying finish that has very little hop bitterness .  mouthfeel is thin and weak .
the spiciness attacks your olefactory senses with a vengence . aroma reminds me of some winter warmers i 've had .  mouthfeel feels thin and weak ; this is my only real complaint with this beer .
overall very nice . taste : a little sour up front , but quickly fades to a lingering `` bitterness '' - not of the hop variety .  mouthfeel was just plain flat , no pep to it at all .

aroma is dark , malty , and seductive . roasty sweet malts , golden raisins , dried fruit , scorched caramel , and bittersweet dry cocoa are rounded out by musty yeast notes similar to damp concrete .  m : water thin , light side of champagne-like carbonation .

appearance the ale is a beautiful , almost perfect shiny copper in color with a wonderful golden head that showed good retention . it looks damn near perfect !  no attempt whatsoever to hide the alcohol and the addition of the heavy acidic espresso taste and a watery mouthfeel make this hard to down .
a nearly perfect appearance for a pilsener , with a completely transparent orange-yellow body with a thick white head .  overall feel was very thin , not impressive and not terribly satisfying .

a-dark brown/black s-nice blend of cocoa and leafy hops..really impresses on the nose . t-hops are a little more forward on the taste ... .interesting hop dimensions ... some bright citrus ... .and some grungy pine and weed like notes ... roasted malts ... .also some darker cocoa ... m-rich ... fuller bodied ... .feels bigger than a regular black ipa ... body fits ... o-top notch effort .  the mouthfeel is light and watery , not much substance . a very watered down dunkel , i would skip this in the future .
amazing smell -- coffee and chocolate dominate the aromas with some caramel in the background .  mouthfeel is thin and watery .

s- awesome char smell with chocolate and roasted coffee , and supported by a rich dark fruit sweetness . hoppy bitterness is a fantastic undertone . m- nice smooth mouthfeel .  the finish is lightly sweet rather than crisp , and the mouthfeel , which started out thin , ends on a watery , undercarbonated note . zywiec is an average epl , making it a below average beer in general .

nose is big sweet plums , ripe pears and sweet cooked peaches with light spice - big , full , rich and assertive with big candi sugar tones . flavors are very complex and layered . front palate is sweet spiced cola and compote cooked fruit that goes to a dull bitter mid palate and finish .  2.0 m : light body . way too light for the style . also , too much carbonation .

smell is very sugary with a fruit and spice scent of apple butter . apple , cinnamon , clove , raisin , grape , figs , black pepper and sweet prunes are all in here . taste is drier than expected sweet but not very . good spice flavor that builds as you sip . the flavor just is n't anywhere as complex as the smell . mouthfeel is good nice drinkable belgian here that is worth a try , only problem is that there are lots better around .  it is far too light and leaves the tongue and mouth with a stinging feeling and terrible astringency ... d- one redeeming quality of this is that it seems like a session beer but boasts a 9 % alcohol level .

it looks similar to a darker version of a rose champagne . the nose has cherries and some pear .  the beer was entirely too light bodied for a stout , this really was one of the most disappointing elements of the beer .

when i went to smell the aromas , i was very impressed with the assumed banana and clove . they were very prominent and defined ... i couldnt wait to taste ( damn it has a strong aroma that belies its appearance .  m- this is precisely the opposite mouthfeel that i want . it feels like it wants to be sweet and sticky , but it really just falls watery on the tongue .

intresting , very intens smell , very nice hop aroma , tons of hops , citrus flavour , very similar to pliny the elder , i want to taste this one t : similar to the nose but not that strong , wheat , tons of hops , citrus , sweet malts , nice slightly bitter finish , this could be the little brother of pliny the elder , but this is softer , not so strong , m : very smooth , very well balanced , d : very drinkable , alcohol is well hidden , i could drink this all day long , yammy , well done struise .  very thin feel , little oily .

pours with a fluffy , light tan head that sticks over a deep , hazy , amber brown body . great lace .  the first thing i thought when i tasted it was , `` wow that is watery . i think they basically made it too `` light . comparing this to their original , it unfortunately seems to fall into the `` watered-down flavor '' category . if that is what you are looking for , then here 's your beer , otherwise i would stick to the usual recommendation to avoid the light beers . then again it really was n't that bad considering it was so cheap at the time .
smells sweet and inviting . very light caramel malt in the nose .  mouthfeel was poor .

light tan head for a second , poor retention and lacing ... the aroma is sweet with lots of nice sweet bourbon on the front . its a really nice smooth bourbon , makes you really want to drink it ... the taste really lets me down sadly .  this beer reminds me greatly of sol , corona , and modelo . i would n't be surprised if all mexican beer came from the same place ... dirty t-shirts squeezed out into a horse trough and then 'pasteurized ' by the horse before making its way into the bottle , but hey what do i know about cervezas .

s - smells very inviting ! full of citrusy hop aromas ( pineapple , grapefruit , and orange ) and some pine scents as well . t - taste is different than expected . d - moderately drinkable - it would be nice if the malt flavors competed a little more with the hops to help balance it a little .  this is very much like corona . not as good as miller light .

overall the aroma is very nice . first sip , small tingly carbonation and average body . flavor is much less complex and rich than the nose advertised. , some toffee and fruit followed by a very clean yet somewhat empty finish .  very carbonated ... .too much .
really fantastic nose , the raspberries shine through . good interesting beer that is cool to try to reach both the girls and the boys beer drinkers or not .  3.0 m thin .

nose : an absolutely great floral hop aroma consumes the nose . very nice ! it has a fantastic aroma , a great hop bite but a low ibu and low abv . one word : impressive .  a thin mouthfeel . extremely drinkable . but that 's all i can really say good about it , the taste is n't great , and the mouthfeel is too thin .

aroma is excellent . it 's full of fresh hops , citrus and pine .  mouthfeel is where the beer suffers . it just feels wrong . a very tasty and aromatic beer , and if you can get past or prefer the super-low carbonation level .
s-this beer has a nice sweet flower aroma with hints of roses and apricots .  m : really unappealing .

the mystery beer in my joe 's garage variety pack , poured a deep brown with dark near crimson hue when held up to the light with a large 2 finger mocha colored head.perfect 5 for me aroma wise its american big on the fruity , piney hop mixed with chocolate and earth just fantastic love the big hop profile.the same goes for the flavors big piney drier hop profile intertwined with bitter chocolate with a earthy raw nut lingering finish.a little prickly on the mouth but nothing to take away from the great flavors of the beer , damn i wish there more porters like this it is the most hoppedup version i think i have had to date .  d-a little rough on the palate with the huge carbonation and extremely grainy feel .
very nice . taste : mmm .. chocolate and coffee with quite a few roasted flavors .  mouthfeel is thin , macro thin .
