the aroma of this beer was the highlight for me : banana , apple , belgian yeastiness , other fruits ... really great . golden yellow in color with a small ring of head at the top after it settles . alcohol comes through very nicely . sweet aftertaste is enjoyable .  mouthfeel is very thin .

aroma is lots of banana and lemon , very nice and assertive .  here we go : a - opaque reddish-brown , small head with minimal lacing s - malts , hint of hops , not much else t - much like the aroma , mildly sweet malts , faint hop bitterness with weak coffee m - thin , a bit too thin for a brown ale d - no problem putting down a few if i chose to , but i do n't think i would unless it was my only alternative to bmc lagers .
this was hard to decide on , the smell was really intriguing , but taste more mediocre .  the second sip shows that this beer is just really thin and more watered down .

the aroma is both unique and memorable , with a cornucopia of fruitiness : pineapple , mango , strawberry , and starfruit . the hops taste grassy and resinous , but the highlight is the tropical fruits derived from the yeast ... excellent stuff , even though it 's not the most cohesive-tasting flavor profile . a crafty anniversary beer..complex , tasty , and original . kudos , real ale .  mouth : enters the mouth with very light carbonation that flattens as it goes back . overall , it 's not a bad brew , it 's got a great hop flavor but not enough depth or balance , and the weak mouthfeel ruins the experience .
s- great pumpkin smell up front with a nutmeg spice on the back end . smells like a fresh baked pumpkin pie at thanksgiving .  way too carbonated here , which hurts the mouthfeel quite a bit .

a - pitch black with a carbonated type head that fades quickly s - fruity , chocolatey , roasty , and malty t - huge dried fruit on the forefront followed by massive chocolate and roasty accompaniment . different then most ris , but a pretty good example .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . it took much diligence to see my way to the end of this beer , and , were it not for the runaway carbonation , it could 've been far better . one to revisit , provided they clear up the carbonation issue .

smell- it does smell very good . i will give it that much . loads of dark and milk chocolate . one of the more chocolate scents i have set my nose upon in a beer .  taste is malty to start , but very thin . the body leaves one wanting more . dry finish with an almost soda-like feel . despite the lack of body , this beer is rather drinkable .
huge pepper aroma and a very pronounced and balanced flavor . thanks to the lovely folks at elysian fields today , very gracious hosts .  mouthfeel : way too carbonated .

s : absolutely heavenly . fresh herbal hops , minty even , along with grassy and citric hops as well . m : full , with an excellent long finish , but not overbearing . it 's wonderful . the smell will hook you and the taste will not disappoint . the brilliant combination of hops had me wishing it would never end , and even at a relatively high abv , it remains highly drinkable .  m - too light , watery , bleh .

aroma is of banana , the spiciness of clove , and actually some pineapple . taste is not as good as the smell . it 's a bit earthy , and far less of a phenolic presence than most hefeweizens i 've had .  the mouthfeel is way thin , but drinkability is ok .

it has a very sweet aroma to it and that makes it all the more appealing . smell is more prevalent the more it warms up .  the mouthfeel is disappointing with absolutely no carbonation and mild flavors lingering around . overall , i could have possibly gotten a flat beer but this beer had potential ( when carbonated ) but it didnt come through in my bottle .
very good . taste : like the smell , there 's lots of clove and sweet malt .  the first thing i notice with this beer is the watery mouthfeel . the mouthfeel is terrible .

s : belgian yeasts , lemons , a touch of honey at the end , dust , peppers , banana and clove . t : taste does not match the smells .  maybe a little dusty , but i probably dislike the low carbonation & tackiness more . my tongue feels like i just drank a pot of black tea .

absolutely amazing grapefruit , lemon , and orange aroma . also has a touch of sweet toffee and vanilla . this was a beautiful hazy golden pour , with typical cask frothy head . very well balanced flavor , then a wonderful dry bitter finish . this is an amazing brew , and the cask only adds to it .  very little mouthfeel , this beer is meant to be drank ice cold as implied with the cold indicator on the can unlike most beers that i drink .

very addicting aromas . thick chocolatey dark fudge , coffee accents , with heaps of dark fruits thrown in and integrated almost perfectly . sweet malty aromas lay behind the sheen of fruit and lend towards caramel and vanilla . this is a very dry stout that lingers for a long time that i find slightly displeasing . damn good stout worth drinking if for only the smell .  smells and tastes bland and grain like . almost stale . it is a good beer to party with if all your doin is playin beer pong or circle .

wonderful aromas of fresh pumpkin pie ! i could really smell the spices of nutmeg and cinnamon , plus the fresh smell of carved pumpkin to round out the spice . t- pretty much tasted like it smelled but not as pronounced . it 's easy drinking , great autumn flavors and smells ... .a real pleasure to drink !  very sweet flavour , largely the same elements as in the aroma , but far too sugary and overwhelmingly sweet for me .

nose is certainly affected with the trademark jolly pumpkin barrel aroma/flavor.. light vanilla wood without imparting too much diacetyl . finally , i 've found the beer this balances with perfectly.. the creamy whipped dreaminess of the barrel versus the stark , bright , ripe fruits of an american dubbel.. this exudes a mindblowing aroma . superb . blueberry ice cream scent with a blondie underneath . delectable . taste does n't disappoint either . jolly pumpkin seems to be a real one trick pony , but this is one of the times when that pony executes its trick perfectly .  the body is kind of thin , and there 's too much carbonation , which brings the drinkability down a fair bit .
pours a fluffy/clingy finger and a half light tan head over a crystal clear dark rust brownish liquid .  mouthfeel is very , very light -- it goes down like nothing at all .

a- a perfect golden look in the glass . looks great .  mouthfeel : this is where the beer went south for me . the carbonation was almost non-existent , which was in stark contrast to the initial appearance .
bottle : poured a deep opaque brown color ale with a huge dirty white color foamy head with good retention and some lacing .  the mouthfeel is poor . it seems to lack enough carbonation .
s - good smell , lots going on .  m - light bodied , very thin feeling , and very little carbonation o - not too impressed with this beer .

some alcohol noted as well but very pleasant on the nose . t - the taste starts sweet , fruity and malty reminding me a lot of a traditional abbey abt .  t- vanilla/cream soda , one-dimensional caramel malt . very vanilla . m- mouth is unrefined and rough in the way i would expect from good ol bmc . sweetness lingers in an unpleasant and sticky way .

drank on-tap at deep ellum , allston , ma poured a deep brown/black with a two-finger , bubbly , cocoa-colored head that slowly faded to a thick ring of lace . large , irregular-shaped patches of lacing coated the glass .  i will admit that i did not like the mouthfeel very much . too bubbly .

the aroma is amazing . major chocolate aroma with a dose of roasted malts , vanilla , toffee and cocoa . sort of a letdown on the taste .  the smell reminds me of anchor liberty ale , only slightly less pungent . watery body , with some caramel notes . theres a citrus hop flavor in there too , but there is also a tannic `` spent hops '' flavor which is not so good . it lacks some bitterness too .
smell is superior . a robust but citrusy smell that you get a hint of straight out of the bottle .  it 's low in carbonation and a little thin and watery , which is a real shame .

the aroma is out of this world . a very , very bready smell . heavy yeast and a cake-like aroma . immense . the taste is very strong carrot cake . pumpkin spice and brown sugar . hits the back of the tongue with authority . rich and bready , like a sugary cake .  m : thin and watery , very little carbonation , too thin to be cloying , but i 'd rather this beer be full bodied .
pleasant overall unlike some other fruit beers .  perhaps age will remedy.. m : explosive mouthfeel upon drinking , but the body is very light , with the alcohol evident .
golding hops , great hoppy aroma . some barley initially .  mouthfeel was stingy and watery .

s : big yeast smell right up front . the yeast and hops work really well together . excellent nose . t : wow . d : very nice beer . still excellent beer all around .  the taste was simple and good , but part of me thinks it was overshadowed by the dominant carbonation .

color is a soft , medium brown , almost clear . tall , light tan head , which falls slowly and unevenly , creating an attractive effect .  mouthfeel - this is where this one lets me down . feels very thin for a porter , very watery .

nose was erupting from the pour with plenty of darker malts , some dark wheats , a bit of a roasty and toasty aroma , a very slight chocolate , some dark fruits with a bit of fig , hint of booze , some toffee , and lots of dark wheat aromas . taste starts with darker wheats and malts again , a slight caramelized wheat flavor , some brown sugar and molasses , plenty of toffee , darker wheat flavors , a bit of a cola like syrup flavor but just a hint , some darker malts , roasted malts and some toasted malts , slight chocolate again , more fruits , fig and touch of a nutty flavor , hint of coffee , fairly complex , and even a hint of warming booze , that comes out a bit more on the finish but never heavy , very slightly sticky and hint of sweetness but dries slightly .  the taste is cloyingly sweet , viscous , the aromas transfer , and turn very bready on the finish , the middle has cherries candies , almost medicinal the mouth feel is vaguely reminiscent of cough syrup , but watered down . there is no bitterness and even less carbonation .

s - sweet malt , candy , prune , marmalade t - sweet malt that very quickly becomes medicinal ( cough syrup ) and spicy m - low carbonation and syrupy with a neutral finish d - enjoyable flavors , but the medicinal taste is overbearing  m : dammit , i hate porters like this . light , watery body , slightly oily , and slick on the palate . this would have been so much better with more body to it .
this beer pours a cloudy , browning apricot with a massive 4 inch , creamy head that leaves soap like lacing down the entirety of the glass .  medium body . nearly flat .

s : smell is awesome . so complex for a stout which are normally one dimensional . coffee and dark unsweetened cocoa powder , whiskey/bourbon and even some woody notes that are muted .  mouthfeel is lacking as was expected . all in all this one is a step above the macro light brews .

i actually smell this beer about 2 feet away when opening . very citrusy and piney , a small amount of orange juice sweetness is present . a very nice extreme beer , i may be afraid to try fresh .  i feel like i have now experienced the true port/lost abbey experience , this is the first one i 've had that is flat ... a : pours dark brown with caramel highlights , zero head even after stiff pour , some clarity s : nose is predominantly oak and vanilla , some char quality in there , stout base takes a back seat t : vanilla and bourbon again dominate , some ashy character in there along with light notes of leather and tobacco , a bit of of boozieness on the finish mf : low carbonation is an understatement , medium body o : good flavors here , the lack of carbonation takes away from the quality a bit , for the premium price tag , i would expect carbonation .

smells amazing . the pine and citra form a wave of hoppy goodness .  taste : decidedly like its nose , only more so ; large notes of bittersweet chocolate and espresso rule the roost , here ; not nearly as sweet as you might imagine ; total lack of carbonation left the impression of a somewhat light , thin mouthfeel .

awesome bouquet ; fruitiness and candy malts . even so a pretty good drop .  the herbal hops will become medicinal with traces of alluminum and will become a bit less appealing as it goes from a zippy feel to rather stagnent . a flat and bitter hop flavor is the finish .

pitch black beer with creamy tan head , good retention and plenty of lacing .  high carbonation and a continental hop aroma mixed with corn . light , watery body with a vegtable-grainy taste . dry , crisp finish . strictly unsatisfying .

i 'm a huge fan of strong , hoppy pilsners , and this is just great . tons of fresh grassy floral hops , a touch of pale malt . definitely enjoyable , regardless .  mouthfeel is thin , almost no carbonation .

was picked up by my bro-in-law and quickly swept away to milly 's tavern to begin our pre-race inebriation . the pumpkin ale was a solid beer , and had a wonderful nose and flavor . the color was clear golden and the glass came lined with sugar and spice !  the mouthfeel is watery with medium carbonation .

huge smell of prunes , chocolate , a hint of molasses and some licorice . has that belgian `` funk '' as i call it . i do n't care , smells great ! deep rich chocolate and molasses covered prunes . this is a brew that has been blessed by the gods . there are hints of mint and licorice along side with a hint of anise and some bitter chocolate . a+ taste ! omg this beer makes me want to guzzle , but i think twice and enjoy each and every sip .  very , very foamy in the mouth .
smell : malty with some pie like characteristics and caramel . very bready on the nose making it quite appetizing .  it is very thin like any us macro , making it very drinkable like water .

the brett funk really comes through . i wanted to like this beer after smelling it , but it just has an off bitterness and some tannins that make it less than desirable .  mouthfeel : bad , fizzy foamy body , hot finish drinkability : meh

pours a cloudy , very dark golden orange/chestnut mahogany brown color with dark golden orange hues when held to a light source and a two finger frothy , pillowy yellowish beige head . excellent retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap . sporadic chunks of soapy lacing left behind .  mouthfeel is very thin and weak .
really interesting .  the carbonation sort of ruins the mouthfeel from the can and hides the taste .

spicy and compliments the smell . m - thin and smooth , carbonation does not come in to play which may be from the age . d - this beer is very drinkable .  mouthfeel was light in body and watery in texture with a flat carbonation .

the smell has that fruity scent that just says dfh in my mind , must be the local weather . lots of subtle scents here and i am sure i am not picking them all out .  the mouthfeel is this beer 's weakest point . also , it feels a bit heavy on the palate and is almost syrupy .

a very attractive beer . powerful aroma . moist , sweet raisins at the forefront , with bitter chocolate , roasted malt , soy sauce and sweet sherry behind .  mouthfeel is very thin and overly carbonated .

the aroma is absolutely wonderful . absolutely huge brett notes , pungent and funky with a very clear tartness .  mouthfeel : thin and watery ( or slim-bodied , which sounds more positive ) , medium-low carbonation ( too low for the style ) .

the beer is certainly lighter than i expected with an almost straw color . the nose on this brew is phenomenal ! i 'm immediately transported to magical grapefruit land as the beer screams citrus into my nostrils . there is a piney base note to this smell to that compliments the soaring citrus very well . not on hops of course , as the grapefruity citrus notes yielded to a piney bite on the finish , but rather the malt character . while still a world class ipa , i felt that the backbone of this brew just was n't quite as strong as i would have liked and the huge hop profile was almost overwhelming .  mouthfeel this one was clumsy and , worst of all , lacked the fluffy character of a good hefe weizen .
smell - coffee , roasted malt , dark chocolate , and a touch of bitter , maybe hops .  on top of that , the beer tasted a bit flat and felt thin .

the first thing that hit me and my friend was the fantastic smell -- heavy with alcohol and woody wine overtones .  the taste is similar , just a little sweeter , with more wateriness and less hops . i could n't get over how watery this beer tasted and felt . maybe i 'm rating it a little low because of that , but it has a lot of strikes against it : watery , bland , and definitely not a bargain .

amazingly strong - smells of syrupy semi-sweet chocolate and very deep roasty and toasty malts ; smells like very fresh brewed espresso ... actually , the `` freshness '' of the smell is really quite intense . taste : very burnt and roasty malt characteristics that are reminiscent of fresh brewed espresso and grounds ; faint flavors of semi-sweet baking chocolate ; i have to admit , this would be an amazing morning drink .  the flavor is closer to my expectations , but the body is way too light for an oatmeal stout -- there 's no chew . the carbonation , which is on the high side , does n't help .

s- great smell like a realy fruity white wine , dark raspberries , some of the cereal grains come through , no hop aroma . it doesn ; t over power though .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is very high , way too high , for a milk stout . the body is thin . drinkability : just an ok beer , the mouthfeel also hurts the drinkability .

this beer smells great and looks good but the flavor is so confusing for you tastebuds .  mouthfeel - super watery overall - the only thing this beer has going for it is the aroma which is misleading .

smell : really great smelling chocolate aromas .  i really like a strong flavor from my beer ... or food for that matter m : watery . with the cloudy , opaque look of this stuff i was expecting ( and hoping for ) a little creamier or more substantial mouthfeel .
really enjoyable . t : sweet malts and slight hop bitterness .  dissapointing , watery mouthfeel .
a : black it is ! with a thick brown head .  m : this was the most dissapointing . aside from the lingering dry finish this was a very thin porter .
the hazelnut scent was so strong and so nice , it easily could have been mistaken for frangelico .  the mouthfeel was a bit thin and watery .
this really is a lovely looking beer .  empty , chalky mouthfeel , not much going on here .

the aroma is full on citrus hops . love it . the flavor is much more balanced than the nose . the citrus blast is there but the malt `` grinds '' away at it . overall another great beer from surly .  mouthfeel is overly fizzy , making an already light beer even fluffier . overall , this is an interesting beer that could be very refreshing if less carbonated .
s- it smells of pumpkin pie very strong spices . t- it 's a very sweet beer .  mouthfeel is thin .
allspice cinnamon and nutmeg all very strong a beautiful smelling ! t-the spices hit upfront with an impressive strength .  m : watery , very light-bodied , body of a light lager .
it 's got a nice effervescence and aromas of citrus and orange .  mf : too smooth and wet . watery even , but not creamy .

s- very delicate yet strong lemony aroma . t- great yeast character elevates the otherwise bland hop/malt balance to something very enjoyable . m- very smooth yet light .  the carbonation and the bitterness overpower the toasty flavors .

nose was also top notch , liqourice comes to mind first followed by a healthy serving of alcohol which was no surprise at this abv , also some very sweet candylike notes as well . taste for me was ok . i really must admit that i had high hopes but this was n't bad by any means just not as i expected .  mouthfeel is very thin , again very soda like .

50cl bottle poured into my paulaner weissbier glass a - hazy pale golden body , with the thickest ice-creamiest 4 finger head i have ever seen . super brussels lacing on the glass throughout .  mouthfeel is painfully carbonated . light bodied , way way to much carbonation .

this brew poured a medium head of fine bubbles and left behind a nice lacing as it receded . it has a dark cloudy red brown body and a malty aroma .  it 's piercing , almost . the nose lands itself squarely on the tongue , unadulterated . what you are left with is a diminished , pale , watery finish . this , fortunately , leads to high quaffability .

s- very large coffee smell . great complexity . t- taste starts with sweet fruits and a little bit of chocolate then is balance excellently by fresh bitter coffee .  the flavor was both too light and 'way too bitter for a pils . it was watery and lacking in aroma . not much foam - what there was disappeared quickly . the word i 'd use to describe this beer is `` insubstantial . ''

a big aroma of pine on the nose , a little lemon rind and malt too . the pine is huge at first and hits your nose during the pour . a piney , bitter start as expected . i think a little all spice or cinnamon replacing the pepper would do this ale some good .  mouthfeel was very light bodied and again , watery .

rarely , have i encountered an iipa with a nose as complex as this . it 's earthy , fruity , funky , dank . wow . dripping with pine and citrus oils . behind the woodsiness and sweetness a delicate floral aroma gently emerges ... seriously could smell this and be happy . thick , oily dark orange pour with a sustained white , frothy head . shit this is good . thick and mouth coating body never becomes oily or cloying . dripping and oozing with oily and resinous hops throughout but still manages to show a wonderful balance . thanks a ton brian !  m surprisingly watery for the body ; slightly carbonated with a light , watery finish . my major complaint is with the mouthfeel , the watery texture really detracts from its drinkability in my book .

smells fantastic ! fruity , citrus , & some serious hops . one of the better smelling beers i 've had .  flavor is good and somewhat spicy , but fades too quickly because body is too thin and watery .

pours a pitch black , with a solid 3/4 inch head that has serious staying power .  high gravity beer , this one is king . drink alot of water when drinking or a major headache occurs . so drink with caution .
dark brown pour with a solid tan head .  mouthfeel is way watery and i feel like it is slightly udnercarbonated .

boisterous smoked malt aroma , meaty , beaty , big , & bouncy , with light noble hops accompanying .  m : very overly carbonated to the point where it was difficult to drink early on , mild acidity , medium-bodied .

aroma vomits forth ripe , rich fruits . raisin paste and juicy plum notes jump out of the glass from a distance . the slightest hint of raw cocoa beans top off this exotic nasal medley . still , tastewise , there are better dubbels . it 's no 12 , but it 's a solid beer wrapped in an exquisite package . worth a try , glad i did .  the mouth is super thin . the thinnest mouth i 've ever had on an ipa . d= the thin mouth makes me go for sips more often and the flavor does n't linger long ... great flavor on this one no doubt .

appearance- poured a golden copper color with a decent carbonation and quickly dissipating white foam head smell- sweet malts and green apples were the first things to hit me off the nose , sugar sweet , lots of apples maybe caramel dipped ones even , appealing smell taste- a mix of sweet with slight twinge of bitter at the end .  i 'm no fan of bud , and probably have n't had a bmc beer in 2 years , but this is not one of the worst 50 beers in the world . it 's far better than many of the cheap , crappy pale lagers in many parts of the world . although it had little taste to speak of , it was exceedingly easy to drink , which , for bmc swill , ai n't that terrible .
citrus ( grapefruit ) - yes , strong and good , wow . apricot flavor notes .  one thing about this beer is it feels extremely watery .
a delicious aroma of coffee , and bready malts , and a flavor which delivers with a nice hop bitterness at the finish .  m - weak and thin . lifeless .
a harmonious aroma of raisins and rosemary , dominating . dates and caramel , intoxicating sugars . wow , taste is right there too . it 's just alluring .  the body was water and medium light .
a little touch of banana , but the citrus and spices take over , with some solid carbonation throughout and very nice , semi-complex flavors in the mouth .  watery mouthfeel .
m : moderate to heavy mouthfeel d : smells was awesome , taste was too much for me .  watery mouthfeel .

i smell a fruity and floral characteristic along with a strong citrusy hop overtone . this is a classic ipa and the brewers knew what they were doing with this batch .  i must admit i was suprised to see this new offering from coopers as i have never heard of it , it pours a pale golden see thru champagne colour with a nice frothy one finger head , sparkling carbonation and bubbly clingy lacing , it has a green , grassy hop aroma with a malty background , it has a thin mouthfeel even thinner for the style for my liking and the taste isnt as pleasant as it looks it has tastes of watery hops with a feint grainish aftertaste not as great as i was hoping for but definately better than the other macro swill out there .

nose is great on this - grassy hops , estery yeast and sugary , bready rye . very nice , everything comes together extremely well . yeast seems more tripel than saison , but compared to the smell the yeast is quite tame unfortunately .  2.5 m thin , with only the grain tastes and the slightest stickiness keeping it from being water itself .
s : pinot barrel with some dark fruit riding a wave bringing a boatload of vanilla and whiskey .  m : a very thin and watery beer .

the aroma seems to transcend the dopplebock style with a delightful boozy elixier : notes of dark rum , brandy , sherry and the like . currants , produce , fresh grass , and a slight hint of citrusy hops provide a great balance to the smell . this is not a beer for the faint of palate . i 'm not exactly sure how i feel about samichlaus ... one one hand , it 's an exceptionally complex , well-crafted beer that probably deserves its own style .  almost no body present .

i gave it a good rating for smell just because it 's so damn unique . taste is sweet malts , some hops and a bitter finish .  the flavor echoes the aroma , but the mouthfeel is n't quite up to scratch - weirdly thin and watery , which does no favors to the toasty , nutty , tea-like , and hoppy notes that are all individually assertive but harmonious and balanced in tandem , like a good jazz band .

poured from the 22oz bomber into a belgian duvel glass . appearance- beer pours a clear brown with red hues with a finger thick cap of irish cream foam .  the body is very thin -- like there was a lot of adjuncts added .

s - lots of hop presence , a strong floral aroma . unfortunately , there 's a lot of alcohol present too . i wished the hops ' taste was as present as their aroma . last but not least , the alcohol , a strong scotch like taste .  better than expected , but as someone who despises ab products + light beer i was n't expecting much trouble is , within the same can it tasted like lemonade in some sips , water in others . giving it a 4 on drinkability because it 's light , so one could drink a lot of these if they chose to .
bottle : poured a medium amber color ale with super big foamy head with great retention and good lacing .  mf- watery and too light bodied for a red ale . mouthfeel lacking .

the aroma is very nice , a heady mixture of malt , honey and alcohol . unfortunately the flavor does n't come close to fulfilling the promise in the aroma . the body is carbonated with a rather lager-ish character .  mouthfeel is very thin with low carbonation , almost watery , drinkability is poor , huge bitterness and watery mouthfeel is a disappointment .
4.5 a : lightly hazed light orange color . three fingers of pillowy white head with very good retention and plenty of lacing too .  carbonation is way too high .
s- lots and lots of chocolate here . roasted malts as well .  it 's drinkable , but the body and carbonation are really lacking .

delightful aroma but blindfolded you would never identify this as a strong dark . regardless , very nice . salvation rr reasserts itself in the taste .  really fizzy ( like coca-cola fizzy ) on the tongue , with a metallic finish , not really what i was hoping for , dissapointing .
